var __index = {"config":{"lang":["en"],"separator":"[\\s\\-]+","pipeline":["stopWordFilter"],"fields":{"title":{"boost":1000.0},"text":{"boost":1.0},"tags":{"boost":1000000.0}}},"docs":[{"location":"index.html","title":"\ud83c\udf73 Home Culinary School \u2014 The 52-Week Culinary Project","text":"<p>A 52-Week Program for the Home Cook Who Already Cooks</p> <p>Philosophy: Every session layers a professional skill into a meal you'd be cooking anyway. Skills compound. Confidence grows.</p> <p>Pace: The program is designed to run across 52 weeks \u2014 one 2-week block at a time. But life happens. Each block is self-contained, so you can take a week off between blocks, double up when you're on a roll, or revisit a block before moving on. The 52-week target is the intent, not a deadline.</p>"},{"location":"index.html#how-to-use-this","title":"How to Use This","text":"<p>Each 2-week block has three files: - Full guide \u2014 daily skill focus, reading, recipes, and context for each session - Quick ref \u2014 one-page recipe + link table for when you're in a rush - Shopping list \u2014 organized grocery list for both weeks in the block</p> <p>New to the program? Read How to Get the Most Out of This Program first \u2014 it covers the mindset, the reading habit, and how to use Claude throughout. Then check the Kitchen Equipment Guide for every tool you'll need, when you'll first use it, and how to buy in phases.</p>"},{"location":"index.html#the-program","title":"The Program","text":""},{"location":"index.html#foundational-skills-blocks-18","title":"\ud83d\udd2a Foundational Skills (Blocks 1\u20138)","text":"Blocks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 1\u20132 Knife Skills &amp; Kitchen Setup \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 3\u20134 Heat &amp; Cooking Methods \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 5\u20136 The 5 Mother Sauces \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 7\u20138 Module 1 Capstone: Stocks &amp; Eggs \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"index.html#building-flavor-blocks-916","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Building Flavor (Blocks 9\u201316)","text":"Blocks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 9\u201310 Seasoning &amp; Flavor Building \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 11\u201312 Vegetables &amp; Plant-Forward Cooking \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 13\u201314 Pasta &amp; Grains from Scratch \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 15\u201316 Module 2 Capstone: Poultry &amp; Flavor Review \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"index.html#the-proteins-blocks-1728","title":"\ud83e\udd69 The Proteins (Blocks 17\u201328)","text":"Blocks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 17\u201318 Beef \u2014 Fundamentals \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 19\u201320 Fish \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 21\u201322 Beef \u2014 Advanced Cuts \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 23\u201324 Shellfish \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 25\u201326 Pork \u2014 All Cuts \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 27\u201328 Module 3 Capstone: Charcuterie &amp; Curing \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"index.html#the-worlds-kitchens-blocks-2944","title":"\ud83c\udf0d The World's Kitchens (Blocks 29\u201344)","text":"Blocks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 29\u201330 French \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 31\u201332 Italian \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 33\u201334 Japanese \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 35\u201336 Chinese \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 37\u201338 Mexican \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 39\u201340 Indian \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 41\u201342 Middle Eastern \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 43\u201344 Module 4 Capstone: Southeast Asian Cuisines \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"index.html#mastery-pastry-blocks-4552","title":"\ud83c\udf5e Mastery &amp; Pastry (Blocks 45\u201352)","text":"Blocks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 45\u201346 Bread \u2014 Fundamentals \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 47\u201348 Pastry &amp; Desserts \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 49\u201350 Your Signature Dishes \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 51\u201352 Module 5 Capstone: Menus, Timing &amp; The Final Exam \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"index.html#weekly-rhythm","title":"Weekly Rhythm","text":"Element What it is The Skill One technique practiced with intention The Meal A complete dinner built around that skill \u2014 protein + veg + starch (or salad) The Read A short article that explains the why behind what you cooked Project Meal A bigger cook at the end of each block that makes the skills visible <p>Program design: Built for cooks who already cook 5 days a week and want to think like a chef \u2014 not just follow recipes. 52 weeks. Every skill. No fluff.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html","title":"Curriculum Proposals: Gap Analysis &amp; Repetition Review","text":"<p>Status: Proposals only \u2014 no curriculum files have been changed. Sources used: The Professional Chef (CIA, 9th ed.) full text, verified against actual recipe lists extracted from the archive.org copy. All proposed free-source links are to Serious Eats, The Woks of Life, Red House Spice, or similar freely accessible sites \u2014 no CIA recipes used.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#part-1-cia-chapter-by-chapter-assessment","title":"Part 1 \u2014 CIA Chapter-by-Chapter Assessment","text":"<p>The CIA Professional Chef is organized into 35 chapters grouped into six parts. Below, every chapter is compared against the current 26-block curriculum. Ratings: Strong / Adequate / Thin / Absent.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#part-i-the-profession-ch-15","title":"Part I \u2013 The Profession (Ch 1\u20135)","text":"CIA Chapter Topic Curriculum Coverage Rating Ch 1 The Culinary Professional Block 01-02 intro text only Absent Ch 2 Menus &amp; Recipes Block 15-16 midpoint review (partial) Thin Ch 3 Nutrition Not covered anywhere Absent Ch 4 Food Safety Block 01-02 has one external FDA link Absent Ch 5 Equipment Named throughout but no dedicated session Absent <p>Notes: - Nutrition and food safety are not mere professional formalities \u2014 they affect every dish decision (salt, fat, temperature). Worth at least one session each. - Equipment identification (mandoline, spider, tamis, thermometers, scales) is currently handled by brief bullet mentions. A single session framing why each tool matters would pay dividends in later blocks.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#part-ii-mise-en-place-ch-616","title":"Part II \u2013 Mise en Place (Ch 6\u201316)","text":"CIA Chapter Topic Curriculum Coverage Rating Ch 6 Stocks Block 07-08, full session Strong Ch 7 Poultry Block 03-04 (roasting), world cuisines Adequate Ch 8 Beef &amp; Veal Blocks 03-04, 15-16, 17-18 Strong Ch 9 Lamb Incidental (Block 39-40 Indian, 41-42 Middle Eastern) Thin Ch 10 Pork Block 25-26 Adequate Ch 11 Fish &amp; Shellfish Blocks 19-20, 21-22 Adequate Ch 12 (Stocks, cont.) Already counted in Ch 6 \u2014 Ch 13 Sauces Block 05-06 (mother sauces) Adequate Ch 14 Soups Scattered individual dishes \u2014 no framework Thin Ch 15 MeP \u2014 Spice Blends &amp; Marinades Incidental in world cuisine blocks Thin Ch 16 (additional stocks/MeP) \u2014 \u2014 <p>Detailed notes:</p> <p>Ch 13 \u2014 Sauces. CIA covers: jus li\u00e9, demi-glace, espagnole, velout\u00e9 (Supreme, Fish, Shrimp, Vegetable), b\u00e9chamel (Mornay, Cheddar), tomato + Bolognese, b\u00e9arnaise + choron + paloise, hollandaise + mousseline + maltaise, beurre blanc, compound butters (8 varieties), pesto, red pepper coulis. Block 05-06 covers the five mother sauces but beurre blanc, compound butters, and pan-sauce derivatives (marchand de vin, sherry vinegar, sauce Robert/charcuti\u00e8re) are absent. These are exactly the sauces used to finish grilled and saut\u00e9ed proteins later in the curriculum.</p> <p>Ch 14 \u2014 Soups. CIA chapter structure: consomm\u00e9 (beef, royale), broths (all proteins), cream soups (tomato, broccoli, asparagus, celery), chowders (New England clam, Manhattan clam, corn, Pacific seafood), pur\u00e9e soups (lentil, split pea, black bean, Senate bean), bisques (shrimp, lobster), gumbo, cold soups (gazpacho, vichyssoise), global soups (miso, Thai coconut, tom yum, wonton, minestrone, Tuscan white bean, tortilla). The curriculum has individual soup dishes scattered across blocks but teaches no soup taxonomy. A learner completing the curriculum could make onion soup and bouillabaisse but would not understand the difference between a bisque, a chowder, a cream soup, and a pur\u00e9e soup or why consomm\u00e9 requires clarification.</p> <p>Ch 15 \u2014 MeP for Meats. CIA teaches spice blends as a library: garam masala, Chinese five-spice, BBQ blend, chili blend, curry blend, quatre \u00e9pices, fines herbes \u2014 plus curry pastes (red, green, yellow) and marinades (Asian, BBQ, fish, game, mojo, teriyaki, citrus). The curriculum treats these incidentally. No session teaches spice blend construction or the principle of a dry rub vs. a wet marinade vs. a paste.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#part-iii-cooking-methods-ch-1721","title":"Part III \u2013 Cooking Methods (Ch 17\u201321)","text":"CIA Chapter Topic Curriculum Coverage Rating Ch 17 Grilling, Broiling &amp; Roasting Block 03-04 (dry heat overview) Adequate Ch 18 Saut\u00e9ing, Pan Frying &amp; Deep Frying Block 03-04, Block 05-06 (pan sauces) Adequate Ch 19 Steaming, Poaching &amp; Submersion Block 03-04 (moist heat, briefly) Thin Ch 20 Braising &amp; Stewing Block 03-04 + many protein blocks Strong Ch 21 (Garde manger methods) Covered in Block 27-28 Adequate <p>Detailed notes:</p> <p>Ch 17 \u2014 Grilling, Broiling &amp; Roasting. CIA recipe scope: grilled steaks with compound butter, sirloin with marchand de vin, beef teriyaki, pork chops with sherry vinegar sauce, lamb chops with cipollini onions, Indian grilled lamb with mango chutney, grilled chicken variations, grilled fish, spatchcocked birds. Block 03-04 addresses the principle of dry heat but reviews are primary. No session targets grilling variables specifically (direct vs. indirect heat, grill mark management, resting protocols, internal temperature targets by protein). This is foundational execution knowledge that learners self-discover late.</p> <p>Ch 18 \u2014 Saut\u00e9ing, Pan Frying &amp; Deep Frying. CIA covers: fond-based pan sauces (fines herbes sauce, sauce Robert, sauce charcuti\u00e8re), saut\u00e9 of veal/pork scaloppine, trout amandine, trout meuni\u00e8re, bibimbap, stir-fried squid, vatapa. Deep frying is treated as a technique category (fish and chips, hush puppies, croquettes). Curriculum includes saut\u00e9ed proteins but pan frying as a distinct method and deep frying as a category get no dedicated coverage. Learners encounter battered and fried items in the Japanese block (tempura) without prior framework.</p> <p>Ch 19 \u2014 Steaming, Poaching &amp; Submersion. CIA covers: fish en papillote (bass with scallops, snapper with tropical garnish), poached sea bass with clams, poached trout with saffron mousse, sole paupiettes, shore dinner (court bouillon method), cioppino, Boston scrod with court bouillon, pescado veracruzana, poached chicken breast. The curriculum's moist-heat mentions in Block 03-04 are cursory. Court bouillon, en papillote, paupiettes, and submersion poaching are absent as teachable techniques. These appear incidentally in the French block (poached sole) without prior method grounding.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#part-iv-cooking-ch-2230","title":"Part IV \u2013 Cooking (Ch 22\u201330)","text":"CIA Chapter Topic Curriculum Coverage Rating Ch 22 Vegetables Block 11-12 full block Strong Ch 23 Potatoes Used as sides throughout; never taught Thin Ch 24 Grains &amp; Legumes Block 13-14 (grains/risotto) Adequate Ch 25 Pasta &amp; Dumplings Block 13-14 Adequate Ch 26 Eggs Block 07-08 full session Strong Ch 27 Salads &amp; Dressings Block 05-06 (vinaigrette only) Thin Ch 28 Sandwiches Not covered (appropriate omission) \u2014 Ch 29 Hors d'Oeuvres &amp; Appetizers Block 27-28 (charcuterie only) Thin Ch 30 Charcuterie &amp; Garde Manger Block 27-28 Adequate <p>Detailed notes:</p> <p>Ch 23 \u2014 Potatoes. CIA lists 20+ preparations: whipped, duchesse, boiled parsley, baked, Tuscan roasted, glazed sweet potato, gratin dauphinoise, Lyonnaise, ch\u00e2teau, Delmonico, hash brown, latkes, pommes Anna, macaire, r\u00f6sti, French-fried, chips, souffl\u00e9 potatoes, croquette, Lorette. Also: German potato salad and curried sweet potato salad. The curriculum uses \"roasted potatoes\" and \"mashed potatoes\" as default sides (appearing ~20 times combined) but never dedicates a session to potato technique. Learners never learn what makes a gratin different from a dauphinoise, or how resting post-boil affects mash texture.</p> <p>Ch 24 \u2014 Grains &amp; Legumes. CIA scope: bean preparations (black beans 6 ways, frijoles refritos, chickpeas, white beans, lima beans, falafel, white bean stew, vegetarian chili), rice variations (pilaf \u2014 white, wild, wheat berry, barley, brown; arroz blanco, mexicano, brasileiro; coconut rice; risotto 5 variants including Milanese and mussels). Block 13-14 covers pasta, risotto, and some grains. Legumes as a topic \u2014 bean cookery, soaking vs. no-soak, dried vs. canned, falafel, refried beans from scratch \u2014 receive no dedicated session. They appear as side dishes in world cuisine blocks without instruction on the technique of cooking dried beans.</p> <p>Ch 25 \u2014 Pasta &amp; Dumplings. CIA covers: fresh egg pasta in 10 color/flavor variants (whole wheat, buckwheat, spinach, saffron, citrus, curried, herbed, black pepper, red pepper, tomato, pumpkin/carrot/beet); carbonara, orecchiette with sausage and broccoli rabe, pad thai, glass noodles (japchae), tempeh cashew noodles, lasagna (Bolognese/b\u00e9chamel and Napolitano), ravioli Bercy, gnocchi di semolina, gnocchi di ricotta, gnocchi Piedmontese, spaetzle, bread dumplings, biscuit dumplings, dim sum. Block 13-14 covers pasta well. Gaps: flavored pasta doughs (saffron, squid ink, beet) are not taught; spaetzle is absent; gnocchi is present but only in one form; dim sum dough appears in the Chinese block without prior dumpling method grounding.</p> <p>Ch 27 \u2014 Salads &amp; Dressings. CIA teaches dressings as a systematic library: vinaigrettes (red wine, white wine, mustard-herb, roasted garlic-mustard, lemon-garlic, lemon-parsley, chipotle-sherry, almond-fig, apple cider, balsamic, curry, honey-poppy-citrus, fire-roasted tomato, guava-curry, truffle, pesto, vinaigrette gourmande, walnut oil \u2014 18+ varieties). Also: Caesar, warm bacon dressing, composed salads, grain salads. The curriculum has a vinaigrette session in Block 05-06 and Caesar appears in multiple blocks. However, warm salads, grain salads, and the principle of emulsification ratios across dressing types are not taught. Salad appears throughout the curriculum as a side but not as a studied category.</p> <p>Ch 29 \u2014 Hors d'Oeuvres &amp; Appetizers. CIA covers: mousses (salmon, blue cheese, goat cheese), salsas as a category (pico de gallo, verde asada, verde cruda, roja, papaya-black bean, grapefruit), Cumberland sauce, dipping sauces (Asian, Vietnamese, spring roll), condiments (yogurt cucumber, guacamole, hummus, baba ghanoush, harissa, tapenade, z'hug, wasabi cream, roasted red pepper marmalade, cranberry relish, fruit salsa). The curriculum touches spreads and condiments in world cuisine blocks (mezze in Block 41-42, salsas in Block 37-38) but treats them as recipe items within a cuisine context, not as a construction category. A learner doesn't learn the framework: spread vs. dip vs. cold mousse vs. composed bite.</p> <p>Ch 30 \u2014 Charcuterie &amp; Garde Manger. CIA: seafood terrine, salmon flounder mousseline, p\u00e2t\u00e9 grand-m\u00e8re, aspic, chicken &amp; crayfish terrine, country-style p\u00e2t\u00e9, pork roulade, chicken galantine, foie gras terrine, venison terrine, duck terrine with pistachios, chicken liver p\u00e2t\u00e9, duck &amp; smoked ham terrine, p\u00e2t\u00e9 en cro\u00fbte, vegetable terrine, gravlax. Block 27-28 covers charcuterie and is one of the stronger specialty blocks. Gaps: gravlax (salt-curing), p\u00e2t\u00e9 en cro\u00fbte, and vegetable terrines are not mentioned. Aspic and galantine are absent but their omission is defensible given scope.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#part-v-baking-ch-3135","title":"Part V \u2013 Baking (Ch 31\u201335)","text":"CIA Chapter Topic Curriculum Coverage Rating Ch 31 Baking MeP Block 45-46 intro Adequate Ch 32 Yeast Breads Block 45-46 full block Strong Ch 33 Pastry Doughs &amp; Batters Block 47-48 Adequate Ch 34 Custards, Creams &amp; Mousses Block 47-48 (partial) Adequate Ch 35 Fillings, Frostings &amp; Dessert Sauces Block 47-48 (partial) Thin <p>Detailed notes:</p> <p>Ch 33 \u2014 Pastry Doughs &amp; Batters. CIA scope: basic pie dough (3-2-1 ratio), biscuits, cream scones, soda bread, pancakes/waffles (6 variants), puri, johnny cakes, cr\u00eapes suzette, puff pastry, blitz puff pastry, muffins (5 types), cornbread, banana-nut bread, pumpkin bread, pound cake, devil's food cake, angel food cake, vanilla sponge, chocolate sponge, cheesecake. Block 47-48 covers pastry doughs. Quick breads (biscuits, scones, muffins, cornbread) are a distinct technique category (chemical leaveners vs. yeast) that receives little explicit attention despite appearing in the block. Cr\u00eapes as a batter are absent from the curriculum entirely.</p> <p>Ch 35 \u2014 Fillings, Frostings &amp; Dessert Sauces. CIA: Italian buttercream, fruit pies (apple, cherry, pecan, lemon meringue, pumpkin), frangipane tarts, ganache, chocolate sauce, sabayon/zabaglione, classic caramel sauce, raspberry coulis, apricot glaze, dried cherry sauce, apple butter, fruit salsa. The curriculum covers some desserts in Block 47-48 and Block 45-46 (desserts block). Dessert sauces as a technical category (caramel, coulis, sabayon, ganache) are not explicitly taught. A learner completing the block may know how to make cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e without understanding the broader sauce family it implies.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#part-2-meal-repetition-findings","title":"Part 2 \u2014 Meal Repetition Findings","text":""},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#21-structural-duplicate-blocks","title":"2.1 Structural Duplicate Blocks","text":"<p>These blocks contain essentially the same session sequence as another block:</p> Duplicate Pair Nature of Duplication <code>15-16-beef</code> + <code>17-18-beef</code> All 10 sessions nearly identical (same mains, same sides, same skills focus) <code>19-20-fish</code> + <code>21-22-fish</code> All 10 sessions nearly identical (crispy salmon, miso salmon, bouillabaisse, whole roasted fish repeated exactly) <code>31-32-japanese</code> + <code>33-34-japanese</code> All 10 sessions identical <p>These three pairs waste six weeks of a 52-week curriculum. The duplication appears to be from a copy-paste scaffolding error.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#22-main-dish-repetition-across-non-duplicate-blocks","title":"2.2 Main Dish Repetition Across Non-Duplicate Blocks","text":"Main Dish Appearances Blocks Crispy pan-seared salmon 5\u00d7 03-04, 05-06, 07-08, 13-14, 19-20/21-22 Braised short ribs 4\u00d7 03-04, 13-14, 15-16, 17-18 Whole roasted / salt-baked fish 4\u00d7 09-10, 19-20, 21-22, 31-32 Italian Miso-glazed salmon 3\u00d7 03-04, 19-20, 21-22 Mushroom risotto 3\u00d7 07-08, 13-14, 31-32 Italian Bouillabaisse 3\u00d7 07-08, 19-20, 21-22 Gnocchi + brown butter sage 3\u00d7 09-10, 13-14, 31-32 Italian French onion soup 2\u00d7 01-02, 29-30 French Eggs Benedict + Hollandaise 2\u00d7 05-06, 29-30 French Ricotta ravioli + brown butter 2\u00d7 13-14, 31-32 Italian Pork chop + pan sauce 2\u00d7 05-06, 25-26 Pork Shakshuka 2\u00d7 01-02, 41-42 Middle Eastern Spatchcocked roast chicken 2\u00d7 03-04, 15-16"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#23-side-dish-monotony","title":"2.3 Side Dish Monotony","text":"Side Estimated Frequency Simple green salad / vinaigrette ~28\u00d7 Steamed / jasmine rice ~22\u00d7 Crusty bread ~18\u00d7 Roasted potatoes ~12\u00d7 Arugula salad (parmesan/lemon) ~9\u00d7 Mashed potatoes ~8\u00d7 Asparagus ~6\u00d7 Steamed bok choy ~5\u00d7 <p>The side dish menu is effectively three options rotating for the entire year. This also means potato technique (see CIA Ch 23) is never taught because the curriculum never requires it.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#part-3-proposed-changes","title":"Part 3 \u2014 Proposed Changes","text":"<p>Organized by type and priority. All proposals are for curriculum changes only \u2014 no CIA recipes will be used. Free sources are suggested where links are needed.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#priority-1-eliminate-structural-duplicates-6-weeks-recovered","title":"Priority 1 \u2014 Eliminate Structural Duplicates (6 weeks recovered)","text":"<p>Proposal A: Collapse <code>15-16-beef</code> + <code>17-18-beef</code> into one beef block. Weeks 15-16 remain as Beef Fundamentals. Weeks 17-18 reuse the freed slot for a Lamb &amp; Game block. CIA Ch 9 (Lamb) is one of the weakest areas in the curriculum \u2014 lamb currently appears only as a side note in Indian and Middle Eastern blocks. Content: braised lamb shanks (osso buco\u2013style), lamb navarin, grilled lamb chops with herb crust, Indian spiced leg of lamb. Free sources: SE lamb shanks, SE grilled lamb chops.</p> <p>Proposal B: Make <code>19-20-fish</code> and <code>21-22-fish</code> distinct. Weeks 19-20: Flatfish &amp; Round Fish (filleting, pan techniques, meuni\u00e8re, crudo). Weeks 21-22: Whole fish, curing, and advanced seafood (gravlax, bouillabaisse, shellfish cookery). This also absorbs the current separate <code>25-26-shellfish</code> block gap (shellfish appears in neither current 19-20 nor 21-22 with meaningful distinction).</p> <p>Proposal C: Collapse <code>31-32-japanese</code> + <code>33-34-japanese</code> into one Japan block. Weeks 31-32 become Japan. Weeks 33-34 become Korea (currently completely absent from the curriculum despite CIA Ch 20 including Korean braised short rib, bibimbap, japchae). Content: bibimbap, japchae, Korean fried chicken, doenjang jjigae, Korean BBQ fundamentals. Free sources: Maangchi bibimbap, Maangchi doenjang jjigae, SE Korean fried chicken.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#priority-2-deduplicate-main-dishes","title":"Priority 2 \u2014 Deduplicate Main Dishes","text":"<p>Proposal D: Replace 4 redundant crispy salmon appearances. Keep salmon in Weeks 05-06 (as a pan technique showcase with a simple pan sauce). Remove or replace the other four appearances: - Block 03-04: replace with spatchcocked chicken (already in curriculum once \u2014 move here instead) - Block 07-08: replace with steamed fish in court bouillon or poached salmon with beurre blanc (introduces CIA Ch 19 technique) - Block 13-14: replace with pasta with seafood (already a pasta block \u2014 linguine alle vongole fits) - Blocks 19-20 / 21-22: salmon belongs in fish blocks but should be one method per block \u2014 19-20 keeps miso-glazed salmon; 21-22 uses whole roasted or salt-baked fish</p> <p>Proposal E: Cut braised short ribs to one appearance. Keep in Block 03-04 (exemplary braising introduction). Remove from 13-14, 15-16, 17-18. Replace: - Block 13-14 (pasta/grains): osso buco (veal cross-cut, braised, served over risotto Milanese \u2014 CIA classic not currently in curriculum) - Block 15-16 (beef fund.): Yankee pot roast or beef rouladen \u2014 different braise profiles teaching pot-roast vs. wrapped-and-tied method respectively - Block 17-18 (opens up for lamb per Proposal A) Free sources: SE osso buco, SE pot roast.</p> <p>Proposal F: Cut bouillabaisse to one appearance. Keep in Block 07-08 (exemplifies stock + finishing technique). In fish blocks, replace second and third instances with: cioppino (American equivalent, different flavor profile) and a whole-fish braise (Indonesian or Portuguese style \u2014 new technique territory).</p> <p>Proposal G: Cut mushroom risotto to one role. Keep in Block 13-14 as the pasta/grains block anchor. Remove from Block 07-08 (replace with risotto Milanese \u2014 saffron + bone marrow, teaches a different risotto variant) and Block 31-32 Italian (replace with pasta al forno or cacio e pepe \u2014 different pasta techniques).</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#priority-3-add-missing-technique-blocks","title":"Priority 3 \u2014 Add Missing Technique Blocks","text":"<p>Proposal H: Add a Soups Architecture session (within existing Block 09-10 Seasoning &amp; Flavor, or Block 02 of any protein block). CIA Ch 14 teaches soups as a taxonomy: broth \u2192 cream soup (roux-based) \u2192 pur\u00e9e (vegetable) \u2192 bisque (crustacean + cream) \u2192 chowder (potato-thickened) \u2192 consomm\u00e9 (clarified). One session on this architecture would retroactively explain all the soups learners have been making. Structure: Session covers the four \"base\" types and demonstrates a cream soup (broccoli), a pur\u00e9e (butternut squash), and cold technique (gazpacho for summer / vichyssoise for winter). Free sources: SE butternut squash soup, SE gazpacho, SE consomm\u00e9 method.</p> <p>Proposal I: Add a Potato Technique session (within Block 11-12 Vegetables or as a standalone skills session). The entire year treats potatoes as a side filler. CIA Ch 23 shows 20+ preparations. One session covering three families: mashed family (whipped, duchess, croquette \u2014 the texture spectrum), dry-heat family (roasted, pommes Anna, r\u00f6sti, gratin dauphinoise), and fried family (hash brown, latkes) would make potatoes teachable for the rest of the curriculum. Free sources: SE perfect mashed potatoes, SE gratin dauphinoise, SE r\u00f6sti, SE latkes.</p> <p>Proposal J: Expand Block 05-06 sauces to include compound butters and beurre blanc. CIA Ch 13 lists 8 compound butters (ma\u00eetre d'h\u00f4tel, tarragon, pimiento, green onion, dill, sun-dried tomato, basil, plus the butter log method). Beurre blanc is the emulsified butter sauce that bridges the French block and the fish blocks. One half-session addition to Block 05-06: make 2-3 compound butters and one beurre blanc \u2014 then these appear naturally as sauce choices in every subsequent protein block. Free sources: SE beurre blanc, SE compound butters.</p> <p>Proposal K: Add Steaming &amp; En Papillote to Block 03-04 moist heat. Currently, court bouillon and en papillote are absent from the curriculum. CIA Ch 19 shows these are a natural family with poaching. One session addition to Block 03-04: en papillote method (fish or chicken breast), and poaching in court bouillon. This builds the vocabulary needed when poached sole appears in the French block. Free sources: SE en papillote, SE court bouillon poached fish.</p> <p>Proposal L: Add a Spice Blends &amp; Marinades session to Block 09-10 (Seasoning &amp; Flavor). CIA Ch 15 teaches spice blends and marinades as a library, not as incidentals. Block 09-10 is \"Seasoning &amp; Flavor\" \u2014 currently underspecified. Adding: dry rub construction (salt + heat + aroma ratios), wet marinade acid/oil ratio, curry paste making (one each red/green base), and a fines herbes vs. bouquet garni distinction would prepare learners for all Module 4 world cuisine blocks. Free sources: SE dry rub guide, SE garam masala from scratch, Woks of Life curry paste.</p> <p>Proposal M: Add Dessert Sauces to Block 47-48 (Pastry). CIA Ch 35 covers: caramel sauce, chocolate sauce (ganache-based), pastry cream, sabayon/zabaglione, raspberry coulis, and apricot glaze. These are the toolkit for plating any pastry item. A half-session: make one fat-based sauce (ganache), one egg-based sauce (sabayon), one fruit sauce (coulis or coulis variation). All three techniques transfer to any dessert. Free sources: SE caramel sauce, SE chocolate ganache, SE sabayon.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#priority-4-side-dish-diversification","title":"Priority 4 \u2014 Side Dish Diversification","text":"<p>The current rotation (green salad / rice / crusty bread) needs systematic replacement. The following substitution table can be applied across all blocks without requiring new skill sessions:</p> Current Default Side Proposed Replacement Pool \"Simple green salad\" Warm salad with bacon vinaigrette; grain salad (farro, freekeh, or wheat berry); fattoush; panzanella; composed salad with protein elements \"Steamed rice\" Rice pilaf (toasted, flavored with aromatics); freekeh pilaf; mujaddara; arroz mexicano; coconut rice \"Crusty bread\" Grissini; cornbread; fougasse; potato bread; roti (Indian blocks specifically) \"Roasted potatoes\" Gratin dauphinoise (in French block); pommes Anna (special occasion); r\u00f6sti (breakfast blocks); patatas bravas (Spanish / Mexican adjacents) \"Mashed potatoes\" Duchesse piped (skill builder); white bean pur\u00e9e; cauliflower pur\u00e9e; parsnip mash <p>Rule of thumb: No side dish should appear in more than 4 consecutive blocks; no side dish should appear more than 8 times total in the curriculum.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#priority-5-absent-protein-types","title":"Priority 5 \u2014 Absent Protein Types","text":"<p>Proposal N: Add Duck to either Block 27-28 (Charcuterie) or Block 29-30 (French). Duck confit is CIA Ch 20 anchor content and is one of the most educational preparations in the French kitchen (teaches fat-submersion cooking, preservation, rendering). Duck breast \u00e0 l'orange or duck breast with cherry sauce are achievable learner targets. Free sources: SE duck confit, SE duck breast, SE duck \u00e0 l'orange.</p> <p>Proposal O: Add Offal/Variety Meats to the Charcuterie block or as a stretch session. CIA covers: chicken liver p\u00e2t\u00e9, foie gras terrine. The curriculum has no offal work whatsoever. A single session on chicken livers (p\u00e2t\u00e9, dirty rice, crostini topping) would fulfill a meaningful gap without cost or difficulty barriers. Free sources: SE chicken liver mousse, SE dirty rice.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#priority-6-korea-as-a-missing-cuisine-per-proposal-c","title":"Priority 6 \u2014 Korea as a Missing Cuisine (per Proposal C)","text":"<p>Korea is one of the most influential culinary forces of the 21st century and is absent from the curriculum. CIA Ch 18 already includes bibimbap and CIA Ch 20 includes Korean braised short ribs, signaling the CIA judged it significant enough even in 2011. Proposed Block 33-34 Korea curriculum anchor sessions: - Session 1: bibimbap (banchan construction, dolsot technique, gochujang sauce) - Session 2: japchae + Korean fried chicken (two technique modes: glass noodle stir-fry and double-fry batter) - Session 3: doenjang jjigae (fermented paste soup \u2014 teaches the fermented pantry) - Session 4: Korean BBQ fundamentals (bulgogi, galbi) + kimchi as a pantry skill - Session 5: Full meal \u2014 Korean BBQ spread with banchan, soup, rice</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#priority-7-food-safety-nutrition-foundational-content","title":"Priority 7 \u2014 Food Safety &amp; Nutrition (Foundational Content)","text":"<p>These two topics are effectively absent from the curriculum:</p> <p>Food Safety \u2014 CIA Ch 4 covers HACCP principles, temperature danger zones, cross-contamination, safe thawing, holding temperatures. The current curriculum has one FDA link in Block 01-02. Proposed: a food safety \"primer\" document (not a full session, but a standalone reference in Block 01-02's quick-ref) covering: danger zone thermometers, FIFO, cross-contamination protocol, and the key internal temperatures by protein.</p> <p>Nutrition \u2014 CIA Ch 3 covers macro ratios, dietary modifications, and reading a nutrition label. Given the scope, this is probably out of scope for this curriculum. No proposal is made to add it.</p>"},{"location":"curriculum-proposals.html#summary-table","title":"Summary Table","text":"Proposal Type Priority Blocks Affected Weeks Recovered/Added A \u2014 Collapse beef duplicates \u2192 Lamb block Structural fix 1 17-18 +2 weeks Lamb B \u2014 Differentiate fish blocks Structural fix 1 19-20, 21-22 \u2014 C \u2014 Collapse Japan duplicates \u2192 Korea block Structural fix 1 33-34 +2 weeks Korea D \u2014 Reduce crispy salmon 5\u21921 Deduplication 2 03-04, 07-08, 13-14, 19-22 \u2014 E \u2014 Reduce short ribs 4\u21921 Deduplication 2 13-14, 15-16 \u2014 F \u2014 Reduce bouillabaisse 3\u21921 Deduplication 2 19-20, 21-22 \u2014 G \u2014 Reduce mushroom risotto 3\u21921 Deduplication 2 07-08, 31-32 Italian \u2014 H \u2014 Soup taxonomy session Gap: soups 3 09-10 or 07-08 \u2014 I \u2014 Potato technique session Gap: potatoes 3 11-12 \u2014 J \u2014 Beurre blanc + compound butters Gap: sauces 3 05-06 \u2014 K \u2014 Steaming + en papillote Gap: methods 3 03-04 \u2014 L \u2014 Spice blends &amp; marinades Gap: MeP 3 09-10 \u2014 M \u2014 Dessert sauces Gap: pastry 3 47-48 \u2014 N \u2014 Duck (confit/breast) Gap: proteins 4 27-28 or 29-30 \u2014 O \u2014 Offal/variety meats Gap: proteins 4 27-28 \u2014 P \u2014 Side dish diversification Repetition 4 All blocks \u2014 Q \u2014 Food safety quick-ref Gap: safety 5 01-02 \u2014 <p>Document created March 2026. No curriculum files were modified in the creation of this document.</p>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html","title":"Kitchen Equipment Guide","text":"<p>For students starting out: This guide lists every piece of equipment used across all 26 blocks of the program, when you'll first need it, and how essential it is. Use this to plan your purchases in phases \u2014 one module at a time \u2014 rather than buying everything upfront.</p> <p>Three tiers: - \ud83d\udd34 Essential \u2014 You cannot complete the skill without this. Buy before the block shown. - \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended \u2014 You'll use it repeatedly and improvisation is awkward. Worth buying. - \ud83d\udfe2 Optional \u2014 Nice to have. A workaround exists and is noted.</p>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#how-to-use-this-guide","title":"How to Use This Guide","text":"<p>The first module (Blocks 1\u20138) requires around 14 essential items. That's not a short or cheap list \u2014 expect $150\u2013400 depending on what you already own. The upside is that almost everything from Module 1 is used in every subsequent module. You're building a kitchen, not buying a kit for one class.</p> <p>Buy in phases: 1. Before Module 1: Everything in the Module 1 section below. Get this sorted before Block 1. 2. Before each subsequent module: Check the module's section and buy new Essential items at least a week before the block where they first appear. 3. World's Kitchens equipment: Buy in sub-batches as each cuisine arrives \u2014 see the Module 4 section for the breakdown by block.</p>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#buying-by-module","title":"Buying by Module","text":""},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-module-1-blocks-18-foundational-skills-150400","title":"Before Module 1 (Blocks 1\u20138): Foundational Skills \u2014 ~$150\u2013400","text":"<p>Everything here is used constantly from Block 1 onward.</p> <p>Essential - Chef's knife, 8\u201310 inch (German or Japanese) - Cutting board, large plastic or wood (at least 12\u00d718 in) - Honing steel - Kitchen shears / scissors (keep two pairs) - Tongs, 12-inch locking (\u00d72) - Instant-read thermometer - Half-sheet pans (\u00d72) - 10-inch stainless steel or carbon steel skillet - 2-qt saucepan - 8\u201312 qt stockpot - Fine-mesh strainer - Wooden spoons (\u00d72) - Silicone spatula - Ladle</p> <p>Recommended - Paring knife - Box grater - Food processor - Microplane / rasp grater</p>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-module-2-blocks-916-building-flavor-100250","title":"Before Module 2 (Blocks 9\u201316): Building Flavor \u2014 ~$100\u2013250","text":"<p>These items first appear mid-module \u2014 you don't need them all on Day 1 of Block 9.</p> <p>Needed by Block 13 - Potato ricer \u2014 gnocchi and smooth mash; workaround: hand masher (less smooth) - Pasta machine, hand-cranked \u2014 fresh pasta; workaround: rolling pin + patience</p> <p>Needed by Block 15 - 12-inch cast iron skillet \u2014 non-negotiable for beef sear and oven-to-stove cooking - Dutch oven, 5\u20137 qt (enameled cast iron) \u2014 workhorse across modules 2\u20135 - Roasting pan with rack \u2014 also used for bain-marie - Wire rack (fits half-sheet pan) \u2014 resting meat, draining</p>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-module-3-blocks-1728-the-proteins-2070","title":"Before Module 3 (Blocks 17\u201328): The Proteins \u2014 ~$20\u201370","text":"<p>Smaller additions; the cast iron investment happened at the end of Module 2.</p> <p>Essential - Fish spatula, thin flexible slotted (first needed Block 19) - Kitchen twine \u2014 trussing roasts and poultry (first needed Block 21) - Spider strainer / skimmer \u2014 shellfish, blanching (first needed Block 23)</p> <p>Recommended - Shellfish brush \u2014 cleaning mussels and clams (first needed Block 23)</p>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-module-4-blocks-2944-the-worlds-kitchens-100250","title":"Before Module 4 (Blocks 29\u201344): The World's Kitchens \u2014 ~$100\u2013250","text":"<p>Buy in sub-batches as each cuisine arrives \u2014 no point buying a wok at Block 29.</p> <p>Before Block 33 (Japanese) \u2014 ~$30\u201350 - Tamagoyaki pan (rectangular) \u2014 workaround: small nonstick pan - Steamer insert or tamale pot \u2014 dumplings, tamales, vegetables - Bamboo skewers \u2014 yakitori, satay (optional)</p> <p>Before Block 35 (Chinese) \u2014 ~$50\u201380 - Wok, 14-inch carbon steel \u2014 round or flat-bottom depending on burner - High-powered blender \u2014 mole, curry paste, smooth soups</p> <p>Before Block 37 (Mexican) \u2014 ~$30\u201350 - Comal or flat cast iron griddle \u2014 tortillas, flatbreads - Tortilla press, cast iron or aluminum \u2014 workaround: two heavy skillet bottoms + parchment paper</p> <p>Before Block 43 (Southeast Asian) \u2014 ~$30\u201360 - Mortar and pestle \u2014 Thai curry pastes; workaround: food processor (inferior result) - Pressure cooker / Instant Pot \u2014 braising acceleration; workaround: Dutch oven + 3\u00d7 the time (optional)</p>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#before-module-5-blocks-4552-mastery-pastry-200400","title":"Before Module 5 (Blocks 45\u201352): Mastery &amp; Pastry \u2014 ~$200\u2013400","text":"<p>The biggest single-module equipment investment. Spread the cost across Module 4 if needed \u2014 most items can be sourced during Blocks 41\u201344.</p> <p>Essential - Stand mixer with dough hook, whisk, and paddle \u2014 workaround for bread: by hand. For pastry: hand mixer for most tasks. - Digital kitchen scale (0.1 g resolution) \u2014 required for bread; also recommended from Block 1 for all baking - Bench scraper (metal) - Banneton / proofing basket \u2014 workaround: bowl lined with floured cloth - Bread lame (scoring blade) \u2014 workaround: very sharp serrated knife or razor blade - 9-inch tart pan with removable bottom - 9-inch pie dish - 9-inch round cake pans (\u00d73) \u2014 for layer cakes - Ramekins, 4\u20136 oz (set of 6) \u2014 cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e, souffl\u00e9, bain-marie desserts - Kitchen torch + butane canister \u2014 cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e, browning meringue - Candy thermometer (or second instant-read) \u2014 sugar work, deep frying - Whetstone, 1000/3000 grit \u2014 knife sharpening</p> <p>Recommended - Pullman loaf pan with lid \u2014 sandwich bread; workaround: standard loaf pan - Pastry brush \u2014 egg wash, glazing, greasing - Pastry bag + tips (set) \u2014 workaround: ziplock bag with corner snipped - Pie weights (or dried beans) \u2014 blind-baking pastry shells - Multiple-channel timer \u2014 managing multi-dish service; workaround: phone timers</p> <p>Optional - Springform pan, 9-inch \u2014 workaround: regular cake pan with parchment - Madeleine pan - Mandoline slicer</p>"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#full-equipment-reference","title":"Full Equipment Reference","text":""},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#knives-cutting","title":"\ud83d\udd2a Knives &amp; Cutting","text":"Item Priority First Used Module Chef's knife, 8\u201310 inch (German or Japanese) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 1 Foundational Skills Cutting board, large plastic or wood (at least 12\u00d718 in) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 1 Foundational Skills Honing steel \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 1 Foundational Skills Paring knife \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Block 1 Foundational Skills Bench scraper (metal) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 45 Mastery &amp; Pastry Fish spatula (thin, flexible, slotted) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 19 The Proteins Whetstone (1000/3000 grit) \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Block 47 Mastery &amp; Pastry Mandoline slicer \ud83d\udfe2 Optional Block 51 Mastery &amp; Pastry"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#pans-cookware","title":"\ud83c\udf73 Pans &amp; Cookware","text":"Item Priority First Used Module Notes 10-inch stainless steel or carbon steel skillet \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 1 Foundational Skills For saut\u00e9ing, sauce-making 12-inch cast iron skillet \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 15 Building Flavor Non-negotiable for beef sear Dutch oven, 5\u20137 qt (enameled cast iron) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 15 Building Flavor Workhorse across modules 2\u20135 Saucepan, 2 qt \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 1 Foundational Skills Stocks, sauces Large stockpot, 8\u201312 qt \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 7 Foundational Skills Stock and pasta water Roasting pan (large, with rack) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 15 Building Flavor Also used for bain-marie Half-sheet pan (18\u00d713 in) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 1 Foundational Skills Buy 2\u20133; used constantly Wire rack (fits half-sheet pan) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 15 Building Flavor Resting meat, draining Wok, 14-inch carbon steel \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 35 World's Kitchens Round or flat-bottom for gas Comal or flat cast iron griddle \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 37 World's Kitchens Tortillas, flatbreads Tamagoyaki pan (rectangular) \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Block 33 World's Kitchens Workaround: small nonstick pan Steamer insert or tamale pot \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 33 World's Kitchens Dumplings, tamales, vegetables Springform pan, 9-inch \ud83d\udfe2 Optional Block 49 Mastery &amp; Pastry Workaround: regular cake pan with parchment Pullman loaf pan with lid \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Block 45 Mastery &amp; Pastry Sandwich bread; workaround: standard loaf pan 9-inch tart pan with removable bottom \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 47 Mastery &amp; Pastry 9-inch pie dish \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 47 Mastery &amp; Pastry 9-inch round cake pans (\u00d73) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 49 Mastery &amp; Pastry For layer cakes Ramekins, 4\u20136 oz (set of 6) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 49 Mastery &amp; Pastry Cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e, souffl\u00e9, bain-marie desserts Madeleine pan \ud83d\udfe2 Optional Block 47 Mastery &amp; Pastry"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#temperature-measurement","title":"\ud83c\udf21\ufe0f Temperature &amp; Measurement","text":"Item Priority First Used Module Notes Instant-read thermometer \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 1 Foundational Skills Most important tool in the kitchen after a knife Digital kitchen scale (0.1 g resolution) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 45 Mastery &amp; Pastry Required for bread; Recommended from Block 1 for all baking Candy thermometer (or second instant-read) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 49 Mastery &amp; Pastry Sugar work, deep frying Multiple-channel timer \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Block 51 Mastery &amp; Pastry Managing multi-dish service; workaround: phone timers"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#tools-gadgets","title":"\ud83d\udd27 Tools &amp; Gadgets","text":"Item Priority First Used Module Notes Tongs (12-inch, locking) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 1 Foundational Skills Buy 2 Wooden spoons (\u00d72) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 1 Foundational Skills Silicone spatula \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 1 Foundational Skills Ladle \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 7 Foundational Skills Fine-mesh strainer \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 7 Foundational Skills Also used for stocks, custards, pasta water rescue Spider strainer / skimmer \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 23 The Proteins Shellfish, blanching, tempura Shellfish brush \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Block 23 The Proteins Cleaning mussels, clams Kitchen twine \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 21 The Proteins Trussing roasts and poultry Kitchen shears / scissors (keep two pairs) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 3 Foundational Skills Pastry brush \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 47 Mastery &amp; Pastry Egg wash, glazing, greasing Pastry bag + tips (set) \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Block 47 Mastery &amp; Pastry Workaround: ziplock bag with corner snipped Box grater \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Block 1 Foundational Skills Cheese, zesting, vegetables Microplane / rasp grater \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Block 5 Foundational Skills Citrus zest, garlic, nutmeg Bamboo skewers \ud83d\udfe2 Optional Block 33 World's Kitchens Yakitori, satay Pie weights (or dried beans) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 47 Mastery &amp; Pastry Blind-baking pastry shells"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#specialty-tools-by-cuisine","title":"\ud83e\udd59 Specialty Tools by Cuisine","text":"Item Priority First Used Module Notes Tortilla press (cast iron or aluminum) \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 37 World's Kitchens Workaround: two heavy skillet bottoms + parchment paper Mortar and pestle \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 43 World's Kitchens Thai curry pastes; workaround: food processor (inferior result) Banneton / proofing basket \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Block 45 Mastery &amp; Pastry Workaround: bowl lined with floured cloth Bread lame (scoring blade) \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Block 45 Mastery &amp; Pastry Workaround: very sharp serrated knife or razor blade Rice cooker \ud83d\udfe2 Optional Block 33 World's Kitchens Workaround: stovetop absorption method Kitchen torch \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 49 Mastery &amp; Pastry Cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e, browning meringue"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#appliances","title":"\u26a1 Appliances","text":"Item Priority First Used Module Notes Stand mixer with dough hook, whisk, and paddle \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 45 Mastery &amp; Pastry Workaround for bread: by hand. For pastry: hand mixer for most tasks. High-powered blender \ud83d\udd34 Essential Block 35 World's Kitchens Mole, curry paste, smooth soups Food processor \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Block 5 Foundational Skills Pastry dough, chopping, pureeing Pasta machine (hand-cranked) \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Block 13 Building Flavor Workaround: rolling pin + patience Potato ricer \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Block 13 Building Flavor Gnocchi, smooth mash; workaround: hand masher (less smooth) Pressure cooker / Instant Pot \ud83d\udfe1 Recommended Block 43 World's Kitchens Braising acceleration; workaround: Dutch oven + 3\u00d7 the time"},{"location":"equipment-guide.html#notes-on-quality","title":"Notes on Quality","text":"<ul> <li>Knife: One great knife beats a block of mediocre ones. If you're buying new, the Victorinox Fibrox 8-inch gives professional results at home-cook prices. Japanese gyuto knives offer better edge retention but require more maintenance.</li> <li>Cast iron: Lodge skillet and Dutch oven are the standard; pre-seasoned and durable for decades.</li> <li>Thermometer: ThermoWorks Thermapen or ThermoPop are the reliable standards. Harbor Freight / cheap probes read slow and drift.</li> <li>Scale: OXO Good Grips, Escali, or My Weigh KD-8000 all hit the 0.1g sweet spot.</li> <li>Dutch oven: Le Creuset and Staub are lifetime purchases. Lodge enamel is the budget-friendly alternative.</li> </ul> <p>Back to: Master Index</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html","title":"How to Get the Most Out of This Program","text":"<p>The short version: Follow the recipes. Read the links. Write three sentences on Sunday. The reading is not optional.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#the-thing-most-people-skip-dont","title":"The Thing Most People Skip (Don't)","text":"<p>Every session has a Read \u2014 a linked article that explains the why behind what you just cooked. These are not supplemental. They are half the curriculum.</p> <p>When you cook a dish without understanding why it works, you learn one recipe. When you read the article alongside it, you learn a transferable principle that applies to a hundred dishes you haven't made yet.</p> <p>Kenji's article on wok hei isn't just about woks. It explains high-heat chemistry in a way that changes how you think about every sear, every saut\u00e9, every time you're tempted to crowd the pan. That's the difference between following a recipe and understanding cooking.</p> <p>The rule: Before you clean up, open the article. Read it while the meal is still in your memory.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#before-every-block-read-before-you-shop","title":"Before Every Block: Read Before You Shop","text":"<p>Before shopping for a new block, open that block's <code>index.md</code> and skim the whole two weeks. It takes 15 minutes and catches problems that would otherwise surface mid-cook on a Wednesday night:</p> <ul> <li>Recipes that need overnight prep you didn't plan for</li> <li>Hard-to-source ingredients worth substituting in advance</li> <li>Sessions that won't fit your schedule as written</li> <li>Links you want to read before the session, not during it</li> </ul>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#two-files-two-contexts","title":"Two Files, Two Contexts","text":"<p>Each block has a full guide (<code>index.md</code>) and a quick ref (<code>quick-ref.md</code>). Use them differently:</p> Full Guide Quick Ref When Before the session During the session What Read the skill explanation, context, and the linked article Glance at the recipe link and move on Why The narrative connects the skill to everything else You don't want to scroll mid-cook <p>The full guide is where you understand the session. The quick ref is where you execute it.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#the-project-session-is-not-optional","title":"The Project Session Is Not Optional","text":"<p>The project session is when the block's skills become real. The earlier sessions build technique in relative isolation \u2014 garlic mince, dice consistency, grip. The project session is where you use all of it in one self-contained cook with a real result.</p> <p>Don't treat it as a harder session. Treat it as a performance. Set the table. Plate carefully. Invite someone if you can.</p> <p>The feedback you get from cooking a full meal \u2014 timing pressure, heat management, plating decisions \u2014 is different from anything you get from a skill-focused session. It's irreplaceable.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#the-three-sentence-end-of-block-habit","title":"The Three-Sentence End of Block Habit","text":"<p>Every block ends with a reflection prompt. It asks for three sentences:</p> <ol> <li>What felt awkward this block?</li> <li>What clicked?</li> <li>What do you want to fix?</li> </ol> <p>This sounds trivial. It isn't. After 52 blocks you'll have a document that tracks your actual development as a cook \u2014 not a highlight reel, but a real log. It also forces you to pay attention during the block in a way that knowing you'll have to write about it creates.</p> <p>Your notes app is fine. A text file is fine. The format doesn't matter. The habit does.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#your-progress-log-if-youve-forked-this","title":"Your Progress Log (If You've Forked This)","text":"<p>The <code>progress/</code> folder at the root of the repo is for you. After each block, copy <code>template-block.md</code>, fill in what you cooked and what clicked, and commit it to your fork. It's public \u2014 which is the point. A record of your actual journey that others can follow.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#when-you-mess-something-up","title":"When You Mess Something Up","text":"<p>You will burn something. You will break an emulsion. You will undercook a braise and eat at 9pm. This is correct.</p> <p>The sessions that go wrong teach more than the ones that go right \u2014 but only if you stay curious about why. When something fails, before you move on, ask:</p> <ul> <li>Was the pan not hot enough?</li> <li>Did I skip a step?</li> <li>Was the timing unrealistic for a weeknight?</li> <li>Is the recipe wrong, or was I?</li> </ul> <p>Write down what you think went wrong. Even a single sentence before you move on is enough to get the insight to stick.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#skills-compound-trust-the-sequence","title":"Skills Compound \u2014 Trust the Sequence","text":"<p>The program is deliberately sequenced. Block 1's knife skills feed into Block 3's mise en place, which feeds into Block 7's stock timing, which feeds into Block 15's butchery. You will notice callbacks and repetitions throughout \u2014 they're intentional.</p> <p>If you skip blocks or jump ahead, you'll cook the recipes but miss the compounding. The whole point is that by Block 40, you're not following a recipe for Thai curry \u2014 you understand what's happening in the pan and can adapt on the fly. That only happens if the foundations were built underneath it.</p> <p>Do the blocks in order. Skip a session if life happens \u2014 that's fine \u2014 but don't skip a block.</p>"},{"location":"how-to-use.html#the-mindset-that-makes-this-work","title":"The Mindset That Makes This Work","text":"<p>You already cook. The goal isn't to teach you to follow recipes \u2014 it's to change how you think while you're cooking. That shift happens through:</p> <ul> <li>Reading the linked articles (not skimming them)</li> <li>Noticing what's happening in the pan, not just watching the timer</li> <li>Writing three sentences on Sunday even when it feels unnecessary</li> </ul> <p>The recipes are the vehicle. The reading, the reflection, and the repetition are the program.</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html","title":"The 52-Week Culinary Project \u2014 Proposed Program Overview","text":"<p>This document reflects the curriculum as it would look after all proposals in <code>curriculum-proposals.md</code> are implemented. Changes are noted with <code>[CHANGED]</code>, <code>[NEW]</code>, or <code>[REMOVED]</code> tags. No curriculum files have been modified.</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#module-1-foundational-skills","title":"Module 1: Foundational Skills","text":""},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-12-knife-skills-unchanged","title":"Weeks 1\u20132: Knife Skills (unchanged)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 The Pinch Grip Pasta with Butter and Parmesan - Main: Parmesan-crusted pasta - Veg: Wilted baby spinach, saut\u00e9ed in the pasta pan with olive oil, garlic, and lemon</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 The Claw The Best Chicken Noodle Soup - Protein: Chicken breast, poached in the broth, then diced - Veg: Charred onion into the stock; diced carrot and celery added for last 10 minutes - Starch: Egg noodles, cooked separately</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Rock Chop vs. Push Cut Shrimp Scampi - Protein: Shrimp, saut\u00e9ed in garlic butter and white wine - Veg/Salad: Arugula, fennel, and orange salad - Starch: Crusty bread or linguine</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Mise en Place Stir-Fried Beef and Broccoli - Protein: Thinly sliced flank steak, seared in small batches - Veg: Broccoli florets, seared in the same pan - Starch: Steamed jasmine rice</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: French Onion Soup French Onion Soup (Soupe \u00e0 l'Oignon)</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 The Julienne The Best Pad Thai - Protein: Shrimp, chicken, or tofu - Veg: Julienned carrots and scallions, bean sprouts, fresh basil chiffonade - Starch: Rice noodles</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 The Dice (Small, Medium, Large) Home Fries + Pan-Seared Crispy Chicken Thighs - Protein: Crispy pan-seared bone-in chicken thighs - Veg/Salad: Warm green bean and walnut salad [CHANGED from simple green salad] - Starch: Home fries (the dice drill is the recipe)</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Breaking Down a Whole Chicken Chicken Piccata + Burst Cherry Tomatoes - Protein: Chicken piccata using the breasts you broke down - Veg: Burst cherry tomatoes with garlic and olive oil - Starch: Linguine tossed with the burst tomatoes</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Speed Benchmark Shakshuka - Protein: Eggs poached in the shakshuka sauce - Veg: Onion, bell pepper, tomatoes (the shakshuka base) - Starch: Crusty bread for dipping</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Proven\u00e7al Vegetable Tian Proven\u00e7al Summer Vegetable Tian - Protein: Optional \u2014 burrata or soft-boiled egg on top - Veg: The tian (eggplant, zucchini, squash, tomato) - Starch: Fougasse or crusty baguette [CHANGED from plain crusty bread]</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-34-heat-cooking-proposal-k-en-papillote-added","title":"Weeks 3\u20134: Heat &amp; Cooking (Proposal K: en papillote added)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Saut\u00e9: Hot Pan, Don't Crowd Saut\u00e9ed Chicken Breasts with Quick Pan Sauce + Saut\u00e9ed Zucchini - Protein: Saut\u00e9ed boneless chicken breast, finished with a quick pan sauce of shallot, white wine, and butter - Veg: Saut\u00e9ed zucchini with garlic - Starch: Rice pilaf with toasted vermicelli [CHANGED from plain steamed rice]</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Roasting: Hot Oven, Dry Surface Sheet Pan Chicken Thighs with Roasted Vegetables - Protein: Bone-in skin-on chicken thighs, roasted until crackling - Veg: Sheet pan vegetables (broccoli, onions) - Salad: Panzanella with torn croutons [CHANGED from simple green salad]</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Braising: Low, Slow, Wet Braised Chicken Thighs with Tomatoes and Capers - Protein: Braised chicken thighs in a rich tomato-caper sauce - Starch: Creamy polenta [CHANGED from crusty bread]</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Steaming, Poaching &amp; En Papillote [CHANGED \u2014 expanded from \"Gentle, Wet Heat\"] Sea Bass en Papillote + Poached Chicken Breast in Court Bouillon - Protein: Sea bass packet (herbs, lemon, capers) \u2014 en papillote; poached chicken breast in court bouillon - Veg: Steam-wilted spinach with lemon - Starch: Plain white rice to contrast</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Spatchcocked Roast Chicken Spatchcocked Roast Chicken - Protein: Spatchcocked whole chicken - Veg: Roasted carrots with honey and thyme [CHANGED from roasted potatoes] - Salad: Simple green salad with vinaigrette</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Searing Steak: The Art of Doing Nothing Pan-Seared Ribeye + Pan Sauce - Protein: Ribeye, seared in cast iron - Starch: Pommes Anna [CHANGED \u2014 introduces potato technique early] - Veg: Roasted asparagus</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 High-Heat Fish: Crispy Skin [CHANGED \u2014 no longer the salmon-with-nothing recipe] Pan-Seared Branzino with Brown Butter and Capers - Protein: Whole branzino fillet, skin-on, seared to glass - Veg: French green beans (haricots verts) with toasted almonds - Starch: Crusty bread</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Broiling: Overhead Heat Broiled Salmon with Herb Crust + Broiled Grapefruit Salad - Protein: Salmon fillet under the broiler - Veg/Salad: Warm grain salad with farro and roasted peppers [CHANGED]</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Recap Cook: No Recipes Multi-Method Dinner: learner's choice across all four methods</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-56-mother-sauces-proposals-d-j-beurre-blanc-added-crispy-salmon-moved-here-as-the-one-canonical-occurrence","title":"Weeks 5\u20136: Mother Sauces (Proposals D, J: beurre blanc added; crispy salmon moved here as the one canonical occurrence)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 B\u00e9chamel: The White Sauce Croque Monsieur + Mornay-Dressed Broccoli - Protein: Ham and gruy\u00e8re croque monsieur - Veg: Broccoli florets in Mornay sauce</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Velout\u00e9: Stock Instead of Milk Chicken Breast with Velout\u00e9 + Steamed Vegetables - Protein: Saut\u00e9ed chicken breast finished with chicken velout\u00e9 - Veg: Steamed green beans and carrots - Starch: Rice pilaf [CHANGED from plain rice]</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Tomato Sauce: The Italian Mother [CHANGED \u2014 was missing in original; added to fill the gap] Pasta al Pomodoro + Burrata - Protein/Main: Hand-torn pasta in slow-cooked tomato sauce - Accompaniment: Fresh burrata, olive oil</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Espagnole and Demi-Glace (Simplified) Pan-Seared Duck Breast with Cherry Sauce [CHANGED \u2014 was vague; now a specific use-case] - Protein: Duck breast, rendered fat, demi-glace-based cherry reduction - Starch: Creamed lentils [CHANGED \u2014 introduces legumes early]</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 Hollandaise: The Emulsion Eggs Benedict with Hollandaise - Protein: Poached eggs, Canadian bacon - Starch: English muffin - Salad: Arugula salad with lemon</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Beurre Blanc + Compound Butters [NEW \u2014 Proposal J] Pan-Seared Salmon with Beurre Blanc + Crispy Capers [THE ONE canonical crispy salmon \u2014 Proposal D] - Protein: Crispy skin-on salmon fillet \u2014 the definitive version - Sauce: Classic beurre blanc (white wine reduction + cold butter) - Veg: Steamed asparagus with ma\u00eetre d'h\u00f4tel butter - Starch: New potatoes with dill butter [CHANGED \u2014 uses compound butter just made]</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Mayonnaise: Emulsion Without Heat Ni\u00e7oise Salad - Protein: Tuna (canned or seared), hard-boiled eggs - Veg: Green beans, tomatoes, olives, potatoes</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 The Vinaigrette: A Temporary Emulsion Composed Salad with Warm Bacon Vinaigrette [CHANGED \u2014 illustrates warm vs. cold dressing] - Protein: Lardons, poached egg - Veg: Fris\u00e9e and bitter greens - Starch: Torn croutons</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Pan Sauce: The Working Sauce Pork Chop with Sauce Robert [CHANGED \u2014 was generic; now teaches a specific CIA-classic derivative sauce] - Protein: Bone-in pork chop, fond-based sauce Robert (mustard, white wine) - Veg: Braised cabbage with caraway - Starch: Mashed potatoes</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Classic French Bistro Dinner (3 Courses) French onion soup \u2192 Chicken Chasseur \u2192 Tarte Tatin - First: French onion soup (contextually revisited from a sauce perspective) - Main: Chicken chasseur (hunter-style, demonstrates tomato-espagnole derivative) - Dessert: Tarte Tatin with cr\u00e8me fra\u00eeche</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-78-stocks-eggs-proposals-f-g-bouillabaisse-stays-mushroom-risotto-replaced-with-milanese-soup-architecture-promoted","title":"Weeks 7\u20138: Stocks &amp; Eggs (Proposals F, G: bouillabaisse stays; mushroom risotto replaced with Milanese; soup architecture promoted)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Soup Architecture: The Five Families [PROMOTED from optional to Session 1 \u2014 Proposal H] Cream Soup (Broccoli) + Pur\u00e9e (Butternut Squash) + Cold Soup (Gazpacho) - Demonstrates: broth \u2192 cream \u2192 pur\u00e9e \u2192 bisque \u2192 chowder taxonomy in one session - Full meal: three mini soup courses, served in sequence</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Chicken Stock from Scratch Hearty Chicken Vegetable Soup (from the stock made today) - Main: Clear chicken broth with vegetables \u2014 tastes the difference between real stock and water</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Pan Sauces from Real Stock Roast Chicken Thighs + Three Pan Sauces from One Pan - Protein: Chicken thighs, three sauce variants from the same fond - Starch: Wheat berry pilaf [CHANGED \u2014 introduces whole grains]</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Fish Stock + Fumet Mussels Marini\u00e8re (uses the fumet) + Grilled Bread - Protein: Mussels in white wine and fumet broth - Starch: Grilled baguette</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 Vegetable Stock + Risotto Milanese [CHANGED \u2014 Proposal G: mushroom risotto replaced] Risotto Milanese (Saffron + Bone Marrow if available) - Main: Risotto alla Milanese \u2014 saffron-gold, enriched; this becomes the definitive risotto session</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Whole Soup Kitchen Day + Bouillabaisse [THE ONE canonical bouillabaisse \u2014 Proposal F] Bouillabaisse with Rouille and Gruy\u00e8re Toasts - Main: Full bouillabaisse \u2014 multiple fish, fennel, saffron broth - Accompaniment: Rouille on grilled bread</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 The French Scramble Soft Scrambled Eggs on Toast + Simple Side Salad - Protein: Butter-finished scrambled eggs - Salad: Watercress and radish salad [CHANGED from green salad]</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 The Perfect Poached Egg Eggs Florentine - Protein: Poached eggs on creamed spinach - Sauce: Hollandaise (review from 05-06)</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 The Omelette Classic French Omelette + C\u00f4te de Porc - Protein: French omelette (technique focused \u2014 no color, soft curd) - Side: Small arugula salad with lemon</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 Custard: Eggs as Thickener \u2014 Quiche Lorraine Quiche Lorraine (full savory custard) - Main: Quiche Lorraine with lardons and gruy\u00e8re in p\u00e2te bris\u00e9e - Salad: Fris\u00e9e salad with mustard vinaigrette</p> <p>Session 11 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Complete Egg Dinner Party (3 Courses) Leek and Gruy\u00e8re Tart \u2192 Omelette Station \u2192 Cr\u00e8me Caramel</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#module-2-building-flavor","title":"Module 2: Building Flavor","text":""},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-910-seasoning-flavor-proposals-h-l-spice-blends-soup-architecture-extended","title":"Weeks 9\u201310: Seasoning &amp; Flavor (Proposals H, L: spice blends + soup architecture extended)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Early Salt: Brining Dry-Brined Roast Chicken - Protein: 24-hour dry-brined whole chicken, roasted - Veg: Roasted root vegetables (carrots, parsnips) - Starch: Freekeh pilaf [CHANGED \u2014 introduces whole grain]</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 During Salt: Layered Seasoning Pasta Carbonara \u2014 Season Every Step - Main: Carbonara \u2014 season pasta water, eggs, and finish - Salad: Shaved fennel and parmesan salad [CHANGED]</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Late Salt: Finishing Steak with Maldon + Vegetable Crudo - Protein: Seared steak finished with flaked salt - Veg: Raw vegetable crudo, finished salts demonstrated</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Salt as Texture and Contrast Dark Chocolate and Sea Salt Tasting + Salted Caramel Sauce - Focus: Salt amplifying sweetness \u2014 dessert context</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Salt-Crusted Whole Roasted Fish Salt-Crusted Sea Bass - Main: Whole fish in salt crust \u2014 aromatic herbs inside, cracked tableside - Veg: Roasted fennel and olives - Starch: Grilled ciabatta</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Acid: The Brightness Lever Fish Tacos with Three Acid Salsas - Protein: Fish tacos with lime crema - Condiments: Pico de gallo, pickled red onion, salsa verde \u2014 acid compared</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Different Acids, Different Effects Pan-Seared Chicken with Three Vinegar Pan Sauces - Protein: Chicken thigh, tested with sherry vinegar, rice vinegar, and balsamic</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Fat as Flavor Duck Fat Potatoes + Confit Garlic Butter Bread - Starch: Duck fat\u2013roasted potatoes - Accompaniment: Bread with confit garlic butter</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Spice Blends, Dry Rubs &amp; Marinades [NEW \u2014 Proposal L] Garam Masala\u2013Rubbed Lamb Chops + Flatbread + Cucumber Raita - Focus: Build garam masala from scratch; construct a wet marinade (mojo citrus); construct a curry paste (red Thai base) - Protein: Lamb chops, dry-rubbed and grilled - Starch: Homemade flatbread - Sauce: Cucumber raita made during the session</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 Umami: The Depth Dial Miso-Glazed Eggplant + Dashi Broth + Mushroom Toast - Focus: Fermented + glutamate umami sources: miso, Parmesan, anchovies, soy - Main: Miso-glazed eggplant over rice - Additional: Dashi broth tasting; mushroom toast with Parmesan gremolata</p> <p>Session 11 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Composed Tasting Plate Five-bite tasting plate applying salt, acid, fat, umami, and spice systematically</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-1112-vegetables-proposal-i-potato-technique-promoted-to-full-session","title":"Weeks 11\u201312: Vegetables (Proposal I: potato technique promoted to full session)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Potatoes: Five Techniques, One Vegetable [CHANGED \u2014 Proposal I; was optional or absent] Gratin Dauphinoise + R\u00f6sti + Whipped Potatoes \u2014 Three Versions, One Session - Family 1 (Mashed): Whipped potatoes with brown butter - Family 2 (Dry Heat): R\u00f6sti (pan-crispy, starch released) - Family 3 (Baked/Gratin): Gratin dauphinoise \u2014 cream, garlic, slow oven - Serve all three as a composed potato dinner</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Blanching, Shocking, and Color Science Blanched Vegetable Platter with Three Dipping Sauces - Veg: Asparagus, haricots verts, broccoli rabe \u2014 all blanched and shocked - Sauces: Warm anchovy butter, mustard vinaigrette, aioli</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Roasting: Caramelization and Concentration Honey-Roasted Carrots + Oven-Roasted Tomatoes + Curried Roasted Cauliflower - Focus: Three vegetables, three sugar/caramelization profiles</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Saut\u00e9, Braise, and the Crucifer Redemption Braised Red Cabbage + Pan-Saut\u00e9ed Brussels Sprouts with Bacon - Veg: Two preparations, two textures \u2014 braised vs. saut\u00e9ed crucifer</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 Grilling and Charring: Fire as Flavor Grilled Vegetables Proven\u00e7al-Style - Veg: Zucchini, peppers, eggplant, tomato \u2014 marinated and charred - Starch: Grilled flatbread</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 PROJECT: Plant-Forward Dinner Party Three-course vegetable dinner: soup \u2192 main vegetable dish \u2192 dessert</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 The Composed Salad: Dressing Is a Technique Warm Farro Salad + Three Vinaigrette Variants [CHANGED \u2014 was generic composed salad] - Focus: Emulsification ratio, warm vs. room temp dressings, grain-based salad - Main: Warm farro with roasted beets, goat cheese, walnuts \u2014 three different vinaigrettes tested</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Legumes and Beans: The Forgotten Protein [EXPANDED \u2014 Proposal: legumes as a technique] Falafel + White Bean Stew + Quick-Soaked vs. No-Soak Black Beans (tasting comparison) - Focus: Soaking vs. no-soak; canned vs. dried; mashed vs. whole; fried (falafel) - Main: Falafel plate with hummus, white bean stew on the side</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Mushrooms: Umami in Plant Form Pan-Roasted King Trumpet Mushrooms + Mushroom Duxelles on Toast - Main: Mixed mushroom dinner \u2014 saut\u00e9ed, roasted, and duxelles variations - Starch: Grilled sourdough</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 A Completely Vegetable-Driven Main Eggplant Parmesan [CHANGED \u2014 was vague; CIA-classic vegetable main] - Main: Eggplant parmesan \u2014 breaded, fried, baked in tomato sauce - Salad: Shaved fennel and citrus salad</p> <p>Session 11 \u2014 PROJECT: The Vegetable Tasting Menu Five-course vegetable dinner designed and executed by the learner</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-1314-pasta-grains-proposals-e-g-osso-buco-replaces-duplicate-short-ribs-duplicate-mushroom-risotto-replaced","title":"Weeks 13\u201314: Pasta &amp; Grains (Proposals E, G: osso buco replaces duplicate short ribs; duplicate mushroom risotto replaced)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 The Dough: Meeting Gluten Fresh Egg Pasta \u2014 Fettuccine with Brown Butter and Sage - Main: Fresh-rolled fettuccine, brown butter, sage, parmesan</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Ravioli: Pasta as a Vessel Ricotta Ravioli with Tomato-Butter Sauce [CHANGED sauce \u2014 removes duplicate brown butter ravioli] - Main: Ricotta and herb ravioli in a simple tomato-butter sauce</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Gnocchi: Potato and Restraint Gnocchi with Gorgonzola Cream Sauce [CHANGED \u2014 removes duplicate brown butter gnocchi] - Main: Light potato gnocchi, dolcelatte variation - Veg: Wilted spinach</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Pasta Water: The Secret Sauce Ingredient Cacio e Pepe (Master Level) [CHANGED \u2014 teaches pasta water emulsion in its purest form] - Main: Cacio e pepe \u2014 three ingredients, perfected through technique</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 Osso Buco alla Milanese [NEW \u2014 Proposal E: replaces duplicate braised short ribs] Veal Cross-Cut Braised Over Risotto Milanese + Gremolata - Protein: Braised veal shank \u2014 teaches the same braising logic as short ribs but a new cut and preparation - Starch: Risotto Milanese (review from 07-08) - Finish: Gremolata (lemon zest, garlic, parsley) \u2014 classic finish</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Risotto: Patience as Technique [CHANGED \u2014 not mushroom risotto] Risotto alle Vongole (Clam Risotto) - Main: Risotto with clams and white wine \u2014 teaches risotto method applied to a seafood context - Veg: Grilled radicchio salad [CHANGED from plain salad]</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Flavored Pasta Doughs [NEW \u2014 fills CIA Ch25 gap; saffron, squid ink, beet] Saffron Pasta with Seafood + Squid Ink Pasta with Shrimp (tasting comparison) - Main: Two flavored pasta sheets rolled and cut \u2014 students taste and compare technique</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Spaetzle and Dumplings [NEW \u2014 fills CIA Ch25 gap] Spaetzle with Caramelized Onions and Gruy\u00e8re - Main: Spaetzle \u2014 German egg dumpling, teaches batter-drop technique - Veg: Braised red cabbage</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Farro and Grains That Think for Themselves Farro Risotto with Mushrooms and Thyme - Main: Farrotto \u2014 whole grain cooked risotto-style - Salad: Arugula with lemon and parmesan</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Grain-Forward Dinner Party Three-course grain dinner: grain soup \u2192 pasta/grain main \u2192 grain dessert (rice pudding)</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-1516-midpoint-review-unchanged","title":"Weeks 15\u201316: Midpoint Review (unchanged)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Menu Planning Session 2 \u2014 Dry Run: The Most Difficult Component Session 3 \u2014 Knife Speed Benchmark Session 4 \u2014 Final Prep Day Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: The Midpoint Dinner Session 6 \u2014 High-Heat Whole-Bird Roast Session 7 \u2014 Spatchcock: Why It Changes Everything Session 8 \u2014 Braised Poultry: Coq au Vin Session 9 \u2014 Pan-Seared Chicken Breast + Pan Sauce</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#module-3-the-proteins","title":"Module 3: The Proteins","text":""},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-1516-beef-fundamentals-proposal-a-consolidated-from-two-duplicate-blocks-short-ribs-replaced-proposal-e","title":"Weeks 15\u201316: Beef Fundamentals (Proposal A: consolidated from two duplicate blocks; short ribs replaced \u2014 Proposal E)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Beef Fabrication: Primal to Plate (optional) Cold tasting: raw beef cuts identified and handled, no cooking</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 The Dry Brine + Reverse Sear Method Reverse-Seared Ribeye + Compound Butter - Protein: Thick-cut ribeye, oven-finished, seared to crust - Sauce: Ma\u00eetre d'h\u00f4tel compound butter (review from 05-06) - Veg: Roasted bone marrow and grilled bread - Starch: Crispy hash browns [CHANGED \u2014 uses potato technique from 11-12]</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Pan-Seared Strip Steak + Compound Butter Steak Frites - Protein: New York strip, seared in cast iron - Starch: Double-fried French fries - Salad: Watercress salad with blue cheese</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Burgers: Understanding Ground Beef Smash Burger + Pickled Everything - Protein: Smash burger \u2014 fat percentage, grind, technique - Starch: Potato bun - Side: Dill pickles and pickled onion (quick pickle review)</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 Skirt Steak: Thin Cuts &amp; Marination Carne Asada + Warm Corn Tortillas - Protein: Marinated skirt steak, grilled hot and fast - Starch: Corn tortillas, charred directly on flame - Salsa: Charred salsa roja</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 PROJECT: The Prime Rib Standing Rib Roast + Au Jus + Horseradish Cream - Protein: Prime rib, low-and-slow then high-heat sear - Starch: Yorkshire pudding - Veg: Roasted root vegetables</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Yankee Pot Roast: The American Braise [CHANGED \u2014 Proposal E: replaces duplicate short ribs] Pot Roast with Root Vegetables + Braised Potatoes - Protein: Chuck roast braised in beef stock and aromatics - Veg: Carrots, parsnips, pearl onions braised alongside - Starch: Braised potatoes cooked in the pot liquid</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Beef Rouladen in Burgundy Sauce [CHANGED \u2014 Proposal E: new preparation, different braise logic] Rouladen (Stuffed Beef Rolls) + Potato Pancakes + Red Cabbage - Protein: Thin beef round, stuffed with bacon, pickle, and mustard; braised in Burgundy - Starch: Potato pancakes (latkes technique \u2014 review from 11-12) - Veg: Braised red cabbage with apple</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Steak au Poivre Steak au Poivre with Cognac Cream Sauce - Protein: Filet or strip steak, peppercorn crust, flamb\u00e9ed cognac cream - Veg: Asparagus with browned butter - Starch: Pommes Lyonnaise [CHANGED \u2014 uses potato technique from 11-12]</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: The Beef Dinner for Four Three-course beef dinner: consomm\u00e9 \u2192 main beef preparation \u2192 cheese course</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-1718-lamb-game-new-block-proposal-a","title":"Weeks 17\u201318: Lamb &amp; Game (NEW BLOCK \u2014 Proposal A)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Lamb Fundamentals: Cuts and Flavor Profile Grilled Lamb Chops with Herb Crust + Tzatziki - Protein: Loin or rib lamb chops, direct-grilled over high heat - Sauce: Herb-and-garlic crust, served with homemade tzatziki - Starch: Grilled flatbread - Veg: Grilled zucchini with lemon</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Braised Lamb Shanks Braised Lamb Shanks + White Bean Rag\u00f9 + Gremolata - Protein: Lamb shanks, braised until falling off the bone - Starch: White bean rag\u00f9 (introduces lamb's natural pairing) - Finish: Gremolata \u2014 reviews the technique from osso buco in 13-14</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Lamb Navarin (French Spring Stew) Navarin d'Agneau + New Potatoes + Spring Vegetables - Protein: Shoulder pieces braised with turnips, carrots, and peas - Starch: New potatoes cooked in the braise</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Rack of Lamb: French Trim &amp; Herb Crust Rack of Lamb Persillade + Gratin Dauphinoise - Protein: French-trimmed rack, roasted to medium-rare - Crust: Herbed breadcrumb persillade - Starch: Gratin dauphinoise (review from 11-12) - Veg: Roasted asparagus</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Leg of Lamb Butterflied Leg of Lamb (Grilled) or Slow-Roasted Bone-In - Protein: Learner's choice of method \u2014 butterflied and marinated (mojo or herb) or slow-roasted bone-in - Starch: Arroz blanco - Salad: Fattoush with pomegranate</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Lamb Kebabs: Ground &amp; Whole Adana Kebab (Ground Lamb) + Shish Kebab (Whole) - Protein: Two kebab traditions side by side \u2014 ground meat on flat skewer vs. marinated cubes - Starch: Lavash and rice pilaf - Sauce: Muhammara (roasted pepper and walnut)</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Lamb Curry: Building a Spice Braise Lamb Khorma - Protein: Shoulder pieces, yogurt-marinated, braised with whole spices - Starch: Basmati rice with crispy onions - Bread: Puri or store-bought naan</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Duck Confit [NEW \u2014 Proposal N: duck introduced in lamb block as a parallel fat-submersion technique] Duck Confit + Fris\u00e9e Salad with Lardons and Duck Egg - Protein: Duck legs cured overnight in salt and herbs, submerged in duck fat and slow-cooked - Salad: Fris\u00e9e with warm bacon vinaigrette and a poached (or duck) egg - Note: Start 3\u20134 days early; this is your first \"project that takes longer than a session\"</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Duck Breast \u00e0 l'Orange [NEW \u2014 Proposal N: duck continued] Seared Duck Breast + Orange-Gastrique Sauce - Protein: Scored duck breast, rendered fat, served medium-rare - Sauce: Orange gastrique \u2014 sweet-acid reduction using caramel technique - Starch: Lentilles du Puy with shallots - Veg: Roasted beets</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: The Lamb and Duck Dinner Party Three-course dinner: lamb soup \u2192 lamb main \u2192 duck dessert (duck fat caramel) - First: Lamb broth with orzo and herbs (from trimmings) - Main: Rack of lamb persillade (review Session 4) - Dessert: Tarte Tatin with duck fat pastry (demonstrates fat substitution)</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-1920-flatfish-round-fish-proposal-b-differentiated-from-21-22-no-duplicate-salmon-or-miso-salmon","title":"Weeks 19\u201320: Flatfish &amp; Round Fish (Proposal B: differentiated from 21-22; no duplicate salmon or miso salmon)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Fish Anatomy: Flatfish vs. Round Fish (optional) Cold session: filleting a whole flounder and a whole trout side by side</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Sole Meuni\u00e8re: The Flatfish Lesson Sole Meuni\u00e8re + Blanched Haricots Verts - Protein: Dover or lemon sole pan-fried in clarified butter, finished with lemon, capers, and brown butter - Veg: Blanched French green beans</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Trout Amandine: Round Fish Variant Trout Amandine + Roasted Carrots with Honey - Protein: Whole trout or fillet, skin-on, finished with toasted almond butter - Veg: Honey-glazed roasted carrots</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Court Bouillon Poaching Poached Halibut in Court Bouillon + Beurre Blanc - Protein: Thick halibut fillet poached in aromatic court bouillon - Sauce: Beurre blanc (review from 05-06) \u2014 the natural pairing - Veg: Steamed new potatoes with parsley</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: A Classic French Fish Dinner Sole en Paupiettes + Sauce Vin Blanc - Protein: Rolled sole fillets stuffed with a light mousse, poached, sauced - Starch: Rice pilaf with herbs</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Ceviche: Acid as Heat Leche de Tigre Ceviche + Tostones - Protein: White fish in citrus marinade \u2014 demonstrates protein denaturation through acid - Starch: Tostones (fried green plantain)</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Miso-Glazed Black Cod [CHANGED \u2014 Proposal D: miso glaze moves off salmon to black cod] Miso-Glazed Sablefish (Black Cod) + Bok Choy + Rice - Protein: Black cod marinated in white miso and mirin \u2014 the Nobu classic - Veg: Steamed bok choy with sesame - Starch: Steamed rice</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Fish Tacos: West Coast Done Right Baja Fish Tacos with Cabbage Slaw and Chipotle Crema - Protein: Beer-battered or grilled white fish - Starch: Fresh corn tortillas - Slaw: Cabbage with lime and crema</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Crudo: Raw Fish Technique Four Crudi: Italian, Japanese, Peruvian, Nordic Styles - Focus: Fish quality evaluation, knife techniques for raw fish, four acid/oil/salt profiles</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Cioppino [CHANGED \u2014 Proposal F: replaces duplicate bouillabaisse] San Francisco-Style Cioppino (American Seafood Stew) - Protein: Mixed seafood \u2014 clams, mussels, shrimp, fish - Broth: Tomato-based (distinct from bouillabaisse's saffron/fennel profile) - Starch: Grilled sourdough for dipping</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-2122-whole-fish-curing-advanced-seafood-new-content-proposal-b","title":"Weeks 21\u201322: Whole Fish, Curing &amp; Advanced Seafood (NEW CONTENT \u2014 Proposal B)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Fabricating and Presenting a Whole Fish (optional) Cold session: scaling, gutting, and scoring three whole fish; discussion of freshness markers</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Whole Roasted Branzino or Sea Bass Herb-Stuffed Whole Roasted Branzino + Roasted Fennel + Lemon Aioli - Protein: Whole fish, cavity filled with herbs and lemon, roasted at high heat - Veg: Roasted fennel wedges with olive oil - Sauce: Homemade aioli</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Salt-Baked Whole Fish Salt-Baked Sea Bream + Salsa Verde - Protein: Whole fish encased in salt crust \u2014 different from scoring and roasting - Sauce: Italian salsa verde (parsley, capers, anchovies, olive oil) - Starch: Grilled bread</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Gravlax: Salt-Curing as Preservation [NEW \u2014 Proposal: fills charcuterie gap in fish context] Gravlax + Cr\u00e8me Fra\u00eeche + Cucumber-Dill Salad - Protein: Salmon fillet cured in salt, sugar, and dill for 48 hours - This session starts 2 days before it's served* - Accompaniment: Rye bread, cr\u00e8me fra\u00eeche, pickled cucumber - Note:** Teaches the same curing logic as the charcuterie block but applied to fish</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 Whole Grilled Fish over Charcoal Spatchcocked Whole Red Snapper + Nam Prik (Thai Chili Sauce) - Protein: Whole snapper grilled direct over coal - Sauce: Thai-style chile relish - Starch: Sticky rice</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 PROJECT: The Whole Fish Dinner Party Five-course whole-fish dinner: cured appetizer \u2192 broth \u2192 crudo \u2192 roasted whole fish \u2192 dessert</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Shellfish: Clams, Mussels &amp; Oysters Mussels Marini\u00e8re + Oysters Mignonette + Clam Chowder (New England) - Protein: Three shellfish, three techniques \u2014 steamed, raw, chowder - Starch: Grilled bread for mussels; oyster crackers for chowder</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Lobster &amp; Crab: Breaking Down and Cooking Steamed Lobster + Drawn Butter + Crab Cakes - Protein: Live lobster steamed; Dungeness or blue crab picked for cakes - Sauce: Brown butter, remoulade - Starch: New potatoes with parsley butter</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Scallops: Searing to a Perfect Crust Seared Scallops + Pea Pur\u00e9e + Crispy Pancetta - Protein: Dry-packed scallops seared to a mahogany crust - Veg: Smooth pea pur\u00e9e - Garnish: Rendered pancetta, micro herbs</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: The Grand Seafood Platter Fruits de Mer \u2014 a cold and room-temperature seafood selection for four to six - Protein: Oysters, shrimp cocktail, crab, smoked salmon (gravlax from Session 4), pickled mussels - Sauces: Mignonette, cocktail, aioli, lemon butter</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-2526-pork-minor-modifications-proposal-e-removes-pork-chop-pan-sauce-duplicate-keep-here","title":"Weeks 25\u201326: Pork (minor modifications \u2014 Proposal E removes pork chop + pan sauce duplicate; keep here)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Perfect Pork Chop + Pan Sauce Pork Chop with Sauce Charcuti\u00e8re + Mustard Greens - Protein: Thick bone-in pork chop, reverse-seared or pan-to-oven - Sauce: Sauce charcuti\u00e8re (mustard + gherkin Pan sauce \u2014 CIA derivative) - Veg: Braised mustard greens [CHANGED from generic side]</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Pork Tenderloin: Speed and Precision Pork Tenderloin Roulade with Spinach and Prosciutto - Protein: Butterflied tenderloin, stuffed and tied, roasted - Starch: Lentilles du Puy - Veg: Roasted root vegetables</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Vietnamese Grilled Pork Chop (Th\u1ecbt Heo N\u01b0\u1edbng) Grilled Pork Chop + Broken Rice (C\u01a1m T\u1ea5m) + Pickled Daikon - Protein: Lemongrass-marinated pork chop, charred on grill - Starch: Broken rice - Veg: Pickled daikon and cucumber</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Pork Belly: Pan-Crispy Crispy Pork Belly + Pickled Apple Slaw + Grain Mustard - Protein: 3-hour braise then hard sear \u2014 maximum contrast - Veg: Apple and cabbage slaw - Starch: Potato r\u00f6sti [CHANGED \u2014 uses potato technique from 11-12]</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 Porchetta: Italian Pork at Its Peak Porchetta + Polenta + Roasted Peppers - Protein: Pork belly/shoulder rolled with herbs, roasted - Starch: Creamy polenta - Veg: Marinated roasted peppers</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Pork Meatballs: Ground Pork Technique Pork and Fennel Meatballs in Tomato Sauce - Protein: Fennel-seasoned ground pork meatballs, simmered in tomato sauce - Starch: Spaghetti</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 PROJECT: Carnitas and the Whole Shoulder Taco Dinner Carnitas + Corn Tortillas + Salsa Bar - Protein: Pork shoulder, lard-braised until pull-apart tender - Starch: Corn tortillas - Condiments: Pico de gallo, pickled jalape\u00f1os, crema, guacamole</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-2728-charcuterie-garde-manger-proposals-n-o-duck-confit-promoted-chicken-liver-pate-added","title":"Weeks 27\u201328: Charcuterie &amp; Garde Manger (Proposals N, O: duck confit promoted; chicken liver p\u00e2t\u00e9 added)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Duck Confit (Full Session) [CHANGED \u2014 Proposal N: duck made the lead session] Duck Confit + Lentilles du Puy + Fris\u00e9e Salad - Protein: Duck legs cured and slow-rendered in fat \u2014 the original preservation method - Starch: Green lentils with shallots and Dijon - Salad: Fris\u00e9e with warm lardons vinaigrette</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Duck Rillettes and Duck Liver Mousse Rillettes on Rye + Duck Liver Mousse on Toast - Protein: Pulled confit duck packed in its own fat (rillettes) - Offal: Duck liver mousse \u2014 smooth, enriched with butter</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Sausage Making Fundamentals Pork and Fennel Sausage + Braised Lentils - Protein: Ground pork, seasoned, stuffed into natural casings - Starch: Braised beluga lentils</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Chicken Liver P\u00e2t\u00e9 [NEW \u2014 Proposal O: offal/variety meats] Chicken Liver P\u00e2t\u00e9 + Cornichons + Dijon + Toasted Baguette - Protein: Smooth chicken liver p\u00e2t\u00e9 \u2014 butter-enriched, port-finished - Accompaniment: Cornichons, grain mustard, sliced baguette</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Charcuterie Board Complete Cured Board: rillettes, chicken liver p\u00e2t\u00e9, cured meats, pickles, condiments, bread</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Quick Pickles &amp; Lacto-Fermented Vegetables Lacto-Fermented Vegetables + Quick Pickle Plate - Focus: Sauerkraut-style lacto (3-day), quick pickle (same-day), brine ratios</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Country-Style Terrine (P\u00e2t\u00e9 de Campagne) P\u00e2t\u00e9 de Campagne Sliced + Chutney + Cornichons - Protein: Ground pork, pork liver, fatback, herbs \u2014 pressed and sliced cold</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Pancetta and Cured Belly Pancetta Tesa + Pasta all'Amatriciana - Protein: Flat-cured pancetta \u2014 salt, spice, cure 2 weeks - Recipe using it: Amatriciana (pasta after the cure project starts)</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Module 3 Capstone: Skills Inventory Cook the best thing you've made in Module 3 \u2014 no restrictions</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Complete Cured Meat and Duck Tasting Self-curated tasting of 6+ preparations made across the block</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#module-4-worlds-kitchens","title":"Module 4: World's Kitchens","text":""},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-2930-french-unchanged-beurre-blanc-already-present-sessions-already-distinctive","title":"Weeks 29\u201330: French (unchanged \u2014 beurre blanc already present; sessions already distinctive)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 French Onion Soup (contextually appropriate \u2014 not redundant with 01-02 knife drill) Session 2 \u2014 Hollandaise and Eggs Benedict (contextually appropriate \u2014 classic French bistro entry) Session 3 \u2014 B\u00e9arnaise Sauce with Steak Session 4 \u2014 Steak Frites Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Bouillabaisse [NOTE: bouillabaisse was moved to 07-08 as the canonical session \u2014 this project becomes Brandade de Morue (salt cod gratin) instead] Brandade de Morue + Crusty Bread + Ni\u00e7oise Salad Session 6 \u2014 Beurre Blanc (White Butter Sauce) Session 7 \u2014 Duck \u00e0 l'Orange (duck now also studied in 17-18; this is the French restaurant version) Session 8 \u2014 Souffl\u00e9 (Cheese or Chocolate) Session 9 \u2014 French Bistro Dinner Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Le Grand A\u00efoli (Provence-Style)</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-3132-italian-proposal-g-mushroom-risotto-replaced-gnocchi-removed-already-in-13-14","title":"Weeks 31\u201332: Italian (Proposal G: mushroom risotto replaced; gnocchi removed \u2014 already in 13-14)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Cacio e Pepe (Advanced Review) [CHANGED \u2014 Proposal G: replaces duplicate mushroom risotto] Cacio e Pepe + Suppl\u00ec al Telefono (Fried Risotto Balls) - Main: Cacio e pepe at full technical depth \u2014 the Italian perspective on pasta water sauce - Second: Suppl\u00ec (fried leftover risotto from any prior session)</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Minestrone (The Full Version) Minestrone + Ribollita Bread - Main: Full-body minestrone with seasonal vegetables and cannellini - Bread: Reheated ribollita bread from prior prep</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Lasagna al Forno [CHANGED \u2014 Proposal: gnocchi removed; lasagna added to fill the pasta gap] Classic Bologna Lasagna (Rag\u00f9 + B\u00e9chamel) - Main: Layered lasagna \u2014 homemade pasta sheets (review), Bolognese rag\u00f9, b\u00e9chamel, parmigiano - Salad: Arugula and shaved parmesan</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Ribollita (Tuscan Bean Bread Soup) Ribollita + Salted White Bean Bruschetta - Main: Two-day ribollita \u2014 thickened, reheated, finished with olive oil</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Pan-Roasted Whole Branzino + Tiramisu Session 6 \u2014 Pasta Fresca (Fresh Egg Pasta) Pappardelle with Wild Boar or Mushroom Rag\u00f9 Session 7 \u2014 Spaghetti alle Vongole Spaghetti alle Vongole in Bianco Session 8 \u2014 Saltimbocca alla Romana Veal Saltimbocca + Wilted Spinach + Roast Potatoes Session 9 \u2014 A Complete Italian Sunday Dinner Antipasto \u2192 Primo (pasta) \u2192 Secondo (meat) \u2192 Dolce Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Italian Sunday Dinner (Learner-Planned)</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-3334-korea-new-block-proposal-c-replaces-duplicate-japanese-block","title":"Weeks 33\u201334: Korea (NEW BLOCK \u2014 Proposal C: replaces duplicate Japanese block)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 The Korean Pantry (optional) Cold session: taste and identify gochujang, doenjang, ganjang, fish sauce, sesame oil, dried chiles</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Bibimbap: The Stone Bowl Dolsot Bibimbap + Banchan (Three Side Dishes) - Main: Rice, namul (seasoned vegetables), egg, gochujang \u2014 assembled in hot stone bowl - Sides: Kongnamul (bean sprout), sigeumchi (spinach), japchae (preview of next session)</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Japchae (Glass Noodle Stir-Fry) Japchae + Gyeran Mari (Rolled Egg) + Steamed Rice - Main: Glass noodles stir-fried with vegetables and beef strips in sesame soy - Accompaniment: Rolled egg (Korean variation on tamagoyaki)</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Doenjang Jjigae (Fermented Soybean Stew) Doenjang Jjigae + Steamed Rice + Quick Kimchi - Main: Earthy, fermented soybean paste stew with tofu and zucchini - Side: Quick-pickle kimchi (demonstrates the fermented pantry)</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 Korean BBQ Fundamentals Bulgogi + Galbi + Banchan Spread - Protein: Bulgogi (sweet-soy beef) and galbi (short rib) marinated and grilled at the table or on cast iron - Starch: Steamed short-grain rice in lettuce wraps - Banchan: At least four items (kimchi, pickled vegetables, spinach, egg)</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 PROJECT: Full Korean BBQ Spread Complete Korean BBQ dinner for four, plated with full banchan selection</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Korean Fried Chicken (Double-Fry Technique) Korean Fried Chicken (Two Ways: Soy-Garlic + Yangnyeom) - Protein: Double-fried chicken \u2014 first fry renders fat, second fry crisps; two sauce styles - Starch: White rice and pickled radish (danmuji)</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Tteokbokki (Spicy Rice Cakes) Tteokbokki + Odeng Fish Cake Skewers - Main: Chewy rice cakes in gochujang and fish stock sauce - Accompaniment: Boiled fish cake skewers (odeng tang)</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Kimchi: Making Your Own Napa Cabbage Kimchi (Baechu-Kimchi) from Scratch - Focus: Salt-wilting, paste construction (gochugaru, fish sauce, garlic, ginger), packing, fermentation timeline - Meal: Simple rice with fresh kimchi immediately + aged kimchi from a previous batch</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Modern Korean Dinner Party Three-course Korean dinner: cold naengmyeon or jeon starter \u2192 main course \u2192 dessert (bingsu) - Starter: Haemul Pajeon (seafood scallion pancake) - Main: Learner's choice from the block - Dessert: Bingsu (shaved ice with red bean and tteok) or Hotteok (sweet pancake)</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-3536-chinese-unchanged-sessions-already-unique","title":"Weeks 35\u201336: Chinese (unchanged \u2014 sessions already unique)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 The Wok: Heat, Motion, and Wok Hei Session 2 \u2014 Red-Braised Pork Belly (Hong Shao Rou) Session 3 \u2014 Cantonese Steamed Fish Session 4 \u2014 Mapo Tofu Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Sichuan Dinner Session 6 \u2014 Congee (Rice Porridge) Session 7 \u2014 Dim Sum at Home: Har Gow (Shrimp Dumplings) Session 8 \u2014 Chinese Egg Fried Rice Session 9 \u2014 Hot and Sour Soup Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Full Chinese Banquet (for 4\u20136)</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-3738-mexican-unchanged","title":"Weeks 37\u201338: Mexican (unchanged)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Carne Asada Session 2 \u2014 Pozole Rojo Session 3 \u2014 Guacamole + Salsa Verde (The Fundamentals) Session 4 \u2014 Tacos al Pastor Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Enchiladas + Red Chile Sauce Session 6 \u2014 Birria de Res (Beef Birria) Session 7 \u2014 Mole Negro (Simplified) Session 8 \u2014 Tamales (Team Project) Session 9 \u2014 Chiles Rellenos Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Full Mexican Celebration Dinner</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-3940-indian-unchanged","title":"Weeks 39\u201340: Indian (unchanged)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Butter Chicken (Murgh Makhani) Session 2 \u2014 Moong Dal (Yellow Split Lentils) Session 3 \u2014 Chicken Tikka Masala (Grilled Version) Session 4 \u2014 Lamb Biryani Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: North Indian Feast Session 6 \u2014 Chana Masala (Chickpea Curry) Session 7 \u2014 Aloo Gobi (Potato and Cauliflower) Session 8 \u2014 Dosa and South Indian Fundamentals Session 9 \u2014 Garam Masala from Scratch + Spice Inventory (cross-trains with 09-10 spice blends session) Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: South Indian Weekend</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-4142-middle-eastern-unchanged","title":"Weeks 41\u201342: Middle Eastern (unchanged)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Hummus b'Tahini (From Scratch) Session 2 \u2014 Shakshuka (contextually appropriate here \u2014 the Middle Eastern version; 01-02 version was a knife drill) Session 3 \u2014 Baba Ghanoush + Muhammara Session 4 \u2014 Falafel Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Beef Shawarma Session 6 \u2014 Adana Kebab (Turkish Ground Lamb Skewer) Session 7 \u2014 Fattoush + Tabbouleh Session 8 \u2014 Persian-Style Herb Frittata (Kuku Sabzi) Session 9 \u2014 Kabsa (Saudi Spiced Chicken and Rice) Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Full Mezze Table</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#module-5-mastery-pastry","title":"Module 5: Mastery &amp; Pastry","text":""},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-4546-desserts-unchanged-in-structure","title":"Weeks 45\u201346: Desserts (unchanged in structure)","text":"<p>Sessions TBD \u2014 block to be developed.</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-4748-pastry-proposal-m-dessert-sauces-added","title":"Weeks 47\u201348: Pastry (Proposal M: dessert sauces added)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 P\u00e2te Sucr\u00e9e (Sweet Tart Dough) Lemon Tart in P\u00e2te Sucr\u00e9e Shell - Crust: 3-2-1 ratio sweet dough, blind-baked - Filling: Lemon curd (first custard)</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Pastry Cream (Cr\u00e8me P\u00e2tissi\u00e8re) \u00c9clair with Pastry Cream + Chocolate Glaze - Dough: Choux pastry - Filling: Classic pastry cream (teaches egg-thickened custard)</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Tarte Tatin Tarte Tatin with Cr\u00e8me Fra\u00eeche - Dough: Basic pie dough (3-2-1) - Filling: Caramelized apple \u2014 teaches wet caramel technique</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Choux Pastry Profiteroles + Chocolate Sauce (first dessert sauce) - Dough: Choux - Dessert Sauce: Ganache-style chocolate sauce \u2014 first formal dessert sauce</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Mille-Feuille (Napoleon) Mille-feuille with Pastry Cream and Raspberry Coulis - Dough: Blitz puff pastry - Sauce: Raspberry coulis \u2014 second formal dessert sauce</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Caramel: Wet and Dry Methods Salted Caramel Sauce + Praline + Tarte Tatin Revisited - Focus: Dry caramel (no water, direct melt) vs. wet caramel (water + invert sugar) - Output: Caramel sauce, praline, spun sugar demonstration</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e Classic Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e - Technique: Baked custard, water bath, torch technique</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Panna Cotta Vanilla Panna Cotta + Three Sauces: Caramel, Coulis, Sabayon - Technique: Cold-set cream \u2014 the contrast to baked custard - Sauces: Three review sauces plated alongside to compare</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Chocolate Mousse Dark Chocolate Mousse + Raspberry Coulis - Technique: Egg-foam set mousse; teaches sabayon within the mousse</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 Dessert Sauces: The Builder's Toolkit [NEW \u2014 Proposal M] Five Dessert Sauces Made and Plated in One Session - Sauce 1: Classic caramel (wet method) - Sauce 2: Ganache (chocolate + cream ratio \u2014 hard vs. soft) - Sauce 3: Sabayon/zabaglione (egg-based, served warm) - Sauce 4: Raspberry coulis (fruit + acid + sugar) - Sauce 5: Cr\u00e8me anglaise (pouring custard) - Exercise: Plate the same vanilla ice cream with each sauce \u2014 discuss contrast, weight, and balance</p> <p>Session 11 \u2014 PROJECT: Layer Cake Vanilla Sponge \u2192 Pastry Cream Filling \u2192 Italian Buttercream \u2192 Chocolate Ganache Glaze - Applies: Sponge, pastry cream, buttercream, ganache \u2014 all techniques from the block</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-4950-signature-dishes-unchanged","title":"Weeks 49\u201350: Signature Dishes (unchanged)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Advanced Wok Technique Session 2 \u2014 Knife Skills: Where Are You Now? Session 3 \u2014 The Best Chocolate Chip Cookie (Refinement) Session 4 \u2014 The Caramel Sauce (Perfection) Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: The Dish You Haven't Perfected Yet Session 6 \u2014 Define Your Signature Dishes Session 7\u20138 \u2014 Refine Signatures #1 and #2 Session 9 \u2014 Develop a New Recipe Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: The Personal Tasting Menu</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#weeks-5152-final-exam-unchanged","title":"Weeks 51\u201352: Final Exam (unchanged)","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Menu Design Theory Session 2 \u2014 The Make-Ahead Audit Session 3 \u2014 Timing Under Pressure Session 4 \u2014 Dinner Party #1: Small Table Session 5 \u2014 Post-Dinner Debrief Session 6 \u2014 Scaling Recipes Session 7 \u2014 The Art of Mise en Place for Groups Session 8 \u2014 Wine and Beverage Pairing Basics Session 9 \u2014 Final Prep Day Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Dinner Party #2 \u2014 The Full Table Session 11 \u2014 Skills Inventory Session 12 \u2014 The Forgotten Dish Session 13 \u2014 Cook Something From Memory Session 14 \u2014 The Final Mise en Place Drill Session 15 \u2014 PROJECT: The Anniversary Dinner Session 16 \u2014 Define the Exam for Yourself Session 17 \u2014 Cook the Final Exam Dish Session 18 \u2014 The Retrospective Meal Session 19 \u2014 The Open Kitchen Session 20 \u2014 Week 52: The Final Dinner</p>"},{"location":"program-overview-proposed.html#summary-of-all-changes-applied","title":"Summary of All Changes Applied","text":"Block Change Proposal Weeks 3\u20134 Heat Session 4 expanded to include en papillote + court bouillon K Weeks 5\u20136 Sauces Session 3 (Tomato) added; Session 6 (Beurre Blanc + Compound Butters) added; crispy salmon moved here as sole occurrence D, J Weeks 7\u20138 Stocks Soup Architecture promoted to Session 1 (required); Risotto Milanese replaces mushroom risotto; bouillabaisse stays as sole occurrence F, G, H Weeks 9\u201310 Seasoning Session 9 (Spice Blends &amp; Marinades) added L Weeks 11\u201312 Vegetables Session 1 (Potato Techniques) replaces optional pur\u00e9es session; Legumes session expanded I Weeks 13\u201314 Pasta Session 5 (Osso Buco over Risotto Milanese) replaces duplicate short ribs; Session 6 (Risotto alle Vongole) replaces duplicate mushroom risotto; Sessions 7\u20138 (flavored doughs, spaetzle) added E, G Weeks 15\u201316 Beef Content consolidated from duplicate 17\u201318 block; short ribs replaced with pot roast + rouladen A, E Weeks 17\u201318 NEW: Lamb &amp; Game block (braised shanks, navarin, rack, leg, kebabs, duck confit, duck breast) A, N Weeks 19\u201320 Fish Differentiated to Flatfish &amp; Round Fish only; miso glaze moved to black cod; bouillabaisse removed (\u2192 cioppino) B, D, F Weeks 21\u201322 NEW: Whole Fish, Curing &amp; Advanced Seafood (gravlax, whole fish methods, all shellfish) B Weeks 25\u201326 Pork Sauce charcuti\u00e8re replaces generic pan sauce; potato r\u00f6sti added as side P Weeks 27\u201328 Charcuterie Duck confit promoted to Session 1; duck liver mousse added; chicken liver p\u00e2t\u00e9 added N, O Weeks 29\u201330 French Bouillabaisse project replaced with Brandade de Morue F Weeks 31\u201332 Italian Mushroom risotto replaced with Cacio e Pepe; gnocchi replaced with Lasagna al Forno G Weeks 33\u201334 NEW: Korea block (bibimbap, japchae, doenjang jjigae, Korean BBQ, fried chicken, kimchi) C Weeks 47\u201348 Pastry Session 10 (Dessert Sauces: caramel, ganache, sabayon, coulis, cr\u00e8me anglaise) added M All blocks Side dishes diversified throughout \u2014 grain salads, warm salads, pilaf, braised sides replace generic rotation P <p>Proposed overview only \u2014 no curriculum files were modified. See <code>curriculum-proposals.md</code> for full justification of each change.</p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html","title":"The 52-Week Culinary Project \u2014 Full Program Overview","text":"<p>Every block, every session, every meal \u2014 with components at a glance.</p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#module-1-foundational-skills","title":"Module 1: Foundational Skills","text":""},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-12-knife-skills","title":"Weeks 1\u20132: Knife Skills","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 The Pinch Grip Pasta with Butter and Parmesan - Main: Parmesan-crusted pasta - Veg: Wilted baby spinach, saut\u00e9ed in the pasta pan with olive oil, garlic, and lemon</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 The Claw The Best Chicken Noodle Soup - Protein: Chicken breast \u2014 poach in the broth (or sous vide if you have one), then dice - Veg: Onion (charred, per recipe) into the stock; your diced carrot and celery into the soup for last 10 minutes - Starch: Egg noodles, cooked seperately</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Rock Chop vs. Push Cut Shrimp Scampi - Protein: Shrimp, saut\u00e9ed in garlic butter and white wine - Veg/Salad: Arugula, Fennel &amp; Orange Salad - Starch: Crusty bread or linguine</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Mise en Place Stir-Fried Beef and Broccoli - Protein: Thinly sliced flank steak, seared in very small batches - Veg: Broccoli florets, seared in the same pan - Starch: Steamed jasmine rice, started before you begin the stir-fry</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: French Onion Soup French Onion Soup (Soupe \u00e0 l'Oignon) </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 The Julienne The Best Pad Thai - Protein: Shrimp, chicken, or tofu - Veg: Your julienned carrots and scallions, plus bean sprouts; finish with fresh basil chiffonade - Starch: Rice noodles, soaked per the recipe</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 The Dice (Small, Medium, Large) Home Fries + Pan-Seared Crispy Chicken Thighs - Protein: Crispy pan-seared bone-in chicken thighs - Veg/Salad: Classic Green Salad with Vinaigrette - Starch: Home fries (your dice drill is the recipe)</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Breaking Down a Whole Chicken Chicken Piccata (use the breasts) + Burst Cherry Tomatoes - Protein: Chicken piccata using the breasts you broke down - Veg: Burst Cherry Tomatoes with Garlic and Olive Oil - Starch: Linguine \u2014 toss with the burst tomatoes and a splash of pasta water</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Speed Benchmark Shakshuka + leftover chicken from earlier in the block thighs (warmed in a skillet) - Protein: Eggs poached in the shakshuka sauce + leftover chicken from earlier in the block thighs - Veg: Onion, bell pepper, tomatoes (the shakshuka base) - Starch: Crusty bread for dipping</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Proven\u00e7al Vegetable Tian Proven\u00e7al Summer Vegetable Tian + crusty bread - Protein: Optional \u2014 serve with good burrata or a soft-boiled egg on top - Veg: The tian (eggplant, zucchini, squash, tomato) - Starch: Crusty baguette</p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-34-heat-and-cooking","title":"Weeks 3\u20134: Heat And Cooking","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Saut\u00e9: Hot Pan, Don't Crowd Saut\u00e9ed Chicken Breasts with Quick Pan Sauce + Saut\u00e9ed Zucchini with Garlic and Herbs + Steamed Rice - Protein: Saut\u00e9ed boneless chicken breast, finished with a quick pan sauce of shallot, white wine, and butter - Veg: Saut\u00e9ed zucchini \u2014 notice how a hot pan gives you color on the outside while keeping the inside tender - Starch: Steamed jasmine rice</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Roasting: Hot Oven, Dry Surface Sheet Pan Chicken Thighs with Roasted Vegetables + Simple Green Salad - Protein: Bone-in skin-on chicken thighs, roasted until crackling - Veg: Whatever is on the sheet pan \u2014 broccoli, potatoes, onions - Salad: Simple green salad alongside</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Braising: Low, Slow, Wet Braised Chicken Thighs with Tomatoes and Capers + Crusty bread or polenta - Protein: Braised chicken thighs in a rich tomato-caper sauce - Starch: Crusty bread to mop the sauce, or polenta</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Steaming and Poaching: Gentle, Wet Heat Perfect Poached Salmon + Steamed Bok Choy with Garlic Sauce + Steamed rice - Protein: Gently poached salmon \u2014 silky, delicate, nothing like a seared fillet - Veg: Steamed bok choy, dressed simply with garlic and sesame - Starch: Steamed rice</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Spatchcocked Roast Chicken Spatchcocked Roast Chicken + Roasted Potatoes + Simple Green Salad with Vinaigrette </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Searing Steak: The Art of Doing Nothing Perfect Pan-Seared Steak with Butter Basting + Creamy Mashed Potatoes + Simple Saut\u00e9ed Green Beans - Protein: Ribeye or NY strip, pan-seared in cast iron, basted in butter, thyme, and garlic - Starch: Ultra-creamy mashed potatoes (use more butter than you're comfortable with) - Veg: Green beans saut\u00e9ed in the steak pan drippings</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 High-Heat Fish: Crispy Skin Without Fear Crispy Pan-Seared Salmon + Roasted Asparagus + Simple Arugula and Fennel Salad - Protein: Crispy-skinned salmon fillet, finished with lemon and capers - Veg: Roasted asparagus (high-heat oven, single layer, very dry) - Salad: Arugula salad alongside</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Broiling: Overhead Heat Broiled Salmon with Miso Glaze + Saut\u00e9ed Bok Choy + Steamed rice - Protein: Miso-glazed salmon under the broiler \u2014 8 minutes, no flipping needed - Veg: Saut\u00e9ed or steamed bok choy - Starch: Steamed rice</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Recap Cook: No Recipes Braised Short Ribs + Creamy Polenta + Roasted Root Vegetables - Protein: Bone-in beef short ribs braised in red wine and beef stock until they collapse - Starch: Creamy parmesan polenta (the perfect landing pad for the braising liquid) - Veg: Roasted root vegetables (carrots, parsnips, turnips)</p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-56-mother-sauces","title":"Weeks 5\u20136: Mother Sauces","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 B\u00e9chamel: The White Sauce Baked Mac and Cheese (B\u00e9chamel-Based) + Simple Green Salad - Main: Baked mac and cheese (the whole dish) - Starch: Pasta (built-in) - Salad: Simple green salad to cut through the richness</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Velout\u00e9: Stock Instead of Milk Chicken Pot Pie with Velout\u00e9 Base + Simple green salad - Protein: Chicken (cooked and pulled into the filling) - Starch: The pastry crust - Veg: Peas, carrots, and onion in the filling - Salad: Simple green salad alongside - Protein: Ground beef and pork, slow-cooked into the sauce - Starch: Fresh tagliatelle or good dried pasta - Veg: Mirepoix (in the sauce) + Classic Caesar Salad alongside</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Espagnole and Demi-Glace (Simplified) Steak with Red Wine Pan Sauce + Creamy Mashed Potatoes + Roasted Broccolini - Protein: Pan-seared steak with a red wine reduction pan sauce - Starch: Ultra-creamy mashed potatoes - Veg: Roasted broccolini - Protein: Ground lamb or beef in the tomato layer - Sauce: B\u00e9chamel on top, baked to a golden crust - Veg: Roasted eggplant and potato layers - Salad: Greek salad alongside</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Hollandaise: The Emulsion Eggs Benedict with Hollandaise \u2014 yes, breakfast for dinner. It's legitimate when it teaches you hollandaise. - Protein: Canadian bacon, poached eggs - Sauce: Hollandaise (your skill for tonight) - Starch: English muffins, toasted - Veg/Salad: Simple Watercress Salad alongside</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Mayonnaise: Emulsion Without Heat Seafood Rolls with Homemade Mayo + Classic Coleslaw - Protein: Shrimp, scallop, or lobster roll - Veg: Coleslaw made with your homemade mayo - Starch: Brioche or potato rolls</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 The Vinaigrette: A Temporary Emulsion Pan-Seared Salmon Ni\u00e7oise Salad \u2014 a full composed dinner salad, not a side. - Protein: Seared salmon or tuna - Veg: Green beans, olives, tomatoes, hard-boiled eggs - Starch: Boiled potatoes (dressed warm with the vinaigrette \u2014 they absorb it better)</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Pan Sauce: The Working Sauce Pork Chops with Apple-Cider Pan Sauce + Roasted Sweet Potatoes + Simple Green Salad - Protein: Pan-seared pork chops with apple-cider pan sauce - Starch: Roasted sweet potatoes - Salad: Simple green salad with your from-scratch vinaigrette</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Classic French Bistro Dinner (3 Courses) - Course: Dish - *Starter*: French Onion Dip with Homemade Potato Chips - *Main*: Steak Frites with Pan Sauce - *Salad*: Classic Lyonnaise Salad (Fris\u00e9e aux Lardons)</p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-78-stocks-and-eggs","title":"Weeks 7\u20138: Stocks And Eggs","text":"<p>Session 0 \u2014 Soup Architecture (optional) Roasted Butternut Squash Soup + crusty bread + simple salad - Family: Technique - *Broth/consomm\u00e9*: Clear liquid, flavored by solids - *Pur\u00e9e*: Cooked vegetables blended smooth; no cream needed - *Cream soup*: Pur\u00e9e + cream or b\u00e9chamel for richness and texture - *Bisque*: Shellfish shells simmered into the base; always cream-finished - *Chowder*: Chunky; potato base; salt pork/bacon; cream-finished</p> <p>Session 1 \u2014 Chicken Stock from Scratch Quick Weeknight Ramen Using Homemade Stock - Broth: Your homemade chicken stock, seasoned with soy and mirin - Protein: Soft-boiled eggs, chashu pork or rotisserie chicken, scallions - Starch: Ramen noodles</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Pan Sauces from Real Stock Chicken with Rich Pan Sauce (using your homemade stock) + Roasted Potatoes + Bitter Greens Salad - Protein: Saut\u00e9ed chicken with a pan sauce made from your Block 7 stock - Starch: Crispy roasted potatoes - Salad: Bitter greens salad with a sharp vinaigrette</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Fish Stock + Fumet Bouillabaisse \u2014 the classic Proven\u00e7al fish stew, built on your fresh fish stock - Protein: Mixed seafood \u2014 shrimp, clams, white fish - Stock: Your fresh fish fumet - Starch: Grilled bread rubbed with garlic (rouille on the side) - Veg: Fennel, leek, tomato in the stew</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Vegetable Stock + Risotto Parmesan Risotto + Roasted Mushrooms + Simple Arugula Salad - Protein: Roasted mushrooms (the star) + parmesan as umami - Starch: Risotto (the main dish) - Salad: Arugula alongside to cut richness</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Whole Soup Kitchen Day - Time: Task - Morning: Big batch beef/veal stock (6\u20138 hrs, mostly passive) - Dinner: French Onion Soup using your fresh beef stock - Sides: Simple Green Salad + good bread</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 The French Scramble French Scrambled Eggs + Smoked Salmon with Cr\u00e8me Fra\u00eeche + Toasted Sourdough + Simple Green Salad - Protein: French scrambled eggs + smoked salmon - Starch: Toasted sourdough - Salad: Simple green salad</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 The Perfect Poached Egg Poached Eggs Over Saut\u00e9ed Greens with Crispy Bacon + Roasted Tomatoes + Toasted bread - Protein: Poached eggs + crispy bacon - Veg: Wilted greens (kale or spinach), roasted cherry tomatoes - Starch: Good toast</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 The Omelette The French Omelette + Classic Green Salad + Crusty bread - Protein: Two omelettes (one per person or two attempts) - Filling: Gruy\u00e8re, herbs, or mushrooms - Salad: Classic green salad with vinaigrette - Starch: Crusty bread</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Custard: Eggs as Thickener \u2014 Quiche Lorraine - Quiche Lorraine (lardons + Gruy\u00e8re + chive) - Shell: Store-bought shortcrust \u2014 pastry dough is covered fully in Block 47 - Custard: 3 eggs + \u00be cup heavy cream + salt + white pepper - Cheese: Gruy\u00e8re grated fresh; pre-shredded bags have coatings that prevent clean melting - Bake: 325\u00b0F, 30\u201340 min; pull when center still has a gentle wobble</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Complete Egg Dinner Party (3 Courses) - Course: Dish - *Starter*: Deviled Eggs (vehicle for your homemade mayo from Block 6) - *Main*: Shakshuka (scaled up, served family-style with salad and bread) - *Dessert*: Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e (classic baked egg custard, finished with a torch) - Block 1\u20132 time: Today's time - _____ min: _____ min</p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#module-2-building-flavor","title":"Module 2: Building Flavor","text":""},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-910-seasoning-and-flavor","title":"Weeks 9\u201310: Seasoning And Flavor","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Early Salt: Brining Serious Eats \u2014 Crispy-Skinned Chicken Thighs (use your dry-brined thighs) + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Broccoli with Garlic + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Arugula Salad with Lemon Vinaigrette </p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 During Salt: Layered Seasoning Serious Eats \u2014 Pasta all'Amatriciana + Serious Eats \u2014 Classic Caesar Salad </p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Late Salt: Finishing Serious Eats \u2014 Pan-Seared Halibut or Sea Bass with a squeeze of lemon and a pinch of Maldon flakes right at plating + Serious Eats \u2014 White Bean Salad with Olive Oil and Herbs + Serious Eats \u2014 Saut\u00e9ed Cherry Tomatoes </p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Salt as Texture and Contrast Serious Eats \u2014 Cacio e Pepe + Serious Eats \u2014 Bitter Greens Salad with Anchovy Vinaigrette + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Cauliflower with Crispy Capers </p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Salt-Crusted Whole Roasted Fish Serious Eats \u2014 Salt-Crusted Whole Roasted Fish + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Fingerling Potatoes with Herbs + Serious Eats \u2014 Fennel and Orange Salad </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Acid: The Brightness Lever Serious Eats \u2014 Chicken Marsala + Serious Eats \u2014 Creamy Mashed Potatoes + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Green Salad with Sharp Dijon Vinaigrette </p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Different Acids, Different Effects Serious Eats \u2014 Glazed Pork Tenderloin with Balsamic Reduction + Serious Eats \u2014 Lentil Salad with Sherry Vinaigrette + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Carrots with Cumin </p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Fat as Flavor Serious Eats \u2014 Brown Butter Gnocchi with Crispy Sage + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Mushrooms with Thyme + Serious Eats \u2014 Bitter Greens Salad </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Umami: The Depth Dial Serious Eats \u2014 Umami-Packed Mushroom Pasta + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan + Serious Eats \u2014 Arugula Salad with Shaved Parmesan </p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Composed Tasting Plate </p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-1112-vegetables-plant-forward","title":"Weeks 11\u201312: Vegetables Plant Forward","text":"<p>Session 0 \u2014 Two Pur\u00e9es, One Method (optional) Celery root and parsnip pur\u00e9es as the base + seared duck breast or seared scallops on top + a simple green salad - Pur\u00e9e: Method notes - *Celery root (celeriac)*: Sweat in butter, add stock, simmer until completely soft, blend very fine, strain - *Parsnip with roasted garlic*: Roast garlic until golden; simmer parsnips in stock; blend with roasted garlic and butter</p> <p>Session 1 \u2014 Blanching, Shocking, and Color Science Blanched and shocked asparagus + haricots verts + broccolini \u2014 dressed with brown butter and toasted almonds, served at room temperature - Pigment: Vegetable examples - *Chlorophyll* (green): Broccoli, asparagus, spinach, peas - *Anthocyanin* (red/purple): Red cabbage, purple carrots, beets - *Carotenoid* (orange/yellow): Carrots, squash, sweet potato - *Betanin* (deep red): Beets - Vegetables: Asparagus, haricots verts, broccolini \u2014 all blanched and shocked - Dressing: Brown butter + toasted almonds + lemon zest + fleur de sel - Protein (optional): Soft-boiled eggs on top to make it a dinner</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Roasting: Caramelization and Concentration Sheet Pan Dinner \u2014 roasted carrots, cauliflower, and beets with whatever protein you prefer + a tahini dressing or romesco - Vegetables: Carrots (halved), cauliflower (florets), golden beets (quartered) - Dressing: Tahini sauce or romesco - Protein: Chicken thighs on the same pan, or eat vegetarian</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Saut\u00e9, Braise, and the Crucifer Redemption - Crispy Brussels Sprouts with Fish Sauce and Crispy Shallots \u2014 this dish converts Brussels sprout haters - Brussels sprouts: Halved, pressed cut-side into very hot oil; don't move; then toss - Cabbage: Wedges, cast iron, very high heat; miso glaze brushed at the end</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Grilling and Charring: Fire as Flavor A grilled and charred vegetable spread: - Vegetable: Method - Eggplant: Full char over gas flame or under broiler; peel and season - Zucchini: Direct grill, slight char marks, finish with lemon + mint - Scallions: Whole on the grill until charred and collapsed - Peppers: Full char, steam in bag, peel and seed</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Plant-Forward Dinner Party - Course: Dish - *Starter*: Roasted beet salad with whipped feta and pistachios - *Main*: Seared mushroom \"steaks\" + celery root pur\u00e9e + pan sauce from mushroom fond - *Side*: Blanched and shocked green beans with brown butter - *Bread*: Good sourdough</p> <p>Session 0 \u2014 Quick Pickles &amp; First Ferment (optional) Use the pickles tonight on whatever you're eating \u2014 tacos, a grain bowl, grilled fish. Quick pickles don't need a dedicated meal. They improve everything they touch. </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 The Composed Salad: Dressing Is a Technique Caesar salad (full portion, not a side) + half a roast chicken or grilled fish on top + crusty bread - Dressing: Raw egg yolk + anchovy + garlic + lemon + Worcestershire; emulsify with oil - Croutons: Day-old bread, torn not cut; tossed in olive oil; bake until very crispy - Lettuce: Romaine; the spine of the leaf stays crispy even under dressing</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Legumes and Beans: The Forgotten Protein Braised white beans on toast + crispy chickpeas + wilted greens + poached egg on top - White beans: Braised in stock with garlic, rosemary, anchovy - Chickpeas: Crispy-fried in cast iron, paprika + lemon - Greens: Wilted spinach or kale in the bean liquid - Egg (optional): Poached on top to make it a substantial dinner</p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Mushrooms: Umami in Plant Form Mushroom Bourguignon \u2014 the vegetarian version of the French braise, using a mix of cremini, shiitake, and oyster mushrooms + a proper wine reduction - Mushrooms: Mix of varieties; seared separately, then combined - Sauce: Red wine + stock + tomato paste + herbs and aromatics - Base: Creamy mashed potatoes, polenta, or buttered egg noodles</p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 A Completely Vegetable-Driven Main Stuffed roasted peppers (3 colors \u2014 red, yellow, orange) + simple tomato sauce beneath them + salad - Peppers: Halved, par-roasted before stuffing to soften walls - Stuffing: Saut\u00e9ed onion + garlic + cooked farro or rice + cherry tomatoes + parmesan - Sauce beneath: Simple tomato concass\u00e9 or straight from your Week 5 sauce skills</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: The Vegetable Tasting Menu - Course: Dish - 1: Celery root pur\u00e9e with roasted garlic oil - 2: Blanched asparagus with brown butter and fried capers - 3: Charred cabbage with miso-sesame - 4: Mushroom bourguignon on toast - 5: Quick-pickled vegetables + bread</p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-1314-pasta-and-grains","title":"Weeks 13\u201314: Pasta And Grains","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 The Dough: Meeting Gluten Serious Eats \u2014 Homemade Fresh Pasta (basic egg dough, cut into tagliatelle) + Serious Eats \u2014 Slow-Cooked Tomato Sauce (Sugo di Pomodoro) + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Green Salad with Vinaigrette </p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Ravioli: Pasta as a Vessel Serious Eats \u2014 Ricotta-Filled Ravioli with Brown Butter and Sage using the same base dough + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Cherry Tomatoes + Serious Eats \u2014 Radicchio Salad with Anchovy Vinaigrette </p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Gnocchi: Potato and Restraint Serious Eats \u2014 Light and Tender Potato Gnocchi with Sage Butter + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Broccolini with Garlic and Chili + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Green Salad </p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Pasta Water: The Secret Sauce Ingredient Serious Eats \u2014 Spaghetti Aglio e Olio + Serious Eats \u2014 Saut\u00e9ed Spinach with Garlic and Lemon + Serious Eats \u2014 Tomato and Cucumber Salad with Red Onion </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Risotto: Patience as Technique Serious Eats \u2014 Mushroom and Asparagus Risotto + Serious Eats \u2014 Bitter Greens Salad with Walnut and Gorgonzola </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Farro and Grains That Think for Themselves Serious Eats \u2014 Farro Salad with Roasted Beets and Goat Cheese + Serious Eats \u2014 Crispy Pan-Seared Salmon + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Arugula Salad </p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Grain-Forward Dinner Party 1. Starter: Serious Eats \u2014 Whipped Ricotta on Crostini with Honey and Walnuts \u2014 a quick, beautiful opener that requires no cooking </p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-1516-midpoint-review","title":"Weeks 15\u201316: Midpoint Review","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Menu Planning </p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Dry Run: The Most Difficult Component Your chosen dry-run dish + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Green Salad + whatever protein is simplest alongside </p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Knife Speed Benchmark Serious Eats \u2014 Thai-Style Larb (Ground Meat Salad) + Serious Eats \u2014 Jasmine Rice + Serious Eats \u2014 Quick-Pickled Cucumbers </p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Final Prep Day </p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: The Week 13 Dinner </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 High-Heat Whole-Bird Roast Roast chicken + Serious Eats \u2014 The Best Roast Potatoes Ever + simple green salad </p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Spatchcock: Why It Changes Everything Spatchcocked chicken (your own seasoning, not theirs) + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Cauliflower with Pine Nuts, Raisins &amp; Capers + tahdig or rice </p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Braised Poultry: Coq au Vin Coq au Vin + crusty bread + simple green salad (the braise is the whole meal) </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Pan-Seared Chicken Breast + Pan Sauce Pan-seared chicken breast + pan sauce + Serious Eats \u2014 Honey-Roasted Carrots + whatever grain you have </p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#module-3-the-proteins","title":"Module 3: The Proteins","text":""},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-1516-beef-fundamentals","title":"Weeks 15\u201316: Beef Fundamentals","text":""},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-1718-beef-fundamentals","title":"Weeks 17\u201318: Beef Fundamentals","text":"<p>Session 0 \u2014 Beef Fabrication (optional) The short ribs you trim tonight \u2014 braise them tomorrow or this weekend (see Week 16 for the full recipe). Tonight pair with whatever you have: bread and a salad is fine. - Primal: Characteristics - *Chuck* (shoulder): Well-worked muscle, lots of collagen - *Rib*: Less-worked, heavily marbled - *Short loin*: Tender, central back - *Sirloin*: Moderately worked - *Round* (rear leg): Lean, tough - *Brisket* (chest): Very tough, collagen-heavy - *Flank/plate*: Flat, thin, fibrous - *Shank*: Very tough, maximum gelatin</p> <p>Session 1 \u2014 The Dry Brine + Reverse Sear Method Reverse-seared ribeye + Serious Eats \u2014 Rich and Creamy Mashed Potatoes + simple green salad </p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Pan-Seared Strip Steak + Compound Butter Pan-seared strip steak + compound butter + Serious Eats \u2014 Creamed Spinach + crusty bread </p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Burgers: Understanding Ground Beef Smash burgers (double patty) + whatever you feel like alongside \u2014 this is your call </p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Skirt Steak: Thin Cuts &amp; Marination Skirt steak + chimichurri + grilled or roasted peppers + rice or tortillas </p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: The Prime Rib </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Red Wine Braised Short Ribs Braised short ribs + egg noodles or creamy polenta + whatever vegetables are in season </p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Pot Roast: Low and Slow Chuck Pot roast with braising liquid + the vegetables from the braise + whatever bread is around </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Steak au Poivre Steak au Poivre + Serious Eats \u2014 Best Roast Potatoes Ever + grilled asparagus with olive oil and sea salt </p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: The Beef Meal for Four </p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-1920-fish","title":"Weeks 19\u201320: Fish","text":"<p>Session 0 \u2014 Fillet a Whole Fish (optional) Fillet and cook the fish in whatever style you prefer tonight \u2014 the miso glaze is already prepped for later in the block, or use the earlier pan-sear technique (crispy skin pan sear). You've broken it down yourself. That changes how it tastes. </p> <p>Session 1 \u2014 Crispy-Skin Pan-Seared Salmon Crispy skin salmon + herb oil or lemon butter + Serious Eats \u2014 Stir-Fried Garlic Spinach + steamed rice </p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Sole Meuni\u00e8re: The French Lesson Sole meuni\u00e8re + steamed haricots verts or asparagus + crusty bread to catch the sauce </p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 The Universal Crispy Fish Technique Crispy white fish + whatever vegetable you feel like + rice or potatoes </p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Miso-Glazed Salmon: Japanese Technique Miso-glazed salmon + steamed rice + quick pickled cucumbers + wilted bok choy </p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Whole Roasted Fish </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Seared Fish + Mushroom, Asian Style Seared fish with mushrooms + rice + wilted greens </p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Fish Tacos: West Coast Done Right Baja fish tacos + pickled jalape\u00f1os + guacamole or avocado crema + cold beer (optional) </p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Salmon Teriyaki: The Weeknight Standard Teriyaki salmon rice bowl + cucumber + avocado + sesame seeds + pickled ginger </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Whole Grilled Branzino Whole grilled branzino (or snapper) + salsa verde or gremolata + roasted potatoes + salad </p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Bouillabaisse (The Grand Fish Stew) </p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-2122-fish","title":"Weeks 21\u201322: Fish","text":""},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-2526-pork","title":"Weeks 25\u201326: Pork","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Perfect Pork Chop Bone-in pork chop + pan sauce (apple cider or white wine, shallot, thyme) + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Cauliflower with Pine Nuts and Capers + simple salad </p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Pork Tenderloin: Speed and Precision Seared pork tenderloin + herb pan sauce (deglaze with white wine, add thyme, mount with butter) + Serious Eats \u2014 Honey-Roasted Carrots + rice </p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Vietnamese Grilled Pork Chop (Thit Heo Nuong) Grilled pork chops + steamed jasmine rice + nuoc cham dipping sauce + cucumber slices and herbs </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Belly: Pan-Crispy, No 5-Hour Braise Crispy pork belly lardons over white beans and wilted greens + crusty bread </p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Porchetta: Italian Pork at Its Peak Porchetta slices + braised white beans + simple arugula salad with lemon </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Pork Meatballs: Ground Pork Technique Pork meatballs + simple tomato sugo + fresh pasta or spaghetti </p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Carnitas and the Whole Shoulder Taco Dinner </p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-2728-charcuterie-review","title":"Weeks 27\u201328: Charcuterie Review","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Gravlax (Cured Salmon) - Begin gravlax cure \u2014 no dinner from this tonight </p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Sausage Making Fundamentals - Pan-fried merguez with roasted peppers and couscous </p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Taste the Gravlax / Cured Charcuterie Board - Charcuterie board: your gravlax + store-bought cured meats, mustard, cornichons, bread </p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Quick Pickles &amp; Lacto-Fermented Vegetables - Sausage and pickled pepper sandwiches (use leftover merguez or store-bought sausage) </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Pancetta-Style Cured Belly (Start the Project) - Pasta carbonara using store-bought pancetta while yours cures (perfect comparison for next week) </p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Duck or Chicken Rillettes - Chicken rillettes on toast </p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Module 3 Capstone: Six-Month Inventory </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Bacon-Cured Salmon Breakfast Board - Cured salmon breakfast board (brunch-style dinner \u2014 allowable) </p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Complete Cured Meat Tasting + Pancetta Check-In - Curated cured meat tasting board with accompaniments </p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#module-4-worlds-kitchens","title":"Module 4: Worlds Kitchens","text":""},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-2930-french","title":"Weeks 29\u201330: French","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 French Onion Soup - French Onion Soup, properly gratin\u00e9ed with Gruy\u00e8re and a crouton </p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Hollandaise and Eggs Benedict - Eggs Benedict with blender hollandaise </p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 B\u00e9arnaise Sauce with Steak - Pan seared strip or sirloin steak with B\u00e9arnaise sauce </p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Steak Frites - Steak frites: steak of your choice + twice-fried or oven fries </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Beurre Blanc (White Butter Sauce) - Beurre blanc over pan-seared halibut or salmon </p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Duck \u00e0 l'Orange - Duck \u00e0 l'Orange with rendered skin </p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Souffl\u00e9 (Cheese or Chocolate) - Cheese souffl\u00e9 (Gruy\u00e8re + Parmesan) as main </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 French Bistro Dinner - Salad Lyonnaise \u2192 Duck Breast \u2192 Chocolate Mousse </p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Le Grand Aioli (Provence-Style) - Le Grand Aioli: scratch-made garlic aioli + blanched vegetables + hard-boiled eggs + bread + whatever protein you choose </p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-3132-italian","title":"Weeks 31\u201332: Italian","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Mushroom Risotto - Mushroom Risotto (porcini + cremini, ideally) </p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Minestrone (The Full Version) - Minestrone with Parmesan rind broth </p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Ribollita (Tuscan Bean Bread Soup) - Ribollita, ideally made a day ahead and reheated with good olive oil poured on top at the table </p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Pan-Roasted Whole Branzino + Tiramisu - Pan-Roasted Whole Branzino with herbs and lemon </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Gnocchi from Scratch - Gnocchi with brown butter and sage (simplest and best) </p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Pasta Fresca (Fresh Egg Pasta) - Fresh ricotta and spinach ravioli with brown butter or sage cream sauce </p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Spaghetti alle Vongole (Revisited from Italian Perspective) - Spaghetti alle Vongole (the other version from Week 23) </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Saltimbocca alla Romana - Saltimbocca alla Romana </p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Italian Sunday Dinner - Complete 4-course Italian Sunday dinner </p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-3132-japanese","title":"Weeks 31\u201332: Japanese","text":""},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-3334-japanese","title":"Weeks 33\u201334: Japanese","text":"<p>Session 0 \u2014 The Deep Fry: Method Before Recipes (optional) Japanese Karaage + steamed rice + kewpie mayo + lemon + quick cucumber salad - Variable: What it controls - *Oil temperature*: Crust formation speed; steam generation - *Oil volume*: Temperature recovery after adding food - *Batch size*: Temperature drop - *Moisture in food*: Steam (which escapes) vs. oil absorption - *Batter/coating type*: Crust texture and thickness</p> <p>Session 1 \u2014 Dashi (Kombu and Katsuobushi Stock) - Miso soup from your dashi (the simplest application) </p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Tonkatsu (Japanese Breaded Pork Cutlet) - Tonkatsu with shredded cabbage slaw and tonkatsu sauce </p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Tamagoyaki (Japanese Rolled Omelette) - Tamagoyaki with white rice and miso soup (a full Japanese breakfast-style dinner) </p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Tempura - Vegetable and/or shrimp tempura with tentsuyu dipping sauce (dashi + mirin + soy) </p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Oyakodon + Full Japanese Dinner - Oyakodon \u00d7 4 </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Tonkotsu-Style Ramen (Quick Weeknight Approach) - Miso butter ramen with soft-boiled eggs (marinated in soy + mirin) </p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Teriyaki Sauce from Scratch + Chicken Thighs - Teriyaki chicken thighs </p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Yakitori (Grilled Chicken Skewers) - Yakitori assortment (aim for 3\u20134 different cuts) </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Shabu-Shabu or Sukiyaki (Hot Pot) - Shabu-shabu with thinly sliced beef ribeye, mushrooms, tofu, noodles, napa cabbage </p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Full Japanese Kaiseki-Inspired Dinner - Simplified 4-course Japanese dinner (formal but achievable) </p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-3536-chinese","title":"Weeks 35\u201336: Chinese","text":"<p>Session 0 \u2014 Dan Dan Noodles (optional) Dan dan noodles (a full portion, made as a dinner for yourself or two people) \u2014 nothing else needed, they're substantial - Sesame paste (or tahini): Richness, body, nutty depth - Light soy sauce: Salt, savory baseline - Black vinegar (Chinkiang): Sourness, slight smoke - Chilli oil: Primary heat + red color - Ground Sichuan peppercorns: M\u00e1l\u00e0 numbing sensation - Sugar: Balance against the acid and heat - Chicken stock or hot water: Texture, loosens the sauce - Noodles: Fresh wheat noodles or dried thin lo mein; al dente - Topping: Spiced pork mince with ya cai (preserved mustard greens) - Sauce: Full Sichuan dan dan sauce (above components) - Garnish: Chopped roasted peanuts, scallion greens, chilli oil drizzle - Item: What it does - *Soy sauce* (light/regular + dark): Light for seasoning; dark for color and body - *Shaoxing rice wine*: The workhorse alcohol in Chinese cooking; not the same as sake or mirin - *Sesame oil* (toasted): Finishing oil \u2014 not for cooking high heat - *Doubanjiang* (Pixian brand if possible): Fermented chilli-bean paste; the base of many Sichuan dishes - *Oyster sauce*: Adds rounded savory depth to stir-fries and braises - *Black rice vinegar* (Chinkiang/Zhenjiang): Sharp, slightly smoky fermented vinegar - *Sichuan peppercorns*: Numbing (not burning) heat; floral and citrusy - *Dried red chilli (tianjin or facing heaven)*: Heat + smokiness in Sichuan cooking - *Five-spice powder*: Star anise-led spice blend; a little goes a long way - *Fermented black beans*: Funky, salty, savory; central to Cantonese cooking - *Corn or potato starch*: Thickens sauces and velvetizes proteins</p> <p>Session 1 \u2014 The Wok: Heat, Motion, and Wok Hei Chicken and Broccoli Stir-Fry (substitute chicken) with velveted chicken and hand-cut florets, served on white rice - Protein: Chicken breast, sliced thin against grain, velveted - Sauce: Oyster sauce + light soy + Shaoxing wine + cornstarch slurry - Aromatics: Ginger + garlic + scallion - Vegetable: Broccoli florets, blanched 1 minute first</p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Red-Braised Pork Belly (Hong Shao Rou) Hong shao rou over steamed white rice + blanched baby bok choy with garlic - Pork: 1.5 lbs skin-on pork belly, cut into 1.5-inch squares - Rice: Plain jasmine rice cooked in a rice cooker or pot - Vegetable: Baby bok choy, halved, wok-saut\u00e9ed with garlic and a splash of oyster sauce</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Cantonese Steamed Fish Steamed whole fish + steamed rice + saut\u00e9ed morning glory or Chinese broccoli (gai lan) with oyster sauce - Fish: Whole branzino or sea bass (1\u20131.5 lbs); or 2 large fillets - Sauce: Light soy + Shaoxing wine + sesame oil + pinch of sugar - Garnish: Julienned ginger, scallion chiffonade, hot oil flash</p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Mapo Tofu (\u9ebb\u5a46\u8c46\u8150) Mapo tofu over steamed rice + simple soy-dressed cucumber salad (smashed cucumbers with black vinegar + garlic + sesame oil + chilli flake) - Tofu: Soft or silken tofu, cubed, blanched - Base: Doubanjiang + fermented black beans + ground pork + aromatics - Sauce: Stock + soy + rice wine; thickened with cornstarch slurry - Finish: Sichuan peppercorn oil + scallion greens</p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Sichuan Dinner - Dish: Heat level - Smashed cucumber salad: Low (just chilli flake) - Mapo tofu: High m\u00e1l\u00e0 - Stir-fried green beans with garlic: None - Steamed white rice: None - Dan dan noodles (half portion, dressed lighter): Medium</p> <p>Session 0 \u2014 Kung Pao Chicken (optional) Kung pao chicken over steamed rice + sliced cucumber dressed with sesame oil and white vinegar - Ingredient: Amount - Black vinegar: 2 tsp - Soy sauce: 2 tbsp - Sugar: 1 tsp - Sichuan peppercorn oil: 1 tsp - Chilli oil: 1 tsp - Cornstarch: 1 tsp - Chicken stock: 3 tbsp</p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Congee (Rice Porridge) A congee bar \u2014 make a large pot of plain rice congee, and provide: - Topping: How to prepare - Century egg: Nicked and sliced (an acquired taste; try it) - Poached or sous vide chicken: Shredded; seasoned with soy + sesame - Crispy shallots: Thin-sliced, fried until deep gold - Pickled ginger: Pre-made or store-bought - White pepper: Freshly ground; essential - Sesame oil: A few drops to finish - Sliced scallions: Raw, added at the last moment - Fried dough (youtiao): Buy from an Asian bakery or skip</p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Dim Sum at Home: Har Gow (Shrimp Dumplings) Har gow (make at least 16 \u2014 the first 4 will be ugly) + char siu bao (steamed BBQ pork buns) from store-bought char siu pork or pork belly </p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Chinese Egg Fried Rice Egg fried rice (a proper full-dinner portion) + Chinese cucumber salad + any leftover hong shao rou from earlier in the week if you made it ahead </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Hot and Sour Soup (\u9178\u8fa3\u6c64) Hot and sour soup as a complete dinner (it's substantial) + steamed white rice if needed + scallion pancakes (store-bought or make your own) - Stock: Pork or chicken stock \u2014 good homemade makes this sing - Mushrooms: Reconstituted dried wood ear + shiitake - Proteins: Silken tofu cubes + thin pork strips - Thickener: Cornstarch slurry \u2014 add gradually until soup coats a spoon - Acid + heat: Black vinegar + white pepper \u2014 both added OFF heat to preserve sharpness</p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Full Chinese Banquet (for 4\u20136) - Dish: Why it's on the menu - Celery root and cucumber appetizer: Light opener; no cooking - Hot and sour soup: Starter; the egg ribbon technique on display - Steamed whole fish: Cantonese technique; freshness as the statement - Hong shao rou: Red-braised pork; make it early in the block, reheat and it's even better - Stir-fried bok choy with garlic: Fast, green, balancing the rich dishes - Steamed jasmine rice: Cook double the amount</p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-3738-mexican","title":"Weeks 37\u201338: Mexican","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Carne Asada - Carne Asada tacos on warm corn tortillas </p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Pozole Rojo - Pozole Rojo with whatever garnishes you have: shredded cabbage, sliced radish, dried oregano, lime juice, tostadas </p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Guacamole + Salsa Verde (The Fundamentals) - Guacamole + charred salsa verde served as dinner accompaniments </p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Tacos al Pastor - Tacos al Pastor: pork, pineapple, white onion, cilantro, lime, corn tortillas </p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Enchiladas + Red Chile Sauce from Scratch - Enchiladas Rojas (beef or cheese and onion) </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Birria de Res (Beef Birria) - Birria tacos / quesabirria with consomm\u00e9 for dipping </p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Mole Negro (Simplified Introduction) - Simplified Mole Negro with chicken thighs </p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Tamales (Team Project) - Tamales (makes 12\u201316) \u2014 eat some tonight; freeze the rest </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Chiles Rellenos - Chiles Rellenos (cheese or picadillo filled) </p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Full Mexican Celebration Dinner - Multi-dish Mexican celebration spread </p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-3940-indian","title":"Weeks 39\u201340: Indian","text":"<p>Session 0 \u2014 Garlic Naan (optional) - Garlic Naan \u00d7 8\u201310 (it's flatbread night \u2014 pair with leftover dal from earlier in the block or butter chicken) </p> <p>Session 1 \u2014 Butter Chicken (Murgh Makhani) - Butter Chicken </p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Moong Dal (Yellow Split Lentils) - Moong Dal with tarka finish </p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Chicken Tikka Masala (Grilled Version) - Chicken Tikka Masala (grilled tikka + masala sauce) </p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: North Indian Feast - Full Indian banquet spread </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Chana Masala (Chickpea Curry) - Chana Masala </p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Aloo Gobi (Potato and Cauliflower) - Aloo Gobi </p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Lamb Biryani - Lamb Biryani </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Garam Masala from Scratch + Spice Inventory - Make garam masala as the session </p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: South Indian Weekend - Masala Dosa + Sambar + Coconut Chutney (South Indian thali) </p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-4142-middle-eastern","title":"Weeks 41\u201342: Middle Eastern","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Hummus b'Tahini (From Scratch) - Hummus b'Tahini with olive oil, cumin, paprika, and warm pita </p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Shakshuka - Shakshuka with crusty bread or pita for scooping </p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Baba Ganoush + Muhammara - Mezze board: baba ganoush + muhammara + hummus (from Session 1) + pita </p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Falafel - Falafel in warm pita with tahini sauce, tomato, cucumber, pickled onions </p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Beef Shawarma - Beef Shawarma wraps with garlic sauce (toum) \u2014 mashed garlic + lemon + oil emulsion </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Adana Kebab (Turkish Ground Lamb Skewer) - Adana Kebab with warm flatbread, grilled tomatoes and peppers </p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Fattoush + Tabbouleh Deep Dive - Fattoush + Tabbouleh (a vegetarian evening) </p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Persian-Style Herb Frittata (Kuku Sabzi) or Rice (Chelow) - Kuku Sabzi with yogurt and bread, OR Chelow with tahdig as a side to grilled lamb </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Kabsa (Saudi Spiced Chicken and Rice) - Kabsa with charred tomato salsa (dakka) on the side </p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Full Mezze Table - Complete Middle Eastern mezze table </p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#module-5-mastery-and-pastry","title":"Module 5: Mastery And Pastry","text":""},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-4546-desserts","title":"Weeks 45\u201346: Desserts","text":""},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-4748-pastry","title":"Weeks 47\u201348: Pastry","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 P\u00e2te Sucr\u00e9e (Sweet Tart Dough) - Fill the baked tart shell with pastry cream and fresh fruit (strawberry, raspberry, kiwi) </p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Pastry Cream (Cr\u00e8me P\u00e2tissi\u00e8re) - Eclairs or cream puffs using pastry cream (choux pastry \u2014 see for the full technique, or make a basic choux: butter + water + flour + eggs piped and baked at 400\u00b0F) </p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Tarte Tatin - Tarte Tatin with cr\u00e8me fra\u00eeche or vanilla ice cream </p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Choux Pastry (\u00c9clairs or Profiteroles) - Chocolate-glazed \u00e9clairs with pastry cream filling (pastry cream from Session 2) </p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Mille-Feuille (Napoleon) - Mille-Feuille: pastry cream + puff pastry </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Caramel: Wet and Dry Methods - Caramel sauce over vanilla ice cream </p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e - Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e \u00d7 4 (make ahead; refrigerate; br\u00fbl\u00e9e right before serving) </p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Panna Cotta - Panna cotta with raspberry coulis or simply excellent olive oil and sea salt (the Sicilian approach) </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Chocolate Mousse - Chocolate mousse, chilled 2 hours minimum </p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Layer Cake - Layer cake \u2014 serve to anyone available; this is a milestone bake </p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-4950-signature-dishes","title":"Weeks 49\u201350: Signature Dishes","text":"<p>Session 0 \u2014 Mise en Place at Scale (optional) </p> <p>Session 1 \u2014 Advanced Wok Technique </p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 Knife Skills: Where Are You Now? </p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 The Best Chocolate Chip Cookie (Refinement) </p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 The Caramel Sauce (Perfection) </p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: The Dish You Haven't Perfected Yet </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Define It </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Develop a New Recipe </p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: The Personal Tasting Menu </p>"},{"location":"program-overview.html#weeks-5152-final-exam","title":"Weeks 51\u201352: Final Exam","text":"<p>Session 1 \u2014 Menu Design Theory </p> <p>Session 2 \u2014 The Make-Ahead Audit - Dessert: Day before - Braise: Day before - Bread: Day before - Starter: Morning of - Sauce: Hour before - Protein final cook: 20\u201330 min before - Plating: During service</p> <p>Session 3 \u2014 Timing Under Pressure </p> <p>Session 4 \u2014 Dinner Party #1: Small Table </p> <p>Session 5 \u2014 POST-DINNER DEBRIEF </p> <p>Session 6 \u2014 Scaling Recipes </p> <p>Session 7 \u2014 The Art of Mise en Place for Groups </p> <p>Session 8 \u2014 Wine and Beverage Pairing Basics </p> <p>Session 9 \u2014 Final Prep Day </p> <p>Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Dinner Party #2 \u2014 The Full Table </p> <p>Session 11 \u2014 Skills Inventory </p> <p>Session 12 \u2014 The Forgotten Dish </p> <p>Session 13 \u2014 Cook Something From Memory </p> <p>Session 14 \u2014 The Final Mise en Place Drill </p> <p>Session 15 \u2014 PROJECT: The Anniversary Dinner </p> <p>Session 16 \u2014 Define the Exam for Yourself </p> <p>Session 17 \u2014 Cook the Final Exam Dish </p> <p>Session 18 \u2014 The Retrospective Meal </p> <p>Session 19 \u2014 The Open Kitchen </p> <p>Session 20 \u2014 Week 52: The Final Dinner - Skill: Week 1 - Sharp knife, proper grip: Learning - Stock from scraps: Unknown - Sauce from pan drippings: Never - Pasta from flour and eggs: Unfamiliar - Sourdough from wild yeast: Impossible-seeming - A 3-course dinner for 8: Stressful - Cook anything with what's available: Unlikely</p> <p>Auto-generated from block index files. No curriculum files were modified.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/index.html","title":"Module 1: Foundational Skills (Block 1\u20138)","text":"<p>The goal of this module: Build the physical and conceptual toolkit every cook needs before anything else \u2014 a confident knife hand, a fluent understanding of heat, the five mother sauces as a flavor map, and the ability to make great stock and eggs from memory.</p> <p>By the end of Week 8, you should be able to walk into any kitchen and produce restaurant-quality fundamentals without a recipe.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/index.html#weeks-in-this-module","title":"Weeks in This Module","text":"Weeks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 1\u20132 Knife Skills &amp; Kitchen Setup \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 3\u20134 Heat &amp; Cooking Methods \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 5\u20136 The 5 Mother Sauces \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 7\u20138 Stocks &amp; Eggs (includes Module 1 Checkpoint) \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/index.html#core-skills-covered","title":"Core Skills Covered","text":"<ul> <li>Knife work \u2014 grip, rocking motion, julienne, brunoise, chiffonade; blade maintenance and honing</li> <li>Heat control \u2014 saut\u00e9, sear, roast, braise, poach, steam; Maillard reaction and caramelization</li> <li>The mother sauces \u2014 b\u00e9chamel, velout\u00e9, espagnole, hollandaise, and tomato; their derivatives</li> <li>Stock fundamentals \u2014 white and brown stocks; roasting bones; the difference between stock and broth</li> <li>Eggs \u2014 every technique: scrambled, poached, basted, fried, soft-boiled; emulsification basics</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/index.html#equipment-youll-need","title":"Equipment You'll Need","text":"<p>See the Kitchen Equipment Guide for the full list. Essential items introduced in this module:</p> Item Introduced Chef's knife (8\u201310 inch) Week 1 Honing steel Week 1 Large cutting board Week 1 Instant-read thermometer Week 1 Kitchen shears Week 3 <p>Next module: Module 2 \u2014 Building Flavor (Weeks 9\u201316)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html","title":"\ud83d\udd2a Block 1\u20132: Knife Skills &amp; Kitchen Setup","text":"<p>\"Learn to hold a knife properly and half the battle is won.\"</p> <p>Quick Reference: \u2192 Week 1\u20132 Recipe Quick Ref</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#before-you-start-block-1","title":"Before You Start Block 1","text":"<p>Read these first \u2014 they'll make every session click:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Hold a Chef's Knife \u2014 the pinch grip vs. handle grip, with photos</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The 4 Knife Cuts Every Cook Should Know \u2014 the slice, chop, back-slice, and rock chop</li> </ul> <p>Rule for the week: Hone your knife before every session. Non-negotiable.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#block-1-your-knife-is-a-liar-and-your-hands-dont-know-it-yet","title":"Block 1 \u2014 Your Knife Is a Liar (And Your Hands Don't Know It Yet)","text":""},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#session-1-the-pinch-grip","title":"Session 1 \u2014 The Pinch Grip","text":"<p>Skill: Switch to the blade pinch grip tonight and don't revert. Your thumb and forefinger rest directly on the blade just in front of the bolster \u2014 it's intimidating, but it gives you far better control. Hold it this way for the entire meal.</p> <p>Full Meal: Pasta with Butter and Parmesan</p> <p>The prep is simple \u2014 garlic and parsley \u2014 which lets you focus entirely on your grip without managing a complicated recipe. This is intentional.</p> Component Recipe Main Parmesan-crusted pasta Veg Wilted baby spinach, saut\u00e9ed in the pasta pan with olive oil, garlic, and lemon <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: POV Cacio e Pepe \u2014 Nearly the same dish. Watch how he builds the sauce with pasta water and keeps the heat low. Compare his approach to ours and see what you'd borrow.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#session-2-the-claw","title":"Session 2 \u2014 The Claw","text":"<p>Skill: Before touching the stove, take 2\u20133 carrots and 2\u20133 celery stalks. Practice the claw grip \u2014 fingers curled, knuckles as the guide rail for the blade. Keep the tip of the blade in contact with the board, pull back slightly until the blade slices in, then press down and forward using the full length of the blade. Dice everything into rough \u00bd\" pieces. Time yourself. Don't worry about speed yet \u2014 worry about uniformity. You want enough cuts to feel the motion start to settle.</p> <p>The onion is handled separately: halve it through the root, press it cut-side down into a dry, screaming-hot pan (no oil) until deeply charred \u2014 nearly black. That char goes straight into the broth and gives it color and depth. It's a different technique from dicing and worth doing intentionally.</p> <p>Full Meal: The Best Chicken Noodle Soup</p> <p>The recipe only uses charred onion for the stock \u2014 carrot and celery aren't in it. Your diced carrot and celery go straight into the soup for the last 10 minutes. The recipe doesn't call for them but they belong there, and the soup is better for it.</p> <p>Sous vide note: The recipe calls for cooking the chicken breast sous vide (140\u00b0F, 2 hours). You don't need a circulator \u2014 but don't rely on timing either. Lower the heat so the broth is barely simmering (small bubbles, not a rolling boil), add the chicken breasts, and cook until the thickest part reads 165\u00b0F on an instant-read thermometer. For average supermarket chicken breasts this takes roughly 25\u201335 minutes but thickness varies enough that a thermometer is the only safe call. Remove and dice.</p> Component Recipe Protein Chicken breast \u2014 poach in the broth (or sous vide if you have one), then dice Veg Onion (charred, per recipe) into the stock; your diced carrot and celery into the soup for last 10 minutes Starch Egg noodles, cooked seperately <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Knife Skills: How to Slice and Dice an Onion \u00b7 How to Make Chicken Noodle Soup \u2014 Watch the knife video for the claw grip in real time at speed. The soup video shows a completely different approach to the same dish \u2014 both are worth thinking about.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#session-3-rock-chop-vs-push-cut","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Rock Chop vs. Push Cut","text":"<p>Skill: Mince a full head of garlic and a large bunch of flat-leaf parsley before you start cooking. Use two strokes deliberately \u2014 the rock chop (blade tip stays on the board, heel rocks) and the push cut (blade lifts fully, pushes through cleanly). Notice the difference in speed and texture. The rock chop gives control; the push cut gives speed. Both have their place.</p> <p>Full Meal: Shrimp Scampi</p> <p>Shrimp scampi is built almost entirely on well-minced garlic and parsley. Your drill is the most important prep step in the dish.</p> Component Recipe Protein Shrimp, saut\u00e9ed in garlic butter and white wine Veg/Salad Arugula, Fennel &amp; Orange Salad Starch Crusty bread or linguine <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Knife Skills: How to Mince Shallots \u2014 Shallots, garlic, parsley \u2014 same motions, different ingredient. Watch how he uses the rock chop and push cut interchangeably depending on the task.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#session-4-mise-en-place","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Mise en Place","text":"<p>Skill: The real chef's secret. Tonight, before you turn on a single burner, prep everything first. Every ingredient chopped, measured, and arranged in small bowls or on the cutting board. Then cook. Notice how the experience changes \u2014 you're not scrambling, you're assembling.</p> <p>Full Meal: Stir-Fried Beef and Broccoli</p> <p>Stir-fries punish you for skipping mise en place. The heat is too high and things move too fast. This recipe forces you to have everything ready before the pan gets hot.</p> <p>No wok? The recipe is written for a wok, but a 12-inch cast-iron or stainless-steel skillet works fine. The key differences: get the pan completely smoking before anything goes in, cook beef in two or three very small batches (crowding kills the sear), and do the same with the broccoli. A wok handles everything in fewer passes because of its shape and heat distribution \u2014 a skillet needs more discipline about batch size to compensate.</p> Component Recipe Protein Thinly sliced flank steak, seared in very small batches Veg Broccoli florets, seared in the same pan Starch Steamed jasmine rice, started before you begin the stir-fry <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Beef with Broccoli \u2014 This is the exact dish. Watch it before you cook. Notice how everything is prepped and staged before the wok gets hot \u2014 mise en place isn't a warm-up, it's the whole game in a stir-fry.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#session-5-project-meal-french-onion-soup","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: French Onion Soup","text":"<p>Skill: Slicing 4\u20135 lbs of onions into uniform thin half-moons. This takes 20+ minutes and teaches you more than any drill \u2014 because caramelization depends entirely on uniform thickness. Thin, even slices cook at the same rate. Uneven ones create pockets of raw and burned.</p> <p>Full Meal: French Onion Soup (Soupe \u00e0 l'Oignon)</p> <p>A self-contained stunning dinner \u2014 nothing else needed except a glass of red wine.</p> <p>Skill targets: Uniform half-moon slices. Pinch grip maintained throughout. Knife honed before you start.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Mathematically Best Way to Cut an Onion \u2014 He breaks down the geometry of onion-cutting and why the angle of your cuts determines whether pieces stay together or fall apart. Perfect viewing before 4\u20135 lbs of half-moons.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#block-2-cuts-have-names-learn-them","title":"Block 2 \u2014 Cuts Have Names. Learn Them.","text":"<p>The grip is feeling more natural. Now we add vocabulary and intentionality to the cuts themselves.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#session-6-the-julienne","title":"Session 6 \u2014 The Julienne","text":"<p>Skill: Take two carrots and one zucchini. Square off each vegetable first (cut a flat face on one side so it doesn't roll). Slice into planks. Stack the planks and cut into matchsticks \u2014 roughly 2\u20133 inches long, \u215b inch thick. This is also the foundation of the brunoise (tiny dice). Go slow. Precision before speed.</p> <p>While you have your knife out: grab a small handful of fresh basil leaves. Stack them neatly, roll the stack into a tight cylinder, and slice straight across it into thin ribbons. That's chiffonade \u2014 the same logic as julienne, applied to soft leaves instead of hard vegetables. It takes 30 seconds and it's the right garnish for Pad Thai.</p> <p>Why it matters: Julienned vegetables cook faster and more evenly than rough cuts. Chiffonade keeps delicate herbs from bruising \u2014 a rough chop turns basil black at the edges almost immediately. Both cuts signal control.</p> <p>Full Meal: The Best Pad Thai</p> Component Recipe Protein Shrimp, chicken, or tofu Veg Your julienned carrots and scallions, plus bean sprouts; finish with fresh basil chiffonade Starch Rice noodles, soaked per the recipe <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Get More Out of Your Broccoli With This Knife Trick \u2014 Not broccoli today, but the principle is the same: thin, even cuts change how a vegetable cooks and eats. Watch the logic, apply it to your julienne.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#session-7-the-dice-small-medium-large","title":"Session 7 \u2014 The Dice (Small, Medium, Large)","text":"<p>Skill: Dice three potatoes \u2014 one small (\u00bc\"), one medium (\u00bd\"), one large (\u00be\"). Notice the process: planks first, then batons, then cubes. Cook all three in the same hot pan at the same time. Watch what happens \u2014 the small ones finish first. The large ones are still raw when the small ones are done. That's the entire lesson.</p> <p>Why it matters: Uniform cuts = uniform cooking. This is the single biggest quality gap between home cooks and professionals.</p> <p>Full Meal: Home Fries + Pan-Seared Crispy Chicken Thighs</p> Component Recipe Protein Crispy pan-seared bone-in chicken thighs Veg/Salad Classic Green Salad with Vinaigrette Starch Home fries (your dice drill is the recipe) <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Food Lab: How to Roast the Best Potatoes of Your Life \u2014 He explains why cut size and uniformity determine texture and doneness \u2014 the exact lesson from your three-potato drill, applied to the oven.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#session-8-breaking-down-a-whole-chicken","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Breaking Down a Whole Chicken","text":"<p>Skill: Buy a whole chicken. Read How to Break Down a Chicken first, then do it. You'll get two bone-in breasts, two thighs, two drumsticks, two wings, and a carcass. Put the carcass in a zip-lock in the freezer \u2014 that's Week 7 stock material. Follow the joints, not the bones. Let the knife find the natural seams.</p> <p>Full Meal: Chicken Piccata (use the breasts) + Burst Cherry Tomatoes</p> <p>The thighs and legs go in the fridge (use them later in the block) or freeze for later. Nothing wasted.</p> Component Recipe Protein Chicken piccata using the breasts you broke down Veg Burst Cherry Tomatoes with Garlic and Olive Oil Starch Linguine \u2014 toss with the burst tomatoes and a splash of pasta water <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: POV How to Break Down a Chicken \u00b7 28-Second Chicken Breakdown \u2014 Watch the full POV version before you start. The short shows what the motion looks like fully internalized. You'll get somewhere between the two.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#session-9-speed-benchmark","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Speed Benchmark","text":"<p>Skill: Time yourself dicing one onion. Write it down. This is your baseline. At the end of Week 4, you'll time yourself again. Speed is not the goal \u2014 having a reference point is.</p> <p>Full Meal: Shakshuka + leftover chicken from earlier in the block thighs (warmed in a skillet)</p> <p>Shakshuka requires dicing onion, pepper, and garlic as its entire prep \u2014 your speed drill is built into the recipe.</p> Component Recipe Protein Eggs poached in the shakshuka sauce + leftover chicken from earlier in the block thighs Veg Onion, bell pepper, tomatoes (the shakshuka base) Starch Crusty bread for dipping <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Shakshuka \u2014 The same dish. Notice that his onion and pepper dice is the entire prep step \u2014 the very thing you're timing today.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#session-10-project-meal-provencal-vegetable-tian","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Proven\u00e7al Vegetable Tian","text":"<p>Skill: Slice eggplant, zucchini, yellow squash, and tomatoes into rounds of identical thickness \u2014 ideally \u215b to \u00bc inch. The beauty of the finished dish is a direct function of your slicing precision. Uniform slices = a dish that looks like a restaurant made it.</p> <p>Full Meal: Proven\u00e7al Summer Vegetable Tian + crusty bread</p> Component Recipe Protein Optional \u2014 serve with good burrata or a soft-boiled egg on top Veg The tian (eggplant, zucchini, squash, tomato) Starch Crusty baguette <p>Skill targets: Consistent thickness on every slice. Go slow. This is about control, not speed.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Knife Skills: How to Dice Butternut Squash \u2014 Same family of vegetable, same slicing challenge. Watch the board control and how he maintains consistent pressure through each stroke.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#food-safety-fundamentals","title":"Food Safety Fundamentals","text":"<p>Covered in Block 3 \u2014 Before You Start \u2014 that's the first block where you cook raw protein directly, which is the right time to read it.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#buying-maintaining-your-knife","title":"Buying &amp; Maintaining Your Knife","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Best Chef's Knives \u2014 Serious Eats' tested roundup. The short answer for most people: a 8\" German-style knife (W\u00fcsthof or Victorinox) to start.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Wirecutter: The Best Chef's Knife \u2014 independent testing with a different methodology. Worth comparing both.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 German vs. Japanese Chef's Knives \u2014 What's the Difference? \u2014 harder steel, thinner bevel, more acute angle on Japanese; softer, more robust, easier to maintain on German. Useful context if you're buying soon.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Store Your Knives \u2014 magnetic strip vs. block vs. in-drawer protectors. The dishwasher is the enemy.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<p>Reading about knife technique only goes so far. These videos show you what the grip and motion actually look like at speed:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Jacques P\u00e9pin \u2014 Knife Skills \u2014 He's filmed these sessions multiple times across decades. Watching a 90-year-old chef break down an onion is humbling and clarifying.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Ethan Chlebowski \u2014 How to Actually Improve Your Knife Skills \u2014 More data-driven and modern. Good on speed benchmarks and how deliberate practice actually works in the kitchen.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#the-broader-concept-mise-en-place","title":"The Broader Concept: Mise en Place","text":"<p>Session 4 introduces mise en place but only as setup. The idea runs a lot deeper:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Set Up a Prep Station Like a Pro Cook \u2014 Sohla El-Waylly on the practical side of mise en place: how professional kitchens organize their workspace for vegetables, proteins, frying, and more. Session 4 introduces the habit; this shows you what it looks like fully applied.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Food Lab by J. Kenji L\u00f3pez-Alt \u2014 The first chapter covers knife skills and mise en place with the same scientific rigour as everything else in the book. If you're going to own one reference book for this program, this is it.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Block 1\u20132 Quick Reference \u2014 Knife Skills &amp; Kitchen Setup","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/quick-ref.html#week-1-recipes","title":"Week 1 Recipes","text":"Session Dish Skill Link Session 1 Pasta with Butter and Parmesan + Wilted Spinach Pinch grip Recipe Session 2 The Best Chicken Noodle Soup The claw / mirepoix (sous vide optional \u2014 poach in broth works fine) Recipe Session 3 Shrimp Scampi + Arugula, Fennel &amp; Orange Salad Rock chop vs. push cut Scampi \u00b7 Salad Session 4 Stir-Fried Beef and Broccoli Mise en place Recipe Session 5 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: French Onion Soup Uniform half-moon slices Recipe"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/quick-ref.html#week-2-recipes","title":"Week 2 Recipes","text":"Session Dish Skill Link Session 6 The Best Pad Thai Julienne cut Recipe Session 7 Home Fries + Crispy Pan-Seared Chicken Thighs + Green Salad Small/medium/large dice Home Fries \u00b7 Chicken \u00b7 Salad Session 8 Chicken Piccata + Burst Cherry Tomatoes Break down whole chicken Piccata \u00b7 Breakdown \u00b7 Tomatoes Session 9 Shakshuka + Leftover Chicken Thighs Speed benchmark \u2014 time your onion dice Recipe Session 10 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Proven\u00e7al Vegetable Tian + Bread Uniform round slices Tian"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/quick-ref.html#shopping-notes","title":"Shopping Notes","text":"<p>Buy early in Block 1: A honing steel (if you don't own one)</p> <p>Buy for Block 2: One whole chicken \u2014 you'll break it down yourself. Breasts go in Piccata; thighs/legs go in the fridge for Session 4's Shakshuka.</p> <p>Freeze: The chicken carcass from Block 2 \u2192 this is your Week 7 stock.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/quick-ref.html#food-safety","title":"Food Safety","text":"<p>\ud83d\udce2 Before you cook raw protein for the first time (Block 3), read the food safety primer embedded in Block 3\u20134.</p> Key rule Detail Danger zone 40\u00b0F\u2013140\u00b0F (4\u00b0C\u201360\u00b0C) \u2014 bacteria multiply here. Food should not sit in this range for more than 2 hours. Cross-contamination Raw protein never touches ready-to-eat food. Use separate cutting boards or wash and sanitize between tasks. Cooling stocks Transfer hot stock to a wide shallow container; ice-bath until below 70\u00b0F within 2 hours before refrigerating. Internal temperatures Poultry 165\u00b0F. Pork 145\u00b0F. Ground beef 160\u00b0F. Whole-muscle steak can be seared at lower internal temps because bacteria live on the outside. <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Full primer: See the Block 3\u20134: Heat &amp; Cooking Methods \u2014 Food Safety Fundamentals section.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 1\u20132: Knife Skills &amp; Kitchen Setup","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Do this in two produce trips \u2014 one before Week 1 starts, one before Week 2 starts. The list is already split that way. Produce bought in one go at the start of Week 1 will not survive to Week 2.</p> <p>Pantry and dry goods (pasta, sauces, oils, spices) can all be bought in one trip before Week 1 \u2014 they keep indefinitely.</p> <p>Proteins: Buy the Week 1 proteins (chicken breasts, shrimp, beef) before Week 1. Buy the Week 2 Pad Thai protein (shrimp or tofu) with your Week 2 shop. Buy the Week 2 whole chicken the day before you plan to break it down \u2014 it must be fresh, not frozen, and fresh chicken has a short window.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html#proteins","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Boneless, skinless chicken breasts \u2014 1 lb (Week 1 Tue, for soup)</li> <li>[ ] Large shrimp (16/20 count), peeled and deveined \u2014 1 lb (Week 1 Wed scampi)</li> <li>[ ] Flank steak or beef sirloin \u2014 1 lb, thinly sliced (Week 1 Fri, stir-fry)</li> <li>[ ] Bone-in, skin-on chicken thighs \u2014 6 pieces (Week 2 Tue + Friday leftovers)</li> <li>[ ] Whole chicken \u2014 1 (Week 2 Wed): You will break this down yourself. This is the lesson. The breasts go into piccata; the thighs and legs are your Week 2 Friday leftovers. Save the carcass in the freezer \u2014 it becomes your Week 7 stock.</li> <li>[ ] Shrimp (16/20 count) OR firm tofu \u2014 8 oz (Week 2 Mon Pad Thai protein)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce","text":"<p>Week 1:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Yellow onions \u2014 7 large (1 for soup stock, charred + 5\u20136 for French onion soup \u2014 they cook down to almost nothing)</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 6 (4 for Week 1 soup claw-grip drill + 2 reserved for Week 2 Mon julienne drill)</li> <li>[ ] Celery \u2014 1 bunch (2\u20133 stalks for Week 1 Tue claw-grip drill; remainder available for stock/other uses)</li> <li>[ ] Baby spinach \u2014 5 oz bag (Week 1 Mon pasta)</li> <li>[ ] Arugula \u2014 1 bag (Week 1 Wed salad)</li> <li>[ ] Fennel \u2014 1 bulb (Week 1 Wed salad)</li> <li>[ ] Orange \u2014 1 (Week 1 Wed salad)</li> <li>[ ] Broccoli \u2014 1 head (Week 1 Fri stir-fry)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 3 heads (multiple uses throughout both weeks)</li> <li>[ ] Lemon \u2014 4 (Week 1 Wed scampi + salad + piccata + dressings)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh ginger \u2014 2-inch knob (Week 1 Fri stir-fry)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh thyme \u2014 1 bunch (French onion soup)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh flat-leaf parsley \u2014 1 bunch (Week 1 Wed scampi, garnishes throughout)</li> </ul> <p>Week 2:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 1 pint (Week 2 Wed piccata side / pasta sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Lime \u2014 1 (Week 2 Mon Pad Thai)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh rosemary \u2014 1 small bunch (Week 2 Tue pan-seared chicken)</li> <li>[ ] Russet or Yukon Gold potatoes \u2014 2 lbs (Week 2 Tue home fries + dice drill)</li> <li>[ ] Red bell peppers \u2014 2 (Week 2 Tue home fries)</li> <li>[ ] Poblano pepper \u2014 1 (Week 2 Tue home fries \u2014 the SE recipe uses it)</li> <li>[ ] Zucchini \u2014 3 medium (1 for Week 2 Mon julienne drill + 2 for Week 2 Sat tian)</li> <li>[ ] Eggplant \u2014 1 medium (Week 2 Sat tian)</li> <li>[ ] Tomatoes \u2014 6 medium (Week 2 Sat tian + Week 2 Fri shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Yellow squash \u2014 2 medium (Week 2 Sat tian)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed greens / butter lettuce \u2014 1 bag (Week 2 Tue salad)</li> <li>[ ] Bean sprouts \u2014 1 bag (Week 2 Mon Pad Thai)</li> <li>[ ] Scallions \u2014 1 bunch (Week 2 Mon Pad Thai + garnishes)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh basil \u2014 1 bunch (Week 2 Mon Pad Thai chiffonade drill)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html#dairy","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Parmesan (Parmigiano-Reggiano block) \u2014 8 oz (Week 1 Mon pasta + salad + piccata)</li> <li>[ ] Gruy\u00e8re \u2014 10 oz total (4\u20136 oz for Week 1 Sat French onion soup croutons + 4 oz for Week 2 Sat tian)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 2 sticks</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (Week 2 Mon Pad Thai + Week 2 Fri shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 small carton (optional for pasta)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Pasta \u2014 short shape, e.g. rigatoni or spaghetti \u2014 1 lb (Week 1 Mon cacio e pepe-style)</li> <li>[ ] Pasta (linguine) \u2014 2 lbs (Week 1 Wed scampi + Week 2 Wed piccata)</li> <li>[ ] Egg noodles \u2014 8 oz (Week 1 Tue soup)</li> <li>[ ] Rice noodles, medium width \u2014 8 oz (Week 2 Mon Pad Thai)</li> <li>[ ] Jasmine rice \u2014 1 lb (Week 1 Fri stir-fry)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken stock or broth \u2014 32 oz carton (soup)</li> <li>[ ] Beef stock or broth \u2014 32 oz + 1 extra carton (Week 1 Sat French onion soup)</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole peeled tomatoes \u2014 2 cans (Week 2 Fri shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Dry white wine \u2014 1 bottle (Week 1 Wed scampi + Week 2 Wed piccata)</li> <li>[ ] Dry sherry \u2014 small bottle (Week 1 Sat French onion soup; also works as a Shaoxing wine sub in stir-fry)</li> <li>[ ] Oyster sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Week 1 Fri stir-fry)</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 1 bottle</li> <li>[ ] Sesame oil \u2014 1 small bottle (Week 1 Fri stir-fry)</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Pad Thai)</li> <li>[ ] Tamarind paste or concentrate \u2014 1 jar (Pad Thai) \u2014 Asian grocery or Amazon</li> <li>[ ] Brown sugar or palm sugar \u2014 1 bag (Pad Thai)</li> <li>[ ] Cornstarch \u2014 1 box (stir-fry velveting)</li> <li>[ ] All-purpose flour \u2014 1 bag (Week 2 Wed piccata dredge)</li> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard \u2014 1 jar (Week 2 Tue vinaigrette + general use)</li> <li>[ ] Red wine vinegar \u2014 1 bottle (Week 2 Tue vinaigrette)</li> <li>[ ] Unseasoned rice vinegar \u2014 1 bottle (Pad Thai)</li> <li>[ ] Roasted peanuts \u2014 1 bag (Pad Thai garnish)</li> <li>[ ] Capers \u2014 1 jar (Week 2 Wed piccata)</li> <li>[ ] Cumin, smoked paprika, dried chili flakes, ground coriander (Week 2 Fri shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Neutral oil (vegetable, grapeseed, or canola) \u2014 1 bottle if you don't have one</li> <li>[ ] Extra-virgin olive oil</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html#bread","title":"\ud83e\udd56 Bread","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Good baguette \u2014 1 (Week 1 Sat French onion soup croutons)</li> <li>[ ] Crusty bread \u2014 1 loaf (Week 2 Fri shakshuka dipping + Week 2 Sat tian)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html#equipment-if-you-dont-own-these-yet","title":"\ud83d\udd2a Equipment (if you don't own these yet)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Chef's knife \u2014 if you don't own a good one (8\" Victorinox Fibrox is the reliable budget pick)</li> <li>[ ] Honing steel \u2014 not optional. Buy one this week.</li> <li>[ ] Cutting board \u2014 large, wood or plastic (at least 12\" \u00d7 18\")</li> <li>[ ] Instant-read thermometer \u2014 useful now, essential from Week 3 on</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/01-02-knife-skills/shopping-list.html#notes","title":"\ud83d\udcdd Notes","text":"<p>French onion soup (Week 1 Sat) needs a huge amount of onions. 5\u20136 large yellow onions is not too many \u2014 they cook down to about 10% of their raw volume over 45\u201360 minutes. Don't rush the caramelization.</p> <p>Pad Thai (Week 2 Mon): Soak rice noodles in cold water for 30 minutes before cooking \u2014 don't boil them. They finish in the wok. Mise en place is even more critical here than in the stir-fry.</p> <p>Stir-fry (Week 1 Fri): Dry sherry is an acceptable sub for Shaoxing wine. If you're buying it anyway for French onion soup, you're covered \u2014 just reserve some before the onion soup.</p> <p>Whole chicken (Week 2 Wed): Watch the Serious Eats chicken breakdown video before you start. Takes about 20 minutes the first time; 8 minutes by Week 6.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html","title":"\ud83d\udd25 Block 3\u20134: Heat &amp; Cooking Methods","text":"<p>\"Understanding heat is understanding cooking. Everything else is detail.\"</p> <p>Quick Reference: \u2192 Week 3\u20134 Recipe Quick Ref</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#before-you-start-block-3","title":"Before You Start Block 3","text":"<p>Read this first:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 An Introduction to the Maillard Reaction \u2014 the science of browning, flavor, and why a dry, hot pan matters more than any spice blend</li> </ul> <p>Core concept: Dry heat above 300\u00b0F triggers the Maillard reaction \u2014 the chemical cascade that creates crust, color, and hundreds of flavor compounds. Wet heat (steam, water) cannot get food above 212\u00b0F, which means it cannot trigger this reaction. This is why a boiled steak tastes nothing like a seared one.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#food-safety-fundamentals","title":"Food Safety Fundamentals","text":"<p>This block is the first time you'll cook raw protein directly \u2014 saut\u00e9ed chicken, seared beef, braised cuts. Read this before Session 1.</p> <p>The four things every cook must know:</p> <ol> <li> <p>The danger zone is 40\u00b0F\u2013140\u00b0F (4\u00b0C\u201360\u00b0C). Bacteria multiply rapidly in this range. Cooked food left at room temperature should not spend more than 2 hours in the danger zone \u2014 shorter in a warm kitchen. If you can't serve it within 2 hours, refrigerate it.</p> </li> <li> <p>Cross-contamination is the most common home kitchen mistake. Raw poultry, beef, pork, and seafood carry bacteria. They should never touch anything that will be eaten raw \u2014 cutting boards, counters, hands, knife blades. Use separate boards for raw protein and produce, or wash and sanitize between tasks.</p> </li> <li> <p>Cool stocks and braises safely. A large pot of hot stock cools slowly through the danger zone. Don't put a hot pot directly in the fridge (it raises the ambient temperature and endangers everything else). Transfer to a wide, shallow container, ice bath it until it's below 70\u00b0F within 2 hours, then refrigerate. Improper cooling is the most common cause of home stock contamination.</p> </li> <li> <p>Internal temperatures are not optional suggestions. Poultry must reach 165\u00b0F. Pork at least 145\u00b0F. Ground beef 160\u00b0F. Whole-muscle beef steaks can be cooked lower because bacteria live on the surface and are killed by the sear \u2014 knowing why these numbers differ is as useful as knowing the numbers.</p> </li> </ol> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Safe Food Handling: What You Need to Know \u2014 danger zones, safe storage, cross-contamination. 10 minutes.</p> <p>The professional standard: CIA students spend their first week on food safety before they touch a hot stove. You're about to cook your first proteins. A cook who knows safe temperatures isn't being paranoid \u2014 they're being professional.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#block-3-dry-heat-the-maillard-reaction-is-your-best-friend","title":"Block 3 \u2014 Dry Heat: The Maillard Reaction Is Your Best Friend","text":"<p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 10 (Short Ribs): plan for a 3\u20134 hr cook; start by early afternoon</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#session-1-saute-hot-pan-dont-crowd","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Saut\u00e9: Hot Pan, Don't Crowd","text":"<p>Skill: Saut\u00e9ing means high heat, small amount of fat, food in a single layer, moving frequently. The most common home cook mistake: cold pan, crowded pan, food that steams instead of browns. Tonight, heat your pan until a drop of water evaporates immediately before adding oil. Cook in batches if needed.</p> <p>Full Meal: Saut\u00e9ed Chicken Breasts with Quick Pan Sauce + Saut\u00e9ed Zucchini with Garlic and Herbs + Steamed Rice</p> Component Recipe Protein Saut\u00e9ed boneless chicken breast, finished with a quick pan sauce of shallot, white wine, and butter Veg Saut\u00e9ed zucchini \u2014 notice how a hot pan gives you color on the outside while keeping the inside tender Starch Steamed jasmine rice <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Pan-Seared Chicken Breasts with Pan Sauce and Spring Vegetables \u2014 Same cut, same pan sauce technique \u2014 notice how he builds flavor in the pan after pulling the chicken.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#session-2-roasting-hot-oven-dry-surface","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Roasting: Hot Oven, Dry Surface","text":"<p>Skill: Roasting is dry oven heat that circulates around food, browning all exposed surfaces. The two secrets: (1) high heat (400\u00b0F+) and (2) a dry surface on the food. Pat everything dry. Never roast wet food \u2014 the moisture steams before it can brown.</p> <p>Full Meal: Sheet Pan Chicken Thighs with Roasted Vegetables + Simple Green Salad</p> <p>Use bone-in, skin-on thighs. Pat them completely dry. Compare the color and crispness tonight to earlier in the block's braise \u2014 you'll eat the difference.</p> Component Recipe Protein Bone-in skin-on chicken thighs, roasted until crackling Veg Whatever is on the sheet pan \u2014 broccoli, potatoes, onions Salad Simple green salad alongside"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#session-3-braising-low-slow-wet","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Braising: Low, Slow, Wet","text":"<p>Skill: Braising is a two-step method. First, sear the meat in a very hot pan (dry heat, Maillard reaction). Then add a small amount of liquid, cover, and cook at low heat for a long time. The collagen in tough cuts breaks down into gelatin, making the meat spoon-tender and the braising liquid silky. Never rush a braise.</p> <p>Full Meal: Braised Chicken Thighs with Tomatoes and Capers + Crusty bread or polenta</p> <p>Notice the difference in texture from earlier in the block roasted thighs \u2014 same cut of meat, entirely different result because of heat and moisture.</p> Component Recipe Protein Braised chicken thighs in a rich tomato-caper sauce Starch Crusty bread to mop the sauce, or polenta <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Crispy Braised Chicken with Tomatoes, Carrots, and Kale \u2014 Different vegetables, same braising logic \u2014 notice the deep sear he builds before any liquid goes in.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#session-4-steaming-poaching-and-en-papillote-gentle-heat","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Steaming, Poaching, and En Papillote: Gentle Heat","text":"<p>Skill: Wet heat keeps food moist and tender but produces no browning. It's ideal for delicate proteins and vegetables where you want to preserve texture and color. The trick: control your temperature. A hard boil beats up delicate proteins; a gentle simmer protects them.</p> <p>Tonight's two techniques:</p> <p>Poaching and steaming \u2014 cook the salmon gently in simmering liquid; steam the bok choy in a basket.</p> <p>En papillote \u2014 place a fish fillet, a spoonful of butter, aromatics (sliced fennel, capers, lemon), and a splash of white wine on one half of a large sheet of parchment paper. Fold and crimp the paper into a sealed parcel. Bake at 400\u00b0F for 12\u201315 minutes. The parcel puffs and steams the fish in its own moisture. This is the most foolproof fish technique in the kitchen \u2014 it's nearly impossible to overcook. Open the parcel at the table.</p> <p>Full Meal: Perfect Poached Salmon + fish en papillote (technique from description above; choose your fish based on what's freshest) + Steamed Bok Choy with Garlic Sauce + Steamed rice</p> Component Recipe Protein Gently poached salmon \u2014 silky, delicate, nothing like a seared fillet Veg Steamed bok choy, dressed simply with garlic and sesame Starch Steamed rice"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#session-5-project-meal-spatchcocked-roast-chicken","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Spatchcocked Roast Chicken","text":"<p>Skill: Spatchcocking (butterflying) a whole chicken removes the backbone, flattens the bird, and allows it to roast evenly in about half the time of a trussed bird. You'll use your knife skills from Weeks 1\u20132 and your roasting knowledge from this week. The result: the crispiest skin you've ever made at home.</p> <p>Full Meal: Spatchcocked Roast Chicken + Roasted Potatoes + Simple Green Salad with Vinaigrette</p> <p>Skill targets: Even butterflying, dry skin before roasting, proper resting time (10 minutes) before carving.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Cook a Perfect Roast Chicken (Spatchcock it!) \u00b7 Spatchcock Roast Chicken \u2014 The Fastest, Juiciest Method \u2014 He's done this twice; compare both approaches and borrow what you like.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#block-4-dry-heat-mastery-the-benchmark-cook","title":"Block 4 \u2014 Dry Heat Mastery + The Benchmark Cook","text":"<p>This week you'll revisit dry-heat methods with beef and fish, and end with your first real benchmark: a complete multi-component dinner cooked with no recipes open in front of you.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#session-6-searing-steak-the-art-of-doing-nothing","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Searing Steak: The Art of Doing Nothing","text":"<p>Skill: Put the steak in a screaming hot cast iron pan. Now don't touch it. The instinct to move, prod, and flip food constantly is the enemy of a good sear. Let the Maillard reaction happen. The steak will release from the pan when it's ready to flip. If you have to force it, it's not ready.</p> <p>Full Meal: Perfect Pan-Seared Steak with Butter Basting + Creamy Mashed Potatoes + Simple Saut\u00e9ed Green Beans</p> Component Recipe Protein Ribeye or NY strip, pan-seared in cast iron, basted in butter, thyme, and garlic Starch Ultra-creamy mashed potatoes (use more butter than you're comfortable with) Veg Green beans saut\u00e9ed in the steak pan drippings <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: POV How to Cook a Steak \u2014 Watch before you turn on the pan. Notice what \"don't touch it\" actually looks like in real time.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#session-7-high-heat-fish-crispy-skin-without-fear","title":"Session 7 \u2014 High-Heat Fish: Crispy Skin Without Fear","text":"<p>Skill: Fish with crispy skin requires a hot, well-oiled pan and patience. Press the fish gently against the pan for the first 30 seconds to prevent curling. Then leave it alone. Cook 80% of the way on the skin side. Flip only once, finish for 60 seconds on the flesh side.</p> <p>Full Meal: Crispy Pan-Seared Salmon + Roasted Asparagus + Simple Arugula and Fennel Salad</p> Component Recipe Protein Crispy-skinned salmon fillet, finished with lemon and capers Veg Roasted asparagus (high-heat oven, single layer, very dry) Salad Arugula salad alongside"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#session-8-broiling-overhead-heat","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Broiling: Overhead Heat","text":"<p>Skill: Broiling is essentially an upside-down grill \u2014 radiant heat comes from above. It's ideal for finishing dishes (melting cheese, charring a surface) or for cooking thin items quickly. Keep the rack close to the element and watch constantly. Broilers operate at max heat and burn food in seconds.</p> <p>Full Meal: Broiled Salmon with Miso Glaze + Saut\u00e9ed Bok Choy + Steamed rice</p> Component Recipe Protein Miso-glazed salmon under the broiler \u2014 8 minutes, no flipping needed Veg Saut\u00e9ed or steamed bok choy Starch Steamed rice <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Kenji's Cooking Show | Miso-Glazed Salmon \u2014 This is the exact dish \u2014 compare his glaze timing and broiler distance to yours.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#session-9-recap-cook-no-recipes","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Recap Cook: No Recipes","text":"<p>Skill challenge: Tonight you cook a full meal using only methods you've learned in Weeks 3\u20134, but with no recipe open. Pick a protein in your fridge. Choose a heat method. Season it. Make a simple sauce from the pan drippings. Cook a vegetable. Plate it.</p> <p>If you need to glance at times and temperatures, that's fine. But close the recipe tab.</p> <p>This is the week's most important session.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#session-10-project-meal-braised-short-ribs","title":"\u23f0 Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Braised Short Ribs","text":"<p>Skill: The full braise from start to finish. This is a long cook (3\u20134 hours) but almost entirely passive \u2014 you sear the ribs in batches, build the braising liquid, and let the oven do the rest. The hardest part is the patience.</p> <p>Full Meal: Braised Short Ribs + Creamy Polenta + Roasted Root Vegetables</p> Component Recipe Protein Bone-in beef short ribs braised in red wine and beef stock until they collapse Starch Creamy parmesan polenta (the perfect landing pad for the braising liquid) Veg Roasted root vegetables (carrots, parsnips, turnips) <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How Braises Get Tender \u00b7 Ask Kenji | How Can I Tell If My Braise Is Done? \u2014 Watch before you start; the short explains collagen breakdown in 60 seconds.</p> <p>Skill targets: A deep, dark sear on every side of the ribs before braising. Correct liquid level (one-third up the meat, not submerged). Internal temp of 200\u00b0F+ for collagen breakdown.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#the-science-of-the-sear","title":"The Science of the Sear","text":"<p>Understanding why a brown crust forms changes how you cook everything forever. The Maillard reaction is probably the single most important piece of food science a home cook can learn.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Right Way to Use a Meat Thermometer \u2014 Temperature is the only honest answer to \"is it done?\" This is the guide.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#braising-why-low-and-slow-works","title":"Braising: Why Low and Slow Works","text":"<p>You did a full braise this week. Here's the architecture behind it.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Food Lab on Resting Meat \u2014 Carries directly into braising logic: what happens to proteins and juice as meat cooks and rests.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Cooking With Olive Oil: Should You Fry and Sear in It? \u2014 The oil question every cook has. Answered properly.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#understanding-cooking-fats","title":"Understanding Cooking Fats","text":"<p>Oil isn't just oil. Fat choice affects flavor, smoke point, and technique \u2014 this week you used several.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 What's a Smoke Point and Why Does It Matter? \u2014 The concept behind why you use butter for finishing but not for searing.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda CookWise by Shirley Corriher \u2014 Corriher is a food scientist who explains not just how to cook, but why techniques work at a chemical level. The chapters on searing, browning, and fat behavior are the most practical food-science reading available for the exact techniques you did this week.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Block 3\u20134 Quick Reference \u2014 Heat &amp; Cooking Methods","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/quick-ref.html#block-3-recipes","title":"Block 3 Recipes","text":"Session Dish Method Link Session 1 Saut\u00e9ed Chicken Breasts with Pan Sauce + Saut\u00e9ed Zucchini + Steamed Rice Saut\u00e9 Chicken \u00b7 Zucchini Session 2 Sheet Pan Chicken Thighs + Roasted Veg + Green Salad Roast (dry) Chicken \u00b7 Salad Session 3 Braised Chicken Thighs with Tomatoes and Capers + Bread/Polenta Braise (wet) Recipe Session 4 Perfect Poached Salmon + Steamed Bok Choy + Rice Poach / Steam Salmon \u00b7 Bok Choy Session 5 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Spatchcocked Roast Chicken + Roasted Potatoes + Green Salad Roast Chicken \u00b7 Potatoes \u00b7 Salad"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/quick-ref.html#block-4-recipes","title":"Block 4 Recipes","text":"Session Dish Method Link Session 6 Pan-Seared Steak (Butter Basted) + Mashed Potatoes + Green Beans Sear (cast iron) Steak \u00b7 Mash \u00b7 Beans Session 7 Crispy Pan-Seared Salmon + Roasted Asparagus + Arugula Salad Sear (fish) Salmon \u00b7 Asparagus Session 8 Broiled Miso-Glazed Salmon + Bok Choy + Steamed Rice Broil Salmon \u00b7 Bok Choy Session 9 No-recipe recap cook \u2014 use what's in your fridge Your choice \u2014 Session 10 \u23f0 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Braised Short Ribs + Creamy Polenta + Roasted Root Veg Braise Ribs \u00b7 Polenta \u00b7 Veg"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/quick-ref.html#key-reminders","title":"Key Reminders","text":"<ul> <li>Before every session: Hone the knife. Pat proteins completely dry.</li> <li>Don't crowd the pan. One layer, high heat, batches if needed.</li> <li>Session 4 is a freeform cook \u2014 close the recipes, use the techniques.</li> <li>Project session short ribs: 3\u20134 hours. Start early. Internal temp 200\u00b0F+ for full collagen breakdown.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 3\u20134: Heat &amp; Cooking Methods","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Buy week 3 proteins and produce at the start of Week 3, week 4 mid-week. The short ribs for Saturday of Week 4 should be bought Friday or early Saturday morning \u2014 they need 3\u20134 hours in the oven.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/shopping-list.html#proteins","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins","text":"<p>Week 3: - [ ] Boneless, skinless chicken breasts \u2014 4 pieces (Week 3 Mon) - [ ] Bone-in, skin-on chicken thighs \u2014 6 pieces (Week 3 Tue sheet pan + Wed braise) - [ ] Salmon fillets (skin-on) \u2014 2 pieces (Week 3 Fri poached) - [ ] Whole chicken \u2014 1 large (Week 3 Sat spatchcocked roast)</p> <p>Week 4: - [ ] Ribeye or NY strip steaks \u2014 2 (Week 4 Mon, 1\u20131.5\" thick \u2014 don't go thin) - [ ] Salmon fillets (skin-on) \u2014 4 pieces (Week 4 Tue seared + Wed broiled/miso) - [ ] Bone-in beef short ribs \u2014 3\u20134 lbs (Week 4 Sat PROJECT \u2014 buy early, they're expensive; ask the butcher)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce","text":"<p>Week 3: - [ ] Zucchini \u2014 3 medium (Week 3 Mon + leftover use) - [ ] Bell peppers (red and yellow) \u2014 4 (Week 3 Tue sheet pan + Wed braise) - [ ] Onions (yellow) \u2014 4 (braise base, mirepoix) - [ ] Broccoli \u2014 1 head (Week 3 Tue sheet pan component) - [ ] Bok choy \u2014 1 large head (Week 3 Fri) - [ ] Potatoes (Yukon Gold) \u2014 3 lbs total for Week 3 Sat and Week 4 Mon mash - [ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads - [ ] Lemons \u2014 3 - [ ] Fresh thyme and rosemary \u2014 1 bunch each - [ ] Fresh dill \u2014 1 small bunch (Week 3 Fri poached salmon sauce) - [ ] Mixed greens \u2014 2 bags (salads)</p> <p>Week 4: - [ ] Asparagus \u2014 1 bunch (Week 4 Tue) - [ ] Arugula \u2014 2 bags (Week 4 Tue salad + Week 4 Fri) - [ ] Fennel \u2014 1 bulb (Week 4 Tue arugula &amp; fennel salad) - [ ] Orange \u2014 1 (Week 4 Tue arugula, fennel &amp; orange salad) - [ ] Bok choy \u2014 1 head (Week 4 Wed) - [ ] Green beans \u2014 1 lb (Week 4 Mon) - [ ] Root vegetables (carrots, parsnips, turnips) \u2014 2 lbs total (Week 4 Sat)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/shopping-list.html#dairy","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 3 sticks (basting, pan sauces, mash)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 cup (Week 4 Mon mashed potatoes)</li> <li>[ ] Parmesan \u2014 4 oz (arugula salad)</li> <li>[ ] Plain whole-milk yogurt \u2014 1 cup (Week 3 Fri poached salmon dill yogurt sauce)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] White wine (dry) \u2014 1 bottle (pan sauces, braise \u2014 use something drinkable)</li> <li>[ ] Red wine (dry) \u2014 1 bottle (Week 4 Sat short rib braise)</li> <li>[ ] Polenta (coarse-ground) \u2014 1 bag (Week 3 Wed + Week 4 Sat)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken stock \u2014 64 oz total (sauces, braise liquid)</li> <li>[ ] Beef stock \u2014 32 oz (Week 4 Sat short ribs)</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole peeled tomatoes \u2014 2 cans (Week 3 Wed braise)</li> <li>[ ] Capers \u2014 1 jar (Week 3 Wed braise)</li> <li>[ ] Black olives (pitted) \u2014 1 can or jar (Week 3 Wed optional)</li> <li>[ ] White miso paste \u2014 1 container (Week 4 Wed glazed salmon)</li> <li>[ ] Mirin \u2014 1 bottle (miso glaze)</li> <li>[ ] Sake or dry sherry \u2014 small bottle (miso glaze)</li> <li>[ ] Rice (long grain or jasmine) \u2014 1 lb (Week 3 Mon + Fri steamed rice; also Week 4 Wed broiled salmon)</li> <li>[ ] Neutral oil \u2014 for high-heat searing</li> <li>[ ] Extra-virgin olive oil</li> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 1 bag (pan sauces)</li> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard \u2014 1 jar (vinaigrette + Week 4 Sat marinade)</li> <li>[ ] Canola or vegetable oil (Week 4 Sat long braise)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/03-04-heat-and-cooking/shopping-list.html#notes","title":"\ud83d\udcdd Notes","text":"<p>Week 4 Saturday \u2014 Braised Short Ribs (the big one): This is a 3\u20134 hour cook. Buy the ribs fresh on Friday or Saturday morning. Pat them completely dry, salt generously, and sear in batches over very high heat until a deep brown crust forms on all sides. Don't rush this step. The fond from the sear is most of the sauce's flavor.</p> <p>Week 3 Spatchcock (Sat): Ask yourself the question before you buy: do I have kitchen shears? If not, buy a pair. A sharp chef's knife works too, but shears make spatchcocking dramatically easier.</p> <p>Miso glaze (Week 4 Wed): Mix equal parts white miso, mirin, and sake with a bit of sugar. Marinate salmon for 24 hours minimum for the full effect. Make it Tuesday night.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html","title":"\ud83e\udd63 Block 5\u20136: The 5 Mother Sauces","text":"<p>\"Master these five sauces and you can make virtually any sauce on earth.\"</p> <p>Quick Reference: \u2192 Week 5\u20136 Recipe Quick Ref</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#before-you-start-block-5","title":"Before You Start Block 5","text":"<p>Read this first:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The 5 French Mother Sauces, Explained</li> </ul> <p>The five mother sauces are: B\u00e9chamel (milk + roux), Velout\u00e9 (stock + roux), Espagnole (dark stock + roux + tomato), Hollandaise (emulsified egg yolk + butter), and Sauce Tomat (tomato-based).</p> <p>Four out of five start with a roux. Learn the roux and you learn four sauces at once.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#block-5-roux-based-sauces","title":"Block 5 \u2014 Roux-Based Sauces","text":"<p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 3 (Bolognese): needs 3\u20134 hrs simmering; start early in the session</li> <li>Session 5 (Moussaka project): plan for 2 hrs: make both b\u00e9chamel and tomato sauce before assembly</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#session-1-bechamel-the-white-sauce","title":"Session 1 \u2014 B\u00e9chamel: The White Sauce","text":"<p>Skill: A b\u00e9chamel is a white roux (equal parts butter and flour, cooked briefly until it smells nutty but hasn't browned) whisked with warm milk. The key is adding the milk gradually while whisking constantly, and cooking it long enough to lose the raw flour taste. Season with salt, white pepper, and a pinch of nutmeg.</p> <p>Full Meal: Baked Mac and Cheese (B\u00e9chamel-Based) + Simple Green Salad</p> <p>You'll make the b\u00e9chamel from scratch and transform it into a Mornay sauce (b\u00e9chamel + cheese). Then it becomes mac and cheese. This is the mother sauce \u2192 daughter sauce chain in action.</p> Component Recipe Main Baked mac and cheese (the whole dish) Starch Pasta (built-in) Salad Simple green salad to cut through the richness"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#session-2-veloute-stock-instead-of-milk","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Velout\u00e9: Stock Instead of Milk","text":"<p>Skill: A velout\u00e9 starts with the same white roux as b\u00e9chamel but uses chicken (or fish, or veal) stock instead of milk. The result is lighter, more savory, and more versatile as a sauce base. It should coat a spoon lightly when done \u2014 if it's too thick, thin it with more warm stock.</p> <p>Full Meal: Chicken Pot Pie with Velout\u00e9 Base + Simple green salad</p> <p>The pot pie filling is a classic chicken velout\u00e9 extended with vegetables and cream. You're learning the mother sauce and a classic comfort food simultaneously.</p> Component Recipe Protein Chicken (cooked and pulled into the filling) Starch The pastry crust Veg Peas, carrots, and onion in the filling Salad Simple green salad alongside"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#session-3-sauce-tomat-the-slow-tomato","title":"\u23f0 Session 3 \u2014 Sauce Tomat: The Slow Tomato","text":"<p>Skill: The mother tomato sauce is not marinara. It's a deeply flavored, long-cooked sauce built on a pork fat base, mirepoix, tomatoes, stock, and aromatics. The key is patience \u2014 low heat, long time, and tasting as the sauce develops. Learn to season in layers, not all at once.</p> <p>Full Meal: The Best Slow-Cooked Bolognese</p> <p>Bolognese takes 3\u20134 hours. Make it on a low-key evening when you can let it simmer while doing other things.</p> Component Recipe Protein Ground beef and pork, slow-cooked into the sauce Starch Fresh tagliatelle or good dried pasta Veg Mirepoix (in the sauce) + Classic Caesar Salad alongside <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Rag\u00f9 Bolognese is Easy, Actually \u2014 Compare how he builds the soffrito and when he adds each liquid \u2014 the patience is the technique.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#session-4-espagnole-and-demi-glace-simplified","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Espagnole and Demi-Glace (Simplified)","text":"<p>Skill: Espagnole is a brown roux-based sauce made with dark beef stock and tomato. The demi-glace is espagnole reduced by half until it becomes intensely flavored and glossy. Tonight you make a simplified version \u2014 the same concept, without a days-long reduction.</p> <p>Full Meal: Steak with Red Wine Pan Sauce + Creamy Mashed Potatoes + Roasted Broccolini</p> <p>The pan sauce is your simplified Espagnole: browned bits from the steak, deglazed with wine, reduced with stock. It tastes like a restaurant made it because it is the technique restaurants use.</p> Component Recipe Protein Pan-seared steak with a red wine reduction pan sauce Starch Ultra-creamy mashed potatoes Veg Roasted broccolini <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Best Way to Cook Steak: The Reverse Sear \u2014 A different approach to the same result \u2014 watch how he thinks about internal temperature versus crust formation.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#session-5-project-meal-greek-moussaka","title":"\u23f0 Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Greek Moussaka","text":"<p>Skill: A synthesis dish \u2014 you'll make a tomato-based lamb meat sauce and a b\u00e9chamel and roast eggplant, then layer them together and bake. Uses two of the five mother sauces in a single dish.</p> <p>Full Meal: Greek Moussaka + Greek Salad + Crusty bread</p> Component Recipe Protein Ground lamb or beef in the tomato layer Sauce B\u00e9chamel on top, baked to a golden crust Veg Roasted eggplant and potato layers Salad Greek salad alongside <p>Skill targets: Smooth, lump-free b\u00e9chamel. Uniform eggplant slices (Week 2 callback). Full mise en place before assembly.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#block-6-emulsified-sauces-vinaigrette","title":"Block 6 \u2014 Emulsified Sauces + Vinaigrette","text":""},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#session-6-hollandaise-the-emulsion","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Hollandaise: The Emulsion","text":"<p>Skill: Hollandaise is the most technically demanding of the five mother sauces \u2014 an emulsion of egg yolks and clarified butter, stabilized by the lecithin in the yolks. The keys: gentle heat (too hot and the eggs scramble), constant whisking, adding the butter slowly. Use a double boiler and your thermometer tonight.</p> <p>Full Meal: Eggs Benedict with Hollandaise \u2014 yes, breakfast for dinner. It's legitimate when it teaches you hollandaise.</p> Component Recipe Protein Canadian bacon, poached eggs Sauce Hollandaise (your skill for tonight) Starch English muffins, toasted Veg/Salad Simple Watercress Salad alongside <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Eggs Benedict the Classic Way \u2014 Watch how he handles the hollandaise temperature \u2014 the moment it breaks and how to rescue it.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#session-7-mayonnaise-emulsion-without-heat","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Mayonnaise: Emulsion Without Heat","text":"<p>Skill: Mayo is a cold emulsion \u2014 egg yolk, acid (lemon or vinegar), and oil, whisked until stable. Same principle as hollandaise (fat suspended in water-based liquid via lecithin) but much more forgiving. Start with a small amount of oil and add it very slowly at first to establish the emulsion before adding more quickly.</p> <p>Full Meal: Seafood Rolls with Homemade Mayo + Classic Coleslaw</p> <p>Make the mayo from scratch. Use it in the roll filling and the coleslaw.</p> Component Recipe Protein Shrimp, scallop, or lobster roll Veg Coleslaw made with your homemade mayo Starch Brioche or potato rolls <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Mayonnaise \u2014 Watch the oil addition speed \u2014 this is where the emulsion either forms or breaks.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#session-8-the-vinaigrette-a-temporary-emulsion","title":"Session 8 \u2014 The Vinaigrette: A Temporary Emulsion","text":"<p>Skill: A vinaigrette is an unstable emulsion \u2014 oil and acid mixed together, which separate unless stabilized with an emulsifier like Dijon mustard or honey. The classic ratio is 3:1 oil to acid. Taste it on a piece of bread (not a spoon) to understand how it will actually taste on food.</p> <p>Full Meal: Pan-Seared Salmon Ni\u00e7oise Salad \u2014 a full composed dinner salad, not a side.</p> <p>Make the vinaigrette from scratch. Use it as the dressing and as a marinade for the salmon.</p> Component Recipe Protein Seared salmon or tuna Veg Green beans, olives, tomatoes, hard-boiled eggs Starch Boiled potatoes (dressed warm with the vinaigrette \u2014 they absorb it better) <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make a Ni\u00e7oise Salad \u2014 This is the exact dish \u2014 compare how he sequences the components and when the vinaigrette goes on.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#session-9-pan-sauce-the-working-sauce","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Pan Sauce: The Working Sauce","text":"<p>Skill: A pan sauce isn't one of the five mother sauces, but it's descended from all of them. After searing a protein, deglaze the pan (scraping the fond), reduce a liquid (wine, stock), and finish with butter. This is how restaurants make almost every sauce on their menu.</p> <p>Extension \u2014 Compound Butter: The simplest possible pan-sauce alternative: softened butter mixed with aromatics (herbs, garlic, lemon zest, anchovies, blue cheese) rolled in plastic wrap and refrigerated. Slice off a coin and place it on a hot steak or fish as it rests. It melts into an instant sauce. Make one tonight alongside the pork chops.</p> <p>Full Meal: Pork Chops with Apple-Cider Pan Sauce + compound butter (herb + garlic + lemon zest) + Roasted Sweet Potatoes + Simple Green Salad</p> Component Recipe Protein Pan-seared pork chops with apple-cider pan sauce Starch Roasted sweet potatoes Salad Simple green salad with your from-scratch vinaigrette <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Pan-Seared Pork Chops with Apple Pan Sauce \u2014 This is the exact dish \u2014 compare when he deglazes and how he reduces the sauce to a glaze.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#session-10-project-meal-a-classic-french-bistro-dinner-3-courses","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Classic French Bistro Dinner (3 Courses)","text":"<p>Skill: Ties together everything from Weeks 5\u20136. Pan sauce, vinaigrette, and a three-course French bistro-style dinner at home \u2014 everything on the table at the same time.</p> Course Dish Link Starter French Onion Dip with Homemade Potato Chips Recipe Main Steak Frites with Pan Sauce Recipe Salad Classic Lyonnaise Salad (Fris\u00e9e aux Lardons) Recipe <p>Skill targets: Properly executed pan sauce. Vinaigrette made from memory. Everything on the table at the same time.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#the-architecture-of-french-sauce","title":"The Architecture of French Sauce","text":"<p>The five mother sauces aren't really recipes \u2014 they're frameworks. Understanding the progression (mother \u2192 daughter sauces) transforms how you read any European recipe.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Butter-Basting: The Technique Behind Restaurant Flavor \u2014 A pan sauce technique that applies directly to everything you built this week.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Make Brown Butter \u2014 Beurre noisette is one step past clarified butter and one of the most useful flavors in cooking.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 BBC Good Food \u2014 Beurre Blanc \u2014 The emulsified white butter sauce: white wine, shallots, and cold butter whisked in just off the boil. The follow-on to hollandaise in terms of technique; the go-to sauce for poached fish and vegetables in French restaurants.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#emulsification-why-sauces-break-and-how-to-fix-them","title":"Emulsification: Why Sauces Break (and How to Fix Them)","text":"<p>The reason hollandaise breaks and mayonnaise holds is the same \u2014 it's all about emulsification. Understanding the physics lets you rescue disasters and prevent them.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Guide to Cooking With Wine \u2014 Wine reductions are the backbone of dozens of French pan sauces. What wine does when it cooks is worth understanding.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Jacques P\u00e9pin's omelette \u2014 His 30-second French omelette is a direct counterpart to what you've been building: technique over time, speed as the result of understanding.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Gordon Ramsay's pan sauce \u2014 Overexplained in some ways but very clear on the mechanics of building flavor in a pan after a sear.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Jacques P\u00e9pin: New Complete Techniques \u2014 The definitive classical French reference from the man who best bridges professional technique and home cooking. Goes deep on every sauce category.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Block 5\u20136 Quick Reference \u2014 The 5 Mother Sauces","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/quick-ref.html#block-5-recipes","title":"Block 5 Recipes","text":"Session Dish Sauce Link Session 1 Baked Mac and Cheese + Green Salad B\u00e9chamel \u2192 Mornay Mac &amp; Cheese \u00b7 Salad Session 2 Chicken Pot Pie + Green Salad Velout\u00e9 Pot Pie Session 3 \u23f0 Slow-Cooked Bolognese + Fresh Pasta + Caesar Salad Sauce Tomat Bolognese \u00b7 Caesar Session 4 Steak with Red Wine Pan Sauce + Mashed Potatoes + Roasted Broccolini Espagnole (simplified) Steak/Sauce \u00b7 Mash \u00b7 Broccolini Session 5 \u23f0 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Greek Moussaka + Greek Salad + Bread B\u00e9chamel + Sauce Tomat Moussaka \u00b7 Salad"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/quick-ref.html#block-6-recipes","title":"Block 6 Recipes","text":"Session Dish Sauce Link Session 6 Eggs Benedict with Hollandaise + Watercress Salad Hollandaise Eggs Benedict \u00b7 Salad Session 7 Seafood Roll + Classic Coleslaw Homemade Mayo Seafood Roll \u00b7 Coleslaw Session 8 Pan-Seared Salmon Ni\u00e7oise Salad Vinaigrette Ni\u00e7oise Session 9 Pork Chops with Apple-Cider Pan Sauce + Roasted Sweet Potatoes + Salad Pan sauce Pork Chops \u00b7 Sweet Potato Session 10 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: 3-Course French Bistro Dinner Pan sauce + Vinaigrette French Onion Dip \u00b7 Steak Frites \u00b7 Lyonnaise Salad"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/quick-ref.html#the-5-mother-sauces-cheat-sheet","title":"The 5 Mother Sauces \u2014 Cheat Sheet","text":"Sauce Base This Week's Dish B\u00e9chamel Butter + flour roux + milk Mac &amp; cheese, Moussaka top Velout\u00e9 Butter + flour roux + stock Chicken pot pie Espagnole Dark roux + dark stock + tomato Steak pan sauce (simplified) Sauce Tomat Tomato + mirepoix + pork fat Bolognese, Moussaka bottom Hollandaise Egg yolk + clarified butter (emulsion) Eggs Benedict <p>Ratio to memorize: Vinaigrette = 3 parts oil : 1 part acid + Dijon to stabilize.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 5\u20136: The 5 Mother Sauces","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Weeks 5\u20136 are butter, flour, and eggs weeks. Buy your dairy in full at the start \u2014 you'll go through more butter and milk than you expect. The moussaka (Week 5 Sat) and eggs benedict (Week 6 Mon) both require prep the day before.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/shopping-list.html#proteins","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins","text":"<p>Week 5: - [ ] Ground beef \u2014 1 lb (Bolognese + moussaka) - [ ] Ground pork \u2014 \u00bd lb (Bolognese \u2014 adds richness; can sub with all beef) - [ ] Pancetta or guanciale \u2014 4 oz (Bolognese) - [ ] Bone-in chicken thighs \u2014 4 pieces (chicken pot pie filling) - [ ] Ribeye or NY strip steaks \u2014 2 (Week 5 Fri red wine pan sauce) - [ ] Ground lamb (or more beef) \u2014 1 lb (moussaka meat layer)</p> <p>Week 6: - [ ] Canadian bacon (back bacon) \u2014 8 slices (Week 6 Mon Eggs Benedict) - [ ] Lobster (pre-cooked) or large shrimp \u2014 1 lb meat (Week 6 Tue seafood roll) - [ ] Salmon fillets \u2014 2 pieces (Week 6 Wed Ni\u00e7oise) - [ ] Bone-in pork chops (thick-cut, 1.5\") \u2014 2 (Week 6 Fri) - [ ] Thick-cut bacon or lardons \u2014 6 oz (Week 6 Sat Lyonnaise salad) - [ ] Ribeye or hanger steaks \u2014 2 (Week 6 Sat steak frites)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce","text":"<p>Week 5: - [ ] Eggplant \u2014 2 large (moussaka \u2014 salt and drain before using) - [ ] Potatoes (Yukon Gold) \u2014 4 lbs (2 lbs for moussaka base layer + 2 lbs for Week 5 Fri creamy mashed potatoes) - [ ] Carrots \u2014 3 (Bolognese mirepoix + pot pie) - [ ] Celery \u2014 1 bunch (Bolognese + pot pie) - [ ] Onions (yellow) \u2014 7 large (Bolognese mirepoix 2 + pot pie 1 + moussaka 2 + general use 2) - [ ] Broccolini \u2014 2 bunches (Week 5 Fri) - [ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads - [ ] Roma tomatoes \u2014 4 (Greek salad) - [ ] English cucumbers \u2014 2 (Greek salad) - [ ] Red onion \u2014 2 (Greek salad + Bolognese) - [ ] Fresh flat-leaf parsley \u2014 1 bunch - [ ] Mixed greens \u2014 2 bags (salads) - [ ] Romaine lettuce \u2014 2 hearts (Caesar salad)</p> <p>Week 6: - [ ] Watercress \u2014 2 bunches (Week 6 Mon) - [ ] Green cabbage \u2014 \u00bd head (coleslaw) - [ ] Carrots \u2014 2 (coleslaw) - [ ] Baby potatoes or fingerlings \u2014 1 lb (Ni\u00e7oise) - [ ] Green beans \u2014 \u00bd lb (Ni\u00e7oise) - [ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 1 pint (Ni\u00e7oise) - [ ] Sweet potatoes \u2014 2 large (Week 6 Fri) - [ ] Fris\u00e9e or endive \u2014 2 heads (Week 6 Sat Lyonnaise salad) - [ ] Yellow onions \u2014 5 large (Week 6 Sat French Onion Dip \u2014 needs long caramelization) - [ ] Apples \u2014 2 (apple-cider pan sauce for pork chops) - [ ] Russet potatoes \u2014 3 lbs (Week 6 Sat frites) - [ ] Lemons \u2014 4 - [ ] Fresh tarragon \u2014 1 small bunch (hollandaise + optional)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/shopping-list.html#dairy-eggs","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy &amp; Eggs","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 2 dozen minimum (hollandaise uses 4 yolks; Ni\u00e7oise needs hard-boiled; omelette practice; cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e next block. Buy extra.)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 4 sticks (beurre blanc, hollandaise, roux for b\u00e9chamel/velout\u00e9, mashed sauces)</li> <li>[ ] Whole milk \u2014 \u00bd gallon (b\u00e9chamel, moussaka topping, pot pie sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 pint (moussaka topping, pot pie, pork chop sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Sharp cheddar \u2014 8 oz, block (mac &amp; cheese)</li> <li>[ ] Gruy\u00e8re \u2014 8 oz (moussaka b\u00e9chamel + mac topping)</li> <li>[ ] Parmesan (block) \u2014 8 oz (Caesar + Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] Feta cheese \u2014 6 oz (Greek salad)</li> <li>[ ] Kalamata olives \u2014 1 jar (Greek salad + Ni\u00e7oise)</li> <li>[ ] Sour cream \u2014 1 cup (Week 6 Sat French Onion Dip base)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] All-purpose flour \u2014 2 cups (roux for 3 mother sauces this week)</li> <li>[ ] Elbow macaroni \u2014 1 lb (baked mac)</li> <li>[ ] Dried pasta (rigatoni or tagliatelle) \u2014 1 lb (Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] Dry breadcrumbs \u2014 1 cup (mac &amp; cheese topping)</li> <li>[ ] Puff pastry or pie dough \u2014 2 sheets (pot pie)</li> <li>[ ] Peas (frozen) \u2014 1 cup (pot pie)</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole peeled tomatoes \u2014 4 cans (Bolognese + shakshuka + moussaka)</li> <li>[ ] Tomato paste \u2014 1 small can</li> <li>[ ] Chicken stock \u2014 64 oz (pot pie velout\u00e9 + ramen)</li> <li>[ ] Beef stock \u2014 32 oz (pan sauces, moussaka)</li> <li>[ ] Red wine (full bottle, drinking quality) \u2014 1 (Bolognese + pan sauce)</li> <li>[ ] White wine (dry) \u2014 1 bottle (hollandaise, pan sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Apple cider or apple cider vinegar \u2014 1 bottle (Week 6 Fri pork chops)</li> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard \u2014 1 jar</li> <li>[ ] Capers \u2014 1 jar (Ni\u00e7oise salad)</li> <li>[ ] Tinned anchovies \u2014 1 can (Caesar salad)</li> <li>[ ] White wine vinegar \u2014 1 bottle (hollandaise poaching liquid)</li> <li>[ ] Cinnamon stick, allspice, bay leaves (moussaka \u2014 these make it taste right)</li> <li>[ ] Mayonnaise \u2014 1 jar (or make your own for coleslaw)</li> <li>[ ] Neutral oil \u2014 for frites (you'll need 1 quart of oil if deep-frying; shallow fry is easier)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/shopping-list.html#bread","title":"\ud83e\udd56 Bread","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Hot dog buns (top-split preferred) \u2014 4 (lobster/shrimp rolls, Week 6 Tue)</li> <li>[ ] English muffins \u2014 4 (Week 6 Mon Eggs Benedict)</li> <li>[ ] Crusty baguette (Week 5 Wed, for serving with Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] Crusty bread \u2014 1 loaf (Week 5 Sat moussaka)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/05-06-mother-sauces/shopping-list.html#notes","title":"\ud83d\udcdd Notes","text":"<p>Moussaka (Week 5 Sat) \u2014 the day-before prep: Slice eggplant, salt generously, and let drain on paper towels for 30 minutes. This removes bitterness and prevents a watery moussaka. B\u00e9chamel also benefits from being made fresh.</p> <p>Lobster rolls (Week 6 Tue): Pre-cooked whole lobster from a fishmonger is easiest. Or buy frozen lobster tails and steam them. Large shrimp are a fine substitute if lobster is cost-prohibitive.</p> <p>Steak frites (Week 6 Sat): Frites need a double-fry (once at 325\u00b0F to cook through, once at 375\u00b0F to crisp). Plan to start them 30 minutes before the steaks. Or make oven fries at 450\u00b0F \u2014 not quite the same but much less mess.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html","title":"\ud83e\udd5a Block 7\u20138: Stocks &amp; Eggs","text":"<p>\"Stocks are the foundation of professional cooking. Eggs are the chef's ultimate test.\"</p> <p>Quick Reference: \u2192 Block 7\u20138 Recipe Quick Ref</p> <p>\u2697\ufe0f Experimental \u2014 This block has not yet been cooked through by the author. Content is draft; recipes and timing are untested.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#before-you-start-block-7","title":"Before You Start Block 7","text":"<p>Read these first:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Difference Between Stock and Broth</li> </ul> <p>The Block 7 Rule: Get your frozen chicken carcass from Block 2 out of the freezer the night before the block starts. You're going to use it.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#session-1-soup-architecture","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Soup Architecture","text":"<p>Skill: Understanding soup as a category \u2014 not recipes, but architecture. Tonight you make one pur\u00e9e soup and learn how the same structure produces every pur\u00e9e soup in existence.</p> <p>This session is required \u2014 soup architecture is foundational to stock-building and flavor layering in everything that follows.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read first: How to Make Any Pur\u00e9e Soup \u2014 the technique scales to any vegetable.</p> <p>The five soup families \u2014 know these and you can improvise forever:</p> Family Technique Example Broth/consomm\u00e9 Clear liquid, flavored by solids Chicken noodle, pho, ramen broth Pur\u00e9e Cooked vegetables blended smooth; no cream needed Butternut squash, tomato, parsnip Cream soup Pur\u00e9e + cream or b\u00e9chamel for richness and texture Cream of mushroom, vichyssoise Bisque Shellfish shells simmered into the base; always cream-finished Lobster bisque, shrimp bisque Chowder Chunky; potato base; salt pork/bacon; cream-finished New England clam chowder, corn chowder <p>The universal pur\u00e9e method \u2014 memorize this, not any specific recipe: 1. Sweat aromatics (onion, leek, garlic, celery) in fat until soft \u2014 don't brown them 2. Add your main vegetable, cut uniformly so it cooks evenly 3. Add stock (just enough to cover); season lightly now, adjust at the end 4. Simmer until vegetables are completely tender \u2014 they should crush against the pot wall 5. Blend (immersion blender in the pot, or batches in a blender with the vent cracked) 6. Adjust consistency with stock; adjust seasoning. Finish with cream, butter, or acid.</p> <p>Full Meal: Roasted Butternut Squash Soup + crusty bread + simple salad</p> <p>The roasting step is optional but worth it: it caramelizes the squash and adds depth a boiled pur\u00e9e can't match.</p> <p>The professional difference between good and great pur\u00e9e soup: Seasoning at every stage (the aromatics, the stock, and the final adjust), and texture \u2014 it should be silky enough to coat a spoon without being so thick it's porridge. Strain it through a fine mesh sieve if it isn't smooth enough after blending.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Also read: How to Make Restaurant-Quality Stock at Home</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#block-7-stocks-broths","title":"Block 7 \u2014 Stocks &amp; Broths","text":"<p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 1 (Chicken Stock): 3\u20134 hrs of gentle simmering; start afternoon or earlier</li> <li>Session 5 (PROJECT: Beef Stock Day): start stock by 9 AM; 6\u20138 hrs passive + soup assembly at dinner</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#session-1-chicken-stock-from-scratch","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Chicken Stock from Scratch","text":"<p>Skill: Cold water start, gentle simmer (never boil), skim the foam in the first 20 minutes, don't stir. A good stock simmers for 3\u20134 hours. It should be golden, clear (not murky), and taste of chicken without being aggressively salty. Cool it in an ice bath, then refrigerate. A proper stock should gel when cold \u2014 that's the gelatin from the bones.</p> <p>This takes time but is mostly passive. Start it when you get home, let it simmer while you do other things.</p> <p>Full Meal: Quick Weeknight Ramen Using Homemade Stock</p> Component Recipe Broth Your homemade chicken stock, seasoned with soy and mirin Protein Soft-boiled eggs, chashu pork or rotisserie chicken, scallions Starch Ramen noodles"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#session-2-pan-sauces-from-real-stock","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Pan Sauces from Real Stock","text":"<p>Skill: Now that you have fresh stock, you understand why pan sauces taste so much better when made with real stock instead of water or canned broth. The gelatin creates body and silkiness that nothing else can replicate. Tonight's lesson: the difference is in your freezer.</p> <p>Full Meal: Chicken with Rich Pan Sauce (using your homemade stock) + Roasted Potatoes + Bitter Greens Salad</p> Component Recipe Protein Saut\u00e9ed chicken with a pan sauce made from your Block 7 stock Starch Crispy roasted potatoes Salad Bitter greens salad with a sharp vinaigrette"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#session-3-fish-stock-fumet","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Fish Stock + Fumet","text":"<p>Skill: Fish stock (fumet) takes only 20\u201330 minutes \u2014 fish bones give up their gelatin quickly and become bitter if cooked too long. Ask your fishmonger for frames (carcasses) or use shrimp shells. Aromatics are lighter: white wine, leek, fennel, parsley stems, bay leaf.</p> <p>Full Meal: Bouillabaisse \u2014 the classic Proven\u00e7al fish stew, built on your fresh fish stock</p> Component Recipe Protein Mixed seafood \u2014 shrimp, clams, white fish Stock Your fresh fish fumet Starch Grilled bread rubbed with garlic (rouille on the side) Veg Fennel, leek, tomato in the stew"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#session-4-vegetable-stock-risotto","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Vegetable Stock + Risotto","text":"<p>Skill: Vegetable stock is the quickest and most approachable. Key: don't over-simmer \u2014 45\u201360 minutes max, or it turns bitter. Tonight you'll use it immediately for risotto, which also teaches you another core technique: the gradual addition of hot liquid while stirring to coax starch from Arborio rice.</p> <p>Full Meal: Parmesan Risotto + Roasted Mushrooms + Simple Arugula Salad</p> Component Recipe Protein Roasted mushrooms (the star) + parmesan as umami Starch Risotto (the main dish) Salad Arugula alongside to cut richness"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#session-5-project-meal-a-whole-soup-kitchen-day","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Whole Soup Kitchen Day","text":"<p>The project session you make three things \u2014 stock, soup, and a complete dinner \u2014 that set you up with leftovers and frozen stock for weeks.</p> Time Task Recipe Morning Big batch beef/veal stock (6\u20138 hrs, mostly passive) Homemade Beef Stock Dinner French Onion Soup using your fresh beef stock French Onion Soup Sides Simple Green Salad + good bread Salad <p>Freeze the remaining stock in 1-cup portions. You now have stock in your freezer at all times. This changes your cooking permanently.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#block-8-eggs","title":"Block 8 \u2014 Eggs","text":"<p>\"A chef is judged by their eggs.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#before-you-start-block-8","title":"Before You Start Block 8","text":"<p>Block 8 dives straight into egg technique \u2014 no additional reading required. Sessions pick up below.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#session-6-the-french-scramble","title":"Session 6 \u2014 The French Scramble","text":"<p>Skill: French scrambled eggs are not American scrambled eggs. They're cooked low and slow, constantly stirred with a spatula, off and on the heat, until they form soft, creamy, barely-set curds. The result tastes like what restaurants serve for brunch at $22 a plate.</p> <p>Full Meal: French Scrambled Eggs + Smoked Salmon with Cr\u00e8me Fra\u00eeche + Toasted Sourdough + Simple Green Salad</p> <p>A French scramble dinner is a legitimately elegant meal when served with smoked salmon and a sharp green salad.</p> Component Recipe Protein French scrambled eggs + smoked salmon Starch Toasted sourdough Salad Simple green salad <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Really Good Scrambled Eggs \u2014 Same goal, different execution \u2014 notice how often he's moving the pan and when he pulls it off the heat entirely.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#session-7-the-perfect-poached-egg","title":"Session 7 \u2014 The Perfect Poached Egg","text":"<p>Skill: Fresh eggs, a wide shallow pan, simmering (not boiling) water with a splash of vinegar, a gentle swirl, and confidence. The white should be fully set and the yolk should run when broken. Most home cooks are afraid of poached eggs \u2014 by the end of tonight, you shouldn't be.</p> <p>Full Meal: Poached Eggs Over Saut\u00e9ed Greens with Crispy Bacon + Roasted Tomatoes + Toasted bread</p> Component Recipe Protein Poached eggs + crispy bacon Veg Wilted greens (kale or spinach), roasted cherry tomatoes Starch Good toast <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Truly Foolproof Poached Eggs \u2014 Watch the water temperature and the swirl \u2014 two details that determine whether you get a poached egg or a cloud of egg white.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#session-8-the-omelette","title":"Session 8 \u2014 The Omelette","text":"<p>Skill: The French omelette is one of the hardest things in cooking to get right \u2014 pale, barely colored outside, softly set inside, folded into a cylinder in under 2 minutes. Practice the French version until you get it right. Make two omelettes \u2014 one for practice, one to eat.</p> <p>Full Meal: The French Omelette + Classic Green Salad + Crusty bread</p> <p>A properly made omelette with a glass of wine and a green salad is one of the most satisfying dinners in existence.</p> Component Recipe Protein Two omelettes (one per person or two attempts) Filling Gruy\u00e8re, herbs, or mushrooms Salad Classic green salad with vinaigrette Starch Crusty bread <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make a French Omelette \u00b7 Want Perfect French Omelettes? Start With Water \u2014 Watch the wrist and the pan angle. The fold happens faster than you think it should.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#session-9-custard-eggs-as-thickener-quiche-lorraine","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Custard: Eggs as Thickener \u2014 Quiche Lorraine","text":"<p>Skill: Savory egg custard in a tart shell; cream-to-egg ratio; setting without overcooking.  Read first: Quiche Lorraine</p> <p>What you're learning: Quiche custard sets at 160\u2013165\u00b0F \u2014 the exact same temperature window you'll return to with cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e in Block 48. The ratio is 1 egg per \u00bc cup heavy cream; this scales to any savory tart. Overbaked quiche is grainy and rubbery; done correctly it is silky and sliceable. The tart shell can be store-bought this session \u2014 the custard technique is the entire point.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Quiche Lorraine (lardons + Gruy\u00e8re + chive) - Simple green salad with mustard vinaigrette</p> Component Notes Shell Store-bought shortcrust \u2014 pastry dough is covered fully in Block 47 Custard 3 eggs + \u00be cup heavy cream + salt + white pepper Cheese Gruy\u00e8re grated fresh; pre-shredded bags have coatings that prevent clean melting Bake 325\u00b0F, 30\u201340 min; pull when center still has a gentle wobble <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Quiche Lorraine (Claire Saffitz) \u2014 Watch her custard pour and the oven pull moment \u2014 those two steps are the whole skill.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#session-10-project-meal-a-complete-egg-dinner-party-3-courses","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Complete Egg Dinner Party (3 Courses)","text":"<p>The challenge: Cook a 3-course egg-forward dinner for at least two people, without recipes open in front of you during service.</p> Course Dish Link Starter Deviled Eggs (vehicle for your homemade mayo from Block 6) Recipe Main Shakshuka (scaled up, served family-style with salad and bread) Recipe Dessert Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e (classic baked egg custard, finished with a torch) Recipe <p>Skill targets: Proper custard texture in the cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e. Perfectly poached eggs in the shakshuka. Smooth, properly seasoned deviled egg filling from scratch.</p> <p>You've been cooking for eight weeks with deliberate intention. Before Block 9 (Seasoning &amp; Flavor Building), write five sentences:</p> <ol> <li>What is the technique you're most proud of?</li> <li>What still feels unnatural?</li> <li>What recipe from the past 8 weeks did you want to make again?</li> <li>What did you learn that changed how you think about food?</li> <li>What do you want to tackle in the next 8 weeks?</li> </ol>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#module-1-checkpoint","title":"Module 1 Checkpoint","text":"<p>Before you move on to Module 2 (Building Flavor), take stock of where you are. The next module assumes everything here is solid.</p> <p>This is not graded. It is honest.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#knife-benchmark-repeat-from-block-12","title":"Knife Benchmark (repeat from Block 1\u20132)","text":"<p>Set a timer. Brunoise one medium onion. Stop the timer when you're done.</p> Block 1\u20132 time Today's time \u0394 _____ min _____ min _____ <p>If your time has improved by more than 20%, your knife skills are compounding. If not \u2014 that's useful information too, not a failure. Return to the Block 1\u20132 onion exercise on a the project session before Block 9.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#cook-from-memory-test","title":"Cook-From-Memory Test","text":"<p>Without opening any recipe, cook one of the following from scratch:</p> <ul> <li>A velout\u00e9 or b\u00e9chamel (one of the mother sauces from Blocks 5\u20136)</li> <li>A properly seasoned chicken stock (Blocks 7\u20138)</li> <li>A three-component dinner: seared protein + pan sauce + simply cooked vegetable</li> </ul> <p>The only rule: once anything goes on heat, no tabs open.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#skills-checklist","title":"Skills Checklist","text":"<p>Before Module 2, you should be able to answer yes to all of these:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] I can julienne, brunoise, and chiffonade without looking up how</li> <li>[ ] I understand the difference between saut\u00e9, sear, braise, poach, and steam \u2014 and when to use each</li> <li>[ ] I can make at least two of the five mother sauces from memory</li> <li>[ ] I can make a proper stock (bones, mirepoix, cold water, long simmer, strain)</li> <li>[ ] I can cook an egg five different ways and explain what I'm doing and why</li> <li>[ ] My knife is sharp and I know how to maintain it</li> </ul> <p>If you're checking all of these: you're ready for Module 2.</p> <p>If you have two or more unchecked: spend the start of Block 9 revisiting the weak spots before committing to the new material. It's worth it.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#the-truth-about-stock","title":"The Truth About Stock","text":"<p>Stock is the most important prep you can do. The difference between a sauce made with real stock versus carton stock is the difference between a restaurant dish and a home-cooked dish.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Chicken Stock vs. Broth: What's the Difference? \u2014 This gets misunderstood constantly. Read this once and you'll never confuse them again.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#egg-science","title":"Egg Science","text":"<p>You cooked eggs five ways this week. Understanding the protein science \u2014 why they set at different temperatures, why salting before vs. after matters \u2014 unlocks every egg technique that exists.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Gordon Ramsay Was Wrong About Salting Scrambled Eggs \u2014 A properly controlled test on one of cooking's most debated questions. The answer will change how you make scrambled eggs.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Do 'Better' Eggs Really Taste Better? \u2014 Kenji runs the experiment so you don't have to. Includes what labels actually mean and when they matter.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Perfect Hard-Boiled Eggs \u2014 Everything you need to know about the hidden complexity in the simplest egg preparation.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda On Food and Cooking by Harold McGee \u2014 The original deep dive into food science. The egg chapter alone justifies the entire book. Not a cookbook \u2014 a reference work that explains why everything in the kitchen works.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Block 7\u20138 Quick Reference \u2014 Stocks &amp; Eggs","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/quick-ref.html#block-7-recipes","title":"Block 7 Recipes","text":"Session Dish Notes Link Session 1 \u23f0 Quick Weeknight Ramen (homemade chicken stock) Use the Block 2 carcass Ramen Session 2 Saut\u00e9ed Chicken with Pan Sauce (homemade stock) + Roasted Potatoes + Bitter Greens Salad Stock = silky pan sauce Chicken \u00b7 Potatoes \u00b7 Salad Session 3 Bouillabaisse (fish fumet) + Grilled Garlic Bread + Rouille 20\u201330 min fish stock only Bouillabaisse Session 4 Parmesan Risotto + Roasted Mushrooms + Arugula Salad Vegetable stock (make first) Risotto \u00b7 Mushrooms \u00b7 Salad Session 5 \u23f0 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Beef Stock (all day) \u2192 French Onion Soup (dinner) + Green Salad Freeze leftover stock in 1-cup portions Beef Stock \u00b7 French Onion Soup \u00b7 Salad"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/quick-ref.html#block-8-recipes","title":"Block 8 Recipes","text":"Session Dish Egg Technique Link Session 6 French Scrambled Eggs + Smoked Salmon + Toasted Sourdough + Greens Salad Low &amp; slow scramble Scramble \u00b7 Salmon Session 7 Poached Eggs over Saut\u00e9ed Greens + Crispy Bacon + Roasted Tomatoes + Toast Poach Poached Eggs \u00b7 Tomatoes Session 8 French Omelette + Green Salad + Crusty Bread Fold/omelette Omelette Session 9 Pasta Carbonara + Bitter Greens Salad Egg custard (savory) Carbonara \u00b7 Salad Session 10 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: 3-Course Egg Dinner \u2014 Deviled Eggs \u00b7 Shakshuka \u00b7 Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e All of them Deviled Eggs \u00b7 Shakshuka \u00b7 Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/quick-ref.html#stock-cheat-sheet","title":"Stock Cheat Sheet","text":"Stock Time Gelatin Source Don't Chicken 3\u20134 hrs Bones + carcass Boil \u2014 gentle simmer only Fish (fumet) 20\u201330 min Fish frames/shrimp shells Go longer \u2014 turns bitter Vegetable 45\u201360 min None (no gelatin) Over-simmer \u2014 turns bitter Beef/veal 6\u20138 hrs Bones + knuckles Rush it <p>Freeze in 1-cup portions. This changes your cooking permanently.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 7\u20138: Stocks &amp; Eggs","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Week 7 is about using your stock. Get the Week 2 chicken carcass out of the freezer on Sunday night to thaw. Week 8 is egg week \u2014 buy 3 dozen eggs. You will use all of them.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#pre-week-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Pre-Week Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Week 2 chicken carcass from the freezer \u2014 this is your Week 7 Monday stock. If you didn't save it, buy a raw chicken carcass from your butcher or supermarket.</li> <li>[ ] Week 7 Saturday: Buy beef bones (knuckle bones and marrow bones) for beef stock \u2014 order ahead or request from your butcher. You need 3\u20134 lbs.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-7","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 7","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Chicken pieces (thighs + drumsticks) \u2014 4 pieces (Week 7 Tue pan sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed seafood for bouillabaisse: shrimp (\u00bd lb), mussels (1 lb), clams (1 lb), cod or halibut chunks (1 lb), or 1 lb monkfish \u2014 (Week 7 Wed)</li> <li>[ ] Shrimp shells (or save from above) \u2014 freeze for quick shrimp stock or fumet base</li> <li>[ ] Beef knuckle and/or marrow bones \u2014 3\u20134 lbs (Week 7 Sat beef stock, all day project)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-8","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 8","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 3 dozen (every method this week: scrambles, poaches, omelettes, carbonara, deviled, shakshuka, cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e)</li> <li>[ ] Hot-smoked salmon or lox \u2014 4 oz (Week 8 Mon)</li> <li>[ ] Thick-cut bacon \u2014 6 oz (Week 8 Tue + Week 8 Sat deviled eggs garnish)</li> <li>[ ] Guanciale or pancetta (thick pieces) \u2014 4 oz (Week 8 Fri carbonara)</li> <li>[ ] Whole milk or heavy cream \u2014 1 pint (Week 8 Sat cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e \u2014 use full-fat cream)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#produce-week-7","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 7","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Yellow onions \u2014 6 large (Week 7 Sat French onion soup + stock mirepoix)</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 6 (stock vegetables + week meals)</li> <li>[ ] Celery \u2014 1 bunch (stock vegetables)</li> <li>[ ] Fennel \u2014 1 bulb (bouillabaisse + stock)</li> <li>[ ] Leeks \u2014 2 (vegetable stock, Week 7 Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Mushrooms (cremini or mixed) \u2014 1 lb (Week 7 Fri risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Butternut squash \u2014 1 medium (Session 0 Soup Architecture / Week 7 roasted pur\u00e9e soup)</li> <li>[ ] Potatoes (Yukon Gold) \u2014 1.5 lbs (Week 7 Tue crispy roasted potatoes)</li> <li>[ ] Arugula \u2014 2 bags (Week 7 Fri salad + Week 8 Fri salad)</li> <li>[ ] Bitter greens (radicchio, endive) \u2014 1 head each (Week 7 Tue salad)</li> <li>[ ] Scallions \u2014 1 bunch (Week 7 Mon ramen garnish)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Fresh thyme, parsley, bay leaves \u2014 1 bunch each (stocks)</li> <li>[ ] Tomatoes or canned tomatoes \u2014 2 cans (bouillabaisse)</li> <li>[ ] Saffron \u2014 1 small tin (bouillabaisse \u2014 expensive but essential)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#produce-week-8","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 8","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Baby spinach or Swiss chard \u2014 1 bag (Week 8 Tue poached eggs)</li> <li>[ ] Roma tomatoes \u2014 4 (Week 8 Tue oven roasted)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed greens \u2014 1 bag (Week 8 Mon green salad + Week 8 Wed omelette night salad)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh chives \u2014 1 bunch (Week 8 Mon scrambled eggs + omelette)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh tarragon \u2014 1 small bunch (omelette filling, optional)</li> <li>[ ] Sourdough bread \u2014 1 loaf (Week 8 Mon toast + omelette bread)</li> <li>[ ] Baguette or crusty bread \u2014 1 (Week 8 Wed)</li> <li>[ ] Canned tomatoes \u2014 2 cans (Week 8 Sat shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Red bell pepper \u2014 2 (shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Yellow onion \u2014 2 (shakshuka + French onion soup Sat if making again)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#dairy","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 4 sticks (Week 8 omelettes use a lot; Week 7 risotto finishing)</li> <li>[ ] Cr\u00e8me fra\u00eeche or sour cream \u2014 1 tub (Week 8 Mon with smoked salmon)</li> <li>[ ] Parmesan (block) \u2014 8 oz (Week 7 risotto + Week 8 carbonara)</li> <li>[ ] Pecorino Romano \u2014 4 oz (Week 8 Fri carbonara \u2014 use together with parmesan)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 pint (Week 8 Sat cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e needs 2 cups)</li> <li>[ ] Gruy\u00e8re \u2014 6 oz (Week 7 Sat French onion soup topping)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Arborio or Carnaroli rice \u2014 1.5 cups (Week 7 Fri risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Ramen noodles \u2014 4 servings (Week 7 Mon)</li> <li>[ ] Spaghetti or rigatoni \u2014 1 lb (Week 8 Fri carbonara)</li> <li>[ ] Dry white wine \u2014 1 bottle (risotto + pan sauces)</li> <li>[ ] Red wine \u2014 1 bottle (Week 7 Sat French onion soup braising base)</li> <li>[ ] Beef stock \u2014 64 oz (Week 7 Tue pan sauce + Week 7 Sat French onion soup)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken stock \u2014 64 oz (risotto + ramen base)</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 1 bottle (ramen seasoning)</li> <li>[ ] Mirin \u2014 1 bottle (ramen tare)</li> <li>[ ] Kombu \u2014 a few strips (ramen base \u2014 found at Asian grocery stores or Amazon)</li> <li>[ ] White wine vinegar (ramen seasoning, risotto touch)</li> <li>[ ] Granulated sugar \u2014 1 cup (Week 8 Sat cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e)</li> <li>[ ] Vanilla beans \u2014 2 (cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e \u2014 or 1 tsp pure vanilla extract)</li> <li>[ ] Mayo, Dijon, paprika, capers \u2014 small amounts (Week 8 Sat deviled eggs)</li> <li>[ ] Tinned anchovies \u2014 1 can (Week 8 Fri bitter greens salad with anchovy vinaigrette)</li> <li>[ ] Cumin, smoked paprika, chili flakes \u2014 (Week 8 Sat shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Rouille ingredients: jarred roasted red peppers, garlic, breadcrumbs (bouillabaisse)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#bread","title":"\ud83e\udd56 Bread","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Baguette \u2014 2 loaves (Week 7 Sat French onion soup + general use)</li> <li>[ ] Thick-sliced sourdough \u2014 1 loaf (Week 8 Mon + Wed)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#equipment-nice-to-have-for-this-block","title":"\ud83d\udd27 Equipment (Nice to Have for This Block)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Kitchen torch \u2014 for cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e (Week 8 Sat). Can substitute: broiler works, but you have less control. A cheap culinary torch costs less than $20.</li> <li>[ ] Fine mesh strainer (chinois) \u2014 essential for clarifying stocks. If you don't have one, a colander lined with cheesecloth works.</li> <li>[ ] Stockpot (8+ quart) \u2014 if you're making proper beef stock on Week 7 Saturday.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/01-foundational-skills/07-08-stocks-and-eggs/shopping-list.html#notes","title":"\ud83d\udcdd Notes","text":"<p>Beef stock (Week 7 Sat) is an all-day project. Roast the bones at 450\u00b0F for 45 minutes first (this is what makes beef stock different from chicken stock). Then 6\u20138 hours of simmering. Start by 10 AM.</p> <p>Carbonara (Week 8 Fri) \u2014 no cream. Real carbonara is eggs, cheese, pasta water, and guanciale. The heat from the pasta cooks the eggs into a silky custard. Take the pan fully off the heat before adding the egg mixture. Temperature is everything.</p> <p>Cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e (Week 8 Sat) \u2014 make it the day before. They need 4\u20136 hours to set in the fridge after baking. Br\u00fbl\u00e9e the tops right before serving.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/index.html","title":"Module 2: Building Flavor (Block 9\u201316)","text":"<p>The goal of this module: Move beyond technique into taste. Learn how salt, acid, fat, and heat interact to build layered flavor \u2014 then apply that understanding to one of the most satisfying skill sets in the kitchen: fresh pasta, handmade grains, and confident poultry cookery.</p> <p>By the end of Week 14, your palate should be a tool as reliable as your knife.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/index.html#weeks-in-this-module","title":"Weeks in This Module","text":"Weeks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 9\u201310 Seasoning &amp; Flavor Building \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 11\u201312 Vegetables &amp; Plant-Forward Cooking \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 13\u201314 Pasta &amp; Grains from Scratch \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 15\u201316 Module 2 Capstone: Poultry &amp; Flavor Review \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/index.html#core-skills-covered","title":"Core Skills Covered","text":"<ul> <li>Seasoning \u2014 salting at the right moment, finishing acids, building depth with fat; tasting analytically</li> <li>Flavor layering \u2014 aromatics, fond, deglazing, reduction; how flavor compounds develop and stack</li> <li>Vegetables \u2014 blanching and shocking; high-heat roasting; charring; pur\u00e9e method; quick-pickling and lacto-fermentation</li> <li>Fresh pasta \u2014 dough by hand and machine, lamination, rolling to thickness, cutting tagliatelle and pappardelle</li> <li>Grains \u2014 pilaf method, risotto technique, polenta ratios; the difference between toasting and not</li> <li>Poultry \u2014 breaking down a whole chicken; roasting, pan-saucing, and braising; carryover cooking</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/index.html#equipment-youll-need","title":"Equipment You'll Need","text":"<p>See the Kitchen Equipment Guide. New items introduced in this module:</p> Item Introduced Mandoline slicer Week 11 Fine-mesh sieve Week 11 Potato ricer Week 13 Pasta machine (or rolling pin) Week 13 Large pasta pot (8+ qt) Week 13 <p>Previous module: Module 1 \u2014 Foundational Skills (Weeks 1\u20138) Next module: Module 3 \u2014 The Proteins (Weeks 17\u201328)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Block 9\u201310: Seasoning &amp; Flavor Building","text":"<p>\u2190 Quick Reference \u2192 | Shopping List \u2192</p> <p>Where we are: Knife skills done. Heat methods done. Mother sauces done. Stocks and eggs done. Now we go deeper \u2014 into the invisible architecture of flavor itself.</p> <p>\"Salt makes food taste more like itself. Acid makes it taste more alive. Fat makes it taste more satisfying. Understanding all three changes everything.\"</p> <p>The core idea for these two weeks: Most home cooks season once, at the end, with a generic shake of salt and pepper. Professional cooks season in layers \u2014 each component seasoned individually, each layer building on the last. By the end of Week 10, you should never walk away from a dish thinking \"something's missing\" without knowing exactly what that something is.</p> <p>Before you start Week 9, read these two pieces back to back:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 The Food Lab: The Science of Salt \u2014 Why salt is more than a flavoring; how it restructures proteins, manages moisture, and builds flavor from the inside out</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 Why Every Recipe Should Have Acid \u2014 The most underused tool in the home cook's arsenal</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#block-9-salt-when-what-and-why","title":"Block 9 \u2014 Salt: When, What, and Why","text":"<p>The lesson: salt behaves differently at different stages of cooking, and learning to recognize what your food is missing \u2014 flat? dull? one-dimensional? \u2014 is more valuable than any single technique.</p> <p>The Week 9 experiment (do this before the block starts): Take a carrot. Cut it in two. Salt one half with a pinch of kosher salt and wait two minutes. Taste both back to back. The salted carrot will taste more carrot-y \u2014 brighter, sweeter, more itself. That's the point. Salt doesn't make food taste salty. It makes food taste like food.</p> <p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 1 (Brined Chicken Thighs): dry-brine the night before your first session</li> <li>Session 10 (Miso-Glazed Cod Project): apply miso marinade 24\u201348 hrs ahead; start two days before</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#session-1-early-salt-brining","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Early Salt: Brining","text":"<p>Skill: Dry-brining (salting well in advance) allows salt to penetrate proteins deeply, seasoning from within rather than just the surface. The meat loses moisture initially, which is then reabsorbed as a concentrated, seasoned brine. The result: more flavorful, more evenly seasoned meat, and \u2014 as a bonus \u2014 drier skin that crisps better in the oven. Tonight you'll dry-brine chicken thighs in the morning and cook them at dinner.</p> <p>Before you leave for work or start your day: Pat 4\u20136 bone-in, skin-on chicken thighs dry, season generously with kosher salt (about \u00be tsp per pound), place on a rack over a sheet pan, and refrigerate uncovered. Come back to them at dinner.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Crispy-Skinned Chicken Thighs (use your dry-brined thighs) + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Broccoli with Garlic + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Arugula Salad with Lemon Vinaigrette</p> <p>Before you season the broccoli, taste a raw floret. Season it with salt and taste again. Notice the difference before it goes in the oven.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Dry-brined chicken thighs, seared until the skin is lacquer-crisp</li> <li>Veg: Roasted broccoli, each floret seasoned before roasting</li> <li>Salad: Arugula with shaved parmesan and a sharp lemon vinaigrette</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Dry Brining Is the Easiest Way to Improve Any Roast \u2014 A 60-second demonstration of the exact technique you're using tonight \u2014 notice that the salt goes on much earlier than most people think.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#session-2-during-salt-layered-seasoning","title":"Session 2 \u2014 During Salt: Layered Seasoning","text":"<p>Skill: Tonight, season every single component of your dish at the moment it goes into the pan \u2014 not just at the beginning or the end. Salt the onions when they go in. Salt the garlic when you add it. Salt the tomatoes when they hit the pan. Taste after each addition. You're building flavor in layers, not slapping it on at the end.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Pasta all'Amatriciana + Serious Eats \u2014 Classic Caesar Salad</p> <p>Amatriciana is one of the great Roman pasta sauces \u2014 guanciale (or pancetta), white wine, tomato, pecorino. Each component is distinct and requires its own seasoning moment. It's a perfect layering teacher.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Guanciale or pancetta, crisped in the pan and layered through the sauce</li> <li>Starch: Bucatini or rigatoni \u2014 both are traditional</li> <li>Salad: Classic Caesar alongside \u2014 learn to taste and adjust the dressing before it goes on the leaves</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Food Lab Basics: POV Bucatini All'Amatriciana \u2014 Watch when he seasons at each stage \u2014 count how many separate times salt or salty ingredients go in before the dish is done.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#session-3-late-salt-finishing","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Late Salt: Finishing","text":"<p>Skill: Some things should not be salted early. Delicate fish toughens if salted too far in advance. Soups and braises that reduce become dangerously salty if heavily salted at the start. Finishing salts \u2014 flaky Maldon, fleur de sel \u2014 exist to add texture and a burst of flavor right at the moment of eating. They should never dissolve. Tonight you'll deliberately hold salt until the final moment and let a finishing salt do the work.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Pan-Seared Halibut or Sea Bass with a squeeze of lemon and a pinch of Maldon flakes right at plating + Serious Eats \u2014 White Bean Salad with Olive Oil and Herbs + Serious Eats \u2014 Saut\u00e9ed Cherry Tomatoes</p> <p>The white bean salad benefits enormously from being dressed early (the beans absorb the seasoning) while the fish is seasoned only at the very end. Two different salt strategies on the same plate, by design.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Pan-seared white fish, seasoned only right before going in the pan and finished with Maldon flakes</li> <li>Veg: Saut\u00e9ed cherry tomatoes, blistered in olive oil</li> <li>Starch/Salad: White bean salad with olive oil, lemon, and fresh herbs \u2014 dressed 20 minutes ahead so the beans absorb the seasoning</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#session-4-salt-as-texture-and-contrast","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Salt as Texture and Contrast","text":"<p>Skill: Tonight's focus is on salt as a textural and contrast element. A finishing salt on a rich braise doesn't just season \u2014 it provides crunch and a burst of concentrated flavor that cuts through the fat. A well-salted pasta water (it should taste \"pleasantly seasoned,\" like a light broth) actually seasons the pasta from within, not just its surface. Both are explored tonight.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Cacio e Pepe + Serious Eats \u2014 Bitter Greens Salad with Anchovy Vinaigrette + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Cauliflower with Crispy Capers</p> <p>Cacio e Pepe is three ingredients: pasta, pecorino, black pepper. There is nowhere to hide. The pasta water must be well-salted. The cheese is the only seasoning. This dish teaches you precision \u2014 and it's one of the best things you can make.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Pecorino and parmesan (the sauce is the protein component here)</li> <li>Starch: Tonnarelli or spaghetti</li> <li>Veg: Roasted cauliflower with crispy capers \u2014 the capers add a salty, briny pop that is the finishing-salt concept in action</li> <li>Salad: Bitter greens to cut through the richness</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Cacio e Pepe \u2014 Three ingredients. Watch how he uses pasta water to build a sauce, not just coat the noodles. That emulsification is the whole technique.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#session-5-project-meal-salt-crusted-whole-roasted-fish","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: Salt-Crusted Whole Roasted Fish","text":"<p>Skill: Salt-crusting is an ancient technique where a whole fish (or chicken or beet) is encased in a thick crust of kosher salt before roasting. The salt absorbs moisture from the surface, seasons the interior gently, and creates a steaming environment inside the crust. The result is the most evenly cooked, delicately seasoned fish you will ever eat at home. Cracking the crust at the table is genuinely theatrical.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Salt-Crusted Whole Roasted Fish + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Fingerling Potatoes with Herbs + Serious Eats \u2014 Fennel and Orange Salad</p> <p>This is one of the most impressive things you can serve to guests and it requires almost no active cooking skill \u2014 just good salt technique and confidence.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Whole branzino or red snapper, salt-crusted and roasted</li> <li>Starch: Crispy roasted fingerling potatoes, dressed with herbs and flaky salt at the end</li> <li>Salad: Fennel and orange salad \u2014 light, acidic, a perfect counterpoint to the fish</li> </ul> <p>Skill targets: A properly sealed salt crust (no cracks before roasting). Even internal temperature of 130\u2013135\u00b0F at the thickest point. Confident tableside crack-and-reveal.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#block-10-acid-fat-and-the-fifth-taste","title":"Block 10 \u2014 Acid, Fat, and the Fifth Taste","text":"<p>The lesson: seasoning is not just salt. Acid brightens. Fat carries and extends. Umami deepens. Knowing which one is missing from a flat dish is the difference between following a recipe and actually cooking.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#session-6-acid-the-brightness-lever","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Acid: The Brightness Lever","text":"<p>Skill: Acid \u2014 lemon juice, vinegar, wine, citrus zest \u2014 does something salt cannot: it lifts and brightens flavors, making food taste fresher and more vibrant. Most dishes benefit from a small hit of acid right at the end of cooking, before serving. Tonight you'll cook a dish twice in your mind: once without the final acid, once with. The difference is immediately obvious.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Chicken Marsala + Serious Eats \u2014 Creamy Mashed Potatoes + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Green Salad with Sharp Dijon Vinaigrette</p> <p>Before you finish the Marsala sauce, taste it. Now add a small squeeze of lemon and taste again. Notice how the whole sauce comes into focus. That is acid as a lever.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Chicken Marsala \u2014 mushrooms, Marsala wine, a final hit of lemon</li> <li>Starch: Mashed potatoes (their richness is exactly what needs the acid in the salad to balance the plate)</li> <li>Salad: Sharp Dijon vinaigrette salad \u2014 the acidic foil for the rich main</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#session-7-different-acids-different-effects","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Different Acids, Different Effects","text":"<p>Skill: Not all acid is the same. Lemon juice is bright and immediate. Red wine vinegar is assertive and fruity. Sherry vinegar is mellow and nutty. White balsamic is sweet and gentle. Tamarind is deep and complex. Tonight you'll use two different acids in two different components of the same meal and taste the difference.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Glazed Pork Tenderloin with Balsamic Reduction + Serious Eats \u2014 Lentil Salad with Sherry Vinaigrette + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Carrots with Cumin</p> <p>Balsamic on the pork: sweet, deep, slightly caramelized. Sherry vinegar in the lentil salad: dry, nutty, assertive. Two acids, two entirely different effects.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Pork tenderloin with balsamic glaze</li> <li>Starch/Salad: Warm French lentil salad with sherry vinaigrette</li> <li>Veg: Roasted carrots with cumin</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#session-8-fat-as-flavor","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Fat as Flavor","text":"<p>Skill: Fat is not just a cooking medium or a source of richness. Different fats carry fundamentally different flavors: brown butter is nutty and toasty; extra-virgin olive oil is grassy and peppery; duck fat is savory and deep; bacon fat is smoky and umami-forward. Tonight you cook the same vegetable three different ways \u2014 once in each of three fats \u2014 and taste the difference.</p> <p>The mini-experiment: Before dinner, saut\u00e9 three small batches of green beans \u2014 one in neutral canola oil, one in good extra-virgin olive oil, one in butter with a little brown at the end. Taste each with just a pinch of salt. The difference is the fat speaking.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Brown Butter Gnocchi with Crispy Sage + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Mushrooms with Thyme + Serious Eats \u2014 Bitter Greens Salad</p> <p>Brown butter is fat transformed \u2014 milk solids toasted to a deep hazelnut color, releasing a complex, nutty flavor that coats the gnocchi and makes the dish. Tonight fat is the whole story.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: The sage and parmesan carry the protein element</li> <li>Starch: Potato gnocchi, tossed in brown butter and crispy sage</li> <li>Veg: Roasted mushrooms alongside</li> <li>Salad: Bitter greens to cut through all that butter</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Spring Vegetable Gnocchi \u2014 Different filling, same brown butter sauce technique \u2014 watch how the butter goes from golden to hazelnut and how the gnocchi absorb the fat.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#session-9-umami-the-depth-dial","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Umami: The Depth Dial","text":"<p>Skill: Umami is the fifth taste \u2014 the savory, lingering depth you get from glutamate-rich ingredients: aged parmesan, soy sauce, miso, fish sauce, anchovies, dried mushrooms, tomato paste. Tonight you'll learn to use umami ingredients as seasoning, not as central flavors \u2014 a tablespoon of fish sauce where you'd normally add salt, a smear of miso in a braise, a parmesan rind dropped into a soup pot. They should deepen the dish without announcing themselves.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Umami-Packed Mushroom Pasta + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan + Serious Eats \u2014 Arugula Salad with Shaved Parmesan</p> <p>This pasta uses anchovies (umami), mushrooms (umami), and tomato (umami) in combination. None of them taste like themselves in the finished dish \u2014 together they create a savory depth that makes you want to keep eating. The parmesan on the asparagus and the salad keeps the umami thread running through the whole meal.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Anchovies melted into the sauce (they disappear \u2014 trust the process)</li> <li>Starch: Spaghetti or rigatoni</li> <li>Veg: Asparagus with shaved parmesan \u2014 the parmesan is doing seasoning work here</li> <li>Salad: Arugula with more parmesan and lemon</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Pasta Puttanesca \u2014 Same principle: anchovies and olives as hidden umami, not as the headline flavors. Watch how they disappear into the sauce while deepening it.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#session-10-project-meal-a-composed-tasting-plate","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Composed Tasting Plate","text":"<p>The challenge: The project session isn't about following a single recipe. It's about applying everything from Weeks 9\u201310 in one deliberate meal. You'll cook a three-component plate and consciously think about salt timing, acid balance, fat choice, and umami depth for each component.</p> <p>Suggested composed plate:</p> <ol> <li>Protein: Serious Eats \u2014 Miso-Glazed Black Cod \u2014 umami from the miso marinade, fat from the fish, a hit of rice vinegar for acid in the glaze</li> <li>Grain: Serious Eats \u2014 Saffron Risotto alla Milanese \u2014 salt-seasoned at every stage, finished with butter (fat) and parmesan (umami), a squeeze of lemon at the end (acid)</li> <li>Salad: Serious Eats \u2014 Fennel and Citrus Salad \u2014 acid-forward, a deliberate foil to the rich risotto and fish</li> </ol> <p>Before you plate everything, taste each component and ask: Is it salty enough? Does it need acid? Is the fat coming through? Is there depth? Adjust one thing at a time.</p> <p>Skill targets: Each component consciously seasoned, not just salted. A finished dish where all four elements \u2014 salt, acid, fat, umami \u2014 are present and in balance.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#salt-when-to-add-it-and-why-it-matters","title":"Salt: When to Add It and Why It Matters","text":"<p>The single biggest improvement most home cooks can make is learning to salt earlier and more confidently. The science backs it up.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Dry-Brining Is the Best Way to Brine Meat, Poultry, and More \u2014 Salting in advance isn't just about flavor \u2014 it transforms texture. This is the technique that restaurants use.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How and When to Brine Vegetables \u2014 The same principle applied to produce. Salting a cucumber vs. a tomato vs. eggplant before cooking changes everything.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#spice-blends-marinades-seasoning-with-depth","title":"Spice Blends &amp; Marinades: Seasoning with Depth","text":"<p>Spice blends are dry-rub seasoning applied before cooking \u2014 essentially a flavored version of the dry-brining technique from Session 1. Marinades are liquid equivalents (acid + fat + spice) that season the surface and, over longer contact time, begin to alter texture.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 Garam Masala \u2014 How to build a spice blend from scratch: toasting whole spices, grinding, balancing. The principle transfers to every spice blend (ras el hanout, za\u2019atar, Chinese five-spice). Once you've made one from scratch, you understand all of them.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 Chimichurri \u2014 The herbaceous Argentine marinade/sauce; a model for understanding how acid (vinegar), fat (oil), and a punch of fresh herb work together as a marinade or a finishing sauce.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#acid-the-underused-seasoning","title":"Acid: The Underused Seasoning","text":"<p>Salt gets all the attention, but acid is what makes a dish taste complete. A squeeze of lemon or a splash of vinegar at the end is often all a dish needs.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 6 Chemistry-Based Cooking Tricks That Actually Make Food Better \u2014 A quick tour of how pH affects color, texture, and flavor in cooking. The sections on finishing with acid and on blanching vegetables are directly applicable to everything you cooked this week.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Samin Nosrat's Salt Fat Acid Heat \u2014 Four episodes, each focused on one of this week's themes. Her episode on salt is the best explanation of when and how to salt that exists on screen.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Salt Fat Acid Heat by Samin Nosrat \u2014 This week's curriculum in book form, written for exactly the stage you're at. Possibly the best cooking book of the last ten years for developing instinct rather than just technique.</li> </ul> <p>\u2190 Weeks 7\u20138 | Block 11\u201312: Vegetables &amp; Plant-Forward \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Block 9\u201310 Quick Reference \u2014 Seasoning &amp; Flavor Building","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/quick-ref.html#block-9-recipes-salt-when-what-and-why","title":"Block 9 Recipes \u2014 Salt: When, What, and Why","text":"Session Dish Skill Link Session 1 \u23f0 Crispy Chicken Thighs + Roasted Broccoli + Arugula Salad Dry-brine (early salt) Chicken \u00b7 Broccoli \u00b7 Salad Session 2 Pasta all'Amatriciana + Caesar Salad Layered seasoning (during salt) Amatriciana \u00b7 Caesar Session 3 Pan-Seared Halibut + White Bean Salad + Saut\u00e9ed Cherry Tomatoes Finishing salt (late salt) Halibut \u00b7 White Bean Salad \u00b7 Tomatoes Session 4 Cacio e Pepe + Bitter Greens Salad + Roasted Cauliflower with Capers Salt as texture and contrast Cacio e Pepe \u00b7 Salad \u00b7 Cauliflower Session 5 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Salt-Crusted Whole Roasted Fish + Fingerling Potatoes + Fennel Orange Salad Salt crust technique Fish \u00b7 Potatoes \u00b7 Salad"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/quick-ref.html#block-10-recipes-acid-fat-and-umami","title":"Block 10 Recipes \u2014 Acid, Fat, and Umami","text":"Session Dish Skill Link Session 6 Chicken Marsala + Creamy Mashed Potatoes + Green Salad Acid as a brightness lever Marsala \u00b7 Mash \u00b7 Salad Session 7 Glazed Pork Tenderloin + French Lentil Salad + Roasted Carrots Two different acids in one meal Pork \u00b7 Lentils \u00b7 Carrots Session 8 Brown Butter Gnocchi + Roasted Mushrooms + Bitter Greens Salad Fat as flavor (brown butter) Gnocchi \u00b7 Mushrooms \u00b7 Salad Session 9 Mushroom &amp; Anchovy Pasta + Roasted Asparagus + Arugula Salad Umami as background seasoning Pasta \u00b7 Asparagus \u00b7 Salad Session 10 \u23f0 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Miso-Glazed Cod + Saffron Risotto + Fennel Citrus Salad All four: salt \u00b7 acid \u00b7 fat \u00b7 umami in balance Cod \u00b7 Risotto \u00b7 Salad"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/quick-ref.html#shopping-notes","title":"Shopping Notes","text":"<p>Buy before Block 9: Kosher salt (Diamond Crystal or Morton), flaky Maldon sea salt or fleur de sel, fine sea salt. These are three distinct tools \u2014 don't skip the Maldon.</p> <p>Buy for Block 9: White fish (halibut or sea bass), canned white beans, cherry tomatoes.</p> <p>Buy for Block 9: 1\u20132 whole branzino or red snapper (ask your fishmonger to gut and scale them for you). Fingerling potatoes.</p> <p>Pantry additions for Block 10: Anchovy paste or tinned anchovies, miso paste (white or red), soy sauce, fish sauce, balsamic vinegar, sherry vinegar.</p> <p>Block 10 project session: Miso marinade goes on the cod/salmon 24\u201348 hours ahead \u2014 start 24-48 hours ahead.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 9\u201310: Seasoning &amp; Flavor Building","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: These weeks are about salt, acid, and umami \u2014 meaning you'll be building your pantry more than stocking up on proteins. Buy the three types of salt before anything else. The miso-marinated cod/salmon (Week 10 Sat) needs 24\u201348 hours in the marinade \u2014 start it Thursday.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#pre-week-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Pre-Week Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Three types of salt you must have: Kosher (Diamond Crystal or Morton), flaky Maldon or fleur de sel, fine sea salt. They are not interchangeable.</li> <li>[ ] Pantry umami builders (Week 10): Anchovies/anchovy paste, miso paste (white or red), soy sauce, fish sauce. You need all of these by Week 10 Monday.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-9","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 9","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Bone-in, skin-on chicken thighs \u2014 6 pieces (Week 9 Mon dry-brine)</li> <li>[ ] White fish fillets \u2014 halibut or sea bass, 2 pieces (Week 9 Wed pan-sear)</li> <li>[ ] Whole branzino or red snapper \u2014 1\u20132 fish (Week 9 Sat PROJECT \u2014 ask fishmonger to gut and scale). Alternatively: whole sea bass or trout works.</li> <li>[ ] Guanciale or pancetta \u2014 4 oz (Week 9 Tue amatriciana)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-10","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 10","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Chicken breasts or thighs \u2014 4 pieces (Week 10 Mon Marsala)</li> <li>[ ] Pork tenderloin \u2014 1 lb (Week 10 Tue)</li> <li>[ ] Black cod or salmon fillets \u2014 2 pieces (Week 10 Sat \u2014 start miso marinade Thursday)</li> <li>[ ] Tinned anchovies \u2014 2 cans (Week 10 Fri pasta + any remaining salads)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#produce-week-9","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 9","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Broccoli \u2014 1 large head (Week 9 Mon)</li> <li>[ ] Arugula \u2014 3 bags (Week 9 Mon salad + Week 9 Fri salad + general use)</li> <li>[ ] Romaine lettuce \u2014 2 hearts (Week 9 Tue Caesar salad)</li> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 2 pints (Week 9 Wed saut\u00e9ed)</li> <li>[ ] Cauliflower \u2014 1 head (Week 9 Fri, with crispy capers)</li> <li>[ ] Radicchio or bitter greens \u2014 1 head (Week 9 Fri salad)</li> <li>[ ] Fennel \u2014 2 bulbs (Week 9 Sat salad)</li> <li>[ ] Navel oranges \u2014 3 (Week 9 Sat fennel orange salad)</li> <li>[ ] Fingerling potatoes \u2014 1.5 lbs (Week 9 Sat)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#produce-week-10","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 10","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Mushrooms (cremini or mixed) \u2014 1 lb (Week 10 Mon Marsala sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 4 (acid finishes, multiple uses)</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 4 (Week 10 Tue roasted with cumin)</li> <li>[ ] Asparagus \u2014 1 bunch (Week 10 Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Arugula \u2014 2 bags (Week 10 Fri salad + Sat salad)</li> <li>[ ] Fennel \u2014 1 bulb (Week 10 Sat salad)</li> <li>[ ] Blood oranges or navel oranges \u2014 2 (Week 10 Sat salad)</li> <li>[ ] Yukon Gold potatoes \u2014 1.5 lbs (Week 10 Mon creamy mashed potatoes)</li> <li>[ ] Russet potatoes \u2014 3 lbs (Week 10 Wed potato gnocchi \u2014 bake them, don\u2019t boil)</li> <li>[ ] Green beans \u2014 \u00bd lb (Week 10 Wed fat-experiment lesson \u2014 three small batches in different fats)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh sage \u2014 1 bunch (Week 10 Wed brown butter gnocchi with crispy sage)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#dairy","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Parmesan (block) \u2014 8 oz (cacio e pepe, pasta, salads)</li> <li>[ ] Pecorino Romano \u2014 4 oz (cacio e pepe \u2014 do not skip, it's different from parmesan)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 3 sticks</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream (optional) \u2014 \u00bd cup (Week 10 Mon Marsala finishing)- [ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (Week 9 Tue Caesar raw egg yolks; Week 9 Sat salt-crust needs 6\u20138 egg whites for the crust paste)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] White miso paste \u2014 1 container (Week 10 Sat \u2014 also useful forever after)</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Week 10 Fri pasta + future use)</li> <li>[ ] Anchovy paste or whole tinned anchovies \u2014 2 cans (Week 10 Fri mushroom pasta)</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 1 bottle (already have? check)</li> <li>[ ] Saffron \u2014 1 small tin (Week 10 Sat risotto \u2014 the good stuff, not the cheap powder)</li> <li>[ ] Marsala wine (dry) \u2014 1 small bottle (Week 10 Mon \u2014 use dry, not sweet)</li> <li>[ ] Balsamic vinegar \u2014 1 bottle (Week 10 Tue pork glaze)</li> <li>[ ] Sherry vinegar \u2014 1 bottle (Week 10 Tue lentil salad \u2014 different from balsamic)</li> <li>[ ] Mirin \u2014 1 bottle (Week 10 Sat miso marinade)</li> <li>[ ] Sake or dry sherry \u2014 small bottle (miso marinade)</li> <li>[ ] Cumin, ground \u2014 for Week 10 Tue roasted carrots</li> <li>[ ] Canned white beans \u2014 2 cans (Week 9 Wed white bean salad)</li> <li>[ ] Tonnarelli or spaghetti \u2014 1 lb (cacio e pepe)</li> <li>[ ] Bucatini or rigatoni \u2014 1 lb (Week 9 Tue amatriciana)</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole tomatoes \u2014 1 can (amatriciana)</li> <li>[ ] Arborio rice \u2014 1.5 cups (Week 10 Sat saffron risotto)</li> <li>[ ] French green lentils (Puy lentils) \u2014 1 cup (Week 10 Tue lentil salad)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken or vegetable stock \u2014 64 oz (risotto + Marsala deglazing)</li> <li>[ ] Capers \u2014 1 jar (Week 9 Fri cauliflower + general use)</li> <li>[ ] Extra-virgin olive oil (good quality \u2014 it will be tasted directly this week)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/09-10-seasoning-and-flavor/shopping-list.html#notes","title":"\ud83d\udcdd Notes","text":"<p>Week 9 Monday dry-brine: Do this in the morning. Salt the chicken thighs, place uncovered on a rack over a sheet pan, and refrigerate until dinner. This 6\u20138 hour window is the minimum; overnight is better.</p> <p>Week 9 Saturday salt-crusted fish: You'll need 3\u20134 cups of kosher salt for the crust. Mix it with egg whites (about 2 per cup of salt) to form a pliable paste that seals around the fish without falling off. The crust should not be eaten.</p> <p>Week 10 Sat miso-marinated cod: Mix 3 parts white miso, 2 parts mirin, 1 part sake, 1 part sugar. Coat the fish completely, cover, and refrigerate 24\u201348 hours. Wipe off excess before broiling or pan-searing \u2014 the sugar burns.</p> <p>The umami experiment (Week 10 Fri): Before you add the anchovies to the pasta, taste the plain saut\u00e9ed garlic and tomato. Then add 2\u20133 anchovies and stir until dissolved. Taste again \u2014 notice it doesn't taste like fish; it just tastes deeper. That's umami at work.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Block 13\u201314: Vegetables &amp; Plant-Forward Cooking","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 9\u201310: Seasoning &amp; Flavor | Block 15\u201316: Pasta &amp; Grains \u2192</p> <p>\"The professional kitchen tests you on your vegetables. Anyone can cook a steak. The chef who can make a carrot taste like the best thing on the plate \u2014 that person has actually learned something.\"</p> <p>Quick Reference: \u2192 Week 11\u201312 Recipe Quick Ref</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#before-you-start-block-11","title":"Before You Start Block 11","text":"<p>Vegetables are where most home cooks coast. The steak gets the technique; the vegetables get the afterthought. This block is a correction. Two weeks of treating vegetables like the main event teaches you more about heat, texture, timing, and flavor than another two weeks of protein cookery would.</p> <p>The CIA spends four full weeks on vegetable fabrication and cookery before touching protein. The principle: if you can't make a carrot interesting, you don't yet understand heat.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read first: Serious Eats \u2014 The Science of Browning Vegetables \u2014 the same Maillard logic from Week 3\u20134 applies here; the only difference is water content and sugar concentration.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#session-0-two-purees-one-method-optional","title":"Session 0 \u2014 Two Pur\u00e9es, One Method (optional)","text":"<p>Skill: A vegetable pur\u00e9e is deceptively simple and technically demanding. The difference between a good pur\u00e9e and a great one is entirely in the texture \u2014 silky versus grainy, the right viscosity to coat a spoon, seasoned at every stage.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Silky Smooth Vegetable Purees \u2014 the principles apply beyond soup to plated pur\u00e9es.</p> <p>Tonight apply the universal pur\u00e9e method to two vegetables simultaneously \u2014 compare the results:</p> Pur\u00e9e Method notes Finish Celery root (celeriac) Sweat in butter, add stock, simmer until completely soft, blend very fine, strain Cream + butter; subtle and elegant Parsnip with roasted garlic Roast garlic until golden; simmer parsnips in stock; blend with roasted garlic and butter Rich, sweet, earthy <p>Both can be passed through a fine mesh sieve for professional-smooth results. This is worth doing at least once.</p> <p>Full Meal: Celery root and parsnip pur\u00e9es as the base + seared duck breast or seared scallops on top + a simple green salad</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#why-texture-matters-this-much-a-great-puree-tastes-better-because-it-coats-your-palate-more-evenly-every-bite-carries-more-flavor-a-grainy-or-waterlogged-puree-tastes-less-of-itself-because-the-structure-interrupts-contact-with-your-taste-receptors-straining-is-not-precious-its-functional","title":"&gt; Why texture matters this much: A great pur\u00e9e tastes better because it coats your palate more evenly \u2014 every bite carries more flavor. A grainy or waterlogged pur\u00e9e tastes less of itself because the structure interrupts contact with your taste receptors. Straining is not precious \u2014 it's functional.","text":""},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#block-11-vegetable-mastery","title":"Block 11 \u2014 Vegetable Mastery","text":""},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#session-1-blanching-shocking-and-color-science","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Blanching, Shocking, and Color Science","text":"<p>Skill: Blanching (brief boiling) plus shocking (ice bath) is the professional technique for preserving color, texture, and nutritional value in vegetables. It's also the mise en place move for any vegetable that needs to be partially cooked ahead of service.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 How and Why to Blanch Vegetables</p> <p>The color science \u2014 why it matters:</p> Pigment Vegetable examples Acid effect Alkali effect Chlorophyll (green) Broccoli, asparagus, spinach, peas Turns drab olive \u2014 add lemon after cooking Stays bright green \u2014 small pinch of baking soda in boiling water Anthocyanin (red/purple) Red cabbage, purple carrots, beets Stays vivid \u2014 add acid (vinegar) to braising liquid Turns blue-green; avoid alkali Carotenoid (orange/yellow) Carrots, squash, sweet potato Stable in acid Stable \u2014 heat-resistant, fat-soluble (cook in fat for best color) Betanin (deep red) Beets Stable but bleeds Stable <p>The blanching method: 1. Large pot, aggressively salted water (like pasta water), rolling boil 2. Add vegetable in small batches \u2014 too many drops the temperature 3. Cook until just tender but with a little resistance (al dente) 4. Shock immediately in salted ice water (the salt prevents leaching) 5. Drain and dry \u2014 wet vegetables steam instead of saut\u00e9</p> <p>Full Meal: Blanched and shocked asparagus + haricots verts + broccolini \u2014 dressed with brown butter and toasted almonds, served at room temperature</p> Component Recipe Vegetables Asparagus, haricots verts, broccolini \u2014 all blanched and shocked Dressing Brown butter + toasted almonds + lemon zest + fleur de sel Protein (optional) Soft-boiled eggs on top to make it a dinner <p>The test: Hold a blanched green bean next to an unblanched one. The color difference is stark. Blanching stops enzymatic activity (which turns vegetables drab) while the ice bath fixes the color at its brightest.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#session-2-roasting-caramelization-and-concentration","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Roasting: Caramelization and Concentration","text":"<p>Skill: Roasting drives out moisture and concentrates flavor while caramelizing the natural sugars in vegetables. It's the technique that turns broccoli from something people tolerate into something people want seconds of.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 How to Roast Any Vegetable</p> <p>The roasting rules: - Hot oven: 425\u2013450\u00b0F. Lower temperatures steam instead of roast. - Dry vegetables: Water is the enemy of browning. Pat dry after washing. - Single layer: Crowded pans steam. One layer always. - Fat on every surface: Toss in oil until lightly coated \u2014 not swimming, not dry. - Don't move them: Let the cut face develop contact with the pan; resist stirring for the first 15 minutes.</p> <p>The flavor family you're learning: Any vegetable with natural sugar caramelizes with high dry heat. Carrots become candy. Cauliflower develops a nutty depth. Beets intensify. Brussels sprouts lose their bitterness and become tender-crisp.</p> <p>Full Meal: Sheet Pan Dinner \u2014 roasted carrots, cauliflower, and beets with whatever protein you prefer + a tahini dressing or romesco</p> Component Recipe Vegetables Carrots (halved), cauliflower (florets), golden beets (quartered) Dressing Tahini sauce or romesco Protein Chicken thighs on the same pan, or eat vegetarian <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The One-Pan Roasted Vegetable Technique (Internet Shaquille) \u2014 Why temperature and spacing are the only two variables that actually matter.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#session-3-saute-braise-and-the-crucifer-redemption","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Saut\u00e9, Braise, and the Crucifer Redemption","text":"<p>Skill: Cruciferous vegetables (Brussels sprouts, cabbage, cauliflower, broccoli) are the most-hated and most-abused vegetable family. The problem is almost always method \u2014 boiled vegetables taste of sulfur; roasted or properly braised vegetables taste of caramelization and sweetness.</p> <p>Two techniques tonight:</p> <p>Pan-braising \u2014 a hybrid of saut\u00e9ing and steaming: sear in fat until color develops, add a small amount of liquid (stock, wine, vinegar), cover and finish until tender. The vegetables get both Maillard browning and tenderizing steam.</p> <p>Charred cabbage \u2014 the full-heat technique that turns cabbage from something tolerable into something remarkable.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Charred Miso Cabbage</p> <p>Full Meal: - Crispy Brussels Sprouts with Fish Sauce and Crispy Shallots \u2014 this dish converts Brussels sprout haters - Charred Cabbage with Miso-Sesame Sauce \u2014 a revelation; whole cabbage wedges charred in cast iron - Simple white rice or crusty bread</p> Component Notes Brussels sprouts Halved, pressed cut-side into very hot oil; don't move; then toss Cabbage Wedges, cast iron, very high heat; miso glaze brushed at the end <p>The insight: Both dishes rely on high heat applied to a flat surface of the vegetable. Steaming or boiling is never the answer for these vegetables at dinner.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#session-4-grilling-and-charring-fire-as-flavor","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Grilling and Charring: Fire as Flavor","text":"<p>Skill: Direct heat on vegetables produces char \u2014 carbon compounds that add bitterness, smokiness, and complexity. This is the single most underused technique for home vegetable cookery.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 How to Grill Vegetables</p> <p>The char distinction: - Light char \u2014 grill marks + some softening; proper char without burning through - Full char \u2014 eggplant, peppers, onions burned until fully black on the outside \u2192 the outside is scraped off, leaving smoky flesh underneath. This is what makes baba ganoush and rajas with poblanos.</p> <p>Full Meal: A grilled and charred vegetable spread:</p> Vegetable Method Served as Eggplant Full char over gas flame or under broiler; peel and season Baba ganoush or dressed salad Zucchini Direct grill, slight char marks, finish with lemon + mint Side Scallions Whole on the grill until charred and collapsed Alongside everything Peppers Full char, steam in bag, peel and seed Roasted pepper salad with olive oil and capers <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Art of Charring Vegetables (Joshua Weissman) \u2014 He goes deep on why char is a flavor, not a mistake.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#session-5-project-plant-forward-dinner-party","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Plant-Forward Dinner Party","text":"<p>Cook a complete dinner where vegetables are the headline, not the support act. No protein required (though a soft-boiled egg or some cheese is allowed).</p> <p>The challenge: Put at least three vegetable techniques from this week on one table.</p> Course Dish Techniques Starter Roasted beet salad with whipped feta and pistachios Roasting + acid dressing Main Seared mushroom \"steaks\" + celery root pur\u00e9e + pan sauce from mushroom fond Pur\u00e9e + sear + pan sauce Side Blanched and shocked green beans with brown butter Blanching + butter sauce Bread Good sourdough Bought is fine <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Mushroom \"steaks\": Serious Eats \u2014 Pan-Seared Mushrooms \u2014 portobello or king oyster, sliced thick, seared in cast iron, finished with thyme butter.</p> <p>Skill targets: Color retention on the green beans. True silkiness on the celery root pur\u00e9e. A fond-based pan sauce from the mushrooms. All three on the table at the same temperature.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#before-you-start-block-12","title":"Before You Start Block 12","text":""},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#session-0-quick-pickles-first-ferment-optional","title":"Session 0 \u2014 Quick Pickles &amp; First Ferment (optional)","text":"<p>Skill: Understanding the difference between quick pickling (brine + acid), lacto-fermentation (brine + time + natural bacteria), and their role in a well-built kitchen.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Quick Pickling Guide</p> <p>Tonight make two things:</p> <p>Quick pickles (ready in 30 minutes): - Pickled Red Onions \u2014 red wine vinegar + salt + sugar + a few peppercorns - Pickled Jalape\u00f1os and Carrots \u2014 white wine vinegar + salt + cumin + garlic</p> <p>Lacto-fermented sauerkraut (takes 5\u20137 days \u2014 start it tonight, finish it next week): - Simple Sauerkraut \u2014 green cabbage + 2% salt by weight; massage until brine releases; pack into jar; weigh down; leave at room temp 5\u20137 days</p> <p>Full Meal: Use the pickles tonight on whatever you're eating \u2014 tacos, a grain bowl, grilled fish. Quick pickles don't need a dedicated meal. They improve everything they touch.</p> <p>Why this matters: Pickles and ferments are balance tools. When a dish is too rich, too fatty, or needs brightness, a quick pickle solves it in 30 seconds. Having pickled red onions in your fridge at all times is one of the highest-leverage kitchen habits you can build.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#block-12-plant-forward-advanced-vegetable-technique","title":"Block 12 \u2014 Plant-Forward &amp; Advanced Vegetable Technique","text":""},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#session-6-the-composed-salad-dressing-is-a-technique","title":"Session 6 \u2014 The Composed Salad: Dressing Is a Technique","text":"<p>Skill: A well-composed salad is not a bowl of things with dressing poured over it. It's a dish with its own architecture: texture contrast, temperature contrast, acid-fat balance, and deliberate seasoning.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 The Food Lab's Guide to Better Salads</p> <p>Caesar dressing from scratch \u2014 the real lesson:</p> <p>Classic Caesar Salad teaches emulsification, acid balance, the role of anchovies as umami backbone, and why freshly grated Parmesan behaves differently than pre-grated.</p> Component Technique Dressing Raw egg yolk + anchovy + garlic + lemon + Worcestershire; emulsify with oil Croutons Day-old bread, torn not cut; tossed in olive oil; bake until very crispy Lettuce Romaine; the spine of the leaf stays crispy even under dressing <p>Full Meal: Caesar salad (full portion, not a side) + half a roast chicken or grilled fish on top + crusty bread</p> <p>The dressing principle that applies everywhere: Season the greens before dressing. Add dressing in thirds, tossing between each. The greens should be lightly coated, not swimming.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#session-7-legumes-and-beans-the-forgotten-protein","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Legumes and Beans: The Forgotten Protein","text":"<p>Skill: Beans cooked from dried are meaningfully better than canned. They also teach you patience, seasoning over time, and how to build flavor in a humble ingredient.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 How to Cook Dried Beans</p> <p>The two legume techniques tonight:</p> <p>White beans \u2014 braised in olive oil, garlic, aromatics, and your homemade chicken stock. Where they end up should taste like they've been simmering in a French farmhouse for 6 hours.</p> <p>Braised White Beans with Roasted Garlic and Rosemary</p> <p>Chickpeas \u2014 pan-fried until crispy in olive oil, finished with smoked paprika and lemon. A completely different texture from boiled chickpeas.</p> <p>Full Meal: Braised white beans on toast + crispy chickpeas + wilted greens + poached egg on top</p> Component Recipe White beans Braised in stock with garlic, rosemary, anchovy Chickpeas Crispy-fried in cast iron, paprika + lemon Greens Wilted spinach or kale in the bean liquid Egg (optional) Poached on top to make it a substantial dinner"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#session-8-mushrooms-umami-in-plant-form","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Mushrooms: Umami in Plant Form","text":"<p>Skill: Mushrooms deserve an entire session because they behave unlike any other vegetable \u2014 they're 80\u201390% water, which means crowding a pan turns them into steamed rubber. The technique that produces deep flavor is identical to a proper sear: high heat, no crowding, don't stir.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 The Food Lab: The Importance of Properly Browning Mushrooms</p> <p>The mushroom rules: - Dry pan, high heat, add mushrooms when pan is smoking \u2014 no fat yet (the mushrooms will immediately give up water if fat is added cold) - Once the water evaporates and the pan is dry again, add butter and aromatics - Never wash mushrooms in water \u2014 wipe clean with a dry cloth or brush - Salt after browning, not before (salt draws moisture)</p> <p>Full Meal: Mushroom Bourguignon \u2014 the vegetarian version of the French braise, using a mix of cremini, shiitake, and oyster mushrooms + a proper wine reduction</p> Component Recipe Mushrooms Mix of varieties; seared separately, then combined Sauce Red wine + stock + tomato paste + herbs and aromatics Base Creamy mashed potatoes, polenta, or buttered egg noodles <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Saut\u00e9 Mushrooms Properly (Ethan Chlebowski) \u2014 He tests the crowding variable specifically. Watch the difference in texture and color between the crowded and uncrowded batches.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#session-9-potatoes-the-technique-spectrum","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Potatoes: The Technique Spectrum","text":"<p>Skill: Potatoes are the most versatile vegetable in the curriculum \u2014 they can be crispy, silky, caramelized, creamy, or crunchy depending entirely on method. Tonight you cook potatoes three ways, comparing the technique differences side by side.</p> <p>The three potato techniques:</p> <p>R\u00f6sti \u2014 the Swiss potato cake: grated raw potato (or parboiled), seasoned and pressed into a skillet with butter, cooked over medium heat until golden and crispy on the outside, soft within. The starch must release and set to hold the cake together.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: The Kitchn \u2014 How to Make R\u00f6sti</p> <p>Pommes pur\u00e9e \u2014 the French mashed potato: baked or boiled potatoes riced while hot, then beaten with butter and warm cream until glossy. The difference from American mash is the amount of butter (more than you think) and the texture (silky, not dense).</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Reference: Serious Eats \u2014 Ultra-Creamy Mashed Potatoes</p> <p>Dauphinoise \u2014 the French gratin: thin potato slices layered in cream and garlic, baked until the top is golden and the potatoes have absorbed the cream into a single silky block. Requires mandoline-thin slices and patience.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Reference: BBC Good Food \u2014 Dauphinoise Potatoes</p> <p>Full Meal: Make one of the three above as the main event + a simple protein (seared chicken thighs or fried eggs work beautifully) + a bitter green salad</p> Technique Key skill Time R\u00f6sti Starch release, patience with the crust 25 min Pommes pur\u00e9e Texture control, butter ratio 35 min Dauphinoise Mandoline slicing, oven patience 90 min <p>Why potatoes deserve their own session: A cook who can produce silky pommes pur\u00e9e, a crispy r\u00f6sti, and a gratin dauphinoise has a side dish for every occasion \u2014 from a Tuesday dinner to a dinner party main. These three techniques cover 90% of what you'll ever need from a potato.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#session-10-project-the-vegetable-tasting-menu","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: The Vegetable Tasting Menu","text":"<p>Cook 4\u20135 vegetable preparations using different techniques. Serve them as a tasting \u2014 small plates, one at a time, with bread.</p> Course Dish Technique 1 Celery root pur\u00e9e with roasted garlic oil Pur\u00e9e 2 Blanched asparagus with brown butter and fried capers Blanching + beurre noisette 3 Charred cabbage with miso-sesame Charring 4 Mushroom bourguignon on toast Sear + braise 5 Quick-pickled vegetables + bread Fermentation + pickling <p>This is practice for the multi-course timing you'll need for the dinner parties in Weeks 53\u201354.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#module-2-checkpoint-continues","title":"Module 2 Checkpoint Continues","text":"<p>Vegetables are now in your repertoire, not just alongside your repertoire. Before moving to Weeks 15\u201316 (Pasta &amp; Grains), you should be able to answer yes to:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] I can blanch and shock a green vegetable and it stays bright green</li> <li>[ ] I can roast any vegetable without it steaming in its own moisture</li> <li>[ ] I can make a smooth, silky vegetable pur\u00e9e</li> <li>[ ] I understand why high heat is almost always the right answer for vegetables</li> <li>[ ] I have pickled onions in my fridge right now</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 The Food Lab: How to Get Maximum Browning on Your Vegetables \u2014 the science behind the single pan, high heat approach</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Samin Nosrat on Salt, Fat, Acid, Heat applied to vegetables \u2014 how acid changes everything</li> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Zuni Cafe Cookbook by Judy Rodgers \u2014 not primarily vegetarian, but contains the most thoughtful writing on vegetable cookery of any English-language cookbook</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html","title":"Block 13\u201314 Quick Reference \u2014 Vegetables &amp; Plant-Forward Cooking","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Block 11\u201312 Guide</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#core-techniques-at-a-glance","title":"Core Techniques at a Glance","text":"Technique Best for Key rule Blanch &amp; shock Green vegetables, par-cooking Salted boiling water \u2192 salted ice water immediately Roasting Root veg, cruciferous, anything with sugar 425\u2013450\u00b0F, single layer, dry surface Panroasting Brussels sprouts, mushrooms, dense cuts Cast iron or stainless, very hot, don't move Pan-braising Cabbage, fennel, leeks Sear \u2192 small splash of liquid \u2192 cover \u2192 finish Charring Eggplant, peppers, scallions, cabbage Open flame or broiler; the burnt outside is removed or eaten Pur\u00e9e Any cooked vegetable Simmer until dead-soft, blend very fine, strain through sieve Grilling Zucchini, asparagus, corn, halved lemons Dry surface, oiled grate, high heat Quick pickle Onions, cucumbers, jalape\u00f1os, carrots Warm brine (water + vinegar + salt + sugar); ready in 20\u201330 min Lacto-ferment Cabbage (sauerkraut), brine-packed anything 2% salt by weight; room temp; 5\u20137 days"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#the-puree-method-universal","title":"The Pur\u00e9e Method (Universal)","text":"<ol> <li>Sweat aromatics in butter or olive oil (don't brown)</li> <li>Add vegetable cut into uniform pieces</li> <li>Add stock or water \u2014 just enough to cover</li> <li>Simmer until completely, fully, collapse-on-a-fork soft</li> <li>Transfer to blender \u2014 blend 2\u20133 minutes until very smooth</li> <li>Pass through a fine mesh sieve, pressing with a ladle</li> <li>Adjust seasoning; add cream or butter to adjust richness and sheen</li> </ol> <p>Texture test: A spoonful held up should drop cleanly and coat the spoon evenly with no graininess.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#color-science-reference","title":"Color Science Reference","text":"Color Pigment Acid Alkali Green Chlorophyll Turns olive/drab Brightens (pinch baking soda) Red/Purple Anthocyanin Stays vivid Turns blue-grey Orange Carotenoid Stable Stable Deep red Betanin (beets) Stable Stable <p>Rule of thumb: Season green vegetables with acid (lemon, vinegar) only after they come off the heat.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#roasting-rules-summary","title":"Roasting Rules Summary","text":"<ul> <li>Oven: 425\u2013450\u00b0F</li> <li>Fat: enough to coat each piece \u2014 not swimming, not bare</li> <li>Pan: sheet pan with space \u2014 crowded = steamed</li> <li>Start: don't stir for the first 10\u201315 minutes \u2014 let the contact surface brown</li> <li>Test: a knife should slide in with no resistance</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#mushroom-saute-protocol","title":"Mushroom Saut\u00e9 Protocol","text":"<ol> <li>Pan (cast iron or stainless) over high heat \u2014 no fat yet \u2014 until smoking</li> <li>Add mushrooms \u2014 they will sizzle and immediately weep water</li> <li>Resist stirring; let the water evaporate (~4\u20135 min)</li> <li>Once pan is dry and mushrooms are shrinking, add butter + aromatics</li> <li>Toss; cook 2 more minutes; season at the end</li> <li>Salt only after browning</li> </ol>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#quick-pickle-formula","title":"Quick Pickle Formula","text":"Ingredient Ratio Vinegar (any) 1 cup Water 1 cup Salt 1 tsp Sugar 1 tsp (optional) Flavoring Peppercorns, garlic, chilli, herbs \u2014 whatever fits <ul> <li>Heat brine until salt and sugar dissolve</li> <li>Pour over sliced vegetables in a clean jar</li> <li>Cool; seal; refrigerate</li> <li>Ready in 20\u201330 minutes, best after 1\u20132 hours</li> <li>Lasts 2\u20134 weeks refrigerated</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#lacto-fermentation-formula","title":"Lacto-Fermentation Formula","text":"Variable Target Salt by weight 2% of vegetable weight Temperature 65\u201375\u00b0F room temperature Time 5\u20137 days (taste daily after day 3) Container Clean glass jar with loose lid (release CO2) Key rule Keep vegetables submerged under the brine at all times"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/quick-ref.html#block-1112-dishes-summary","title":"Block 11\u201312 Dishes Summary","text":"Session Dish Technique Session 1 Brown butter asparagus + haricots verts Blanch + shock + beurre noisette Session 2 Sheet pan carrots, cauliflower, beets Roasting Session 3 Crispy Brussels + charred cabbage with miso Pan sear + char Session 4 Baba ganoush + grilled veg spread Charring + grilling \ud83d\udd28 Session 5 Plant-forward dinner party Multi-technique Session 6 Caesar salad from scratch Emulsification + dressing Session 7 Braised white beans + crispy chickpeas Braising + pan-frying legumes Session 8 Mushroom Bourguignon Sear + braise Session 9 Stuffed roasted peppers Roasting + grain stuffing \ud83d\udd28 Session 10 5-course vegetable tasting menu Multi-technique"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html","title":"Block 13\u201314 Shopping List \u2014 Vegetables &amp; Plant-Forward Cooking","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Block 11\u201312 Guide</p> <p>How to use this list: Shop once at the start of Block 11. The lacto-ferment (sauerkraut) starts on Block 12 with ingredients you'll already have. Items marked \ud83e\udd6c FRESH should be selected for peak quality \u2014 buy the best-looking specimens at the market.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#produce-block-11","title":"\ud83e\udd6c Produce (Block 11)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Asparagus \u2014 1 lb (thin to medium; not thick)</li> <li>[ ] Haricots verts (French green beans) \u2014 \u00bd lb, or use regular green beans</li> <li>[ ] Broccolini \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 6\u20138 medium (not baby cut)</li> <li>[ ] Cauliflower \u2014 1 large head</li> <li>[ ] Golden beets \u2014 1 bunch (about 4)</li> <li>[ ] Brussels sprouts \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Green or Savoy cabbage \u2014 1 large head (will also use for sauerkraut)</li> <li>[ ] Eggplant \u2014 2 medium globe or 4 Japanese</li> <li>[ ] Zucchini \u2014 2 medium</li> <li>[ ] Scallions \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Bell peppers (red, yellow, orange) \u2014 2 of each for Block 12 stuffed peppers</li> <li>[ ] Celery root (celeriac) \u2014 1 large (biggest one you can find)</li> <li>[ ] Parsnips \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 bulbs (roasting a whole head)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 5\u20136</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#produce-block-12","title":"\ud83e\udd6c Produce (Block 12)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Romaine lettuce \u2014 2 heads (for Caesar)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed mushrooms \u2014 2 lbs (cremini + shiitake + oyster or king oyster)</li> <li>[ ] Spinach or kale \u2014 2 large bunches</li> <li>[ ] Red onions \u2014 3\u20134 (pickling + regular use)</li> <li>[ ] Jalape\u00f1os \u2014 4 (pickling)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh rosemary \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Fresh thyme \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 1 large bunch</li> <li>[ ] Fresh mint \u2014 1 bunch</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc4 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Extra-virgin olive oil (good one \u2014 you'll taste it)</li> <li>[ ] Neutral oil (grapeseed or vegetable) \u2014 for high-heat roasting</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 2 sticks</li> <li>[ ] Diamond Crystal kosher salt</li> <li>[ ] Sliced almonds \u2014 \u00bc cup (toasted for asparagus)</li> <li>[ ] Tahini \u2014 \u00bd cup</li> <li>[ ] White miso paste \u2014 2\u20133 tbsp</li> <li>[ ] Toasted sesame oil \u2014 2 tbsp</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce \u2014 2 tbsp (for Brussels sprouts)</li> <li>[ ] Anchovy fillets \u2014 1 tin (Caesar dressing + bean braising)</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 2 tbsp</li> <li>[ ] Worcestershire sauce \u2014 1 tsp (Caesar)</li> <li>[ ] Smoked paprika \u2014 1 tsp (crispy chickpeas)</li> <li>[ ] Red pepper flakes \u2014 1 tsp</li> <li>[ ] Capers \u2014 1 small jar</li> <li>[ ] Whole black peppercorns</li> <li>[ ] Bay leaves \u2014 4\u20135</li> <li>[ ] Pistachios \u2014 \u00bc cup (Block 11 roasted beet salad with whipped feta and pistachios)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#canned-dried-goods","title":"\ud83e\uded9 Canned / Dried Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dried white beans (cannellini or Great Northern) \u2014 1 lb (soak night before Block 12)</li> <li>[ ] Dried or canned chickpeas \u2014 1 can (or 1 cup dried)</li> <li>[ ] Farro or barley \u2014 1 cup (stuffing for peppers)</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole peeled tomatoes \u2014 1 can (28 oz, for stuffed pepper sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Good chicken stock or vegetable stock \u2014 48 oz (beans, pur\u00e9es)</li> <li>[ ] Day-old bread or sourdough \u2014 half a loaf (croutons)</li> <li>[ ] Red wine \u2014 1 bottle (Block 12 mushroom bourguignon)</li> <li>[ ] Jasmine or long-grain white rice \u2014 2 cups (Block 11 \u2014 serve with Brussels sprouts + charred cabbage)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#dairy-eggs","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy / Eggs","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Parmesan \u2014 4 oz, block (grate your own; not pre-grated)</li> <li>[ ] Egg yolks \u2014 2 (Caesar dressing; raw, so use good eggs)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 \u00bd cup (pur\u00e9es, optional)</li> <li>[ ] Feta \u2014 4 oz (roasted beet salad, Block 11)</li> <li>[ ] Ricotta or fresh goat cheese \u2014 4 oz (optional, stuffed peppers)</li> <li>[ ] Yukon Gold potatoes \u2014 1.5 lbs (Block 12 \u2014 creamy mashed potatoes as the base for mushroom bourguignon)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#protein-optional-all-proteins-in-this-block-are-supplementary","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Protein (Optional \u2014 all proteins in this block are supplementary)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Chicken thighs \u2014 4 (for sheet pan ; skip if cooking vegetarian)</li> <li>[ ] Duck breast or scallops \u2014 2 portions (Session 0 Two Pur\u00e9es optional / pur\u00e9e protein)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (poached for bean toast, boiled for salads)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#acids-vinegars","title":"\ud83c\udf76 Acids / Vinegars","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Red wine vinegar \u2014 \u00bd cup (pickled red onions + dressing)</li> <li>[ ] White wine vinegar \u2014 \u00bd cup (pickled jalape\u00f1os and carrots)</li> <li>[ ] Apple cider vinegar \u2014 \u00bc cup (general use)</li> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard \u2014 1 small jar</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#fermentation-block-12","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Fermentation (Block 12)","text":"<p>You'll already have green cabbage and salt from the list above. You only need a clean, wide-mouth glass jar (at least 1 quart) and patience.</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Wide-mouth glass jar \u2014 1-quart or half-gallon (mason jar with loose lid)</li> <li>[ ] Diamond Crystal kosher salt (already on list)</li> <li>[ ] Green or Savoy cabbage (already on list)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/11-12-vegetables-plant-forward/shopping-list.html#equipment-notes-for-this-block","title":"\ud83e\uddca Equipment Notes for This Block","text":"<ul> <li>Sheet pan(s) with a rim \u2014 you want real space. If you only have one sheet pan, cook in shifts.</li> <li>Cast iron skillet \u2014 essential for charred cabbage and mushrooms</li> <li>Fine mesh strainer \u2014 needed for silky pur\u00e9es</li> <li>High-speed blender \u2014 a Vitamix-type produces better pur\u00e9es than a food processor; use what you have</li> <li>Ice bath bowl \u2014 large bowl + ice + water for shocking</li> <li>Knife + board \u2014 heavy fabrication this week (you already have this)</li> <li>Wide-mouth mason jar \u2014 for sauerkraut</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html","title":"\ud83c\udf5d Block 13\u201314: Pasta &amp; Grains from Scratch","text":"<p>\u2190 Quick Reference \u2192 | Shopping List \u2192</p> <p>\"Making pasta from scratch is not about showing off. It's about understanding gluten, hydration, and the relationship between flour and time \u2014 which teaches you more about cooking than any recipe.\"</p> <p>The Week 11\u201312 philosophy: These two weeks are about making things from scratch that most people buy. Not because scratch is always better \u2014 it isn't always \u2014 but because understanding the process makes you a better cook with even the store-bought version. When you've made your own pasta dough, you know what \"properly hydrated\" feels like and why overworked dough turns tough. That knowledge transfers everywhere.</p> <p>Before you start Week 11, read:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 Fresh Pasta vs. Dried Pasta: Which Should You Use?</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 The Science of Pasta Water</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#block-11-pasta-dough-the-foundation","title":"Block 11 \u2014 Pasta Dough: The Foundation","text":"<p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 5 (PROJECT: Italian Pasta Dinner): make Bolognese the morning of \u2014 it needs 3 hrs</li> <li>Session 7 (Persian Rice + Slow-Roasted Lamb Shoulder): lamb shoulder takes 4 hrs; start by early afternoon</li> <li>Session 8 (Polenta + Osso Buco): osso buco braise takes 2\u20133 hrs; start by early afternoon</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#session-1-the-dough-meeting-gluten","title":"Session 1 \u2014 The Dough: Meeting Gluten","text":"<p>Skill: Fresh pasta dough is flour, eggs, and time. The gluten network forms as you knead, the dough becomes elastic, and it needs to rest so the gluten relaxes and becomes rollable. Your job tonight: understand what the dough is telling you at each stage. Too dry \u2014 it cracks when folded. Too wet \u2014 it sticks and tears. Properly rested \u2014 smooth, supple, and cooperative.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Homemade Fresh Pasta (basic egg dough, cut into tagliatelle) + Serious Eats \u2014 Slow-Cooked Tomato Sauce (Sugo di Pomodoro) + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Green Salad with Vinaigrette</p> <p>Make a basic egg pasta dough. Rest it for 30 minutes. Roll it by hand or with a pasta machine. Cut tagliatelle. Cook for 90 seconds in aggressively salted water. Toss with a slow-cooked tomato sauce (or just brown butter and parmesan if you want to let the pasta speak).</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Parmesan carries the protein component; the pasta is the star</li> <li>Starch: Your own fresh tagliatelle</li> <li>Sauce: Slow-cooked tomato sugo (can be made on the weekend and reheated, or made earlier in the week in a big batch)</li> <li>Salad: Simple green salad</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Quick and Easy Pasta With Cherry Tomato Sauce \u2014 A fast tomato sauce versus your slow sugo \u2014 watch what the high heat does to the tomatoes in minutes and compare the result to your 3-hour cook.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#session-2-ravioli-pasta-as-a-vessel","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Ravioli: Pasta as a Vessel","text":"<p>Skill: Stuffed pasta (ravioli, tortellini) requires you to roll the dough thinner than you think and seal the edges properly \u2014 no air pockets inside or they burst during cooking. The filling should be firm enough to hold its shape when piped or spooned but wet enough to be creamy when cooked. Tonight: ricotta and herb filling, classic.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Ricotta-Filled Ravioli with Brown Butter and Sage using the same base dough + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Cherry Tomatoes + Serious Eats \u2014 Radicchio Salad with Anchovy Vinaigrette</p> <p>Make the same dough from Session 1 (make it in the morning if you want to save time \u2014 it keeps in the fridge wrapped tightly overnight). Fill with ricotta, parmesan, lemon zest, and herbs. Toss the finished ravioli in brown butter and crispy sage.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Ricotta filling + parmesan</li> <li>Starch: Your own fresh ravioli</li> <li>Veg: Roasted cherry tomatoes alongside</li> <li>Salad: Radicchio with anchovy vinaigrette</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#session-3-gnocchi-potato-and-restraint","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Gnocchi: Potato and Restraint","text":"<p>Skill: Potato gnocchi is one of the most unforgiving things in cooking. Too much flour and they're heavy and gluey. Too little and they fall apart in the water. The secret: bake your potatoes (don't boil \u2014 water makes them wet and you'll add too much flour), rice them while hot, and handle the dough as little as humanly possible. Overworking develops gluten and makes them tough.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Light and Tender Potato Gnocchi with Sage Butter + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Broccolini with Garlic and Chili + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Green Salad</p> <p>The gnocchi themselves are the project. The sage butter sauce takes 5 minutes. The broccolini goes in the oven while you shape the gnocchi. Everything comes together at the same time.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Parmesan and egg yolks in the gnocchi; the butter sauce finishes it</li> <li>Starch: Potato gnocchi \u2014 your own</li> <li>Veg: Roasted broccolini</li> <li>Salad: Simple green salad</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Ricotta Gnocchi \u2014 Different base ingredient (ricotta vs. potato), but the key instruction is the same: handle it as little as possible. Watch why overworking kills gnocchi.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#session-4-pasta-water-the-secret-sauce-ingredient","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Pasta Water: The Secret Sauce Ingredient","text":"<p>Skill: Starchy pasta water is an emulsifier \u2014 it helps fat and water-based ingredients bind into a silky, coating sauce rather than separating. Aglio e olio and carbonara both depend on it. Tonight you'll make aglio e olio and notice how dramatically the pasta water changes the sauce.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Spaghetti Aglio e Olio + Serious Eats \u2014 Saut\u00e9ed Spinach with Garlic and Lemon + Serious Eats \u2014 Tomato and Cucumber Salad with Red Onion</p> <p>Aglio e olio is garlic, olive oil, pasta water, pasta, chili flakes, and parsley. Nothing else. It teaches emulsification, the function of pasta water, and proper sauce consistency \u2014 all in 15 minutes.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Anchovy in the aglio (optional but recommended \u2014 they dissolve completely)</li> <li>Starch: Spaghetti</li> <li>Veg: Saut\u00e9ed spinach with garlic and lemon</li> <li>Salad: Tomato and cucumber salad, bright and acidic alongside the rich pasta</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Spaghetti Aglio Olio e Fried Shallot \u2014 Same dish with one addition \u2014 watch the emulsification move: that moment when pasta water, oil, and garlic become a sauce instead of a greasy tangle.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#session-5-project-meal-a-full-italian-pasta-dinner","title":"\u23f0 Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Full Italian Pasta Dinner","text":"<p>The challenge: Three pasta shapes, three sauces, made in one evening. This is how an Italian family the rest day lunch actually works \u2014 generous, abundant, and a showcase of everything pasta can do.</p> <p>Full Meal (serves 4\u20136):</p> <ol> <li>Antipasto: Serious Eats \u2014 Bruschetta with Tomato and Basil \u2014 toasted bread, ripe tomatoes, garlic, good olive oil</li> <li>Pasta 1: Serious Eats \u2014 Classic Cacio e Pepe \u2014 a small portion per person as a first pasta</li> <li>Pasta 2: Your fresh tagliatelle from earlier in the block dough (make it ahead) with Serious Eats \u2014 Slow-Cooked Bolognese (make the sauce the morning of the project session \u2014 it needs 3 hours)</li> <li>Salad: Serious Eats \u2014 Classic Italian Green Salad with a simple lemon and olive oil dressing</li> </ol> <p>Skill targets: Bolognese seasoned in layers throughout a 3-hour cook. Fresh pasta cut to even width. Cacio e Pepe silky and sauce-y, not dry and clumpy.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Rag\u00f9 Bolognese (Northern Italian Meat Sauce) \u2014 Watch the sequence of liquid additions \u2014 milk first, then wine, then stock \u2014 and why the order matters for the final texture.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#block-12-grains-rice-polenta-and-beyond","title":"Block 12 \u2014 Grains: Rice, Polenta, and Beyond","text":"<p>\"Every culture has a grain at its center. Learning to cook grains properly \u2014 not just until they're done, but until they're excellent \u2014 is a quiet superpower.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#session-6-risotto-alla-milanese-saffron-and-patience","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Risotto alla Milanese: Saffron and Patience","text":"<p>Skill (with new intention): Saffron risotto \u2014 the gold standard of Italian risotto \u2014 is simpler than it sounds and more demanding than it looks. The saffron blooms in warm stock before it goes in; the gradual ladle-by-ladle addition coaxes starch from the Arborio; the final mantecatura (cold butter stirred in off the heat) makes it loose and silky. Tonight the risotto itself is the subject.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Saffron Risotto alla Milanese + Serious Eats \u2014 Bitter Greens Salad with Walnut and Gorgonzola</p> <p>Bloom a generous pinch of saffron in 2 tablespoons of warm stock for 20 minutes before starting the risotto \u2014 that bloomed liquid goes in early. The risotto should finish with a deep golden colour and a faint floral perfume.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Parmesan and butter carry the richness; add a fried egg on top if you want more substance</li> <li>Starch: The saffron risotto is the dish</li> <li>Salad: Bitter greens with gorgonzola and walnuts to cut through the richness</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Pause Risotto Halfway Through to Finish Later \u2014 A 60-second technique that changes how you host. Watch the starch behaviour when he stops and restarts \u2014 that's what you're riding on every stir.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#session-7-rice-the-worlds-most-important-grain","title":"\u23f0 Session 7 \u2014 Rice: The World's Most Important Grain","text":"<p>Skill: Most home cooks treat rice as an afterthought. Tonight it's the focus. You'll cook Persian-style rice with a tahdig crust \u2014 the goal is a golden, crispy bottom that releases from the pot in a crown. Too high heat and it burns; too low and it stays soft. This is heat control and patience in one dish.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Persian-Style Rice with Crispy Tahdig Crust + Serious Eats \u2014 Slow-Roasted Spiced Lamb Shoulder + Serious Eats \u2014 Cucumber and Yogurt Salad (Tzatziki-Style)</p> <p>Tahdig \u2014 the crispy rice crust at the bottom of the Persian rice pot \u2014 is one of the most coveted things in Iranian cuisine. Get it right and it releases from the pot in a golden crown.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Slow-roasted lamb shoulder (set it in the oven early, it takes 4 hours but is completely passive)</li> <li>Starch: Persian rice with tahdig \u2014 the project of the evening</li> <li>Salad: Cucumber and herb yogurt salad, cool and acidic alongside the rich lamb</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#session-8-polenta-low-and-slow","title":"\u23f0 Session 8 \u2014 Polenta: Low and Slow","text":"<p>Skill: Traditional polenta is not the quick-cook kind. It takes 45\u201360 minutes of stirring over low heat, adding stock or water gradually as the cornmeal absorbs it. The result is fundamentally different from the 5-minute version \u2014 creamier, with a deeper corn flavor and a silky consistency that coats the back of a spoon.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Creamy Parmesan Polenta + Recipe Tin Eats \u2014 Osso Buco (a veal or beef shank braise; the marrow inside the bone is the reward for patience) + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Green Salad</p> <p>The polenta goes underneath. The osso buco braise goes on top. Finish with gremolata (parsley + lemon zest + garlic, stirred in raw at the very end) \u2014 its fresh bite against the deep braise is the whole point of the dish.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Osso buco \u2014 cross-cut veal or beef shank, braised 2\u20133 hrs until the bone loosens</li> <li>Starch: Slow-cooked creamy polenta</li> <li>Salad: Simple green salad</li> </ul> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: POV Polenta Soup With Whatever You Want \u2014 A looser, brothier version of the same grain \u2014 watch how he adjusts the liquid ratio and seasoning as it cooks down. Same instincts, different texture target.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#session-9-farro-and-grains-that-think-for-themselves","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Farro and Grains That Think for Themselves","text":"<p>Skill: Unlike risotto, which needs constant attention, farro and other ancient grains (freekeh, barley, bulgur) are largely self-sufficient. The key is seasoning the cooking liquid well and knowing when to stop \u2014 farro should be tender but still have chew, never mushy.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Farro Salad with Roasted Beets and Goat Cheese + Serious Eats \u2014 Crispy Pan-Seared Salmon + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Arugula Salad</p> <p>The warm farro salad is a full grain side dish. The crispy salmon is the protein. The arugula salad provides the acid counterpoint.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Crispy-skinned salmon fillet</li> <li>Starch/Veg: Warm farro with roasted beets, goat cheese, and vinaigrette</li> <li>Salad: Arugula with lemon</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#session-10-project-meal-a-grain-forward-dinner-party","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: A Grain-Forward Dinner Party","text":"<p>The challenge: Grains as the hero \u2014 not the side. The project session's dinner could comfortably be served to guests who don't cook, and they would never suspect that every dish was a skills exercise in disguise.</p> <p>Full Meal:</p> <ol> <li>Starter: Serious Eats \u2014 Whipped Ricotta on Crostini with Honey and Walnuts \u2014 a quick, beautiful opener that requires no cooking</li> <li>Main: Serious Eats \u2014 Saffron Risotto alla Milanese with Serious Eats \u2014 Pan-Seared Scallops with Lemon-Brown Butter on top \u2014 the scallops rest on the risotto as the protein component</li> <li>Salad: Serious Eats \u2014 Fennel Salad with Blood Orange and Olives \u2014 serve alongside or between courses</li> </ol> <p>Skill targets: Risotto at perfect consistency (flows slowly like lava when plated, not stiff). Scallops with a deep, dry sear on each side. Everything on the table at the same time.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#fresh-pasta-the-physics","title":"Fresh Pasta: the Physics","text":"<p>Fresh pasta looks like pure craft but it's mostly chemistry. The ratio of egg yolks to flour, how the gluten develops as you knead, and why resting the dough matters are all understandable and learnable.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Best Slow-Cooked Tomato Sauce \u2014 The sauce you pair with your fresh pasta defines the dish as much as the pasta itself. This is the canonical red sauce recipe.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Fresh Egg Pasta \u2014 The full technical breakdown of fresh pasta from Kenji, including the science behind the dough.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#risotto-why-the-stir-matters","title":"Risotto: Why the Stir Matters","text":"<p>Risotto is not about patience. It's about starch gelatinization and gradual liquid absorption. Once you understand the mechanism, you can make it in 18 minutes.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Key Techniques for Perfect Risotto \u2014 The full technical breakdown: why the stock goes in gradually, what the starch is actually doing, and how to read the risotto's texture at each stage rather than relying on a timer.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Pasta Grannies \u2014 Documentary-style videos of Italian grandmothers making regional pasta. No voiceover required \u2014 just watching the hand technique is the education.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Mastering Pasta by Marc Vetri \u2014 The most comprehensive English-language book on pasta. Goes deep on shapes, doughs, sauces, and the regional logic behind pairing them.</li> </ul> <p>\u2190 Weeks 9\u201310 | Weeks 15\u201316 \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Block 13\u201314 Quick Reference \u2014 Pasta &amp; Grains from Scratch","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/quick-ref.html#week-11-recipes-pasta-dough-the-foundation","title":"Week 11 Recipes \u2014 Pasta Dough: The Foundation","text":"Session Dish Skill Link Session 1 Homemade Tagliatelle + Slow-Cooked Tomato Sugo + Green Salad Egg pasta dough, rest, roll, cut Pasta \u00b7 Sauce \u00b7 Salad Session 2 \u23f0 Ricotta Ravioli with Brown Butter and Sage + Roasted Cherry Tomatoes + Radicchio Salad Stuffed pasta \u2014 thin rolling and sealing Pasta \u00b7 Tomatoes \u00b7 Salad Session 3 Light Potato Gnocchi with Sage Butter + Roasted Broccolini + Green Salad Gnocchi: bake potatoes, rice hot, minimum flour Gnocchi \u00b7 Broccolini \u00b7 Salad Session 4 Spaghetti Aglio e Olio + Saut\u00e9ed Spinach + Tomato Cucumber Salad Pasta water as emulsifier Aglio e Olio \u00b7 Spinach \u00b7 Salad Session 5 \u23f0 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Full Italian Pasta Dinner \u2014 Bruschetta + Cacio e Pepe + Fresh Tagliatelle Bolognese + Green Salad Three pasta techniques in one service Bruschetta \u00b7 Cacio e Pepe \u00b7 Bolognese \u00b7 Salad"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/quick-ref.html#week-12-recipes-grains-rice-polenta-and-beyond","title":"Week 12 Recipes \u2014 Grains: Rice, Polenta, and Beyond","text":"Session Dish Skill Link Session 6 Mushroom and Asparagus Risotto + Bitter Greens Salad Risotto mastery \u2014 technique, not just recipe Risotto \u00b7 Salad Session 7 \u23f0 Persian Rice with Tahdig + Slow-Roasted Lamb Shoulder + Cucumber Yogurt Salad Tahdig \u2014 heat control and patience Rice \u00b7 Lamb \u00b7 Salad Session 8 \u23f0 Creamy Parmesan Polenta + Braised Short Ribs or Lamb Ragu + Green Salad Slow polenta \u2014 45\u201360 min of stirring Polenta \u00b7 Ribs \u00b7 Salad Session 9 Farro Salad with Beets &amp; Goat Cheese + Crispy Salmon + Arugula Salad Farro \u2014 dress while hot Farro \u00b7 Salmon \u00b7 Salad Session 10 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Grain-Forward Dinner Party \u2014 Whipped Ricotta Crostini + Saffron Risotto + Pan-Seared Scallops + Fennel Blood Orange Salad Grains as the star of a dinner party Crostini \u00b7 Risotto \u00b7 Scallops \u00b7 Salad"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/quick-ref.html#shopping-notes","title":"Shopping Notes","text":"<p>Week 11 pasta essentials: \"00\" flour or all-purpose flour, large eggs (farm eggs if available \u2014 the yolks make a difference), whole-milk ricotta, fresh sage.</p> <p>Block 11 Session 1 tip: Make a double batch of tomato sugo on the day before \u2014 you'll use it Session 1 and the leftover becomes Pasta 2 on the project session dinner if needed.</p> <p>Block 14 Session 7: Lamb shoulder needs 4 hours in the oven. Start it mid-afternoon or set it early and hold warm. Leftover lamb becomes the ragu for Session 8\u2019s polenta.</p> <p>Block 12 project session: Scallops must be completely dry before searing. Pat thoroughly on paper towels and let them sit uncovered on the rack in the fridge for 30 min before cooking. Wet scallops steam; dry scallops sear.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 13\u201314: Pasta &amp; Grains from Scratch","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Week 11 is flour and eggs. Week 12 is grains and patience. Buy the pasta flour and a potato ricer before Week 11 starts \u2014 they're the tools you absolutely need. The lamb shoulder (Week 12 Tue) needs 4 hours in the oven; start it by 3 PM.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Potato ricer \u2014 essential for gnocchi (Week 11 Wed). A box grater works as a backup but the ricer makes better gnocchi. Under $15.</li> <li>[ ] Pasta machine (optional) \u2014 hand-cranked pasta machine (~$35) makes rolling dramatically easier for Weeks 11 Mon/Tue. Rolling by hand works too.</li> <li>[ ] Large pot for pasta \u2014 you need volume and lots of salt. Pasta water should taste like a light broth.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-11","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 11","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Ricotta cheese (whole-milk) \u2014 1 lb (Week 11 Tue ravioli filling + Week 12 Sat crostini)</li> <li>[ ] Anchovies \u2014 1 can (Week 11 Fri aglio e olio, optional but recommended)</li> <li>[ ] Guanciale or pancetta \u2014 4 oz (Week 11 Sat Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] Ground beef \u2014 1 lb (Week 11 Sat Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] Ground pork \u2014 \u00bd lb (Week 11 Sat Bolognese \u2014 adds richness)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-12","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 12","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Mushrooms (mixed: cremini, shiitake, oyster) \u2014 2 lbs (Week 12 Mon risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Lamb shoulder \u2014 3\u20134 lbs, bone-in (Week 12 Tue PROJECT \u2014 buy fresh, ask butcher)</li> <li>[ ] Bone-in beef short ribs or beef cheeks \u2014 2 lbs (Week 12 Wed braised ragu, OR use Tuesday's leftover lamb)</li> <li>[ ] Salmon fillets (skin-on) \u2014 2 pieces (Week 12 Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Sea scallops \u2014 8\u201312 large, dry-packed (Week 12 Sat PROJECT \u2014 must be labeled \"dry-packed\" or \"day-boat\"; wet-packed scallops won't sear properly)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#produce-week-11","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 11","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 2 pints (Week 11 Tue roasted + Week 11 Sat bruschetta)</li> <li>[ ] Radicchio \u2014 1 head (Week 11 Tue salad)</li> <li>[ ] Broccolini \u2014 2 bunches (Week 11 Wed)</li> <li>[ ] Baby spinach \u2014 1 bag (Week 11 Fri saut\u00e9ed)</li> <li>[ ] Tomatoes (Roma or vine-ripe) \u2014 4 large (Week 11 Sat bruschetta)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 4</li> <li>[ ] Fresh sage \u2014 1 bunch (gnocchi butter sauce + ravioli butter sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Fresh basil \u2014 1 bunch (tomato sugo + bruschetta)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumber \u2014 2 (Week 11 Fri salad)</li> <li>[ ] Red onion \u2014 1 (Week 11 Fri salad)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed salad greens \u2014 2 bags</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#produce-week-12","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 12","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Asparagus \u2014 1 bunch (Week 12 Mon mushroom asparagus risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Basmati rice (not standard white) \u2014 2 cups (Week 12 Tue Persian rice / tahdig \u2014 long-grain Basmati is correct here)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumbers \u2014 2 (Week 12 Tue tzatziki)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh dill \u2014 1 bunch (tzatziki)</li> <li>[ ] Beets (raw) \u2014 4 medium (Week 12 Fri farro salad \u2014 roast them yourself)</li> <li>[ ] Arugula \u2014 2 bags (Week 12 Fri + Sat salads)</li> <li>[ ] Fennel \u2014 2 bulbs (Week 12 Sat salad)</li> <li>[ ] Blood oranges or navel oranges \u2014 3 (Week 12 Sat salad)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed bitter greens (radicchio, endive) \u2014 1 head (Week 12 Mon salad)</li> <li>[ ] Walnuts \u2014 \u00bd cup (Week 12 Mon salad)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 1 head</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#dairy","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Parmesan (block) \u2014 12 oz (pasta, risotto, crostini, gnocchi)</li> <li>[ ] Pecorino Romano \u2014 4 oz (Week 11 Sat cacio e pepe)</li> <li>[ ] Gorgonzola \u2014 2 oz (Week 12 Mon salad)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 4 sticks (pasta sauces, risotto finishing, scallop searing)</li> <li>[ ] Whole-milk ricotta \u2014 as above (Week 11 Tue + Week 12 Sat crostini)</li> <li>[ ] Plain Greek yogurt (full-fat) \u2014 1 cup (Week 12 Tue tzatziki)</li> <li>[ ] Cr\u00e8me fra\u00eeche or heavy cream \u2014 \u00bd cup (Week 12 Wed polenta finishing)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 2 dozen (fresh pasta dough requires 1 egg per 100g flour; 2 lbs of \u201900\u201d flour = ~18 eggs minimum; also for soft-boiled and ravioli binding)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] \"00\" flour (Tipo 00) \u2014 2 lbs (fresh pasta \u2014 found at Italian delis or Amazon. All-purpose works but \"00\" makes silkier pasta)</li> <li>[ ] Semolina flour \u2014 \u00bd cup (dusting fresh pasta to prevent sticking)</li> <li>[ ] Russet potatoes \u2014 3 lbs (Week 11 Wed gnocchi \u2014 bake them, don't boil)</li> <li>[ ] Farro \u2014 2 cups (Week 12 Fri farro salad)</li> <li>[ ] Arborio or Carnaroli rice \u2014 2 cups (Week 12 Mon risotto + Sat saffron risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Saffron \u2014 1 tin (Week 12 Sat saffron risotto \u2014 if you used yours in Week 10, restock)</li> <li>[ ] Coarse-ground cornmeal (not instant polenta) \u2014 1 bag (Week 12 Wed)</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole tomatoes \u2014 3 cans (Week 11 Mon slow tomato sugo + Sat Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] Tomato paste \u2014 1 small can</li> <li>[ ] Red wine \u2014 2 bottles (Week 12 Wed short rib braise + Week 11 Sat Bolognese)</li> <li>[ ] White wine (dry) \u2014 1 bottle (Week 12 Mon risotto + general)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken stock \u2014 64 oz (risotto, polenta, general)</li> <li>[ ] Beef stock \u2014 32 oz (Week 12 Wed braise)</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Week 12 Mon mushroom risotto \u2014 a small hit deepens the mushroom flavor; trust it)</li> <li>[ ] Goat cheese \u2014 4 oz (Week 12 Fri farro salad)</li> <li>[ ] Honey \u2014 1 jar (Week 12 Sat crostini)</li> <li>[ ] Walnuts \u2014 \u00bd cup (Week 12 Sat crostini)</li> <li>[ ] Capers \u2014 1 jar (Week 12 Sat scallop sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Extra-virgin olive oil (good quality \u2014 multiple uses)</li> <li>[ ] Kosher salt (large box \u2014 pasta water uses more than you think)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#bread","title":"\ud83e\udd56 Bread","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Crusty bread or baguette \u2014 1 (Week 11 Sat bruschetta base \u2014 slice thick, rub with garlic, drizzle with olive oil)</li> <li>[ ] Good rustic bread \u2014 1 (Week 12 Sat crostini)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/13-14-pasta-and-grains/shopping-list.html#notes","title":"\ud83d\udcdd Notes","text":"<p>Egg pasta dough (Week 11 Mon): The most common mistake is adding too much flour. Start with the minimum, add slowly. The dough should feel like Play-Doh \u2014 supple and smooth, not tacky or stiff. After kneading, wrap tightly and rest 30+ minutes.</p> <p>Gnocchi (Week 11 Wed) \u2014 the rules: 1. Bake the potatoes, don't boil 2. Rice them while they're hot (steam escapes and makes them lighter) 3. Add flour sparingly \u2014 start with less than the recipe says 4. Handle as little as possible. No kneading. Overworked = tough.</p> <p>Bolognese (Week 11 Sat) needs 3 hours. Start it by 11 AM. Add no more than \u00bd cup of liquid at a time and only when the previous addition has fully absorbed. The right consistency is thick and coating, barely any sauce.</p> <p>Scallops (Week 12 Sat) \u2014 critical prep: Pat dry on paper towels, then let them sit uncovered on a rack in the refrigerator for 30 minutes before cooking. They must be completely dry to sear, not steam. The pan must be screaming hot. Don't move them for 90 seconds.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html","title":"\ud83c\udfc1 Block 15\u201316: Module 2 Capstone \u2014 Poultry &amp; Flavor Review","text":"<p>\u2190 Quick Reference \u2192 | Shopping List \u2192</p> <p>\"You've been cooking with deliberate intention since Week 1. This week is your first real test: can you cook a full dinner for people you care about, with no recipes open in front of you during service? It also closes out Module 2 \u2014 Building Flavor. Before you enter the Proteins block, you should be able to season by instinct, not by instruction.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#block-13-the-module-2-capstone-cook","title":"Block 13 \u2014 The Module 2 Capstone Cook","text":"<p>The Week 13 rule: Recipes are allowed for preparation and mise en place. Once service begins \u2014 meaning once anything goes on the heat \u2014 close the tabs.</p> <p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 6 (High-Heat Whole-Bird Roast): dry-brine the bird the night before this session</li> <li>Session 10 (PROJECT: Duck Confit): cure the duck legs the evening before; plan for 4\u20136 hr low cook</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#session-1-menu-planning","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Menu Planning","text":"<p>Skill: Professional kitchens don't decide what to cook while standing in front of the stove. They plan. Tonight's task: design a 3-course dinner menu for the project session using only techniques you've learned in Weeks 1\u201312. Write the menu down. Plan the timing. Make your shopping list.</p> <p>Questions to ask yourself while planning:</p> <ul> <li>Does the menu have balance? (Rich and light? Warm and cool? Fat-forward and acid-bright?)</li> <li>Can I execute all three courses in the same kitchen, at the same time, without losing my mind?</li> <li>Is there anything on this menu I'm not confident about? (If yes, practice that thing this week, not the project session.)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#session-2-dry-run-the-most-difficult-component","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Dry Run: The Most Difficult Component","text":"<p>Whatever you identified as the hardest part of the project menu \u2014 make it tonight as a dry run. No guests, no pressure. Just you and the technique.</p> <p>Full Meal: Your chosen dry-run dish + Serious Eats \u2014 Simple Green Salad + whatever protein is simplest alongside</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#session-3-knife-speed-benchmark","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Knife Speed Benchmark","text":"<p>Skill: Time yourself dicing one onion. This is the third benchmark in the program ( and  were the others). Write the time down. You should be measurably faster than Week 2. More importantly: are your cuts more uniform? Speed is the secondary metric. Consistency is the primary one.</p> <p>Full Meal: Serious Eats \u2014 Thai-Style Larb (Ground Meat Salad) + Serious Eats \u2014 Jasmine Rice + Serious Eats \u2014 Quick-Pickled Cucumbers</p> <p>Larb requires a lot of fine knife work \u2014 fresh herbs, shallots, chili, lemongrass if using. It's also deeply delicious, uses acid (lime juice) and umami (fish sauce) in a way that is immediately instructive, and is unlike anything in the previous 12 weeks.</p> <ul> <li>Protein: Ground pork or chicken, toasted with spices</li> <li>Starch: Jasmine rice</li> <li>Salad: Quick-pickled cucumbers alongside</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#session-4-final-prep-day","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Final Prep Day","text":"<p>Mise en place everything for the project dinner. Every sauce component prepped. Every vegetable cut. Every protein seasoned in advance (if appropriate). Every sauce component thought through. The goal: the project session service should feel calm and controlled, not frantic and reactive.</p> <p>Dinner tonight: Something simple and low-effort \u2014 Serious Eats \u2014 The Best Grilled Cheese + Serious Eats \u2014 Tomato Soup \u2014 because you deserve a night off the skills grind.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#session-5-project-meal-the-week-13-dinner","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT MEAL: The Week 13 Dinner","text":"<p>The cook: Execute your planned 3-course dinner for at least two guests. No recipes open during service. All techniques drawn from Weeks 1\u201312.</p> <p>Suggested framework if you can't decide:</p> <ol> <li>Starter: Serious Eats \u2014 Classic Shrimp Cocktail with Homemade Sauce \u2014 knife skills, salt timing</li> <li>Main: Serious Eats \u2014 Pan-Seared Duck Breast with Cherry Pan Sauce + Serious Eats \u2014 Creamy Polenta + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Root Vegetables \u2014 heat control, pan sauce, seasoning in layers</li> <li>Salad / Cheese: A composed cheese plate with good bread, honeycomb, and a handful of dressed greens \u2014 no recipe needed, just judgment</li> </ol> <p>Skill targets: Everything on the table at the same time. At least one course where you can identify all four flavor elements \u2014 salt, acid, fat, umami \u2014 working in balance. No recipe tabs open during service.</p> <p>This is the most important reflection yet. Five questions, five sentences minimum each:</p> <ol> <li>What is the technique you've improved most since Week 1?</li> <li>What still feels unnatural or mechanical?</li> <li>Which recipe from the past 13 weeks do you want to master \u2014 cook repeatedly until it's genuinely yours?</li> <li>What ingredient have you cooked with for the first time that you now want to use regularly?</li> <li>You're 25% of the way through the program. Where do you want to be by the end?</li> </ol>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#block-14-poultry-in-depth","title":"Block 14 \u2014 Poultry in Depth","text":"<p>\"The chicken is the most cooked protein in the world and the most underestimated. Learning to roast, spatchcock, confit, and sauce a bird properly is the single most transferable skill in cooking.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#session-6-high-heat-whole-bird-roast","title":"Session 6 \u2014 High-Heat Whole-Bird Roast","text":"<p>Skill: The classic high-heat roast \u2014 450\u00b0F, bird dry-brined overnight, no basting. This produces crackling skin and juicy meat if you understand why: the high heat cooks so fast it dries the surface before the interior overcooks. A chicken at high heat is not an accident. It's physics.</p> <ul> <li>Read (before you cook): Serious Eats \u2014 The Science of Perfect Roast Chicken</li> <li>Dry-brine the bird the night before the block starts: kosher salt inside and out, uncovered in the fridge</li> <li>Roast at 450\u00b0F on a rack. No tent. No basting. Let it go.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Roast chicken + Serious Eats \u2014 The Best Roast Potatoes Ever + simple green salad</p> <p>Skill note: Take the bird's temperature in three places \u2014 thigh near the joint, thickest part of the breast, and the cavity near the backbone. They'll never be the same reading. Understand the variance before you declare it \"done.\"</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Properly Roast a Chicken \u2014 Watch his setup before the bird goes in \u2014 dry skin, rack position, pan underneath. Every step is a reason.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#session-7-spatchcock-why-it-changes-everything","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Spatchcock: Why It Changes Everything","text":"<p>Skill: Remove the backbone (kitchen shears, one firm cut down each side). Flatten the bird. Now roast it. Spatchcocking flattens the breast-to-thigh thickness differential \u2014 which is the single reason whole birds are so hard to cook to uniform doneness. When both parts hit the sheet pan at the same level, they cook much more evenly.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Spatchcock Roast Chicken \u2014 strip the flavor profile, study the method</li> <li>Save the backbone: put it in a bag in the freezer. It will go in your next stock.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Spatchcocked chicken (your own seasoning, not theirs) + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Cauliflower with Pine Nuts, Raisins &amp; Capers + tahdig or rice</p> <p>Side-by-side comparison optional: write down the cooking time and internal temp readings compared to earlier in the block's whole bird. Did the spatchcock cook faster? More evenly? This is active learning.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: For the Best Roast Chicken, Slather Your Spatchcock in Mayo \u2014 A twist on the technique you're using \u2014 watch how the mayo acts as a fat and protein barrier that crisps differently than dry-brined skin.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#session-8-braised-poultry-coq-au-vin","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Braised Poultry: Coq au Vin","text":"<p>Skill: Braising breaks the poultry rules deliberately. Low and slow in liquid. The collagen in the legs and thighs converts to gelatin, creating body in the sauce that doesn't exist after a quick sear. This is why drumsticks and thighs are better braised and breasts are better roasted \u2014 they're different muscles with different fat and collagen content.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Chicken Thigh Temperature &amp; Technique \u2014 explains why thighs handle heat differently than breasts</li> <li>Serious Eats \u2014 Coq au Vin \u2014 the classic</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Coq au Vin + crusty bread + simple green salad (the braise is the whole meal)</p> <p>Skill note: Taste the braising liquid at three stages \u2014 raw, after it reduces by half, after the chicken has spent 45 minutes in it. The flavor evolution is the lesson.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Coq au Vin (Jacques P\u00e9pin) \u2014 Watch how he handles the braising liquid at each stage and the moment he decides the sauce is done \u2014 compare it to what your pot smells like halfway through.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#session-9-pan-seared-chicken-breast-pan-sauce","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Pan-Seared Chicken Breast + Pan Sauce","text":"<p>Skill: The hardest everyday cook: a chicken breast at exactly the right temperature, seared in a pan, with a pan sauce built from the fond. Two proteins in two weeks \u2014 earlier in the block's whole bird and tonight's breast \u2014 show you how different the same animal can be when you change the cut and the method.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Pan-Seared Chicken Breast with White Wine Pan Sauce</li> <li>The pan sauce is the skill. Deglaze the fond. Reduce. Mount with butter. Taste. Fix.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Pan-seared chicken breast + pan sauce + Serious Eats \u2014 Honey-Roasted Carrots + whatever grain you have</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Secret Technique for the Juiciest Chicken Cutlets \u2014 Watch how he controls the sear to hit exactly 160\u00b0F without overcooking \u2014 the same logic applies to your breast tonight.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#session-10-project-duck-confit","title":"\u23f0 Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Duck Confit","text":"<p>Skill: Confit is patience-based cooking. Duck legs cured overnight in salt and aromatics, then slow-cooked in their own fat (or olive oil, which works fine) for 2\u20133 hours at 200\u00b0F. The result is impossibly tender, deeply flavorful meat that also crisp-skins beautifully when you finish it in a hot pan.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Classic Duck Confit</li> <li>Start the cure the evening before the project session. the project session is a long, low project cook. This is the kind of thing you can only learn by doing it.</li> </ul> <p>The the project menu: 1. Duck confit legs \u2014 crisped in a cast iron at high heat after the slow cook 2. Serious Eats \u2014 French Bistro Salad \u2014 fris\u00e9e or endive, lardons, mustard vinaigrette, a poached egg if you feel like it 3. Lentils or white beans cooked simply in the duck fat from the confit \u2014 this is called using the whole animal</p> <p>What you're proving to yourself: that patience and low heat create textures that no other method can.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Sunday Roasted Chicken, the Efficient Way (Ethan Chlebowski) \u2014 Before your confit, watch Ethan's reasoning about what heat does to poultry at each temperature \u2014 it gives direct context for why low-and-slow fat immersion produces such a different result.</p> <p>You've now cooked poultry four different ways in one week: high-heat whole roast, spatchcock, red-wine braise, pan sear, and duck confit. Write one paragraph: of everything in the first 14 weeks, what technique do you now feel like you actually own? What still feels like you're following instructions rather than cooking?</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#the-confit-technique","title":"The Confit Technique","text":"<p>Duck confit is the clearest example of a preserved food that gets better with time. The technique predates refrigeration \u2014 understanding the original purpose changes how you think about it.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 What the Heck Is Confit? | Ask The Food Lab \u2014 Kenji explains the term, the technique, and why it produces results that other low-and-slow methods don't.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#breaking-down-a-whole-chicken","title":"Breaking Down a Whole Chicken","text":"<p>The midpoint capstone includes whole-bird cookery. If you want to go deeper on butchery, this is the guide.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Break Down a Chicken \u2014 The step-by-step visual guide. Do this a few times and it becomes muscle memory.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Jacques P\u00e9pin breaks down a chicken \u2014 The most efficient human alive demonstrates what this skill looks like at speed. Watching once is worth three hours of reading.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Complete Robuchon by Jo\u00ebl Robuchon \u2014 The French culinary bible. Heavy reference for the classical techniques that anchor Module 2. Every major cooking method is here.</li> </ul> <p>\u2190 Weeks 13\u201314 | Weeks 17\u201318 \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Block 15\u201316 Quick Reference \u2014 Module 2 Capstone: Poultry &amp; Flavor Review","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/quick-ref.html#week-13-recipes-the-module-2-capstone-cook","title":"Week 13 Recipes \u2014 The Module 2 Capstone Cook","text":"Session Dish Skill Link Session 1 Menu planning Design a 3-course dinner for the project session \u2014 Session 2 Dry-run of your hardest project-session dish + Simple Green Salad Technique rehearsal, no pressure Salad Session 3 Thai-Style Larb + Jasmine Rice + Quick-Pickled Cucumbers Knife speed benchmark; acid + umami balance Larb \u00b7 Rice \u00b7 Pickles Session 4 Grilled Cheese + Tomato Soup Rest \u2014 mise en place the project dinner Grilled Cheese \u00b7 Tomato Soup Session 5 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: 3-Course Dinner for Guests \u2014 no recipes during service Full synthesis: Weeks 1\u201312 techniques Suggested: Shrimp Cocktail \u00b7 Duck Breast \u00b7 Polenta \u00b7 Root Veg"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/quick-ref.html#week-14-recipes-poultry-in-depth","title":"Week 14 Recipes \u2014 Poultry in Depth","text":"Session Dish Skill Link Session 6 \u23f0 High-Heat Roast Chicken + Roast Potatoes + Green Salad Dry brine; high-heat bird science Roast Chicken \u00b7 Roast Potatoes Session 7 Spatchcock Chicken + Roasted Cauliflower with Capers Spatchcocking; even doneness Spatchcock Method \u00b7 Cauliflower Session 8 Coq au Vin + Crusty Bread Braised poultry; collagen \u2192 gelatin Coq au Vin \u00b7 Thigh Technique Session 9 Pan-Seared Chicken Breast + Pan Sauce + Honey-Roasted Carrots Pan sauce from fond; breast precision Pan-Seared Chicken + Sauce \u00b7 Carrots Session 10 \u23f0 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Duck Confit + French Bistro Salad + Duck-Fat Lentils Confit; patience-based fat cooking Duck Confit \u00b7 Bistro Salad"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/quick-ref.html#the-midpoint-benchmarks","title":"The Midpoint Benchmarks","text":"Benchmark Week 1 Target Week 13 Target Onion dice Sub 5 min Sub 2 min, uniform cuts Pan sauce Can make one Can make one from memory with any fond Seasoning Season at end Season in layers, know what's missing Mise en place Forget half of it Everything prepped before heat goes on Stock Just bought it Made it, stored it, used it"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/quick-ref.html#shopping-notes","title":"Shopping Notes","text":"<p>Block 13 project dinner \u2014 shopping depends on your chosen menu. Plan it Session 1, shop mid-week.</p> <p>If using the suggested Shrimp Cocktail + Duck Breast menu: - Shrimp: 1 lb large shrimp (16/20 count), cocktail sauce ingredients - Duck: 2\u20134 duck breasts, cherries or cherry preserves for sauce, good red wine - Polenta: coarse-ground cornmeal, good parmesan, butter, chicken stock - Root vegetables: carrots, parsnips, turnips, beets \u2014 your choice of combination</p> <p>Block 13 Session 3 (Larb): Ground pork or chicken, fresh mint, cilantro, shallots, fish sauce, lime juice, toasted rice powder (make your own: toast rice in a dry pan, grind in spice grinder).</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 15\u201316: Module 2 Capstone: Poultry &amp; Flavor Review","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Block 13 shopping depends on your menu choice for 's dinner. The list below covers the suggested menu (shrimp cocktail + duck + polenta) plus Block 13's fixed weeknight meals. Block 14 content is coming soon.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/shopping-list.html#proteins-block-13-weeknights","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Block 13 Weeknights","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Ground pork or ground chicken \u2014 1 lb (Block 13 Larb)</li> <li>[ ] Duck breasts \u2014 2\u20134 (Block 13 suggested main) \u2014 found at specialty butchers and some grocery stores (Moulard or Pekin duck breasts both work)</li> <li>[ ] Large shrimp (shell-on, 16/20 count) \u2014 1 lb (Block 13 suggested starter)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/shopping-list.html#proteins-block-13-dinner-choose-your-menu","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Block 13 Dinner (choose your menu)","text":"<p>If using the suggested framework: - [ ] 2\u20134 duck breasts, skin-on (main course) - [ ] 1 lb large shrimp, shell-on (cocktail starter \u2014 cook shell-on, then peel)</p> <p>If making your own menu (based on Blocks 1\u201312 techniques): \u2014 write your list here \u2014</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/shopping-list.html#produce-block-13","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Block 13","text":"<p>** Larb:** - [ ] Fresh mint \u2014 1 large bunch - [ ] Fresh cilantro \u2014 1 bunch - [ ] Shallots \u2014 4 (thin-sliced) - [ ] Thai bird chilies or red Fresno chilies \u2014 3\u20134 - [ ] Limes \u2014 4 (fresh lime juice) - [ ] Jasmine rice \u2014 1 cup (also for toasted rice powder) - [ ] Cucumbers \u2014 2 (quick pickle) - [ ] Rice wine vinegar \u2014 1 cup (quick pickle) - [ ] Red onion \u2014 1 (quick pickle)</p> <p>: - [ ] Good bread \u2014 1 loaf (grilled cheese) - [ ] Tomatoes (canned) \u2014 2 cans (tomato soup) - [ ] Yellow onion \u2014 1 (soup)</p> <p>** dinner:** - [ ] Root vegetables (carrots, parsnips, turnips) \u2014 2 lbs (suggested main side) - [ ] Cherries (fresh or preserved) or quality cherry preserves \u2014 \u00bd cup (duck pan sauce) - [ ] Fresh thyme \u2014 1 bunch - [ ] Shallots \u2014 4 additional (duck pan sauce)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/shopping-list.html#dairy","title":"\ud83e\uddc0 Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Good cheese for a cheese board (1\u20132 varieties) \u2014 Block 13 optional third course</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 2 sticks (duck pan sauce, polenta finishing)</li> <li>[ ] Parmesan \u2014 4 oz (polenta)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 \u00bd cup (grilled cheese, optional; polenta finishing)</li> <li>[ ] Nice cheddar or Gruy\u00e8re \u2014 6 oz (grilled cheese)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry-goods","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Pantry &amp; Dry Goods","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Coarse-ground cornmeal (not instant) \u2014 \u00bd bag (Block 13 polenta)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken stock \u2014 32 oz (polenta + duck pan sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Good red wine \u2014 1 bottle (duck pan sauce + table)</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Block 13 Larb \u2014 already in pantry from Block 10?)</li> <li>[ ] Shrimp cocktail sauce: horseradish, ketchup, Worcestershire, Tabasco, lemon</li> <li>[ ] Jasmine rice \u2014 1 cup + extra for toasting (toasted rice powder for larb)</li> <li>[ ] Honey \u2014 1 jar (Block 13 cheese board)</li> <li>[ ] Good crackers or baguette (cheese board)</li> <li>[ ] Honeycomb (Block 13 cheese board \u2014 optional but impressive)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/02-building-flavor/15-16-midpoint-review/shopping-list.html#notes","title":"\ud83d\udcdd Notes","text":"<p>Larb (Block 13) \u2014 toasted rice powder: Toast 3 tbsp raw jasmine rice in a dry skillet over medium heat until golden, stirring constantly. Cool completely, then grind in a spice grinder or mortar and pestle to a coarse powder. This is a classic Thai technique and makes a significant difference in texture and flavor.</p> <p>Duck breast \u2014 the sear: Score the fat cap in a crosshatch pattern without cutting into the meat. Start in a cold pan (no oil) over low heat. Render the fat slowly for 8\u201310 minutes until most of it has melted and the skin is golden. Then flip once and finish in the oven at 400\u00b0F for 5\u20137 minutes. Rest 5 minutes. Duck is best medium-rare (130\u2013135\u00b0F internal).</p> <p>Block 13 rule: Everything is prepped and mis en placed before service starts. Once the first component goes on heat, no recipe tabs. You know what you're doing. Trust it.</p> <p>Block 14 (Poultry in Depth) \u2014 shopping list coming when content is finalized. You'll need: whole chickens, duck legs for confit, duck fat (or buy), and a selection of poultry for roasting experiments.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/index.html","title":"Module 3: The Proteins (Blocks 17\u201330)","text":"<p>The goal of this module: Master every major protein category \u2014 lamb and game, beef from cheap cuts to prime, pork in all its forms, finfish and shellfish, and finally the preserved meats of charcuterie. Each two-week block adds a new protein to your permanent repertoire.</p> <p>By the end of Week 30, you should be able to handle any cut of any animal with confidence and intention.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/index.html#weeks-in-this-module","title":"Weeks in This Module","text":"Weeks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 17\u201318 Lamb &amp; Game \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 19\u201320 Beef Fundamentals \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 21\u201322 Fish \u2014 Flatfish &amp; Round Fish \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 23\u201324 Whole Fish, Curing &amp; Advanced Seafood \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 25\u201326 Shellfish \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 27\u201328 Pork \u2014 All Cuts \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 29\u201330 Module 3 Capstone: Charcuterie &amp; Curing \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/index.html#core-skills-covered","title":"Core Skills Covered","text":"<ul> <li>Lamb &amp; game \u2014 rack, shoulder, shanks; braising and roasting; duck confit; temperature and timing for pink lamb</li> <li>Beef \u2014 steaks (sear, reverse sear, pan sauce); braising (short ribs, chuck, beef cheeks); ground beef and burgers; beef stock</li> <li>Fish \u2014 filleting round and flat fish; skin-on sear; en papillote; ceviche acid-cook; freshness indicators; whole fish grilling; curing and gravlax</li> <li>Shellfish \u2014 live and frozen; steaming, grilling, bisque; breaking down a lobster or Dungeness crab</li> <li>Pork \u2014 pork belly, shoulder, loin, and ribs; cure ratios, brining, fat rendering, crackling</li> <li>Charcuterie \u2014 dry-curing, equilibrium salt method, pork rillettes, p\u00e2t\u00e9, terrines; food safety in curing</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/index.html#equipment-youll-need","title":"Equipment You'll Need","text":"<p>See the Kitchen Equipment Guide. New items introduced in this module:</p> Item Introduced Cast iron skillet (12 inch) Week 17 Large Dutch oven (5\u20137 qt) Week 17 Wire rack + half-sheet pan Week 17 Instant-read thermometer Week 19 Outdoor grill or cast iron grill pan Week 21 Kitchen twine Week 21 Fish spatula Week 23 Shellfish brush Week 25 Spider strainer / skimmer Week 25 Kitchen scissors Week 25 <p>Previous module: Module 2 \u2014 Building Flavor (Weeks 9\u201316) Next module: Module 4 \u2014 The World's Kitchens (Weeks 31\u201348)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html","title":"\ud83d\udc11 Block 17\u201318: Lamb &amp; Game","text":"<p>\u2190 Quick Reference \u2192 | Shopping List \u2192</p> <p>\"Lamb is the most aromatic protein in the Western kitchen. Its fat carries flavors that no other animal's does \u2014 herbs cling to it, heat transforms it, and time mellows it into something profound. Learn lamb and you understand a third of the world's meat cuisines.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#before-you-start-block-17","title":"Before You Start Block 17","text":""},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#session-0-lamb-butchery-overview-optional","title":"Session 0 \u2014 Lamb Butchery Overview (optional)","text":"<p>Skill: Understanding where lamb cuts come from \u2014 and why they cost what they cost. Tonight is theory and light hands-on work.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read first: Serious Eats \u2014 Lamb Cuts Explained \u2014 understand why a rack of loin costs four times what a shoulder does, and why that shoulder will taste better braised.</p> <p>The lamb primal map:</p> Primal Characteristics Cuts it yields Neck/chuck Heavily worked, collagen-rich Neck for stews, shoulder Shoulder Tough with fat, great for slow cooking Bone-in shoulder, blade chops Rack (rib) Tender, elegant Rack of lamb, rib chops Loin Most tender Loin chops, saddle Leg Semi-tough, versatile Bone-in leg, butterflied leg, mince Shank Very tough, gelatin-heavy Braised shank Breast/flank Thin, fatty, cheap Rolled breast, riblets <p>The butchery principle: Like beef, tough cuts (shank, shoulder, neck) need time and low heat. Rack and loin are cooked fast and hot. Leg sits in between \u2014 it can be roasted as a whole or butterflied for the grill.</p> <p>Tonight: Ask your butcher to show you a whole leg alongside a rack. Examine the muscles, fat distribution, and bone placement. If your butcher is willing, watch them French the rack (clean the bones). This is the kind of knowledge you can't get from watching YouTube.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#block-17-lamb-hot-and-fast","title":"Block 17 \u2014 Lamb: Hot and Fast","text":"<p>\"Every culture that raises sheep has a way with lamb. France grills it with herbs de Provence. The Middle East marinates it in yogurt and cumin. Greece roasts a whole leg with lemon and oregano. The cut and the grill are universal; the spice is local.\"</p> <p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 4 (Slow-Roasted Shoulder): needs 4 hours; start by early afternoon</li> <li>Session 5 (PROJECT: Lamb Feast): multi-component; allow 3\u20134 hrs</li> <li>Session 6 (Braised Shanks): 2.5\u20133 hrs braising; start by early afternoon</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#session-1-lamb-chops-pan-sear-grill","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Lamb Chops: Pan-Sear &amp; Grill","text":"<p>Skill: Lamb chops are the steak of the lamb world \u2014 quick-cook, best rare to medium, and benefiting enormously from a hard sear. Tonight: rib chops with a rosemary-garlic crust. The fat cap should be rendered; the interior pink and luscious.</p> <ul> <li>Read first: Recipe Tin Eats \u2014 Lamb Chops \u2014 covers both pan-searing and grilling, seasoning, and resting</li> <li>Technique key: Press the fat cap against the hot pan first (30 seconds to 1 minute) to render it before searing the flesh sides. Lamb fat that hasn't been rendered is the source of the \"muttony\" flavor people complain about \u2014 render it and it becomes sweet and fragrant.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Pan-seared rib chops + Serious Eats \u2014 Best Roast Potatoes Ever + simple salad of cucumber, tomato, and feta</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Cook Lamb Chops \u2014 Gordon Ramsay \u2014 Watch his pan temperature, his herb basting technique, and the resting time. The herbs should be singed and fragrant, not raw.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#session-2-rack-of-lamb-the-showstopper","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Rack of Lamb: The Showstopper","text":"<p>Skill: A rack of lamb is one of the most dramatic presentations in domestic cooking \u2014 a row of eight rib bones, Frenched bare, the loin curved into a perfect arc. The technique is straightforward: a hard sear on all sides, then a brief roasting until the interior reaches 125\u2013130\u00b0F (rare to medium-rare). The crust: breadcrumbs, Dijon, and fresh herbs applied after searing.</p> <ul> <li>Technique: Sear the rack fat-side down to render some fat and build crust. Coat with Dijon mustard, then press herb-breadcrumb crust onto the fat cap. Roast at 425\u00b0F for 12\u201315 minutes. Rest 8 minutes before cutting between the bones.</li> <li>Serve with: BBC Good Food \u2014 Dauphinoise Potatoes \u2014 the classic French pairing. Start the dauphinoise 1.5 hours before the lamb.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Herb-crusted rack of lamb + dauphinoise potatoes + roasted green beans with toasted almonds</p> <p>Skill check: Use your thermometer. A $30 rack of lamb is not the time to \"trust your instincts.\"</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Gordon Ramsay's Rack of Lamb \u2014 Compare his searing order and crust application to your approach. Note when he puts the thermometer in.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#session-3-ground-lamb-kofta-and-beyond","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Ground Lamb: Kofta and Beyond","text":"<p>Skill: Ground lamb behaves differently from ground beef \u2014 it's fattier and more aromatic, which means it handles warming spices better and holds together more easily. Tonight: lamb kofta (grilled ground lamb skewers seasoned with cumin, coriander, cinnamon, and herbs). The technique \u2014 mixing, shaping, and grilling \u2014 applies to any ground lamb dish.</p> <ul> <li>Technique: Mix the ground lamb with spices by hand, working quickly so the fat doesn't warm. Wet your hands with cold water before shaping. Press firmly around the skiwer \u2014 they should be dense, not fluffy. If grilling, get the grill hot; they should cook in 8\u201310 minutes.</li> <li>Reference: The spice ratio for kofta: 1 lb ground lamb + 1 tsp cumin + 1 tsp coriander + \u00bc tsp cinnamon + \u00bd tsp paprika + salt + fresh parsley. That's it.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Lamb kofta skewers + warm flatbread or pita + tzatziki + Serious Eats \u2014 Shirazi Salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Lamb Kofta from Scratch \u2014 Watch the shaping technique and the grill management \u2014 a kofta that falls off the skewer is usually under-mixed or too warm.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#session-4-slow-roasted-lamb-shoulder","title":"\u23f0 Session 4 \u2014 Slow-Roasted Lamb Shoulder","text":"<p>Skill: Lamb shoulder is to lamb what chuck roast is to beef \u2014 the best-flavored, toughest-textured cut that rewards patience with extraordinary results. At 300\u00b0F for 4 hours, the tough shoulder muscles relax, the fat renders, and the meat becomes fork-pullable with a deep, sweet flavor nothing else can replicate.</p> <ul> <li>Technique: Score the fat cap in a crosshatch. Stuff the cuts with garlic slivers and rosemary. Rub with olive oil, salt, lemon zest, and dried oregano. Place on a rack over a pan of onions and a splash of white wine. Roast at 300\u00b0F until a fork twists out with no resistance (4\u20135 hours). Rest 20 minutes before pulling.</li> <li>From the book: This is one of the most satisfying weeknight project cooks \u2014 it takes 10 minutes to prep and 4 hours of patience. The house will smell extraordinary for the last hour.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Slow-roasted lamb shoulder (pulled or sliced) + BBC Good Food \u2014 Dauphinoise Potatoes OR roasted root vegetables + plain Greek yogurt as sauce</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Roast a Lamb Shoulder \u2014 Jamie Oliver \u2014 Note the internal temperature reading and the resting time relative to the size of the cut. Big shoulders need longer rests than their oven time would suggest.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#session-5-project-a-lamb-feast-for-four","title":"\u23f0 Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: A Lamb Feast for Four","text":"<p>The challenge: Cook a complete lamb dinner for at least four people. Every component planned, prepped, and executed together.</p> <p>Suggested menu:</p> Course Dish Notes Starter Serious Eats \u2014 Tzatziki with warm pita Make in the morning Meze Hummus, olives, roasted peppers, feta Bought is fine Main Rack of lamb (from Session 2) or slow-roasted shoulder (from Session 4) Choose the one you found more rewarding Side 1 BBC Good Food \u2014 Dauphinoise Potatoes Start 1.5 hrs before service Side 2 Green vegetable of your choice Season it confidently Dessert Serious Eats \u2014 Best Brownies Make in the morning <p>Skill targets: Everything on the table at the same time. Lamb at proper internal temperature. No phone open during service.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#block-18-braising-lamb-introduction-to-game","title":"Block 18 \u2014 Braising Lamb &amp; Introduction to Game","text":"<p>\"The 18th-century French kitchen didn't waste a single animal. Duck confit, rabbit stew, venison daube \u2014 what we now call 'game cooking' was then just Thursday. Humble ingredients, extraordinary results.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#session-6-braised-lamb-shanks","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Braised Lamb Shanks","text":"<p>Skill: The lamb shank is the gateway braise \u2014 it has a dramatic bone-in presentation, deeply flavored meat that falls away from the bone, and braising liquid that becomes a rich, winey sauce. Plan 2.5 to 3 hours in the oven.</p> <ul> <li>Read first: BBC Good Food \u2014 Braised Lamb Shanks \u2014 follow this technique; it's the canonical approach</li> <li>Also see: Recipe Tin Eats \u2014 Slow Cooked Lamb Shanks for a slightly different flavor profile with similar technique</li> <li>The sauce: After braising, strain and reduce the braising liquid by half. Mount with a tablespoon of cold butter. This should coat a spoon \u2014 not drip.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Braised lamb shanks + Serious Eats \u2014 Creamy Polenta + gremolata (parsley + lemon zest + garlic, raw, scattered on finish)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Braised Lamb Shanks with Rosemary and Red Wine \u2014 Notice how the liquid level is set: one-third up the shank, not covering it. Lamb shanks braise, not boil.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#session-7-lamb-navarin-french-spring-braise","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Lamb Navarin (French Spring Braise)","text":"<p>Skill: Navarin d'agneau is the French version of lamb stew \u2014 but it's lighter and more aromatic than the braised shanks of Session 6. The vegetables go in at different times (root vegetables early, tender vegetables late). The result should taste of spring even in winter.</p> <ul> <li>Technique: Brown lamb neck or shoulder pieces (cut into 2-inch cubes) in batches. Build the sauce with onion, garlic, tomato paste, white wine, and lamb stock. Add turnips and carrots halfway through. Add peas and new potatoes in the last 20 minutes. Finish with fresh tarragon and parsley. The sauce should be light and brothy, not thick.</li> <li>Key lesson: Navarin is the anti-braise braise \u2014 everything is lighter than the shanks from Session 6. The herbs are fresh rather than dried. The liquid is white, not red. Cook it in a Dutch oven at 325\u00b0F for 1.5 hours maximum.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Lamb navarin + crusty baguette + nothing else is needed (it's a complete dish)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Navarin d'agneau \u2014 traditional French lamb stew \u2014 Watch when the different vegetables go in. Timing matters in a navarin; the spring vegetables must stay bright.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#session-8-duck-confit-technique-introduction","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Duck: Confit Technique Introduction","text":"<p>Skill: Duck fat-confiting is the gateway to French game cooking and the charcuterie tradition. Tonight: a simplified confit (duck legs slowly cooked submerged in their own rendered fat at low temperature until silky). You'll return to this technique in Block 27\u201328 with more depth \u2014 tonight is about understanding why it works.</p> <ul> <li>Read first: Recipe Tin Eats \u2014 Duck Confit \u2014 follow the full method</li> <li>Why it works: At 180\u2013200\u00b0F, the duck leg's collagen converts to gelatin while the fat prevents the surrounding liquid from reaching above that temperature. The duck can't overcook because the fat constrains the temperature. It's physics as cooking technique.</li> <li>Prep note: Duck legs benefit from an overnight salt cure (just salt, thyme, garlic, bay leaf rubbed on) before confiting. If you can start this the night before, do it.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Duck confit legs + Serious Eats \u2014 Best Roast Potatoes Ever (roast them in duck fat \u2014 yes, it's worth it) + bitter greens with mustard vinaigrette</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Duck Confit: How, Why, and When to Make It \u2014 The temperature chart midway through the video shows exactly how the confit temperature plateau works. This is phyiscs-as-cooking in a single clear graphic.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#session-9-pan-seared-duck-breast","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Pan-Seared Duck Breast","text":"<p>Skill: Duck breast is the most forgiving of the \"game\" proteins if you understand one thing: render the fat first. Score the skin in a tight crosshatch, place it cold into a cold pan, and bring up the heat slowly. The fat renders from beneath; the skin becomes lacquered and crisp; the interior reaches medium-rare (130\u00b0F) without overcooking.</p> <ul> <li>Technique: Score crosshatch without cutting into the flesh. Season generously. Cold pan, skin-side down, medium-low heat until the fat has rendered and skin is golden \u2014 8 to 12 minutes. Flip, 3 minutes on the flesh side. Rest 5 minutes. The rendered duck fat in the pan is yours to keep \u2014 refrigerate and use for potatoes all week.</li> <li>Sauce option: A quick cherry pan sauce (deglaze with red wine, add chicken stock and a handful of pitted cherries, reduce until syrupy) is the classic pairing.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Pan-seared duck breast + cherry pan sauce + Serious Eats \u2014 Quick-Pickled Cucumbers + saut\u00e9ed greens</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Cook Duck Breast \u2014 Perfect Every Time \u2014 Watch the cold-pan start. The fat renders from beneath before the skin ever browns \u2014 this is the opposite of every other sear you've done this month.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#session-10-project-lamb-duck-dinner","title":"\u23f0 Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Lamb &amp; Duck Dinner","text":"<p>The challenge: A composed dinner using both proteins from Block 18. Cook for at least four people. Plan the timing so both proteins arrive at the table rested and at proper temperature.</p> <p>Suggested menu:</p> Course Dish Timing Starter Chicken liver parfait + toast points BBC Good Food \u2014 Chicken Liver Parfait \u00b7 make the day before Main 1 Braised lamb shank Start 3 hrs before service Main 2 Pan-seared duck breast Start 20 mins before service Side Creamy polenta or dauphinoise potatoes Choose one Salad Bitter greens with walnut vinaigrette Dress right before serving <p>What you learn today: multi-protein timing. The braise waits; the duck can't. Build your timeline backwards from service.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#lamb-across-cultures","title":"Lamb Across Cultures","text":"<p>The same animal, radically different treatments.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 Persian-Style Slow-Roasted Spiced Lamb Shoulder \u2014 The herb and spice treatment is different; the technique is identical to what you did in Session 4. That's the whole lesson.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 Greek Moussaka \u2014 Ground lamb as the base of a baked layered dish with b\u00e9chamel. The same ground meat from Session 3, a completely different application.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#duck-and-game-the-french-tradition","title":"Duck and Game: The French Tradition","text":"<p>Duck confit and duck breast are the entry point into French farmhouse cooking \u2014 a tradition built on preservation and maximum use of every animal.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Recipe Tin Eats \u2014 Duck Confit \u2014 Read the \"Why This Works\" section carefully. The physics of fat-as-temperature-controller are the same principle as sous vide, invented centuries earlier.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Jacques P\u00e9pin \u2014 Duck Preparations \u2014 P\u00e9pin has forgotten more about duck cookery than most chefs will ever know. Watch the efficiency and confidence \u2014 no second-guessing.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Bones: Recipes, History, and Lore by Jennifer McLagan \u2014 McLagan covers the whole animal, including lamb and game cuts most cookbooks ignore. The shank and navarin chapters are the most relevant for this block.</li> </ul> <p>\u2190 Block 15\u201316: Midpoint Review | Block 19\u201320: Beef Fundamentals \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Block 17\u201318 Quick Reference \u2014 Lamb &amp; Game","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/quick-ref.html#block-17-recipes-lamb-chops-to-shoulder","title":"Block 17 Recipes \u2014 Lamb: Chops to Shoulder","text":"Session Dish Skill Links Session 1 Pan-Seared Lamb Chops + Roast Potatoes + Salad Hard sear; render the fat cap first; internal 125\u2013130\u00b0F Lamb Chops \u00b7 Roast Potatoes Session 2 Herb-Crusted Rack of Lamb + Dauphinoise + Green Beans Frenching; dijon-breadcrumb crust; high-heat roast to 125\u2013130\u00b0F Rack of Lamb \u2014 SE \u00b7 Dauphinoise Session 3 Ground Lamb Kofta + Flatbread + Tzatziki Ground lamb; cumin-coriander-cinnamon spice blend; skewer Kofta Session 4 \u23f0 Slow-Roasted Lamb Shoulder + Root Veg Low-and-slow 300\u00b0F / 4\u20135 hrs; collagen conversion; probe-tender Lamb Shoulder Session 5 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Lamb Dinner for Four Full synthesis: butcher, season, cook, plate at scale All Lamb \u2014 SE"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/quick-ref.html#block-18-recipes-braises-duck-game","title":"Block 18 Recipes \u2014 Braises, Duck &amp; Game","text":"Session Dish Skill Links Session 6 \u23f0 Braised Lamb Shanks + Creamy Polenta + Gremolata Brown hard; braise 2.5 hrs; reduce sauce; gremolata finish Braised Shanks \u00b7 Polenta Session 7 \u23f0 Lamb Navarin (French Spring Braise) + Baguette Staggered veg add times; lighter braise; acid balance Lamb Navarin \u2014 SE Session 8 \u23f0 Duck Confit + Duck-Fat Roast Potatoes + Bitter Greens Low-temp fat rendering; no browning until the finish Duck Confit Session 9 Pan-Seared Duck Breast + Cherry Pan Sauce + Pickled Cucumbers Cold-pan fat render; score skin; medium-rare 130\u00b0F Duck Breast \u2014 SE \u00b7 Pickled Cucumbers Session 10 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Game &amp; Lamb Dinner for Guests Full multi-element meal; timing; plating at scale Merguez \u2014 SE"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/quick-ref.html#internal-temperature-guide-lamb-duck","title":"Internal Temperature Guide \u2014 Lamb &amp; Duck","text":"Protein Target Notes Lamb chops / rack 125\u2013130\u00b0F Served pink (medium-rare); carryover to ~135\u00b0F Lamb shoulder / shanks 195\u00b0F+ Collagen fully converted; probe meets no resistance Duck breast 130\u2013135\u00b0F Serve pink; score skin deeply before cooking Duck confit 165\u00b0F+ Food-safety minimum; cook slow until fat-tender"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/quick-ref.html#technique-reference-key-skills-this-block","title":"Technique Reference \u2014 Key Skills This Block","text":"Technique When Key Signal Fat cap rendering (chops) Before searing; hold chop upright Fat turns translucent, stops rolling Dijon-breadcrumb crust (rack) After initial sear, before oven Applied cold; golden at 10 min Low-and-slow shoulder 300\u00b0F / 4\u20135 hours Probe inserts with zero resistance Braising (shanks, navarin) Stovetop brown \u2192 oven Liquid at \u00bd height; never a full boil Gremolata finish Stir in raw at table Parsley + lemon zest + garlic; cuts richness Duck skin scoring Before any heat; cold pan start Tight crosshatch; don't cut the flesh <p>Navigation: \u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 17\u201318: Lamb &amp; Game","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Block 17 is lamb from quick-cook (chops, rack) to slow (shoulder). Block 18 is braises and duck. Buy fresh lamb chops and duck breasts the day before or day-of. Lamb shoulder and shanks may need to be ordered from a butcher \u2014 call ahead. Duck legs for confit should be bought Thursday if you plan a weekend cook.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Instant-read thermometer \u2014 lamb is served pink; you need a thermometer</li> <li>[ ] Cast iron skillet or grill pan \u2014 chops, rack sear, duck breast</li> <li>[ ] Large Dutch oven (5\u20137 qt) \u2014 both braises (shanks, navarin)</li> <li>[ ] Wire rack + half-sheet pan \u2014 elevated roasting for the rack of lamb</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/shopping-list.html#proteins-block-17","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Block 17","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Lamb rib chops \u2014 4\u20136 chops, 1 inch thick (Session 1). Dry brine overnight if time allows.</li> <li>[ ] Rack of lamb \u2014 1 full rack (8 ribs), Frenched or French-it-yourself (Session 2). May need to order from a butcher.</li> <li>[ ] Ground lamb \u2014 1 lb, 80\u201385% lean (Session 3 kofta). Avoid extra-lean \u2014 fat = flavour.</li> <li>[ ] Bone-in lamb shoulder \u2014 3\u20134 lbs (Session 4 slow roast). Call your butcher ahead; shoulder is rarely on display.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/shopping-list.html#proteins-block-18","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Block 18","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Lamb shanks \u2014 2 large or 4 small; hind shanks preferred (Session 6). 2.5\u20133 hours to braise.</li> <li>[ ] Bone-in lamb neck or shoulder cut into stew pieces \u2014 1.5 lbs (Session 7 navarin)</li> <li>[ ] Duck legs \u2014 4 legs with thighs attached, skin on (Session 8 confit). Asian markets and specialty butchers reliable. Buy Thursday for a weekend cook.</li> <li>[ ] Duck breasts \u2014 2 magret-style breasts, skin on (Session 9). Larger breasts are easier \u2014 smaller ones overcook quickly.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/shopping-list.html#aromatics-produce","title":"\ud83e\uddc5 Aromatics &amp; Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Fresh rosemary \u2014 large bunch (chops, rack crust, navarin)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh thyme \u2014 large bunch (braises, confit)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh flat-leaf parsley \u2014 navarin, gremolata</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 4 (gremolata, tzatziki)</li> <li>[ ] White onions \u2014 4 (navarin and braise base)</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 6 (navarin and braise base)</li> <li>[ ] Celery \u2014 1 bunch (braise base)</li> <li>[ ] Turnips or parsnips (optional, navarin)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh peas or haricots verts \u2014 navarin finishing, salad sides</li> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 1 pint</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/shopping-list.html#dairy","title":"\ud83e\udd5b Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Duck fat \u2014 1 jar (~14 oz); or render from extra duck legs bought ahead</li> <li>[ ] Greek yogurt \u2014 16 oz (tzatziki for Session 3, sauce for shoulder)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 2 sticks (pan sauces, duck breast finish)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/shopping-list.html#wine-cooking-liquids","title":"\ud83c\udf77 Wine &amp; Cooking Liquids","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dry red wine \u2014 1 bottle (braised shanks; any C\u00f4tes du Rh\u00f4ne or similar)</li> <li>[ ] Dry white wine \u2014 1 bottle (navarin and vegetables)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken or lamb stock \u2014 32 oz (braise base for Sessions 6 and 7)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/17-18-lamb-and-game/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard \u2014 rack crust and vinaigrette</li> <li>[ ] Panko breadcrumbs \u2014 rack herb crust</li> <li>[ ] Dried cumin, coriander, cinnamon, allspice \u2014 kofta spice blend</li> <li>[ ] Flat pita or lavash \u2014 kofta wraps (Session 3)</li> <li>[ ] Polenta (coarse-ground) \u2014 Session 6 side</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html","title":"Full Guide","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 17\u201318: Lamb &amp; Game</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#block-1920-beef-fundamentals","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Block 19\u201320: Beef Fundamentals","text":"<p>\"Beef is the protein that most home cooks think they know \u2014 and most do not. A good steak is not about the grill. It is about salt, time, temperature, and rest. A good braise is not about long cooking. It is about connective tissue chemistry. Everything else is negotiable.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#the-challenge-of-this-block","title":"The Challenge of This Block","text":"<p>You have cooked poultry, fish, lamb, and pork. Beef presents a different problem: it is the most unforgiving protein at high heat and the most rewarding at low heat. The range between a perfect medium-rare ribeye and an overcooked one is about four minutes and ten degrees. The range between a properly braised short rib and a dried-out one is about two hours and technique.</p> <p>Over two weeks, you will work through the full spectrum of beef cookery: quick, high-heat searing; low-and-slow braising; ground beef applications; stock and sauce extraction; and finally a complete beef-centered dinner as your project session.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#block-19-high-heat-beef-steaks-searing-the-maillard-reaction","title":"Block 19 \u2014 High-Heat Beef: Steaks, Searing &amp; the Maillard Reaction","text":"<p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 1 (Steak Searing): Salt your steak at least 45 minutes before cooking \u2014 or the night before</li> <li>Session 5 (PROJECT: Steak Dinner): Write your mise en place list the day before; rest the steak before slicing</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#session-1-the-science-of-searing-a-steak","title":"Session 1 \u2014 The Science of Searing a Steak","text":"<p>Skill: Dry-brine salting; cast iron vs. stainless searing; internal temperature reading; resting</p> <p>Read first: - The Food Lab's Complete Guide to Pan-Seared Steaks \u2014 the foundational reference; read the full thing - Why You Should Rest Your Meat</p> <p>What you're learning: A steak is not cooked by heat alone \u2014 it is cooked by time at temperature. The Maillard reaction (the browning that creates crust flavor) requires a dry surface and high heat. Moisture prevents browning. This is why patting dry matters, why high-smoke-point oil matters, and why crowding the pan kills the sear.</p> <p>Exercise: - Dry-brine a 1-inch ribeye or NY strip 45 minutes to 24 hours ahead with kosher salt - Pat completely dry before cooking - Sear in cast iron or carbon steel over high heat with a neutral oil - Baste with butter, garlic, and thyme in the final minute - Rest 5 minutes before cutting - Cut and evaluate: internal temp, crust quality, resting juice loss</p> <p>Target: Medium-rare (130\u2013135\u00b0F internal before rest). Crust should be deep brown, not grey.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#session-2-cuts-grades-the-butcher-relationship","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Cuts, Grades &amp; the Butcher Relationship","text":"<p>Skill: Identifying beef primal cuts; understanding USDA grade; shopping for value cuts</p> <p>Read first: - A Complete Guide to Beef Cuts \u2014 understand where every cut comes from and why it cooks differently - The Best Cheap Steaks \u2014 skirt, hanger, flat iron, bavette</p> <p>What you're learning: Beef price correlates with tenderness, not flavor. The most flavorful cuts \u2014 hanger, skirt, chuck \u2014 are often the cheapest because they require more skill or shorter windows for optimal cooking. Once you understand the primal map (chuck, rib, loin, round, brisket, shank) and what connective tissue content means for each cut's ideal cooking method, you can shop intelligently for the rest of your life.</p> <p>Exercise: - Visit a butcher or good grocery and price-compare: ribeye vs. skirt vs. chuck steak vs. flat iron - Buy one \"cheap\" steak cut (hanger, skirt, or flat iron) - Cook it with the same dry-brine and sear method as Session 1 - Note: Where is this cut on the animal? What does that tell you about texture?</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#session-3-reverse-sear-thick-cuts","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Reverse Sear &amp; Thick Cuts","text":"<p>Skill: Reverse-sear method for thick steaks; thermometer reading; achieving even doneness edge-to-edge</p> <p>Read first: - The Reverse Sear is the Best Way to Cook a Thick Steak \u2014 the technique explained in full</p> <p>What you're learning: For steaks over 1.5 inches thick, the traditional high-heat sear produces an overcooked grey band under the crust while the center tries to reach temperature. The reverse sear solves this: bring the steak slowly to within 10\u00b0F of target in a low oven (250\u00b0F), then sear at screaming heat for a perfect crust. The result is edge-to-edge even doneness with no grey band.</p> <p>Exercise: - Buy a thick-cut steak (1.5\u20132 inches): ribeye, T-bone, or porterhouse - Reverse sear to 120\u00b0F internal in a 250\u00b0F oven - Rest, then sear hard for 60\u201390 seconds per side - Compare the cross-section to Session 1's traditional sear \u2014 note the crust-to-center gradient</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#session-4-pan-sauce-from-fond","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Pan Sauce from Fond","text":"<p>Skill: Building a pan sauce from beef drippings; deglazing; reduction; butter mounting</p> <p>Read first: - How to Make a Pan Sauce \u2014 the complete technique</p> <p>What you're learning: The brown bits stuck to your pan after searing a steak are one of the most flavorful things in your kitchen. They are caramelized proteins \u2014 fond \u2014 and the foundation of nearly every classic French sauce. Deglazing with wine or stock lifts them into solution, reduction concentrates the flavor, and a cold butter mount at the end creates emulsion and gloss.</p> <p>Exercise: - Sear a steak (any cut) and remove from pan, keeping it warm - Saut\u00e9 shallots in the residual fat - Deglaze with red wine or beef stock - Reduce by half; add a spoonful of Dijon if desired - Finish with 2 tablespoons of cold butter, swirling off heat - Season, pour over steak, serve immediately - Variation: Replace wine with cognac + cream for a pepper sauce (steak au poivre)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#session-5-project-the-steak-dinner","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: The Steak Dinner","text":"<p>Goal: A complete steak dinner for 2\u20134 people \u2014 starter, main, sides, pan sauce</p> <p>The assignment: Plan and execute a composed steak dinner using techniques from Sessions 1\u20134. Your meal should include at minimum:</p> <ol> <li>A simple starter (charcuterie, salad, or a soup you've made before)</li> <li>A steak \u2014 your choice of cut and method (traditional sear or reverse sear)</li> <li>A pan sauce</li> <li>At least two sides (a starch and a vegetable)</li> <li>Dessert is optional but encouraged</li> </ol> <p>Constraints: - The steak must be served at the correct temperature (use a thermometer) - The pan sauce must be made from the same pan as the steak - Time the dinner so nothing sits more than 5 minutes waiting for another component</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#block-20-low-heat-beef-braises-ground-stock","title":"Block 20 \u2014 Low-Heat Beef: Braises, Ground &amp; Stock","text":""},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#session-6-braising-beef-short-ribs-or-chuck","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Braising Beef: Short Ribs or Chuck","text":"<p>Skill: Proper braising technique; searing before braising; collagen-to-gelatin conversion; braising liquid composition</p> <p>Read first: - The Food Lab's Guide to Braised Short Ribs \u2014 the science of why braising works, and how to do it right - Everything You Need to Know About Braising</p> <p>What you're learning: Braising converts collagen (which makes tough cuts chewy) into gelatin (which makes them silky). This only happens above 160\u00b0F over time \u2014 which is why braising in a covered pot at 275\u2013325\u00b0F for 3\u20134 hours works, and why you can't rush it. The braising liquid becomes the sauce. The sear beforehand creates Maillard flavors that the liquid absorbs.</p> <p>Exercise: - Short ribs (bone-in, 3\u20134 lb) or a 3 lb chuck roast - Hard sear all sides in a Dutch oven; remove - Saut\u00e9 mirepoix (onion, carrot, celery) in the same pot - Add tomato paste; cook 2 minutes - Add 1 cup red wine; reduce by half - Return meat; add stock to cover halfway; add aromatics (bay, thyme, garlic) - Covered braise at 300\u00b0F for 3\u20134 hours until fork-tender - Remove meat; strain and reduce braising liquid to sauce consistency - Reserve: Keep any leftover braise \u2014 it improves with a day's rest</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#session-7-braising-liquid-as-sauce","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Braising Liquid as Sauce","text":"<p>Skill: Sauce extraction from braise liquid; defatting; reduction; finishing</p> <p>What you're learning: The braising liquid from the previous session is almost already a sauce \u2014 it just needs refinement. Defatting removes grease (chill and lift the fat cap, or use a fat separator). Reduction concentrates flavor. A touch of butter or a small amount of cream can finish it. This session teaches you to extract maximum value from what you've already cooked.</p> <p>Exercise \u2014 use yesterday's braise: - Strain all solids from the braising liquid - Chill in refrigerator for 1 hour; lift fat cap and discard - Return liquid to saucepan; reduce by half to two-thirds over medium heat - Taste and adjust: salt, a small splash of vinegar for brightness, or a teaspoon of Dijon - Finish with 1 tablespoon cold butter - Serve alongside reheated braise meat over egg noodles, creamy polenta, or mashed potatoes</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#session-8-burgers-fat-ratios-grind-shape","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Burgers: Fat Ratios, Grind &amp; Shape","text":"<p>Skill: Understanding ground beef fat content; burger blending; the smash burger technique vs. thick patty</p> <p>Read first: - The Food Lab's Best Burger \u2014 why most home burgers go wrong and how to fix them - The Smash Burger Technique Explained \u2014 why the smash works</p> <p>What you're learning: Ground beef fat content determines juiciness. 80/20 (chuck) is the standard for burgers; leaner grinds produce drier patties. The smash burger works because immediate surface contact with a screaming-hot pan maximizes Maillard browning across the whole patty surface \u2014 more crust per bite than any thick patty can achieve. The thick patty works for a different reason: interior moisture and texture that smashing destroys.</p> <p>Exercise A \u2014 Smash Burger: - 80/20 ground chuck, 3\u20134 oz balls (don't compact them \u2014 keep loose) - Screaming-hot cast iron; place ball, smash immediately with a spatula - Season salt and pepper; cook 90 seconds; flip; add cheese; cook 60 seconds - Serve on a toasted bun with simple condiments</p> <p>Exercise B \u2014 Thick Patty: - 80/20, 6\u20137 oz patties, 3/4 inch thick; make a dimple in center to prevent puffing - Same cast iron or grill; 2\u20133 minutes per side for medium-rare - Rest 2 minutes before serving</p> <p>Compare: Which do you prefer? Why?</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#session-9-beef-stock-its-derivatives","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Beef Stock &amp; Its Derivatives","text":"<p>Skill: Making brown beef stock from roasted bones; understanding veal vs. beef stock; demi-glace concept</p> <p>Read first: - How to Make Rich Beef Stock \u2014 the complete process</p> <p>What you're learning: Beef stock is the foundation of every classic French sauce and many other traditions. The difference between white and brown stock is whether the bones are roasted first (they are, for brown stock). Roasting creates Maillard compounds that the hot water extracts during the long, gentle simmer. This is why beef stock is darker, richer, and more complex than chicken stock \u2014 and why it takes 4\u20136 hours. A demi-glace is simply a reduction of brown stock and brown sauce combined, concentrated to near-syrup \u2014 the most powerful flavoring agent in European cooking.</p> <p>Exercise: - 2\u20134 lbs beef bones with marrow (ask your butcher; knuckles and marrow bones work best) - Roast at 425\u00b0F until deep brown, 45 minutes - Add roasted mirepoix (carrot, onion, celery roasted alongside) - Transfer to stockpot; cover with cold water; add tomato paste, bay, peppercorns - Simmer 4\u20136 hours, skimming regularly; never boil - Strain through fine-mesh; cool rapidly; defat - Store: Reduces to a semi-gelatinous consistency when chilled \u2014 that's the collagen working</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#session-10-project-the-braise-dinner","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: The Braise Dinner","text":"<p>Goal: A complete braised beef dinner featuring your Session 6 technique applied to a new cut</p> <p>The assignment: Execute a full dinner centered on a braised beef cut. You may use: - Short ribs (bone-in or boneless) - Chuck pot roast - Beef cheeks (particularly gelatinous and rich \u2014 exceptional result) - Oxtail (long cooking requirement: 5+ hours) - Ossobuco-style cross-cut shanks</p> <p>The meal structure: 1. Starter: Something simple \u2014 a green salad, a slab of bread with good butter, a light soup 2. Main: The braise with its reduction sauce 3. Accompaniment: Creamy polenta, egg noodles, mashed potatoes, or crusty bread to absorb the sauce 4. Optional: Gremolata (lemon zest, garlic, parsley) sprinkled at service \u2014 wakes up a slow braise immediately</p> <p>Metrics for success: - The meat is fork-tender without being dry - The sauce coats the back of a spoon - You have tasted and adjusted the sauce seasoning after reduction</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#the-science-of-beef-why-it-works-the-way-it-does","title":"The Science of Beef \u2014 Why It Works the Way It Does","text":"<p>Beef is unique among proteins in the way muscle fiber type, fat distribution, and collagen content vary so dramatically by cut. Understanding this isn't academic; it directly determines how you should cook every piece of beef you buy.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Food Lab's Guide to Steaks \u2014 If you read only one thing about beef, let it be this. Everything about heat, temperature, searing, resting, and why each decision matters.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Complete Beef Buying Guide \u2014 Every cut, every primal, every cooking method. Bookmark this and use it as a reference whenever you're at the butcher.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Make Demi-Glace at Home \u2014 This is a weekend project. But if you've made brown beef stock and want to understand where professional sauces come from, this is the next step.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#watching-it-done","title":"Watching It Done","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Salt Fat Acid Heat (Netflix) \u2014 Samin Nosrat's episode on fat includes sections on animal fat and its flavor contributions that will change how you think about beef cuts.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Food Lab by J. Kenji L\u00f3pez-Alt \u2014 The protein chapters cover beef in more depth than any other single resource. The steak chapter alone is worth the price of the book.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 17\u201318: Lamb &amp; Game | Block 21\u201322: Fish \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html","title":"Block 19\u201320: Beef Fundamentals \u2014 Quick Reference","text":""},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html#block-overview","title":"Block Overview","text":"Weeks 19\u201320 Focus High-heat searing, braising, ground beef, beef stock Project Sessions Session 5: Steak Dinner \u00b7 Session 10: Braise Dinner Key Equipment Cast iron skillet, Dutch oven, instant-read thermometer, fat separator"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html#the-two-tracks-of-beef-cooking","title":"The Two Tracks of Beef Cooking","text":"Method Best Cuts Target Temp Time High heat (sear/grill) Ribeye, NY strip, hanger, skirt, flat iron 130\u2013135\u00b0F (medium-rare) 4\u201310 min total Reverse sear Thick-cut ribeye, T-bone, porterhouse 120\u00b0F oven \u2192 sear finish 45\u201390 min + 2 min sear Low heat (braise) Chuck, short ribs, brisket, cheeks, oxtail 195\u2013205\u00b0F internal 3\u20136 hours Ground beef 80/20 chuck blend Smash: no temp check; Thick: 155\u00b0F 3\u20136 min total"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html#internal-temperature-guide","title":"Internal Temperature Guide","text":"Doneness Pull Temp Final Temp Rare 120\u00b0F 125\u00b0F Medium-rare 128\u00b0F 130\u2013133\u00b0F Medium 135\u00b0F 140\u00b0F Medium-well 145\u00b0F 150\u00b0F Well (avoid) 155\u00b0F+ 160\u00b0F+ <p>Pull from heat 5\u00b0F before target; carryover cooking does the rest.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html#steak-fundamentals-checklist","title":"Steak Fundamentals \u2014 Checklist","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Salt steak 45 min to 24 hours ahead (dry brine); pat dry before cooking</li> <li>[ ] Pan (cast iron or carbon steel) ripping hot before steak goes in</li> <li>[ ] Neutral oil \u2014 not olive oil; smoke point matters</li> <li>[ ] Sear undisturbed; flip only when crust releases cleanly</li> <li>[ ] Butter baste in final minute with garlic and thyme</li> <li>[ ] Rest minimum 5 min before cutting (longer for thick steaks)</li> <li>[ ] Cut against the grain always</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html#pan-sauce-formula-from-any-steak-fond","title":"Pan Sauce Formula (from any steak fond)","text":"<ol> <li>Remove steak; pour off excess fat; leave fond</li> <li>Saut\u00e9 shallots 1\u20132 min in residual fat</li> <li>Deglaze: wine, cognac, or stock \u2014 scrape every bit of fond</li> <li>Reduce by half</li> <li>Add 1 tsp Dijon (optional); taste; adjust salt</li> <li>Remove from heat; swirl in 2 tbsp cold butter until glossy</li> <li>Pour immediately over rested steak</li> </ol> <p>Pepper Sauce (au poivre): add crushed peppercorns before deglazing; deglaze with cognac; finish with cream instead of butter.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html#braising-the-process","title":"Braising \u2014 The Process","text":"Step Detail Dry and season Pat dry; salt generously; let sit Hard sear All sides in Dutch oven; deep brown crust Build aromatics Mirepoix in same fat; add tomato paste; cook 2 min Deglaze Red wine or stock; scrape fond; reduce by half Add liquid Stock to cover meat by half Low oven 275\u2013325\u00b0F, covered, 3\u20136 hours depending on cut Check tenderness Fork slides in with zero resistance Sauce from liquid Strain; defat; reduce to coating consistency"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html#cut-guide-quick","title":"Cut Guide (Quick)","text":"Cut Method Notes Ribeye Sear or reverse sear High fat marbling; most forgiving NY Strip Sear Firmer texture; great crust Hanger (\"butcher's secret\") Quick sear, medium-rare Intense flavor; must be sliced thin against grain Skirt steak Quick sear, maximum 2 min/side Thin; cooks fast; coarse grain \u2014 always slice across Flat iron Sear Tender and affordable Chuck Braise or pot roast Flavored by fat and connective tissue Short ribs Braise Most collagen \u2192 richest sauce Beef cheeks Long braise (4\u20135 hr) Silkiest texture; best beginner braise Brisket Very long braise or smoke (8+ hr) Low-and-slow; do not rush Oxtail Very long braise (5\u20136 hr) Gelatinous; makes remarkable sauce"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html#ground-beef-two-techniques","title":"Ground Beef \u2014 Two Techniques","text":"<p>Smash Burger: 80/20, loose 3-oz ball, screaming-hot cast iron, immediate smash with spatula, 90 sec per side. Thick Patty: 80/20, 6-7 oz, 3/4-inch thick, dimple center, 3 min per side for medium-rare.</p> <p>Fat content rule: 80/20 for burgers. 85/15 for meatballs and sauce. 90/10 for taco/skillet applications.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html#beef-stock-simplified","title":"Beef Stock \u2014 Simplified","text":"<ol> <li>Roast bones at 425\u00b0F, 45 min, until dark brown</li> <li>Cold water start; bring to bare simmer, never boil  </li> <li>Skim foam for first 30 min; continue to skim occasionally</li> <li>Add roasted mirepoix, tomato paste, bay, peppercorns at hour 1</li> <li>Simmer 4\u20136 hours total; strain through fine mesh</li> <li>Cool rapidly; refrigerate; lift fat cap; freeze in 1-cup portions</li> </ol>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/quick-ref.html#session-targets","title":"Session Targets","text":"Session What You're Cooking Key Technique 1 Pan-seared ribeye or strip Dry brine, Maillard sear, resting 2 Value-cut steak (skirt, hanger, flat iron) Cut selection, quick sear 3 Thick-cut steak (1.5\u20132 in) Reverse sear 4 Steak + pan sauce Fond, deglazing, butter mount 5 (PROJECT) Full steak dinner Complete service 6 Braised short ribs or chuck Dutch oven braise 7 Braise sauce extraction Defatting, reduction 8 Burgers \u2014 smash and thick Two techniques compared 9 Beef stock Bone-roasting, long simmer 10 (PROJECT) Full braise dinner Complete service"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/shopping-list.html","title":"Block 19\u201320: Beef Fundamentals \u2014 Shopping List","text":"<p>This list covers all 10 sessions across both weeks. Sessions 5 and 10 are PROJECT dinners \u2014 buy protein for those when planning your guest count.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/shopping-list.html#proteins","title":"Proteins","text":"Item Qty Notes Ribeye or NY strip steak, 1-inch thick 1\u20132 steaks Session 1 Budget steak: skirt, hanger, or flat iron 1 steak Session 2 Thick-cut ribeye, T-bone, or porterhouse (1.5\u20132 in) 1 steak Session 3 Steak (any cut \u2014 your preference) + extra for sauce 1 steak Session 4 Steak for PROJECT dinner Enough for guests Session 5 Beef short ribs (bone-in) or chuck roast 3\u20134 lb Session 6\u20137 80/20 ground chuck 1.5\u20132 lb Session 8 PROJECT braise cut (short ribs, chuck, beef cheeks, oxtail) 3\u20135 lb Session 10 Beef marrow or knuckle bones 2\u20134 lb Session 9 (ask butcher)"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/shopping-list.html#aromatics-vegetables-sessions-610","title":"Aromatics &amp; Vegetables (Sessions 6\u201310)","text":"Item Qty Notes Yellow onions 4\u20135 Mirepoix, stock Carrots 4\u20135 Mirepoix, stock Celery stalks 4\u20135 Mirepoix, stock Garlic bulb 1 All sessions Shallots 4\u20136 Pan sauces Fresh thyme 1 bunch Basting, braise Bay leaves 4\u20136 Braise, stock Fresh rosemary 1 sprig Optional for lamb-style variations"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"Pantry","text":"Item Notes Kosher salt Generous dry-brining Black peppercorns (whole) Stock; cracked for au poivre Neutral oil (avocado, grapeseed) High-smoke-point for searing Unsalted butter Basting, pan sauce mount, braise finish Dijon mustard Pan sauce option Tomato paste Braise and stock Beef or chicken stock Deglazing, braising liquid (homemade or store-bought) Red wine (1 bottle) Braise + deglazing across multiple sessions Worcestershire sauce Optional burger enhancement"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/shopping-list.html#for-burgers-session-8","title":"For Burgers (Session 8)","text":"Item Qty 80/20 ground chuck 1.5\u20132 lb Burger buns 4\u20136 American cheese (for smash) or your preference 4\u20136 slices Lettuce, tomato, onion As desired Condiments: ketchup, mustard, mayo, pickles As desired"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/shopping-list.html#equipment-checklist","title":"Equipment Checklist","text":"<p>Ensure these are on hand before starting Block 19\u201320:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Cast iron skillet or carbon steel pan (essential for proper searing)</li> <li>[ ] Dutch oven or oven-safe heavy pot (braising)</li> <li>[ ] Instant-read thermometer (non-negotiable for steak doneness)</li> <li>[ ] Tongs (never a fork \u2014 piercing steak loses juice)</li> <li>[ ] Splatter screen (optional but highly recommended for searing)</li> <li>[ ] Fat separator or ladle + small bowl (defatting braising liquid)</li> <li>[ ] Fine-mesh strainer (stock)</li> <li>[ ] Sheet tray + rack (reverse sear, bone roasting)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/19-20-beef-fundamentals/shopping-list.html#notes-for-shopping","title":"Notes for Shopping","text":"<ul> <li>Short ribs: Ask for bone-in English-cut short ribs, 2\u20133 inches thick. English cut gives you large, impressive slabs; flanken cut (thin, across bone) is better for Korean-style cooking.</li> <li>Beef cheeks: An excellent choice for Session 10 if your butcher carries them. Often cheaper than short ribs with a more silky, unctuous result.</li> <li>Oxtail: Available at most butchers and many supermarkets. Requires 5\u20136 hours of braising. Plan ahead.</li> <li>Marrow bones: Ask the butcher to cut them into 2-inch segments. Many butchers give these away or sell very cheaply for stock.</li> <li>Skirt steak: Inside skirt is more tender than outside skirt. Outside skirt has more flavor. Either works.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html","title":"\ud83d\udc1f Block 21\u201322: Seafood \u2014 Fish","text":"<p>\u2190 Quick Reference \u2192 | Shopping List \u2192</p> <p>\"Fish is the most immediate teacher in the kitchen. You overcooked it? You know in 30 seconds. The window for perfection is narrow \u2014 narrow enough that it forces your full attention every time.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#before-you-start-block-21","title":"Before You Start Block 21","text":""},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#session-0-fillet-a-whole-fish-optional","title":"Session 0 \u2014 Fillet a Whole Fish (optional)","text":"<p>Skill: Breaking down a whole round fish into two clean fillets. This is the single most useful fish skill you can own \u2014 when you can fillet, you buy whole fish (cheaper, fresher, more honest), and you understand why a halibut fillet costs what it does.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read and watch before starting: Serious Eats \u2014 How to Fillet a Fish \u2014 the Kenji walkthrough is the clearest English-language video on this.</p> <p>The technique for a round fish (salmon, sea bass, snapper, branzino): 1. Find the backbone \u2014 place the fish belly-down; feel the spine through the flesh 2. First cut \u2014 score behind the head diagonally to the backbone; don't cut through 3. Run the knife along the spine \u2014 blade angled slightly toward the bone, long smooth strokes, let the backbone guide you; use the rib cage as a fence 4. Fillet off the ribcage \u2014 once past the spine, angle the knife to follow the rib curve; you should hear the blade scraping bone (that's correct \u2014 you're not wasting meat that way) 5. Pin bones \u2014 run your finger down the centerline of the fillet; tiny bones perpendicular to the flesh. Pull with needle-nose pliers or fish tweezers, always pulling in the direction the bone points 6. Repeat for the second fillet</p> <p>Freshness signals \u2014 know these before you go to the fishmonger: - Eyes: clear and slightly bulging. Cloudy or sunken = not fresh - Gills: bright red when fresh; brown or grey = older fish - Smell: clean, oceanic, or neutral. \"Fishy\" smell is TMA (trimethylamine) \u2014 bacterial decomposition. Fresh fish smells like the sea, not like fish - Flesh: springs back when pressed; doesn't hold the indentation - \"Sushi-grade\" has no legal definition \u2014 it means the seller is comfortable selling it raw. Ask your fishmonger directly</p> <p>Full Meal: Fillet and cook the fish in whatever style you prefer tonight \u2014 the miso glaze is already prepped for later in the block, or use the earlier pan-sear technique (crispy skin pan sear). You've broken it down yourself. That changes how it tastes.</p> <p>Why this matters beyond skills: A whole 2 lb branzino costs $12\u201314 at a good fishmonger. The same fish sold as fillets costs $18\u201322. You just learned where $6\u20138 of the price comes from \u2014 and you can have fresher fish for less money.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#block-21-the-fundamentals-of-fish-cookery","title":"Block 21 \u2014 The Fundamentals of Fish Cookery","text":"<p>The central principle this week: Fish cooks faster than you think, at lower temperatures than you're used to, and the margin between perfect and overdone is about 30 seconds. Salmon at 125\u00b0F (slightly translucent at the center) is perfect. At 145\u00b0F it becomes dry and flaky in the wrong way. Everything this week is about developing the instinct to pull fish early.</p> <p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 5 (PROJECT: Whole Roasted Fish): buy a whole fish the same day for maximum freshness</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#session-1-crispy-skin-pan-seared-salmon","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Crispy-Skin Pan-Seared Salmon","text":"<p>Skill: Perfectly crisped fish skin in a pan is one of the most technically satisfying results in everyday cooking. The two secrets are: dry the skin completely before cooking (paper towels, uncovered in fridge if possible), and resist the urge to move it. The skin needs sustained contact with the hot pan to release its moisture and crisp. If it sticks, it's not ready.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Crispy Pan-Seared Salmon Fillets \u2014 the technique section is essential reading</li> <li>Cold pan start is debated; we recommend room-temp pan, medium-high heat, oil just to shimmer</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Crispy skin salmon + herb oil or lemon butter + Serious Eats \u2014 Stir-Fried Garlic Spinach + steamed rice</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Grill Salmon (Helen Rennie) \u2014 Different heat source, same goal as your pan sear; notice how she reads doneness and what she says about the margin for error.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#session-2-sole-meuniere-the-french-lesson","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Sole Meuni\u00e8re: The French Lesson","text":"<p>Skill: Sole meuni\u00e8re is one of the first dishes classically taught to French culinary students. It's also one of the most instructive: dredge in flour, cook in butter, make the brown butter sauce in the same pan in 60 seconds, finish with lemon. Brown butter (beurre noisette) is a flavor you'll reach for constantly once you know it.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Sole Meuni\u00e8re</li> <li>The brown butter sauce: butter continues to cook in the hot pan after you remove the fish. Watch it turn amber. Smell it \u2014 it should smell nutty, like hazelnuts. Off the heat. Lemon juice. Pour immediately.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Sole meuni\u00e8re + steamed haricots verts or asparagus + crusty bread to catch the sauce</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Sole Meuni\u00e8re (Jacques P\u00e9pin) \u2014 Watch the brown butter timing and how little it takes to cross from noisette to burned. This is the master class version of what you're cooking tonight.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#session-3-the-universal-crispy-fish-technique","title":"Session 3 \u2014 The Universal Crispy Fish Technique","text":"<p>Skill: Serious Eats \u2014 The Easiest Crispy Pan-Seared Fish \u2014 works on almost any white fish fillet. Tonight: cod, halibut, sea bass, or snapper \u2014 whatever is freshest and least expensive at your market. This is the workhorse technique you'll use for the rest of your life.</p> <ul> <li>The key insight: a stainless steel or cast iron pan, properly preheated, with enough oil, prevents sticking better than nonstick does because it creates a proper sear</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Crispy white fish + whatever vegetable you feel like + rice or potatoes</p> <p>Skill note: If the fish sticks, it's telling you something. It means the pan wasn't hot enough or there isn't enough fat. This is useful information \u2014 not failure.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#session-4-ceviche-fish-cooked-by-acid","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Ceviche: Fish Cooked by Acid","text":"<p>Skill: Ceviche is the technique of \"cooking\" raw fish with citrus acid \u2014 the low pH of lime juice denatures the surface proteins of the fish, turning it opaque and firm without any heat. This is one of the most intellectually interesting preparations in the program: you are cooking without a stove.</p> <ul> <li>Read: BBC Good Food \u2014 Ceviche</li> <li>Use the freshest fish you can find \u2014 sushi-grade sea bass, snapper, or halibut; dice to 1cm cubes; cover completely with fresh lime juice; cure in the fridge for 20\u201330 minutes; season with salt, chili, red onion, and coriander</li> <li>Taste at 10 minutes and again at 30 \u2014 notice the texture change happening in real time</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Ceviche as a starter or light main + quick-pickled cucumbers + tostadas or tortilla chips + avocado slices</p> <p>Skill note: The line between perfectly cured (firm outside, just barely opaque inside) and overcooked (rubbery all the way through) is about 15 minutes. Pull it at the earlier end.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#session-5-project-whole-roasted-fish","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Whole Roasted Fish","text":"<p>Skill: A whole fish \u2014 scored, stuffed with aromatics, and roasted at high heat \u2014 is one of the most impressive and least technically demanding cooks in this program. The bones protect the fish from overcooking significantly more than fillets do. The crispy skin pulls away from the bone with a wonderful texture.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Salt-Baked Whole Fish with Fresh Herbs \u2014 a more dramatic version of the whole-fish concept; alternatively roast the fish simply with just olive oil, lemon, and herbs in a 425\u00b0F oven for 25\u201330 minutes per kilo</li> <li>Any whole fish works: snapper, branzino, sea bass, striped bass, or whatever is freshest</li> </ul> <p>The project meal: Whole roasted or salt-baked fish + olive oil, lemon, and capers dressed over the top + roasted potatoes or simple rice + salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Grill and Eat a Whole Fish (Branzino) (Helen Rennie) \u2014 Same fish, different heat source; pay attention to how she talks about the bones changing the cook time calculus compared to fillets.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#block-22-fish-deeper-techniques-global-preparations","title":"Block 22 \u2014 Fish: Deeper Techniques &amp; Global Preparations","text":""},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#session-6-seared-fish-mushroom-asian-style","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Seared Fish + Mushroom, Asian Style","text":"<p>Skill: Pan-searing fish over a bed of shiitake mushrooms and aromatics \u2014 a technique from Chinese and East Asian cooking where the mushrooms both flavor the fish and prevent it from sticking dramatically. The result is fish with deeply savory umami below it, almost stock-like in the pan.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Pan-Seared Fish with Shiitake Mushrooms</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Seared fish with mushrooms + rice + wilted greens</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#session-7-fish-tacos-west-coast-done-right","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Fish Tacos: West Coast Done Right","text":"<p>Skill: Baja fish tacos \u2014 battered, fried white fish, shredded cabbage, crema, and salsa. The batter is rice-flour-light; the oil temperature matters (350\u00b0F); the fish cooks in 90 seconds. Building a perfect taco is a lesson in acid, fat, heat, and crunch in one bite.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Baja Fish Tacos</li> <li>Set up a simple deep-fry station: Dutch oven, 3 inches of neutral oil, thermometer. Don't skip the thermometer.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Baja fish tacos + pickled jalape\u00f1os + guacamole or avocado crema + cold beer (optional)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#session-8-salmon-teriyaki-the-weeknight-standard","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Salmon Teriyaki: The Weeknight Standard","text":"<p>Skill: True teriyaki is a Japanese glaze (soy, mirin, sake, sugar) applied and cooked in the pan \u2014 not the thick bottled sauce you pour over cooked meat. The technique: sear the salmon, flip, add the teriyaki glaze to the pan, baste continuously as it reduces and lacquers the fish. This takes about 4 minutes total.</p> <ul> <li>Read and follow closely: Serious Eats \u2014 Easy Teriyaki Glazed Salmon</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Teriyaki salmon rice bowl + cucumber + avocado + sesame seeds + pickled ginger</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#session-9-whole-grilled-branzino","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Whole Grilled Branzino","text":"<p>Skill: Small whole fish on the grill \u2014 scored, rubbed with olive oil, placed over direct heat, flipped once. The bones protect the flesh from drying, the skin chars beautifully, and the result is cleaner-tasting than almost any fillet preparation. Two minutes per side is usually enough for a 500g fish.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Whole Grilled Fish</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Whole grilled branzino (or snapper) + salsa verde or gremolata + roasted potatoes + salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Go Fish (Jacques P\u00e9pin) \u2014 Watch how he reads the cooked fish and separates the fillet from the bone at the table; that's the finishing move that makes whole fish feel confident rather than awkward.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#session-10-project-a-full-fish-dinner","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: A Full Fish Dinner","text":"<p>The challenge: Build a complete three-component fish dinner using techniques from the block. Nothing from a packet. Everything cooked the same evening.</p> <p>Full Meal (serves 2\u20134):</p> <ol> <li>Starter: Ceviche (from Session 4 technique) \u2014 fresh-made, served immediately after curing, with tostadas and sliced avocado</li> <li>Main: Crispy-skin pan-seared fish of your choice (Session 1 or 3 technique) + salsa verde drizzled over the top</li> <li>Sides: Roasted potatoes + a simple green salad dressed with vinaigrette</li> </ol> <p>Skill targets: Ceviche fish properly opaque but not rubbery. Crispy fish skin that doesn't stick to the plate. Everything on the table at the same time \u2014 this is the timing challenge.</p> <p>Write: What single technique from this block will you use the most in everyday cooking? Not the most impressive \u2014 the most useful.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#buying-fish","title":"Buying Fish","text":"<p>The most important fish skill happens before you cook. Knowing what fresh fish looks and smells like \u2014 and what to ask a fishmonger \u2014 matters more than technique.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Fillet a Whole Fish \u2014 The knife skill most home cooks never develop. Understanding the angle, pressure, and feel for running a blade along the spine changes how you approach any finned fish \u2014 whether you buy it whole or not.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#the-bouillabaisse-deep-dive","title":"The Bouillabaisse Deep Dive","text":"<p>Bouillabaisse is a lesson in building shellfish stock, saffron, and rouille \u2014 three techniques that extend into a dozen other recipes.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Real Bouillabaisse (Bouillabaisse Marseillaise) \u2014 The full recipe and process: building the saffron-shellfish broth, making the rouille, and understanding why the dish is served in two stages. The technique is transferable to any rich shellfish stew.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Jacques P\u00e9pin fillets a fish \u2014 Watch the knife angle and the way he reads the bones. This is the hand skill that separates cooks who buy fillets from cooks who buy whole fish.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Sole meuni\u00e8re in real time \u2014 Brown butter moves fast. Watching the color progression before attempting it is worth doing.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Whole Fish Cookbook by Josh Niland \u2014 Argues for cooking the entire fish, reduces waste, and teaches you to see fish the way butchers see meat. Transformative for serious fish cooks.</li> </ul> <p>\u2190 Block 19\u201320: Beef Fundamentals | Block 23\u201324: Whole Fish &amp; Curing \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Block 19\u201320 Quick Reference \u2014 Seafood: Fish","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/quick-ref.html#block-21-recipes-fish-fundamentals","title":"Block 21 Recipes \u2014 Fish Fundamentals","text":"Session Dish Skill Link Session 1 Crispy-Skin Pan-Seared Salmon + Garlic Spinach + Rice Dry skin; resist moving; read the stick Crispy Salmon \u00b7 Garlic Spinach Session 2 Sole Meuni\u00e8re + Haricots Verts + Crusty Bread Brown butter sauce; speed; classical French Sole Meuni\u00e8re Session 3 Crispy Pan-Seared White Fish (your choice) + Veg + Rice Universal technique; high-heat; stainless principle Easiest Crispy Fish Session 4 \u23f0 Miso-Glazed Salmon + Rice + Quick-Pickled Cucumbers + Bok Choy Miso cure; broiler caramelization (glaze Thu night) Miso-Glazed Salmon Session 5 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Salt-Baked or Whole Roasted Fish + Roast Potatoes + Salad Whole fish; bone protection; salt crust drama Salt-Baked Whole Fish"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/quick-ref.html#block-22-recipes-fish-deeper-techniques","title":"Block 22 Recipes \u2014 Fish: Deeper Techniques","text":"Session Dish Skill Link Session 6 Seared Fish + Shiitake Mushrooms + Rice + Greens Asian layering; mushroom umami base Pan-Seared Fish + Mushrooms Session 7 Baja Fish Tacos + Picked Jalape\u00f1os + Guacamole Light batter; 350\u00b0F fry; taco acid-fat-crunch Baja Fish Tacos Session 8 Teriyaki Salmon Rice Bowl + Cucumber + Avocado In-pan glaze; real teriyaki technique Teriyaki Salmon Bowl Session 9 Whole Grilled Branzino + Salsa Verde + Roast Potatoes + Salad Whole fish on grill; score and flip once Whole Grilled Fish Session 10 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Bouillabaisse + Rouille Croutons + Crusty Bread Grand fish stew; bone broth + sequenced fish Bouillabaisse"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/quick-ref.html#fish-doneness-quick-reference","title":"Fish Doneness Quick Reference","text":"Fish Pull from Heat at Texture at Target Salmon 120\u2013125\u00b0F Slightly translucent at center; moist and silky White fish (cod, halibut) 130\u00b0F Just opaque throughout; flakes when pressed Sole/flounder 125\u00b0F Cooks very fast \u2014 2\u20133 min each side Whole fish Flesh pulls cleanly from bone Usually 25\u201330 min per kg at 220\u00b0C / 425\u00b0F Tuna (seared) 90\u2013100\u00b0F Raw-cold center; seared crust \u2014 60 sec per side"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/quick-ref.html#shopping-notes","title":"Shopping Notes","text":"<p>Block 21 \u2014 Buy fresh day-of or at most 1 day ahead: - Salmon fillets, skin-on \u2014 2 pieces (Sessions 1 &amp; 4) - Dover sole or flounder \u2014 2\u20134 fillets (Session 2) - Any fresh white fish fillet \u2014 cod, halibut, sea bass (Session 3; buy what's freshest/cheapest) - 1 whole fish \u2014 snapper, branzino, or sea bass; 1\u20131.5 kg (project session) - Coarse sea salt \u2014 3 lbs (if salt-baking)</p> <p>Block 22 \u2014 Again, freshness is the priority: - Firm white fish \u2014 cod or halibut (Session 1)  - White fish for frying \u2014 cod, mahi-mahi, or tilapia (Session 2 tacos) - Salmon fillets \u2014 2 pieces (Session 3 teriyaki) - Branzino or snapper, whole \u2014 2 small fish (Session 4 grill) - Assorted fish + shellfish for bouillabaisse \u2014 2\u20133 types of firm white fish, plus clams or mussels; ask your fishmonger to save fish bones for the broth</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 19\u201320: Seafood Fish","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>The golden rule of fish shopping: Buy it day-of or the day before. Not earlier. Fish quality degrades faster than any other protein. If your usual grocery store doesn't have great seafood, find a fishmonger. Tell them you're cooking fish five nights a week for two weeks \u2014 they will help you figure out timing.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dutch oven \u2014 for Tuesday's fish tacos (frying)</li> <li>[ ] Thermometer \u2014 essential; also useful for checking oil temp for frying (350\u00b0F target)</li> <li>[ ] Fish spatula \u2014 wide, thin, flexible; the tool that makes flipping fish easy</li> <li>[ ] Wire rack + sheet pan \u2014 for draining fried fish tacos (Week 22 Tue)</li> <li>[ ] Coarse sea salt \u2014 3\u20134 lbs if doing the salt-bake version of Saturday's whole fish</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-21-buy-as-close-to-cook-day-as-possible","title":"\ud83d\udc1f Proteins \u2014 Week 21 (buy as close to cook day as possible)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Salmon fillets, skin-on \u2014 2 thick pieces (Mon); 2 more pieces (Fri miso glaze)</li> <li>[ ] Dover sole or flounder fillets \u2014 2\u20134 (Tue meuni\u00e8re)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh white fish fillet \u2014 cod, halibut, or sea bass; 2 pieces (Wed technique practice)</li> <li>[ ] Whole fish \u2014 1\u20132 branzino, snapper, or sea bass, 500g\u20131kg each (Sat; buy an extra for Session 0 filleting practice if doing it)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-22-buy-as-close-to-cook-day-as-possible","title":"\ud83d\udc1f Proteins \u2014 Week 22 (buy as close to cook day as possible)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Firm white fish \u2014 cod or halibut, 2 pieces (Mon mushroom cook)</li> <li>[ ] White fish for frying \u2014 cod, mahi-mahi, or tilapia; 1 lb (Tue tacos)</li> <li>[ ] Salmon fillets \u2014 2 pieces (Wed teriyaki)</li> <li>[ ] Branzino or snapper, whole \u2014 2 small (Fri grill)</li> <li>[ ] Bouillabaisse assortment \u2014 2\u20133 types: e.g., cod (1 lb), monkfish (1 lb) + 1 lb clams or mussels (Sat); ask fishmonger to save bones/heads for the broth</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/shopping-list.html#produce-week-21","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 21","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Baby spinach \u2014 2 bags (Mon + other sides)</li> <li>[ ] Haricots verts or green beans \u2014 1 lb (Tue)</li> <li>[ ] Bok choy \u2014 2 heads (Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumbers \u2014 3 (quick pickled; Fri and Week 22)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Fresh dill \u2014 1 bunch (whole fish garnish)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Fresh thyme \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Yukon gold potatoes \u2014 1.5 lbs (Saturday)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed greens \u2014 1 bag</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/shopping-list.html#produce-week-22","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 22","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Shiitake mushrooms \u2014 8 oz (Mon fish + mushroom)</li> <li>[ ] Avocados \u2014 3 (Tue tacos + Wed bowl)</li> <li>[ ] Cabbage \u2014 \u00bd head, shredded (Tue fish tacos slaw)</li> <li>[ ] Jalape\u00f1os \u2014 4 (quick pickled for tacos)</li> <li>[ ] Limes \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Green onions \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Cucumber \u2014 2 (Wed teriyaki bowl)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh herbs for bouillabaisse \u2014 parsley, fennel fronds, thyme, bay (Sat)</li> <li>[ ] Fennel bulb \u2014 2 (bouillabaisse aromatics)</li> <li>[ ] Tomatoes \u2014 4 (bouillabaisse)</li> <li>[ ] Leeks \u2014 2 (bouillabaisse)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/21-22-fish/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] White miso paste \u2014 small tub (Week 21 Fri glaze)</li> <li>[ ] Mirin and sake \u2014 small bottles (Week 21 Fri glaze + Week 22 Wed teriyaki)</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce</li> <li>[ ] Rice flour \u2014 for fish taco batter (Week 22 Tue; all-purpose also works)</li> <li>[ ] Neutral oil \u2014 1 quart (frying Week 22 Tue)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 1 lb (meuni\u00e8re + pan sauces)</li> <li>[ ] Sesame oil (Week 22 Wed bowl)</li> <li>[ ] Sesame seeds</li> <li>[ ] Saffron \u2014 small pinch (bouillabaisse rouille; expensive but worth it)</li> <li>[ ] Fennel seeds \u2014 1 tsp (bouillabaisse)</li> <li>[ ] Baguette \u2014 for rouille croutons (Sat bouillabaisse)</li> <li>[ ] Corn tortillas \u2014 2 packs (Tue fish tacos)</li> <li>[ ] Rice \u2014 jasmine and/or white (multiple days)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 6 (Week 22 Sat bouillabaisse rouille egg yolks; Week 22 Tue fish taco batter)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html","title":"\ud83d\udc1f Block 23\u201324: Whole Fish, Curing &amp; Advanced Seafood","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 19\u201320: Flatfish &amp; Round Fish | Block 23\u201324: Fish \u2014 Advanced \u2192</p> <p>\"Curing a fish is the most intimate act of preservation \u2014 you are changing its character with nothing but salt, time, and intention. The result tastes like the sea remembered.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#before-you-start-block-23","title":"Before You Start Block 23","text":"<p>What this block adds: Block 19\u201320 built your core fish-cooking technique \u2014 pan-searing, meuni\u00e8re, miso glaze, whole fish in the oven. Block 21\u201322 goes further: salt curing, trout Amandine (a different whole-fish technique), grilled whole fish, mussels, crab cakes, and cioppino. By the end you will have a complete seafood vocabulary.</p> <p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 1 (Gravlax): start the cure 48\u201372 hrs before Session 3 \u2014 it comes out of the fridge tasting transformed</li> <li>Session 8 (Cioppino): ask your fishmonger 2 days ahead to save fish bones/shells for the stock</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#session-0-breaking-down-a-whole-fish-optional-do-this-if-you-didnt-in-block-19","title":"Session 0 \u2014 Breaking Down a Whole Fish (optional \u2014 do this if you didn't in Block 19)","text":"<p>Skill: Filleting a whole round fish \u2014 the most useful fish skill in the kitchen.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 How to Fillet a Whole Fish</p> <p>Buy one whole branzino or snapper. Fillet both sides, remove pin bones, and cook the fillets simply (pan-sear with butter and lemon). Eat the result knowing you got more fish for less money and it was fresher.</p> <p>The economics: A whole 2 lb branzino costs $12\u201314 at a good fishmonger. The same fish sold as fillets: $18\u201322. You just learned where $6\u20138 of the price comes from.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#block-23-whole-fish-curing","title":"Block 23 \u2014 Whole Fish &amp; Curing","text":"<p>The central principle: Whole fish and cured fish are the two preparations that demand attention to the fish itself \u2014 its freshness, its age, its smell \u2014 in a way that a fillet from a vacuum pack never will. This week teaches you to read fish.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#session-1-gravlax-salt-sugar-and-time","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Gravlax: Salt, Sugar, and Time","text":"<p>Skill: Dry curing fish (no heat, no smoke) \u2014 the Scandinavian technique for transforming fresh salmon with nothing but salt, sugar, and dill.</p> <p>The cure penetrates the flesh over 48\u201372 hours, drawing out moisture, firming the texture, and intensifying flavor. The result tastes like the best smoked salmon you've ever had \u2014 except it's not smoked at all. Salt did everything.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: BBC Good Food \u2014 Gravadlax \u2014 the classic recipe and ratio (2:1 salt:sugar by weight, heaped with dill, weighted in the fridge)</p> <p>The technique: - Score the skin side of a 500g\u20131kg salmon fillet lightly - Mix coarse salt and sugar (2:1 ratio salt:sugar by weight) - Press the cure onto both sides, cover with plenty of fresh dill - Place in a dish skin-side down, weigh with another dish and some cans, refrigerate - Flip every 12 hours; cure 48\u201372 hours - Remove, scrape off the dill and cure (don't rinse), and slice thinly on the bias</p> <p>Note: Start the cure tonight (Session 1). It will be ready to slice by Session 3 or 4.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Begin gravlax cure \u2014 no dinner from this tonight - Quick pan-seared salmon for Session 1 dinner (compare texture now against cured version in two days)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#session-2-trout-amandine-whole-fish-brown-butter","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Trout Amandine: Whole Fish + Brown Butter","text":"<p>Skill: Cooking a whole fish in butter \u2014 dredged in flour, pan-fried until golden, finished with a classic brown butter and toasted almond sauce. One of the most elegant French preparations, and fast.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Trout Amandine</p> <p>Trout Amandine teaches you to read a whole fish for doneness (the flesh should pull away from the bone at the dorsal fin; the eye turns white and opaque). The sauce \u2014 beurre noisette with toasted almonds and lemon juice \u2014 is made in the same pan in 90 seconds after the fish comes out.</p> <p>Full Meal: Trout Amandine + steamed haricots verts + crusty bread to catch the sauce</p> Component Notes Fish Whole rainbow trout, butterflied or pan-ready Sauce Beurre noisette + toasted sliced almonds + lemon juice + parsley Veg Haricots verts, blanched or simply steamed <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Sole Meuni\u00e8re (Jacques P\u00e9pin) \u2014 Different fish, identical technique \u2014 watch the brown butter timing and how little time separates noisette from burned.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#session-3-taste-the-gravlax-cured-fish-board","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Taste the Gravlax / Cured Fish Board","text":"<p>Skill: Slicing cured fish, assembling a Scandinavian board, tasting your own cure.</p> <p>Today you slice your gravlax (if it went in at Session 1) and taste it alongside store-bought smoked salmon \u2014 the comparison teaches you what curing does.</p> <p>Slicing: thin, long bias cuts with a very sharp flexible knife, starting from the tail end. Lay slices flat.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Cured salmon board: your gravlax + cream cheese or cr\u00e8me fra\u00eeche + capers + diced red onion + rye bread or blinis - Mustard-dill sauce alongside (Dijon + honey + white wine vinegar + neutral oil + fresh dill)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#session-4-whole-grilled-branzino","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Whole Grilled Branzino","text":"<p>Skill: Small whole fish on the grill \u2014 scored, rubbed with olive oil, placed over direct high heat, flipped once. The bones protect the flesh from drying, the skin chars beautifully, and the result is cleaner-tasting than almost any fillet preparation.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Whole Grilled Fish</p> <p>Score the fish 3\u20134 times on each side (diagonal cuts to the bone \u2014 these allow heat to reach the thickest parts). Rub with oil, stuff the cavity with lemon slices, garlic, and herbs. Grill 4\u20135 minutes per side for a 500g fish over direct high heat.</p> <p>Full Meal: Whole grilled branzino + Italian salsa verde + roasted potatoes + green salad</p> Component Notes Fish Whole branzino or snapper, 500g each Sauce Salsa verde made ahead: parsley, capers, anchovy, olive oil, lemon Starch Smashed and oven-crisped potatoes <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Grill and Eat a Whole Fish (Helen Rennie) \u2014 Pay attention to how she separates the fillet from the bone at the table \u2014 that finishing move makes whole fish feel confident.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#session-5-project-whole-fish-dinner-party","title":"\u23f0 Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Whole Fish Dinner Party","text":"<p>The challenge: A complete dinner centered on whole fish \u2014 plated with intention. Cook for at least two people.</p> <p>Full Meal (3 courses):</p> <ol> <li>Starter: Gravlax board (leftover from Session 3, or freshly sliced) with blinis, cr\u00e8me fra\u00eeche, capers, and pickled onion</li> <li>Main: Salt-Baked Whole Fish \u2014 the enclosed salt crust steams the fish in its own moisture; crack at the table. Dress the revealed fish with olive oil and capers.</li> <li>Side: Roasted potatoes + gremolata or salsa verde alongside</li> </ol> <p>Skill targets: A properly sealed salt crust (no cracks before roasting). Fish pulled at 130\u2013135\u00b0F at the thickest point. Confident tableside crack-and-reveal. Graceful plating directly from the fish to the plate.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#block-24-advanced-seafood-shellfish-stews","title":"Block 24 \u2014 Advanced Seafood: Shellfish &amp; Stews","text":"<p>\"Shellfish are the most immediate form of the sea \u2014 they still smell like the ocean when they're alive, and they cook in minutes. Knowing how to handle them is knowing how to be present.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#session-6-mussels-mariniere-the-french-classic","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Mussels Marini\u00e8re: The French Classic","text":"<p>Skill: Cooking shellfish in wine steam \u2014 the fastest impressive dish in this program. Two pounds of mussels, cleaned and debearded, cooked in white wine and aromatics for 6 minutes. The key: don't drown them in too much liquid. A thin layer of wine and aromatics in the bottom of the pot creates enough steam to open every shell.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: BBC Good Food \u2014 Moules Marini\u00e8re</p> <p>Cleaning mussels: Pull off any beards right before cooking. Discard mussels that don't close when tapped sharply. Discard any that don't open after cooking.</p> <p>Full Meal: Mussels marini\u00e8re + crusty bread (the entire purpose of which is to soak up the cooking liquid \u2014 make extra) + simple green salad</p> Component Notes Mussels 2 lbs per person; scrubbed, debearded right before cooking Broth 1 cup dry white wine + 2 shallots + 3 garlic cloves + parsley stems Bread Sourdough or baguette \u2014 non-optional"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#session-7-crab-cakes-restraint-is-the-technique","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Crab Cakes: Restraint Is the Technique","text":"<p>Skill: The test of a good crab cake is the ratio of crab to filler. Most crab cakes are bread cakes. A proper crab cake is barely held together \u2014 the crab is the thing, the binder is just enough to keep it cohesive.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Simply Recipes \u2014 Crab Cakes</p> <p>Full Meal: Crab cakes + aioli or remoulade + coleslaw or quick-pickled red onion + simple green salad</p> Component Notes Crab cakes 85\u201390% crab; minimal binder (egg, mayo, small amount of panko) Sauce Aioli (Block 5\u20136 technique) or a simple remoulade Side Coleslaw or herb salad \u2014 cool, acidic, a crisp counterpoint <p>Buying crabmeat: Fresh or pasteurized lump crabmeat is the practical choice. Pick through carefully for shell fragments before mixing.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#session-8-cioppino-the-italian-american-fish-stew","title":"\u23f0 Session 8 \u2014 Cioppino: The Italian-American Fish Stew","text":"<p>Skill: Building a great fish stew from a tomato-shellfish broth \u2014 the technique that integrates shellfish and fish at different add times based on their individual cook times.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Simply Recipes \u2014 Cioppino</p> <p>Cioppino was invented by Italian immigrant fishermen in San Francisco \u2014 a tomato-and-wine stew into which firm fish goes first (10\u201312 minutes), then shellfish in order of cook time (clams and mussels first, shrimp last). The broth is the soul: deeply seasoned with fish bones and shellfish shells if you can get them.</p> <p>Plan ahead: Ask your fishmonger 2 days ahead to save fish frames/bones \u2014 they're usually free. Simmer them in water with aromatics for 20 minutes = a quick fumet that transforms the broth.</p> <p>Full Meal: Cioppino with fish, clams, mussels, and shrimp + crusty sourdough bread + simple salad</p> Component Notes Broth Tomato + white wine + fish stock/fumet + saffron (optional) Fish (first in) Firm white fish \u2014 cod, halibut (10\u201312 min) Shellfish (last) Clams, mussels (6\u20138 min), shrimp (2\u20133 min) Bread Thick slices of sourdough, toasted <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Bouillabaisse and How to Make Fish Stock (Helen Rennie) \u2014 The technique for building shellfish stock is identical; watch how she extracts maximum flavor from bones and shells before anything else goes into the pot.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#session-9-miso-glazed-black-cod-or-salmon","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Miso-Glazed Black Cod (or Salmon)","text":"<p>Skill: The Nobu preparation \u2014 white miso, mirin, sake, and sugar applied to black cod or salmon and left to cure overnight. The sugars in the miso caramelize under the broiler in 4 minutes.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Miso-Glazed Salmon</p> <p>Black cod (sablefish) is the traditional fish for this preparation \u2014 its high fat content handles the sweet glaze without drying out. Salmon is the more accessible substitute. Start the cure tonight or apply it two nights ahead.</p> <p>Timing: Apply glaze \u2192 refrigerate 24\u201348 hrs \u2192 broil 4\u20135 minutes on one side only \u2192 done.</p> <p>Full Meal: Miso-glazed cod or salmon + steamed rice + wilted bok choy or spinach + quick-pickled cucumbers</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#session-10-project-seafood-feast","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Seafood Feast","text":"<p>The challenge: A generous seafood dinner that pulls together everything from this block. This is the dinner you serve to impress \u2014 or eat alone on a Friday when you feel like celebrating.</p> <p>Full Meal:</p> <ol> <li>Starter: Mussels marini\u00e8re (Session 6 technique) \u2014 a small portion to start, with bread</li> <li>Main: Cioppino (Session 8 \u2014 a larger pot made the same evening, or made a day ahead and reheated, which makes it richer)</li> <li>Side: Roasted potatoes or polenta alongside the cioppino</li> <li>Dessert: Whatever you feel like \u2014 this meal doesn't need more complexity</li> </ol> <p>Skill targets: Clean mussel broth (not watery or muddy). Cioppino with distinct, properly-cooked fish and shellfish \u2014 nothing rubbery, nothing falling apart. The whole table smells like the sea.</p> <p>Write: What was the single biggest thing you learned about seafood across Blocks 19\u201320 and 21\u201322? Write one paragraph. Then identify the one technique you'd come back to in the next month.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":""},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#whole-fish-why-the-bones-matter","title":"Whole Fish: Why the Bones Matter","text":"<p>A bone-in whole fish cooks more slowly and more evenly than a fillet \u2014 the bones conduct heat and protect the flesh from the outside temperature. Once you understand this, you reach for whole fish differently.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Fillet a Whole Fish \u2014 The knife skill that makes buying whole fish practical.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#curing-beyond-gravlax","title":"Curing: Beyond Gravlax","text":"<p>Gravlax is the entry point. The same principle (salt draws moisture, concentrates flavor, transforms texture) applies throughout Block 27\u201328 (Charcuterie). Once you understand salt curing, you start to see it everywhere.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 BBC Good Food \u2014 Gravadlax \u2014 The full recipe, including the mustard-dill sauce that's traditional with it.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#cioppino-vs-bouillabaisse","title":"Cioppino vs. Bouillabaisse","text":"<p>Cioppino and bouillabaisse use almost identical technique but diverge in flavor profile: cioppino is tomato-forward (Italian-American), while bouillabaisse relies on saffron, fennel, and a Proven\u00e7al rouille. Both teach building a shellfish broth. Once you've made one, the other follows logically.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 Bouillabaisse Marseillaise \u2014 If cioppino has you curious about the French version.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Whole Fish Cookbook by Josh Niland \u2014 Argues for cooking the entire fish \u2014 the cheeks, the collar, the roe. Transforms how you see value and waste at the fish counter.</li> </ul> <p>\u2190 Block 19\u201320: Flatfish &amp; Round Fish | Block 23\u201324: Fish \u2014 Advanced \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Block 21\u201322 Quick Reference \u2014 Whole Fish, Curing &amp; Advanced Seafood","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/quick-ref.html#block-21-recipes-whole-fish-curing","title":"Block 21 Recipes \u2014 Whole Fish &amp; Curing","text":"Session Dish Skill Links Session 0 (opt) Fillet a Whole Round Fish Backbone-following knife technique; minimal waste How to Fillet \u2014 SE Session 1 \u23f0 Gravlax (Cured Salmon) Dry cure salt + sugar + dill; 36\u201348 hr cure; no heat Gravadlax \u2014 BBC GF Session 2 Trout Amandine + Haricots Verts + Bread Whole fish in butter; brown butter sauce; toasted almonds Trout Amandine \u2014 SE Session 3 Gravlax Tasting / Cured Fish Board Slicing cured fish; board assembly; reading the cure Taste your Session 1 gravlax Session 4 Whole Grilled Branzino + Salsa Verde + Roast Potatoes Score the skin; grill direct high heat; flip once Grilled Fish \u2014 SE \u00b7 Salsa Verde Session 5 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Whole Fish Dinner \u2014 3 Courses Ceviche starter + whole fish main + salsa verde Ceviche \u2014 BBC GF"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/quick-ref.html#block-22-recipes-advanced-shellfish-cioppino","title":"Block 22 Recipes \u2014 Advanced Shellfish &amp; Cioppino","text":"Session Dish Skill Links Session 6 Mussels Marini\u00e8re + Crusty Bread Steam in wine; debeard; discard unopened shells Moules Marini\u00e8re \u2014 BBC GF Session 7 Crab Cakes + Aioli + Pickled Onion Minimal binder; crab-to-filler ratio matters; pan sear not deep fry Crab Cakes \u2014 Simply Recipes Session 8 \u23f0 Cioppino + Sourdough Layered seafood stew; different add times per protein Cioppino \u2014 Simply Recipes Session 9 \u23f0 Miso-Glazed Black Cod or Salmon + Rice + Bok Choy Overnight miso marinade; broiler caramelisation 4 min Miso Salmon \u2014 SE Session 10 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Seafood Feast Crab cake starter + fish or mussel main + cured salmon Combine the block's techniques"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/quick-ref.html#freshness-indicators-quick-reference","title":"Freshness Indicators \u2014 Quick Reference","text":"Fish/Shellfish Fresh Not Fresh Whole round fish Eyes bright and clear, gills red, flesh springs back Cloudy eyes, grey gills, ammonia smell Fillets Translucent, shiny, no gaps in flesh Opaque, dull, mushy, strong fishy odour Mussels Shells closed or close when tapped; smell briny Open shells that don't close = discard"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/quick-ref.html#curing-reference-gravlax","title":"Curing Reference \u2014 Gravlax","text":"Element Ratio Notes Salt 3 parts Kosher or sea salt; not iodised (turns flesh grey) Sugar 2 parts White or brown Dill Generous handful Fresh only Optional White pepper, lemon zest, aquavit 1 tbsp Aromatics only; not required Cure time 36\u201348 hours Taste at 36 hrs; refrigerate after curing <p>Navigation: \u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 21\u201322: Whole Fish, Curing &amp; Advanced Seafood","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Block 21 starts with a cure \u2014 buy your salmon first so it has 36\u201348 hours before you need it at Session 3. Whole fish for Session 2 (trout) and Session 4 (branzino) should be bought the day before or day-of at most. Block 22's mussels must be bought and cooked the same day. Buy mixed seafood for cioppino with a plan to cook within 24 hours.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Fish spatula \u2014 thin, flexible; essential for turning whole fish without breaking skin</li> <li>[ ] Large cast iron skillet or grill pan \u2014 trout amandine and branzino</li> <li>[ ] Large Dutch oven or heavy pot \u2014 cioppino and mussels marini\u00e8re</li> <li>[ ] Sheet pan + wire rack \u2014 elevated whole-fish roasting (if not grilling)</li> <li>[ ] Instant-read thermometer \u2014 fish is done at 130\u2013140\u00b0F (or flakes at the bone)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/shopping-list.html#fish-seafood-block-21","title":"\ud83d\udc1f Fish &amp; Seafood \u2014 Block 21","text":"<p>Buy salmon Thursday for the cure; all other fish as close to cook day as possible.</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Skin-on salmon fillet \u2014 1.5\u20132 lbs, centre-cut preferred (Session 1 gravlax). Buy Thursday. Cure immediately.</li> <li>[ ] Whole rainbow trout \u2014 2 fish (1 per person), cleaned and gutted (Session 2 trout amandine). Day before or day-of.</li> <li>[ ] Whole branzino (European sea bass) \u2014 2 fish, scaled and cleaned (Session 4 grilled branzino). Day-of only.</li> <li>[ ] Fresh white fish fillets \u2014 \u00bd lb halibut, snapper or sea bass (Session 5 ceviche starter). Day-of purchase only.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/shopping-list.html#seafood-block-22","title":"\ud83e\udd80 Seafood \u2014 Block 22","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Live mussels \u2014 2 lbs (Session 6 mussels marini\u00e8re). Buy day-of; store in fridge in colander, never sealed.</li> <li>[ ] Jumbo lump crab meat \u2014 8 oz can or fresh (Session 7 crab cakes). Fresh Dungeness or blue crab preferred.</li> <li>[ ] Mixed seafood for cioppino (Session 8):</li> <li>Littleneck clams \u2014 12\u201316, scrubbed</li> <li>Mussels \u2014 \u00bd lb</li> <li>Large shrimp \u2014 \u00bd lb, shell-on</li> <li>Firm white fish \u2014 \u00bd lb (halibut, cod or snapper)</li> <li>[ ] Black cod (sablefish) or salmon \u2014 2 fillets, 6 oz each (Session 9 miso glaze). Black cod is canonical; salmon is the accessible backup.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/shopping-list.html#aromatics-produce","title":"\ud83e\uddc5 Aromatics &amp; Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Fresh dill \u2014 large bunch (gravlax cure)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 1 head</li> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 4 (mussels, crab cake sauce, cioppino)</li> <li>[ ] Fennel \u2014 1 bulb (cioppino)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 4 (trout amandine, salsa verde, ceviche)</li> <li>[ ] Limes \u2014 4 (ceviche acid)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 2 bunches (salsa verde, cioppino garnish)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh cilantro \u2014 ceviche</li> <li>[ ] Capers \u2014 salsa verde, crab cake sauce</li> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 1 pint (cioppino)</li> <li>[ ] Canned crushed tomatoes \u2014 28 oz (cioppino base)</li> <li>[ ] Haricots verts or thin green beans \u2014 trout amandine side</li> <li>[ ] Bok choy or spinach \u2014 miso cod side</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/shopping-list.html#pantry-dry","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Pantry &amp; Dry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] White miso paste \u2014 small tub (Session 9; lasts months after)</li> <li>[ ] Mirin \u2014 small bottle (miso marinade)</li> <li>[ ] Sake or dry sherry \u2014 miso marinade</li> <li>[ ] Sliced almonds \u2014 small bag (trout amandine)</li> <li>[ ] All-purpose flour \u2014 dredging trout</li> <li>[ ] Panko breadcrumbs \u2014 crab cake binder</li> <li>[ ] Good olive oil</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 2 sticks (trout amandine, mussels finish)</li> <li>[ ] Kosher salt and whole white peppercorns \u2014 cure and general use</li> <li>[ ] Sugar \u2014 cure</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/shopping-list.html#wine-liquids","title":"\ud83c\udf77 Wine &amp; Liquids","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dry white wine \u2014 1 bottle (mussels marini\u00e8re and cioppino broth)</li> <li>[ ] Clam juice \u2014 two 8-oz bottles (cioppino base depth)</li> <li>[ ] Extra fish stock or clam juice \u2014 cioppino</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/23-24-fish/shopping-list.html#bread","title":"\ud83e\udd56 Bread","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Crusty sourdough or baguette \u2014 mussels and cioppino service; not optional</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html","title":"\ud83e\udd9e Block 25\u201326: Shellfish","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 23\u201324: Whole Fish &amp; Curing | Block 27\u201328: Pork \u2192</p> <p>\u2697\ufe0f Experimental \u2014 This block has not yet been cooked through by the author. Content is draft; recipes and timing are untested.</p> <p>\"Shellfish are the ocean's most generous gift \u2014 clams that open in minutes, scallops that take eight minutes total, shrimp that go from raw to overcooked in the span of a distracted text message. Shellfish teach the hardest lesson: restraint.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#block-25-bivalves-crustaceans-the-pure-flavor-approach","title":"Block 25 \u2014 Bivalves &amp; Crustaceans: The Pure Flavor Approach","text":"<p>You've cooked through poultry, beef, pork, and finfish. Now comes shellfish week \u2014 the category where the main job is not screwing it up. Clams and mussels are seasoning themselves with their own liquor. Scallops want nothing more than a hot pan and a hard sear. Your restraint and heat management are the only variables that matter.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#session-1-spaghetti-alle-vongole-clams-white-wine","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Spaghetti alle Vongole (Clams + White Wine)","text":"<p>Skill: Clam selection, purging sand, building a brothy pasta sauce from shellfish liquor  Read first: Spaghetti alle Vongole</p> <p>What you're learning: How to coax a restaurant-quality pasta sauce from two dozen little clams, a splash of wine, olive oil, and garlic \u2014 and why the pasta goes into the pan before it's fully cooked.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Spaghetti alle Vongole - Crusty bread for the broth at the bottom of the bowl</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Pasta alle Vongole \u2014 Watch when he adds the pasta to the clam pan \u2014 the starchy pasta water is the sauce, not an afterthought.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#session-2-moules-mariniere-mussels-french-style","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Moules Marini\u00e8re (Mussels, French Style)","text":"<p>Skill: Sourcing and cleaning mussels; building \"broth in a pot\" cooking technique  Read first: The Best Moules Marini\u00e8re</p> <p>What you're learning: Mussels give up their liquid as they open \u2014 that liquid is your sauce. The hard part is building aromatics beforehand and not overcooking once the mussels hit the heat. Open mussels = done.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Moules Marini\u00e8re - Frites (or good store-bought fries; this is mussels-and-fries night)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#session-3-roasted-oysters-with-bacon-and-parmesan","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Roasted Oysters with Bacon and Parmesan","text":"<p>Skill: Buying and handling live oysters; dry heat cooking for bivalves  Read first: Roasted Oysters with Bacon and Parmesan</p> <p>What you're learning: Raw oysters are a skill-and-taste vertical unto themselves. But roasted oysters are accessible, warm, and show you how heat changes shellfish character. No shucking experience required for this preparation \u2014 heat opens them.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Roasted Oysters (appetizer quantity \u2014 6\u201312) - Caesar salad or simple green salad for a full dinner</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Grill Oysters \u2014 The heat-opening approach is the same whether grilling or roasting \u2014 compare when he calls them done and why the timing matters for bivalves.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#session-4-shrimp-scampi","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Shrimp Scampi","text":"<p>Skill: Quick-cooking crustaceans, building a pan sauce in under 5 minutes  Read first: Shrimp Scampi</p> <p>What you're learning: Shrimp cook in 2 minutes total and keep cooking off the heat. The window between raw and rubbery is narrow. Scampi is a study in speed: garlic in oil, shrimp in, flip, wine in, butter swirled, done.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Shrimp Scampi over linguine - Simple green salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Gambas al Ajillo (Spanish Garlic Shrimp) (Helen Rennie) \u2014 Spanish garlic shrimp vs. Italian scampi: same speed, same garlic-and-fat logic, completely different flavor. Watch the oil temperature and how briefly the shrimp touch the heat.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#session-5-project-lobster-night","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Lobster Night","text":"<p>Skill: Cooking whole live lobster humanely and confidently; making a pan sauce or bisque from shells  Read first: Stop Overcooking Lobster | Lobster Bisque</p> <p>Plan: Buy 2 lobsters (1.25\u20131.5 lb each). Cook one for immediate eating (broiled, steamed, or grilled). Save shells + any unused parts for a quick bisque or at minimum a shell oil/butter you can freeze.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Lobster, cooked your chosen method - Lobster bisque from shells (or shell butter to freeze) - Sides of your choice (drawn butter, lemon, herbs)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Prepare and Cook a Lobster (Jacques P\u00e9pin) \u2014 Watch how he dispatches and breaks it down with total confidence. The technique is as much about handling a live animal as it is about cooking \u2014 there's no video that teaches that instinct better.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#block-26-the-next-level-seared-scallops-already-happened-what-comes-after","title":"Block 26 \u2014 The Next Level: Seared Scallops Already Happened. What Comes After?","text":"<p>(Blocks 13\u201314 covered dry-packed seared scallops. This week extends into more complex shellfish territory \u2014 built dishes, larger preparations, and pairing shellfish with other proteins.)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#session-6-chili-crab-singaporean","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Chili Crab (Singaporean)","text":"<p>Skill: Cooking blue crab or Dungeness crab; sweet-savory-spicy sauce building  Read first: Singapore Chili Crab</p> <p>What you're learning: Chili crab is one of the great dishes of Singapore. The sauce (a slightly sweet, slightly spicy, egg-thickened tomato base) clings to the crab and eats like a main course. Messy and worth it.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Singaporean Chili Crab - Steamed white rice - Fried mantou buns or crusty bread for sauce dipping</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#session-7-shrimp-bisque-shrimp-in-compound-butter","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Shrimp Bisque / Shrimp in Compound Butter","text":"<p>Skill: Transforming shrimp shells into flavorful stock; reading shrimp doneness  Read first: Shrimp Scampi \u2014 Butter-Garlic Version</p> <p>What you're learning: Even shell-on shrimp carry flavor that transfers to fat. This session, peel the shrimp yourself (saving shells), then make a quick compound butter or simple shrimp stock that elevates any seafood dish later in the week.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Shrimp in compound butter over grits or polenta - Roasted cherry tomatoes</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#session-8-clam-chowder-or-clam-corn-pasta","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Clam Chowder or Clam + Corn Pasta","text":"<p>Skill: Using canned clams confidently; chowder-building ratios  Read first: New England Clam Chowder</p> <p>What you're learning: Canned clams are a legitimate pantry staple (SE says so). Build a clam chowder from scratch or pivot to a clam + corn + butter pasta that uses the same technique as vongole but heads in a different direction.</p> <p>Full Meal: - New England\u2013style clam chowder or clam-corn linguine - Oyster crackers or crusty bread</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Thicc Clam Chowder \u2014 Watch how he builds the potato-and-cream base before the clams go in \u2014 timing the clams last prevents the rubbery texture that ruins most chowder.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#session-9-mussels-in-tomato-saffron-broth","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Mussels in Tomato-Saffron Broth","text":"<p>Skill: Building a second mussel preparation with Mediterranean flavors vs. French  Read first: Moules Marini\u00e8res (Sailor-Style Mussels) for the base technique \u2014 today you\u2019re swapping white wine and cream for saffron, tomato, and fennel. Same bivalve, different broth logic.</p> <p>What you're learning: Same bivalve, different flavor frame. Saffron + tomato + fennel gives mussels a completely different character than cream and white wine. This is your first \"what changes when I swap the broth?\" lesson applied to shellfish.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Mussels in Tomato-Saffron Broth - Grilled bread rubbed with garlic</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#session-10-project-multi-shellfish-plateau-cold-hot","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Multi-Shellfish Plateau (Cold &amp; Hot)","text":"<p>Skill: Sourcing, timing, and presenting multiple shellfish together  Goal: Buy three types of shellfish. Serve some raw (or cured), some broiled, some in a sauce. This is a dinner-party-ready shellfish spread.</p> <p>Plan:  - Raw oysters or ceviche-style clams (cold) - Roasted oysters or mussels (hot) - Scallops or shrimp (quick-seared at the end) - Lemon, mignonette, aioli on the side</p> <p>Full Meal: - Three-shellfish plateau with accompaniments - Crusty baguette, green salad, white wine</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#sourcing-and-handling-shellfish","title":"Sourcing and Handling Shellfish","text":"<p>Live shellfish is the most time-sensitive ingredient in the kitchen. Knowing how to select, store, and clean it before you cook it is the bulk of the skill.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Clean and Debeard Mussels \u2014 The step-by-step process for mussels: pulling the beard, testing for live ones, and storing properly before cooking. The same inspection logic applies to clams and oysters.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 A Comprehensive Guide to Buying Better Shrimp \u2014 What the labels actually mean, when fresh versus frozen matters, and how to read shrimp quality at the counter. The sourcing principles carry across all shellfish.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#the-scallop-sear","title":"The Scallop Sear","text":"<p>A properly seared scallop has a deep, dry crust on each flat side and remains translucent at the center. Getting there requires a very specific sequence.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Right Way to Use a Meat Thermometer \u2014 Scallops at 115\u2013125\u00b0F interior are perfect. Above 130\u00b0F they become rubbery. Temperature matters more for scallops than almost any other protein.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Scallop sear technique \u2014 The dry-pat, hot pan, single flip, no-fuss method explained step by step.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Oyster shucking \u2014 Watch before you try. The knife angle and the location of the hinge are the whole skill.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Joy of Cooking by Irma Rombauer \u2014 The shellfish chapter remains one of the most comprehensive references for home cooks. Every preparation covered, without unnecessary complexity.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 23\u201324: Whole Fish &amp; Curing | Block 27\u201328: Pork \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Block 23\u201324: Shellfish","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/quick-ref.html#block-23-bivalves-crustaceans","title":"Block 23 \u2014 Bivalves &amp; Crustaceans","text":"Session Dish Technique Key Temp / Timing Session 1 Spaghetti alle Vongole Steam-open in wine Open = done; ~5 min Session 2 Moules Marini\u00e8re Steam open in aromatics Open = done; 4\u20136 min Session 3 Roasted Oysters w/ Bacon Dry heat oven roast 450\u00b0F until open; 8\u201310 min Session 4 Shrimp Scampi Fast saut\u00e9 + butter pan sauce Shrimp: 1\u20132 min/side; pull early Session 5 PROJECT: Lobster Night Broil / steam + shell bisque Internal 140\u00b0F; rest before serving"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/quick-ref.html#block-24-complex-shellfish","title":"Block 24 \u2014 Complex Shellfish","text":"Session Dish Technique Notes Session 6 Singaporean Chili Crab Stir-fry crab in sauce Pre-crack shell before cooking Session 7 Shrimp in Compound Butter Quick saut\u00e9, shell stock Make compound butter for freezer Session 8 Clam Chowder or Clam-Corn Pasta Simmer / pasta Canned clams fine for chowder Session 9 Mussels in Tomato-Saffron Steam open in broth Same technique as Block 23 Session 10 PROJECT: Shellfish Plateau Multi-prep, raw + roasted + seared Time: cold first, hot served last"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/quick-ref.html#key-shellfish-doneness-notes","title":"Key Shellfish Doneness Notes","text":"Shellfish When It's Done Danger Sign Clams Shell opens Still closed after 8 min \u2192 discard Mussels Shell opens Still closed after 6 min \u2192 discard Oysters (roasted) Shell opens, meat barely firms Curled/shrunken = overcooked Shrimp Pink and curled into loose C shape Tight O shape = overcooked Scallops 120\u2013125\u00b0F internal Rubbery = overcooked Lobster 140\u00b0F tail meat Dry/stringy = overcooked"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/quick-ref.html#key-shellfish-sourcing-notes","title":"Key Shellfish Sourcing Notes","text":"<ul> <li>Bivalves: Buy live, shells tightly closed; tap any open ones \u2014 they should close</li> <li>Shrimp: \"Fresh\" shrimp at grocery stores is usually frozen-thawed; frozen wild-caught is fine</li> <li>Lobster: Buy day of cook from a store with a live tank; avoid if tank smells off</li> <li>Crab: Ask fishmonger for live or freshly cooked; frozen legs are a valid option for chili crab</li> <li>Scallops: Dry-packed only (see Blocks 13\u201314 for full technique)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 23\u201324: Shellfish","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Shellfish mantra: Buy it alive, cook it the day you buy it, and don't overthink anything.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Large Dutch oven or pot \u2014 for mussels, clams, and bisque</li> <li>[ ] Tongs + spider strainer \u2014 for pulling shellfish out of liquid</li> <li>[ ] Instant-read thermometer \u2014 lobster tail target: 140\u00b0F</li> <li>[ ] Sharp kitchen scissors \u2014 for lobster shell if broiling</li> <li>[ ] Shellfish brush \u2014 for scrubbing mussels/clams</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/shopping-list.html#proteins-block-23","title":"\ud83e\udd9e Proteins \u2014 Block 23","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Manila or littleneck clams \u2014 2\u20133 dozen (vongole)</li> <li>[ ] Mussels \u2014 2 lbs (moules marini\u00e8re)</li> <li>[ ] Live oysters \u2014 12 (roasted)</li> <li>[ ] Shrimp \u2014 1 lb, 16\u201320 count, peeled or shell-on (scampi)</li> <li>[ ] Live lobsters \u2014 2 \u00d7 1.25\u20131.5 lb (project)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/shopping-list.html#proteins-block-24","title":"\ud83e\udd9e Proteins \u2014 Block 24","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Blue crab or Dungeness crab \u2014 2 lbs (chili crab); or frozen crab legs</li> <li>[ ] Shrimp \u2014 1 lb, shell-on (compound butter; save shells for stock)</li> <li>[ ] Canned clams \u2014 3 \u00d7 6.5-oz cans (chowder or clam pasta)</li> <li>[ ] Mussels \u2014 2 lbs (tomato-saffron)</li> <li>[ ] Shellfish for plateau \u2014 oysters (6), scallops (4 dry-packed), shrimp (\u00bd lb) </li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 3 heads (used every day)</li> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 4</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 8</li> <li>[ ] Fennel \u2014 2 bulbs (tomato-saffron broth + bisque aromatics)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 1 pint (Block 24)</li> <li>[ ] Canned San Marzano tomatoes \u2014 1 can (Block 24)</li> <li>[ ] Potatoes \u2014 1 lb (chowder Block 24)</li> <li>[ ] Russet potatoes \u2014 2 lbs (Block 23 frites for moules-frites \u2014 double-fry method)</li> <li>[ ] Celery \u2014 4 stalks (chowder aromatics)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 cup (chowder)</li> <li>[ ] Corn \u2014 2 ears or 1 cup frozen (if doing clam-corn pasta instead)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/25-26-shellfish/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dry white wine \u2014 1 bottle (used,, and for bisque)</li> <li>[ ] Vermouth \u2014 can substitute for white wine in bisque</li> <li>[ ] Olive oil \u2014 extra-virgin</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 \u00bd lb</li> <li>[ ] Thick-cut bacon \u2014 4 oz (Block 23 Roasted Oysters with Bacon and Parmesan)</li> <li>[ ] Parmesan \u2014 4 oz (Block 23 roasted oysters topping)</li> <li>[ ] Spaghetti or linguine \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Saffron \u2014 pinch (Block 24)</li> <li>[ ] Crushed red pepper flakes</li> <li>[ ] Oyster crackers or crusty baguette (Block 24 chowder)</li> <li>[ ] Baguette \u2014 for both weeks (bread with broth is mandatory)</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce or Worcestershire \u2014 small amount for bisque depth</li> <li>[ ] Sriracha and ketchup \u2014 for chili crab sauce (Block 24)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 2 (chili crab sauce is egg-thickened)</li> <li>[ ] Jasmine rice \u2014 for Block 24 (chili crab)</li> <li>[ ] Cornichons, shallot vinegar \u2014 for oyster mignonette (Block 24)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html","title":"\ud83d\udc37 Block 27\u201328: Pork \u2014 All Cuts","text":"<p>\u2190 Quick Reference \u2192 | Shopping List \u2192</p> <p>\"Pork is the most versatile protein in the world kitchen. It scales from a 2-minute chop to a 12-hour shoulder. It responds beautifully to fat, acid, smoke, sweetness, and spice. Learning pork is learning half the world's food traditions.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#block-27-the-pork-fundamentals","title":"Block 27 \u2014 The Pork Fundamentals","text":"<p>The key principle of pork this week: Pork \u2260 tough. The modern farmed pig is different from 30 years ago \u2014 leaner, safer at lower internal temperatures. The new standard is 145\u00b0F (USDA updated this in 2011), which means medium pork \u2014 still slightly pink \u2014 is correct. Cooking pork to 165\u00b0F the way you might have learned produces dry, grey, flavorless meat.</p> <p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 1 (Pork Chop): dry-brine the pork chop the night before</li> <li>Session 2 (Chashu Pork Belly): 2\u20133 hr braise; plan it as this session's main event</li> <li>Session 4 (Vietnamese Pork Chop): marinate at least 2 hrs ahead; overnight gives best char</li> <li>Session 5 (PROJECT: Slow-Roasted Pork Shoulder): dry-brine the night before; plan for 6\u20138 hr low cook</li> <li>Session 7 (Pork Ribs): 2 hrs low in the oven before finishing on grill/broiler; start the oven early</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#session-1-perfect-pork-chop","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Perfect Pork Chop","text":"<p>Skill: The hardest weeknight cook well-done: a bone-in pork chop, properly seared, properly finished, properly rested. Most home cooks overcook pork chops because they're afraid of undercooked pork. Tonight: understand the actual target (145\u00b0F), achieve it, taste the difference.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Perfect Pan-Seared Pork Chop \u2014 the technique and temperature explanation is the lesson</li> <li>Dry brine the night before. 145\u00b0F. Rest 5 minutes. Cut and taste.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Bone-in pork chop + pan sauce (apple cider or white wine, shallot, thyme) + Serious Eats \u2014 Roasted Cauliflower with Pine Nuts and Capers + simple salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Pork Chops with Madeira Mustard Pan Sauce (Helen Rennie) \u2014 Watch her pan sauce construction after the sear \u2014 the deglazing sequence and butter mount are the same technique you're using, just with different liquid.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#session-2-chashu-pork-belly-low-and-slow-japanese-style","title":"\u23f0 Session 2 \u2014 Chashu Pork Belly: Low and Slow Japanese-Style","text":"<p>Skill: Chashu is braised and rolled pork belly \u2014 the origin is Japanese but the technique (braise in soy, mirin, sake, sugar) is a master class in balancing the four flavor elements in one preparation. The rendered belly collagen gives the braising liquid richness; the soy gives umami; the mirin and sugar give the glaze sweetness and lacquer.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Chashu Pork Belly for Ramen</li> <li>This is a 3\u20134 hour project cook on a Session 2 \u2014 start by 3 PM</li> <li>The leftover chashu will be great later in the block and works for ramen all week</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Chashu pork belly + steamed rice + quick pickled cucumbers + soft-boiled egg</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Why Lu Rou Fan is One of Taiwan's Favorite Comfort Foods (Ethan Chlebowski) \u2014 Different Asian tradition for braised pork belly. Compare how the five-spice and soy base contrasts with your chashu's mirin-sake approach \u2014 same ingredient, entirely different result.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#session-3-pork-tenderloin-speed-and-precision","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Pork Tenderloin: Speed and Precision","text":"<p>Skill: Pork tenderloin is the leanest cut from the pig \u2014 cooked wrong it becomes the driest. The solution: high-heat sear, quick oven finish, immediate rest. There's almost no room for error in temperature here. Practice tonight.</p> <ul> <li>Dry brine 2 hours minimum. Sear in cast iron 2 minutes per side. Into 400\u00b0F oven. Thermometer in. Pull at 140\u00b0F (it'll carry over to 145\u00b0F while resting).</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Seared pork tenderloin + herb pan sauce (deglaze with white wine, add thyme, mount with butter) + Serious Eats \u2014 Honey-Roasted Carrots + rice</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#session-4-vietnamese-grilled-pork-chop-thit-heo-nuong","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Vietnamese Grilled Pork Chop (Thit Heo Nuong)","text":"<p>Skill: Marinated, grilled until caramelized and slightly charred. This is one of the traditional Vietnamese broken rice (c\u01a1m t\u1ea5m) preparations \u2014 the marinade is lemongrass, garlic, fish sauce, and a little sugar. The key technique: high heat, fast cook, maximum caramelization.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Vietnamese Grilled Pork Chop</li> <li>Marinate overnight for best results</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Grilled pork chops + steamed jasmine rice + nuoc cham dipping sauce + cucumber slices and herbs</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#session-5-project-ultra-crispy-slow-roasted-pork-shoulder","title":"\u23f0 Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Ultra-Crispy Slow-Roasted Pork Shoulder","text":"<p>Skill: One of the most satisfying large-format cooks in the pork repertoire. The shoulder (Boston butt or picnic) goes into a 300\u00b0F oven for 5\u20136 hours, then gets blasted at 500\u00b0F for 20\u201330 minutes to develop explosive crackling. The result feeds a crowd and requires almost no active cooking \u2014 mostly patience.</p> <ul> <li>Read (and mostly follow): Serious Eats \u2014 Ultra-Crispy Slow-Roasted Pork Shoulder</li> <li>Start by 11 AM. Score the fat cap deeply. Dry brine overnight.</li> </ul> <p>The project spread: Pulled/sliced pork shoulder + whatever sides feel right \u2014 slaw, pickled jalape\u00f1os, fresh tortillas, or a simple potato salad. This is a meal for the table.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Easy Oven-Pulled Pork (Plus Four Ways to Use the Leftovers) \u2014 Compare his oven temperature and internal temp target to yours \u2014 two different paths to the same falling-apart shoulder, and the differences are instructive.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#block-28-pork-belly-ribs-and-curing","title":"Block 28 \u2014 Pork: Belly, Ribs, and Curing","text":""},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#session-6-belly-pan-crispy-no-5-hour-braise","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Belly: Pan-Crispy, No 5-Hour Braise","text":"<p>Skill: Pork belly doesn't always require hours of cooking. Sliced pork belly (about \u00bd inch thick from your butcher) pan-seared in its own fat until crispy and rendered \u2014 this is the basis for guanciale, pancetta, and bacon-adjacent flavor without the cure. A learning cook this week.</p> <ul> <li>Cut into lardons (1cm x 4cm batons). Render slowly in a dry pan (no oil). Let the fat render out. Finish high heat for the crust.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Crispy pork belly lardons over white beans and wilted greens + crusty bread</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#session-7-pork-ribs-understanding-the-two-methods","title":"\u23f0 Session 7 \u2014 Pork Ribs: Understanding the Two Methods","text":"<p>Skill: Spare ribs (more fat, more flavor) vs. baby back ribs (more tender, faster). Tonight: a hybrid method \u2014 2 hours low in the oven, then a finish on the grill or under the broiler. This solves the classic rib problem: you need collagen conversion (time + moderate heat) AND caramelized exterior (high heat).</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Sous Vide Pork Ribs \u2014 even if you're not sous viding, the texture targets and timing are instructive</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Ribs (your choice of spare or baby back) + coleslaw + cornbread or baked beans</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#session-8-porchetta-italian-pork-at-its-peak","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Porchetta: Italian Pork at Its Peak","text":"<p>Skill: Porchetta is pork belly wrapped around a seasoned loin (or all-belly), rolled, tied, and slow-roasted. Fennel seed, rosemary, garlic, black pepper, and lemon zest are traditional. The skin crackles. The interior stays impossibly juicy. This is the most complex pork project of the block.</p> <ul> <li>Read: Serious Eats \u2014 All-Belly Porchetta</li> <li>Prep and roll a day or two ahead and refrigerate uncovered \u2014 the drying is critical for the skin.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Porchetta slices + braised white beans + simple arugula salad with lemon</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#session-9-pork-meatballs-ground-pork-technique","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Pork Meatballs: Ground Pork Technique","text":"<p>Skill: Ground pork makes the most flavorful meatballs \u2014 more than beef, because the fat content is higher. Tonight: traditional Italian-style meatball technique (bread soaked in milk, gently mixed, seared rather than baked).</p> <p>Full Meal: Pork meatballs + simple tomato sugo + fresh pasta or spaghetti</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Key to Tender Balls: How to Make Excellent Meatballs \u2014 Watch how he handles the mix \u2014 the less you work the meat, the more tender the result, and that principle applies to your pork meatballs too.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#session-10-project-carnitas-and-the-whole-shoulder-taco-dinner","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Carnitas and the Whole Shoulder Taco Dinner","text":"<p>Skill: Carnitas \u2014 Mexican lard-braised pork shoulder \u2014 is one of the finest applications of cheap pork in any cuisine. The shoulder goes into a Dutch oven with lard (or a combination of water + lard), orange, lime, bay, and cumin. The water evaporates and the pork fries in its own fat at the end, creating both tender interior and hard-crisped exterior simultaneously.</p> <ul> <li>Read (and mostly follow): Serious Eats \u2014 No-Waste Tacos de Carnitas</li> <li>Serve with: Serious Eats \u2014 Charred Tomatillo Salsa Verde + guacamole + pickled jalape\u00f1os + fresh white onion and cilantro + warm corn tortillas</li> </ul> <p>The real skill: the warm tortilla is important. Wrap them in a cloth. Keep them warm. The taco is only as good as the tortilla.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Carnitas are Easy, Inexpensive, and Delicious \u2014 Watch the final fat-frying step closely \u2014 that's the moment the pork goes from braised to both tender AND crispy simultaneously.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#the-pork-map","title":"The Pork Map","text":"<p>Pork is the most versatile animal in the kitchen. Understanding the cuts \u2014 shoulder vs. loin vs. belly vs. leg \u2014 explains why carnitas works but a pork loin doesn't shred.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Pork Shoulder Demystified: Boston Butt vs. Picnic \u2014 The same cut, sold under different names \u2014 here's what the difference actually means for your cooking.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#cured-and-preserved-pork","title":"Cured and Preserved Pork","text":"<p>This week is a natural gateway to charcuterie. Bacon, pancetta, and guanciale are the same muscle treated differently \u2014 and understanding that difference changes how you cook with them.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Bacon, Pancetta, and More: Cured Pork Products Explained \u2014 A clear guide to all the cured pork products you'll encounter in Italian and French recipes and why they're not interchangeable.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Case for Pink Pork \u2014 The USDA updated its pork temperature guidelines. Most people still overcook it. This explains what medium-rare pork actually means for food safety.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Kenji's carnitas \u2014 The confit-braised-then-crisped method explained in real time. The key moment is the fat rendering at the end.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Charcuterie: The Craft of Salting, Smoking, and Curing by Michael Ruhlman &amp; Brian Polcyn \u2014 The gateway book into everything you'll explore in Weeks 27\u201328. Covers the principles and science of every cured and preserved pork product.</li> </ul> <p>\u2190 Block 25\u201326: Shellfish | Block 29\u201330: Charcuterie \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Block 25\u201326 Quick Reference \u2014 Pork All Cuts","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/quick-ref.html#week-19-recipes-pork-fundamentals","title":"Week 19 Recipes \u2014 Pork Fundamentals","text":"Session Dish Skill Link Session 1 \u23f0 Bone-In Pork Chop + Pan Sauce + Roasted Cauliflower 145\u00b0F target; dry brine; pan sauce Pork Chop Technique \u00b7 Cauliflower Session 2 \u23f0 Chashu Pork Belly + Rice + Pickled Cucumbers + Soft Egg Braise in soy-mirin; fat rendering; umami layering Chashu Pork Session 3 Pork Tenderloin + Herb Pan Sauce + Roasted Carrots + Rice Lean cut precision; carry-over temp; butter-mounted sauce Honey-Roasted Carrots Session 4 \u23f0 Vietnamese Grilled Pork Chop + Jasmine Rice + Nuoc Cham + Herbs Marinade caramelization; lemongrass; fish sauce balance Vietnamese Pork Chop Session 5 \u23f0 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Ultra-Crispy Slow-Roasted Pork Shoulder + Slaw + Pickled Jalape\u00f1os Long low roast; blast finish; crackling Slow-Roasted Shoulder"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/quick-ref.html#week-20-recipes-belly-ribs-curing","title":"Week 20 Recipes \u2014 Belly, Ribs &amp; Curing","text":"Session Dish Skill Link Session 6 Crispy Pork Belly Lardons + White Beans + Wilted Greens Fat rendering; lardon technique; no brine needed \u2014 Session 7 \u23f0 Oven-and-Grill Ribs + Coleslaw + Cornbread Collagen + caramelization hybrid method Pork Ribs Method Session 8 Porchetta + Braised White Beans + Arugula Salad Roll + tie; fennel-rosemary-garlic; crispy skin All-Belly Porchetta Session 9 Pork Meatballs + Tomato Sugo + Pasta Ground pork; milk-bread ratio; sear not bake \u2014 Session 10 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Carnitas Taco Dinner + Salsa Verde + Guacamole + Pickled Jalape\u00f1os Fat-braise; water-fry finish; taco assembly Carnitas \u00b7 Salsa Verde"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/quick-ref.html#key-pork-temperature-rules","title":"Key Pork Temperature Rules","text":"Cut Target Internal Temp Notes Pork chop 145\u00b0F Rest 5 min; slight pink is correct and safe Pork tenderloin 140\u00b0F (pull early) Carryover to 145\u00b0F Pork shoulder (slow) 195\u2013205\u00b0F For pulling; collagen fully converted Pork belly Internal temp matters less Cook to visual \u2014 rendered fat and tender Pork ribs 195\u2013203\u00b0F Probe should slide in with no resistance"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/quick-ref.html#shopping-notes","title":"Shopping Notes","text":"<p>Week 19: - Bone-in pork chops \u2014 1 inch thick; rib chop preferred; 1 per person. Dry brine Sun night. - Pork belly \u2014 2 lbs, skin-on; ask butcher if not at standard grocer (Chashu, Session 2) - Pork tenderloin \u2014 1 lb; usually comes in a vacuum pack of 2 - Thin pork chops for grilling \u2014 \u00bd inch bone-in (Vietnamese, Session 4) \u2014 marinate overnight - Bone-in pork shoulder \u2014 4\u20135 lbs, fat cap on (the project session; buy by Fri for dry brine overnight)</p> <p>Week 20: - Pork belly slabs \u2014 1.5 lbs (Session 1 lardon cook), skin off; ask butcher to skin - Spare ribs or baby back \u2014 1 rack (Session 2) - Pork belly, skin-on \u2014 2 lbs for porchetta (Session 3); buy early to dry in fridge - Ground pork \u2014 1 lb, 80/20 (Session 4 meatballs) - Pork shoulder \u2014 4 lbs (the project session carnitas); can use the same cut as Week 19 the project session</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 25\u201326: Pork All Cuts","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>How to use this list: Two major project cooks this block \u2014 the slow-roasted pork shoulder (Block 19, start by 11 AM) and carnitas (Block 20, start by noon). Carnitas ingredients are simple; don't overthink the shopping. The porchetta (Block 20) should be assembled and dried uncovered in the fridge at least overnight \u2014 prep it or .</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dutch oven (5\u20137 quart) \u2014 essential for chashu, carnitas, meatballs</li> <li>[ ] Kitchen twine \u2014 for rolling and tying porchetta</li> <li>[ ] Wire rack + sheet pan setup \u2014 pork shoulder needs to sit on a rack in a shallow pan</li> <li>[ ] Instant-read thermometer \u2014 non-negotiable for pork (145\u00b0F target)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/shopping-list.html#proteins-block-19","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Block 19","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Bone-in rib chops \u2014 1 inch thick; 1 per person (; dry brine night)</li> <li>[ ] Pork belly (skin-on, slab) \u2014 2 lbs (chashu; buy early for prep)</li> <li>[ ] Pork tenderloin \u2014 1\u20131.5 lbs (; often sold in 2-pack)</li> <li>[ ] Bone-in pork chops, thin \u2014 \u00bd inch; 2\u20133 pieces (Vietnamese grill; marinate night)</li> <li>[ ] Bone-in pork shoulder \u2014 4\u20135 lbs with fat cap (; buy to dry brine overnight)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/shopping-list.html#proteins-block-20","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Block 20","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Pork belly (skin removed) \u2014 1.5 lbs (lardon cook)</li> <li>[ ] Pork spare ribs or baby back \u2014 1 full rack </li> <li>[ ] Pork belly (skin-on) \u2014 2 lbs (porchetta; buy and prep immediately)</li> <li>[ ] Ground pork \u2014 1 lb (meatballs)</li> <li>[ ] Pork shoulder \u2014 4 lbs boneless (carnitas)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/shopping-list.html#produce-block-19","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Block 19","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 3 heads</li> <li>[ ] Ginger \u2014 1 knob</li> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Lemongrass \u2014 4 stalks (marinade)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Limes \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Oranges \u2014 2 (pork shoulder brine + carnitas)</li> <li>[ ] Jalape\u00f1os \u2014 6 (for pickling;)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumbers \u2014 3 (pickled for chashu bowl + Vietnamese meal)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh mint, cilantro, Thai basil \u2014 for meal and sides</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 4 (honey-roasted)</li> <li>[ ] Cauliflower \u2014 1 head (side)</li> <li>[ ] Green cabbage \u2014 \u00bd head (Block 20 ribs coleslaw)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/shopping-list.html#produce-block-20","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Block 20","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Fennel seed \u2014 (also pantry; Block 20 porchetta)</li> <li>[ ] Tomatillos \u2014 1 lb (Block 20 salsa verde)</li> <li>[ ] Poblano pepper \u2014 1 (salsa verde optional addition)</li> <li>[ ] Avocados \u2014 4 (guacamole, Block 20)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh white onion \u2014 1 (carnitas toppings)</li> <li>[ ] Cilantro \u2014 2 bunches (Block 20)</li> <li>[ ] Arugula \u2014 1 bag (Block 20 porchetta salad)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/shopping-list.html#pantry-block-19","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry \u2014 Block 19","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 \u00bd cup (chashu marinade)</li> <li>[ ] Mirin \u2014 \u00bc cup (chashu)</li> <li>[ ] Sake or dry vermouth \u2014 \u00bc cup (chashu)</li> <li>[ ] Sugar \u2014 white (chashu)</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce (nuoc cham)</li> <li>[ ] Rice vinegar (nuoc cham + quick pickles)</li> <li>[ ] Kosher salt \u2014 plenty; dry brining all week</li> <li>[ ] White wine + chicken stock (tenderloin pan sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (Block 19 chashu bowl soft-boiled eggs; also general use)</li> <li>[ ] Ramen noodles \u2014 4 portions (Block 19 chashu bowl)</li> <li>[ ] Nori sheets \u2014 1 package (Block 19 chashu bowl)</li> <li>[ ] Mayonnaise \u2014 1 jar (Block 20 ribs coleslaw dressing)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/shopping-list.html#pantry-block-20","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry \u2014 Block 20","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Lard or neutral oil \u2014 2 cups (carnitas)</li> <li>[ ] Bay leaves \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Cumin \u2014 ground and seeds</li> <li>[ ] Fennel seed \u2014 for porchetta</li> <li>[ ] Fresh rosemary \u2014 2 bunches (porchetta)</li> <li>[ ] Corn tortillas \u2014 2 packs (carnitas)</li> <li>[ ] White beans \u2014 2 cans (with porchetta + with belly)</li> <li>[ ] San Marzano tomatoes \u2014 1 can (meatball sugo)</li> <li>[ ] Dry pasta (spaghetti or rigatoni) \u2014 1 lb </li> <li>[ ] Day-old bread \u2014 \u00be cup (for meatball panade)</li> <li>[ ] Whole milk \u2014 \u00bd cup (meatball panade)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/27-28-pork/shopping-list.html#bread","title":"\ud83e\udd56 Bread","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Crusty bread \u2014 1 loaf (Block 19 \u2014 serve with pork belly chashu bowl; also Block 20 porchetta)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Block 29\u201330: Charcuterie &amp; Curing","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 27\u201328: Pork | Block 31\u201332: French Classics \u2192</p> <p>\"Charcuterie is patience made edible. A piece of pork belly cured for five days, rinsed, dried, and sliced \u2014 that's the result of standing in a kitchen for twenty minutes spread across a week. The time is doing all the work. Your job is to not rush it.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#block-29-curing-salt-time-and-transformation","title":"Block 29 \u2014 Curing: Salt, Time, and Transformation","text":"<p>Salt curing is the oldest form of preservation in human civilization, and it's also one of the most revelatory cooking methods you'll encounter. This week you'll cure fish, grind your first sausage (or learn to), and understand how salt changes protein texture in ways heat cannot.</p> <p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 1 (Gravlax): start the cure at Session 1 \u2014 it needs 48\u201372 hrs before Session 3</li> <li>Session 5 (PROJECT: Charcuterie Spread + Pork Rillettes): rillettes need 3\u20134 hrs at 300\u00b0F; start early afternoon</li> <li>Session 6 (Pancetta-Style Cured Belly): needs 7-day dry cure; begin mid-block at latest</li> <li>Session 7 (Duck Rillettes): 3\u20134 hr confit cook; plan as a long afternoon project</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#session-1-gravlax-cured-salmon","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Gravlax (Cured Salmon)","text":"<p>Skill: Dry cure ratios, curing time, slicing technique Read first: BBC Good Food \u2014 Gravadlax</p> <p>What you're learning: Gravlax is cured salmon \u2014 no heat involved. A 2:1 salt-to-sugar ratio by weight, plus dill, applied to fresh salmon for 48\u201372 hours. The salt draws out moisture, firms the texture, and intensifies flavor. The result eats like the best smoked salmon you've ever had, made at home for a fraction of the cost.</p> <p>Note: Start the cure tonight (Session 1). It will be ready to slice and eat by Session 3 or Session 4.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Begin gravlax cure \u2014 no dinner from this tonight - Quick seared salmon for Session 1 dinner (side benefit: perfect salmon to compare against cured version later)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#session-2-sausage-making-fundamentals","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Sausage Making Fundamentals","text":"<p>Skill: Sausage stuffing, emulsification, seasoning, casing handling Read first: Homemade Merguez Sausage</p> <p>What you're learning: Sausage is ground and seasoned meat, packed into casings. The fat content matters (25\u201330% for juicy links). Temperature control during grinding matters (keep everything cold \u2014 fat smearing is the enemy). Spice blooming matters. This is your first step into charcuterie production.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pan-fried merguez with roasted peppers and couscous - Yogurt sauce and harissa on the side</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: 8 Rules for Sausages \u2014 The fat temperature and emulsification rules apply to merguez even if the spice profile is different \u2014 pay attention to rule #1 and #3.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#session-3-taste-the-gravlax-cured-charcuterie-board","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Taste the Gravlax / Cured Charcuterie Board","text":"<p>Skill: Slicing cured fish, building a charcuterie spread Read first: Best Charcuterie Boards</p> <p>What you're learning: Today you slice your gravlax (if it went in at Session 1) and taste the result alongside store-bought cured products \u2014 prosciutto, salami, coppa. The comparison trains your palate on what curing does to flavor and texture.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Charcuterie board: your gravlax + store-bought cured meats, mustard, cornichons, bread - Small green salad</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#session-4-quick-pickles-lacto-fermented-vegetables","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Quick Pickles &amp; Lacto-Fermented Vegetables","text":"<p>Skill: Quick-pickle acid ratios; understanding fermentation vs. pickling Read first: Quick-Pickled Onions</p> <p>What you're learning: Quick pickles aren't fermentation \u2014 they're acid baths (vinegar-based). But the result is similar: preserved, tangy, crunchy vegetables that transform simple dishes. This session make pickled red onions + one other vegetable (cucumbers, jalape\u00f1os, or carrots). These become your charcuterie board companions all weekend.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Sausage and pickled pepper sandwiches (use leftover merguez or store-bought sausage) - Quick pickles from today's session on the side</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Kosher Dill Pickles \u2014 His brine ratio and timing explain the chemistry behind quick pickles vs. fermentation \u2014 the acid vs. salt distinction changes everything about how long they keep.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#session-5-project-full-charcuterie-spread-potted-rillettes","title":"\u23f0 Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Full Charcuterie Spread + Potted Rillettes","text":"<p>Skill: Making rillettes (pork potted in its own fat); assembling a composed spread Goal: Cook a rillette-style spread using pork shoulder or duck (slow cook in fat, shred, pot in fat with seasoning). This is beginner charcuterie production. Plus, compose a full charcuterie spread featuring the week's cured products.</p> <p>Reference: Pork Rillettes \u2014 season generously, cook low and slow in fat (300\u00b0F / 3\u20134 hours), shred while warm, mix with rendered fat, pot and chill.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pork rillettes on toasted baguette - Full charcuterie spread: rillettes, gravlax, merguez, pickles, board accompaniments - Wine and bread \u2014 this is a meal celebration</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#block-30-applying-curing-techniques-program-midpoint-check-in","title":"Block 30 \u2014 Applying Curing Techniques + Program Midpoint Check-In","text":"<p>(This is the program's six-month mark. Half the year done. Use this week both to cook and to reflect.)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#session-6-pancetta-style-cured-belly-start-the-project","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Pancetta-Style Cured Belly (Start the Project)","text":"<p>Skill: Multi-day salt cure on pork belly; understanding cure penetration and timing Read first: Reference duck confit and gravlax techniques already covered</p> <p>What you're learning: Pork belly rubbed with salt, black pepper, and aromatics and left to cure in the fridge for 5\u20137 days becomes a homemade pancetta (unsmoked). You won't be able to eat it until next week, but this is how you start to think in longer cooking time scales.</p> <p>Tonight: Apply cure to pork belly. Label with date. Refrigerate uncovered or wrapped loosely.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pasta carbonara using store-bought pancetta while yours cures (perfect comparison for next week)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Sous Chef Erik's Pancetta Class, Part One \u2014 Watch the cure application and the fridge setup \u2014 uncovered and elevated is not optional, it's how the surface dries for proper curing.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#session-7-chicken-liver-pate","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Chicken Liver P\u00e2t\u00e9","text":"<p>Skill: P\u00e2t\u00e9 as a gateway to the broader charcuterie craft \u2014 building smooth, silky spreadable p\u00e2t\u00e9 from chicken livers, butter, aromatics, and brandy. This is one of the simplest luxury preparations in French cooking. Read first: BBC Good Food \u2014 Chicken Liver P\u00e2t\u00e9</p> <p>What you're learning: Properly cooked chicken livers (pink in the center, never gray through) blended with softened shallots, garlic, thyme, and butter into a silky p\u00e2t\u00e9. The butter seal on top (clarified butter poured over the surface) preserves it in the fridge for up to a week and gives it a finished, professional appearance. Chill for at least 2 hours before serving.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Chicken liver p\u00e2t\u00e9 on toast with cornichons, Dijon mustard, and cured pickled vegetables from Session 4 - Glass of Sauternes or a light Riesling pairs perfectly</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Chicken Liver Parfait \u2014 a more refined parfait version; compare the texture difference between blended p\u00e2t\u00e9 (rougher, more rustic) and the strained parfait (silky and smooth). Both are correct \u2014 they're targeting different textures.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#session-8-module-3-capstone-six-month-inventory","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Module 3 Capstone: Six-Month Inventory","text":"<p>Note: This is a reflective cook day \u2014 pick one dish from weeks 1\u201325 that you want to redo.</p> <p>Choose ONE technique that didn't go as planned in the past six months. Cook it again. Measure how different the result is now versus the first time. This is the most important practical exercise in the program.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#session-9-bacon-cured-salmon-breakfast-board","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Bacon-Cured Salmon Breakfast Board","text":"<p>Skill: Applying cure variations; building breakfast charcuterie Read first: Reference gravlax technique from Week 25</p> <p>What you're learning: Make a light variant of gravlax using a bit of brown sugar and cracked pepper instead of white sugar and dill. The result is a \"candied salmon\" cure. Serve on bagels or rye toast with cream cheese, cucumber, capers, and red onion.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Cured salmon breakfast board (brunch-style dinner \u2014 allowable) - Sliced tomatoes, cream cheese, everything bagel spice, capers, pickled onion</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#session-10-project-complete-cured-meat-tasting-pancetta-check-in","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Complete Cured Meat Tasting + Pancetta Check-In","text":"<p>Skill: Evaluating sourced cured meats; understanding regional charcuterie differences Goal: Visit a deli or specialty market and buy 5 different cured meats: one prosciutto, one salami, one coppa or speck, one regional specialty, one p\u00e2t\u00e9 or rillette. Taste critically \u2014 fat content, salt, spice blends, texture. Your pancetta is curing in the fridge \u2192 not done yet, but check it.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Curated cured meat tasting board with accompaniments - Crusty bread, mustards, cornichons, honey, fresh and dried fruits - The pancetta is now 5\u20136 days in \u2014 slice off one thin strip and taste (it's edible, just not fully penetrated yet)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Pasta alla Carbonara: 3 Ricette (Italia Squisita) \u2014 Three Michelin-starred chefs debate guanciale vs. pancetta vs. nothing else \u2014 the cured pork you've been making is the ingredient they fight over. Listen to the arguments.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#the-chemistry-of-curing","title":"The Chemistry of Curing","text":"<p>Salt draws out moisture, creates an inhospitable environment for bacteria, and transforms texture over days or weeks. Understanding the mechanism takes the mystery out of recipes that ask you to wait.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Italian Cured Meats: Salumi Guide \u2014 The full vocabulary of Italian charcuterie: prosciutto, salami, guanciale, mortadella, and everything in between.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Prosciutto di Parma: The Long Road \u2014 A longform piece on what actually goes into making the world's most famous ham. Puts your pancetta project in context.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#gravlax-salt-sugar-and-time","title":"Gravlax: Salt, Sugar, and Time","text":"<p>Gravlax is the cleanest introduction to curing \u2014 no smoking, no casings, no specialized equipment. Salt, sugar, dill, and a weight. The endpoint speaks for itself.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Bacon, Pancetta, and More: Cured Pork Products Explained \u2014 The overlapping chemistry between fish curing and pork curing, laid out clearly.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa How sausage is made \u2014 The mechanical steps of grinding, emulsifying fat, and stuffing casings are easiest to understand visually.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Charcuterie: The Craft of Salting, Smoking, and Curing by Michael Ruhlman &amp; Brian Polcyn \u2014 The foundational English-language charcuterie text. Covers every technique you did this week (and the next ten years of possible projects).</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 27\u201328: Pork | Block 31\u201332: French Classics \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Block 27\u201328: Charcuterie &amp; Curing","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/quick-ref.html#block-25-curing-fundamentals","title":"Block 25 \u2014 Curing Fundamentals","text":"Session Project Method Timing Session 1 \u23f0 Gravlax cure (start) Dry cure (salt + sugar + dill) Cure 48\u201372 hrs; taste Wed\u2013Thu Session 2 Merguez sausage Grind + season + stuff Cook same day Session 3 Taste gravlax + charcuterie board Slice cured fish; compose spread Slice thin, on bias Session 4 Quick pickles Vinegar brine Ready in 1\u20132 hours; keeps 2 weeks Session 5 \u23f0 PROJECT: Pork rillettes + spread Slow confit + shred + pot in fat 3\u20134 hrs active; chill 2+ hrs before serving"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/quick-ref.html#block-26-applied-curing-six-month-review","title":"Block 26 \u2014 Applied Curing + Six-Month Review","text":"Session Project Method Timing Session 6 \u23f0 Pancetta cure (start) Dry cure on pork belly Cure 5\u20137 days (back in Week 27) Session 7 \u23f0 Duck/Chicken rillettes Confit + shred 2 hrs total Session 8 Midpoint Redo Pick one dish; cook it again Reflective cook Session 9 Brown-sugar cured salmon (candied) Variant gravlax cure Cure 24\u201336 hrs; start Thu night Session 10 PROJECT: Cured meat tasting + pancetta check Sourced + produced comparison Buy 5+ types; taste critically"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/quick-ref.html#key-curing-ratios","title":"Key Curing Ratios","text":"Cure Type Salt Sugar Time Notes Gravlax (standard) 2 parts 1 part 48\u201372 hrs Dill, white pepper Candied salmon 1 part 1 part 24\u201336 hrs Brown sugar, black pepper Pancetta / dry cure ~2.5% of meat weight Small amount 5\u20137 days Black pepper, aromatics Quick pickle brine 1:1 water/vinegar 1 tbsp per cup 1\u20132 hrs Salt, spice to taste"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/quick-ref.html#key-sausage-notes","title":"Key Sausage Notes","text":"<ul> <li>Fat content: 25\u201330% for juicy sausage; less \u2192 dry</li> <li>Keep everything cold: meat, grinder parts, bowl</li> <li>Test cook a small patty before stuffing \u2014 adjust seasoning before casings</li> <li>Sheep casings (for merguez) available at good butchers or online</li> <li>No casings? Form as patties or loose ground</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 27\u201328: Charcuterie &amp; Curing","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Plan ahead: Monday of Week 25, you start a 48\u201372 hour gravlax cure. Monday of Week 26, you start a 5\u20137 day pancetta cure. There's always something in the fridge transforming.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Meat grinder or food processor \u2014 for sausage; KitchenAid grinder attachment is fine</li> <li>[ ] Sausage stuffer or piping bag \u2014 for stuffing casings; skip casings for patties</li> <li>[ ] Sheet pan + wire rack \u2014 for curing and airing</li> <li>[ ] Scale \u2014 cure ratios must be by weight, not volume</li> <li>[ ] Czech or glass container with lid \u2014 for gravlax cure</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-25","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 25","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Salmon fillet, skin-on, center-cut \u2014 1\u20131.5 lbs (Mon gravlax cure)</li> <li>[ ] Ground lamb or lamb shoulder \u2014 1 lb (Tue merguez; grind your own if possible)</li> <li>[ ] Pork shoulder \u2014 2 lbs (Sat rillettes \u2014 slow confit)</li> <li>[ ] Duck fat \u2014 1 lb jar (Sat rillettes; lard works too)</li> </ul> <p>For charcuterie board (Wed): - [ ] Prosciutto, salami, coppa \u2014 varied deli assortment - [ ] P\u00e2t\u00e9 or store-bought rillette</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-26","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 26","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Pork belly \u2014 1.5 lbs (Mon pancetta cure \u2014 won't eat until Week 27)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken thighs \u2014 4 bone-in or duck legs \u00d7 2 (Tue rillettes)</li> <li>[ ] Store-bought pancetta \u2014 for Mon pasta carbonara comparison</li> </ul> <p>For cured meat tasting (Sat): - [ ] 5 different cured meats from deli/specialty market \u2014 prosciutto, salami, coppa or speck, regional specialty, p\u00e2t\u00e9</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/shopping-list.html#spices-cure-ingredients","title":"\ud83c\udf3f Spices &amp; Cure Ingredients","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Diamond Crystal Kosher salt \u2014 large box (all curing uses by weight)</li> <li>[ ] Granulated sugar (gravlax) and brown sugar (candied salmon)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh dill \u2014 1 large bunch (Mon gravlax)</li> <li>[ ] Whole black peppercorns (cure + merguez)</li> <li>[ ] Cumin, coriander, smoked paprika, cayenne \u2014 for merguez</li> <li>[ ] Harissa \u2014 small jar (Tue merguez meal)</li> <li>[ ] Bay leaves \u2014 dried (pancetta cure)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh thyme \u2014 1 bunch (pancetta cure + rillettes)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Red onions \u2014 4 (quick pickles Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumbers \u2014 3 (pickles)</li> <li>[ ] Jalape\u00f1os \u2014 4 (optional pickles)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 4</li> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 4</li> <li>[ ] Red bell peppers \u2014 2 (Week 25 Tue merguez plate accompaniment \u2014 roast until charred)</li> </ul> <p>Board accompaniments (Wed + Sat): - [ ] Cornichons \u2014 1 jar - [ ] Whole-grain mustard - [ ] Honey \u2014 small jar - [ ] Grapes or dried cherries - [ ] Marcona almonds</p>"},{"location":"blocks/03-the-proteins/29-30-charcuterie-review/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] White wine vinegar (quick pickles + brine)</li> <li>[ ] Apple cider vinegar</li> <li>[ ] Baguette \u2014 multiple (boards; buy fresh each time)</li> <li>[ ] Rye bread or pumpernickel (Fri cured salmon board)</li> <li>[ ] Cream cheese (Fri cured salmon)</li> <li>[ ] Capers (Fri and boards)</li> <li>[ ] Couscous (Tue merguez dinner)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 6 (Mon Week 26 carbonara; various)</li> <li>[ ] Plain whole-milk yogurt \u2014 1 cup (Week 25 Tue merguez dipping sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Pecorino Romano + Parmesan (carbonara Mon Week 26)</li> <li>[ ] Spaghetti \u2014 1 lb (Mon Week 26 carbonara)</li> <li>[ ] Sheep casings \u2014 optional; order online (Tue sausage)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/index.html","title":"Module 4: The World's Kitchens (Blocks 31\u201348)","text":"<p>The goal of this module: Take every technique you've built and apply it through seven distinct culinary traditions. Each two-week immersion goes beyond recipes \u2014 you'll study the flavor logic, pantry structure, and cultural context that makes each cuisine a coherent system.</p> <p>By the end of Week 48, you should be able to cook with the grammar of eight world cuisines, not just their recipes.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/index.html#weeks-in-this-module","title":"Weeks in This Module","text":"Weeks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 31\u201332 French Classics \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 33\u201334 Italian \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 35\u201336 Japanese Cuisine \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 37\u201338 Korean Cuisine \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 39\u201340 Chinese Cuisine \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 41\u201342 Mexican \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 43\u201344 Indian \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 45\u201346 Middle Eastern \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 47\u201348 Module 4 Capstone: Southeast Asian Cuisines \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/index.html#core-skills-covered","title":"Core Skills Covered","text":"<ul> <li>French \u2014 classical brigade technique; beurre blanc, roux-based soups, coq au vin, tarte Tatin, proper knife work in a French context</li> <li>Italian \u2014 handmade pasta shapes beyond tagliatelle; risotto and polenta deep-dives; soffritto; regional sauce logic</li> <li>Japanese \u2014 dashi and umami foundation; teriyaki; ramen tare system; tempura batter technique; sushi rice and maki rolling; gyoza steam-fry</li> <li>Korean \u2014 kimchi and fermentation logic; banchan construction; gochujang and doenjang pantry; Korean fried chicken; galbi-jjim braising; pajeon technique</li> <li>Chinese \u2014 wok hei and high-heat stir-fry; velveting proteins; red-braising (hong shao); Cantonese steaming; Sichuan flavor logic; congee</li> <li>Mexican \u2014 dried chili taxonomy and toasting; masa and tortilla press; mole foundations; tamales; acid balance with lime</li> <li>Indian \u2014 whole spice blooming; wet and dry masalas; dal technique; tandoor-style high-heat cooking; yogurt-based marinades</li> <li>Middle Eastern \u2014 mezze construction; labneh and dairy ferments; sumac and pomegranate molasses as finishing acids; slow-roasted lamb</li> <li>Southeast Asian \u2014 wok technique (high heat, short time); curry paste from scratch; fish sauce as seasoning backbone; larb and acid-balance</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/index.html#equipment-youll-need","title":"Equipment You'll Need","text":"<p>See the Kitchen Equipment Guide. New items introduced in this module:</p> Item Introduced Tamagoyaki pan Week 35 Bamboo rolling mat (makisu) Week 35 Wok (14 inch carbon steel) Week 35 Bamboo skewers Week 35 Fine-mesh strainer Week 35 Rice cooker (optional) Week 39 Steamer / bamboo steamer Week 39 Tortilla press Week 41 Comal or flat cast iron griddle Week 41 High-powered blender Week 41 Steamer / tamale pot Week 41 Mortar and pestle Week 47 Pressure cooker / Instant Pot Week 47 <p>Previous module: Module 3 \u2014 The Proteins (Weeks 17\u201330) Next module: Module 5 \u2014 Mastery &amp; Pastry (Weeks 53\u201362)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html","title":"\ud83c\uddeb\ud83c\uddf7 Block 31\u201332: French Classics","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 29\u201330: Charcuterie &amp; Curing | Block 33\u201334: Italian \u2192</p> <p>\"French cuisine is not a style or a national preference \u2014 it's a grammar. Learn it and you understand the logic underneath every b\u00e9arnaise, every braise, every reduction. Every other cuisine becomes more readable once you can parse the French sentence.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#block-31-the-sauces-hollandaise-bearnaise-and-the-french-mother-sauces","title":"Block 31 \u2014 The Sauces: Hollandaise, B\u00e9arnaise, and the French Mother Sauces","text":"<p>French cooking week means sauce week. No other cuisine has built such a systematic framework around sauce-making \u2014 not just for tradition's sake, but because the system works. This week you'll tackle the two emulsified egg yolk sauces (hollandaise and b\u00e9arnaise), build a proper French onion soup, and finish with a cassoulet that will take most of the project session day.</p> <p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 5 (PROJECT: Cassoulet): soak beans overnight; plan for 4\u20136 hrs on project day \u2014 start by noon</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#session-1-french-onion-soup","title":"Session 1 \u2014 French Onion Soup","text":"<p>Skill: Low-and-slow caramelized onion technique; proper gratin\u00e9e finish Read first: French Onion Soup</p> <p>What you're learning: Real caramelized onions take 45\u201360 minutes. Not 10, not 20. Any recipe that says \"caramelize in 10 minutes\" is lying. Today is a patience lesson: low-medium heat, stirring every 5 minutes, watching sugar develop \u2014 and then building the soup around that deep onion sweetness.</p> <p>Full Meal: - French Onion Soup, properly gratin\u00e9ed with Gruy\u00e8re and a crouton - Simple green salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: This Video Will Change How You Think About Onions (Ethan Chlebowski) \u2014 The 45-minute caramelization time is the whole argument. Watch him document the color and smell at each interval \u2014 that's the evidence your patience is justified.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#session-2-hollandaise-and-eggs-benedict","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Hollandaise and Eggs Benedict","text":"<p>Skill: Emulsified egg-yolk sauce; gentle double-boiler heat control Read first: Foolproof 2-Minute Hollandaise</p> <p>What you're learning: Hollandaise is an emulsion of egg yolks, clarified butter, and lemon juice. It breaks when it gets too hot (scrambled eggs) or too cold (butter solidifies). SE's blender hollandaise method removes most of the anxiety. Then: poached eggs, Canadian bacon, toasted English muffin. The full build.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Eggs Benedict with blender hollandaise - Simple roasted potatoes or hash browns</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Eggs Benedict for a Crowd \u2014 Watch how he poaches eggs in batches and holds them in water \u2014 the hollandaise staying warm while eggs wait is the real challenge of the dish.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#session-3-bearnaise-sauce-with-steak","title":"Session 3 \u2014 B\u00e9arnaise Sauce with Steak","text":"<p>Skill: B\u00e9arnaise (hollandaise with tarragon vinegar reduction); pan-seared steak application Read first: Foolproof B\u00e9arnaise</p> <p>What you're learning: B\u00e9arnaise = hollandaise with a tarragon-and-shallot reduction swapped for plain lemon. The technique is the same; the flavor completely different. Serve over a reverse-seared or pan-seared steak (you now know how to do this from Weeks 17\u201318). The sauce elevates a simple steak into a restaurant dish.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pan seared strip or sirloin steak with B\u00e9arnaise sauce - Oven fries or saut\u00e9ed haricots verts</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#session-4-steak-frites","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Steak Frites","text":"<p>Skill: The restaurant standard: perfect fries + properly cooked steak in parallel Read first: Steak Frites</p> <p>What you're learning: Steak frites is deceptively hard to execute at home at restaurant quality because it requires parallel timing: the fries can't sit, the steak needs rest time, and a pan sauce is nice but adds another layer of complexity. This is a timing and plate management exercise as much as a cooking one.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Steak frites: steak of your choice + twice-fried or oven fries - Simple Dijon vinaigrette salad alongside</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#session-5-project-cassoulet","title":"\u23f0 Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Cassoulet","text":"<p>Skill: Bean preparation; regional French braising (multi-component slow dish) Read first: Traditional French Cassoulet</p> <p>What you're learning: Cassoulet is the great peasant dish of southwestern France: confit duck, pork sausage, white beans, and a crust that forms and gets pushed down repeatedly. It's a multi-component dish requiring 4\u20136 hours during the project session. The payoff is extraordinary. Start by noon on project day.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Cassoulet (serves 4\u20136; freeze the rest) - Good country bread - Green salad dressed with walnut vinaigrette</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#block-32-duck-beurre-blanc-and-the-composed-plate","title":"Block 32 \u2014 Duck, Beurre Blanc, and the Composed Plate","text":""},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#session-6-beurre-blanc-white-butter-sauce","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Beurre Blanc (White Butter Sauce)","text":"<p>Skill: Pure butter emulsion sauce; wine-and-shallot reduction base Read first: Beurre Blanc</p> <p>What you're learning: Beurre blanc is butter whisked into a reduced shallot-and-white-wine base, creating a light but rich sauce that coats fish and vegetables beautifully. Unlike hollandaise, no eggs involved \u2014 the emulsion is butter protein in an acidic liquid. It will break if overheated.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Beurre blanc over pan-seared halibut or salmon - Steamed asparagus as the vehicle for extra sauce</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#session-7-duck-a-lorange","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Duck \u00e0 l'Orange","text":"<p>Skill: Roasting duck; building a bittersweet gastrique Read first: Duck \u00e0 l'Orange</p> <p>What you're learning: Duck \u00e0 l'orange is a French classic and a useful study in gastrique (sugar caramelized to amber + acid to stop it = sweet-sour syrup base). The duck must render properly \u2014 its fat layer needs time and heat \u2014 and the sauce has to balance sweet, sour, and savory without tipping too far in any direction.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Duck \u00e0 l'Orange with rendered skin - Braised red cabbage and potato gratin as sides</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#session-8-souffle-cheese-or-chocolate","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Souffl\u00e9 (Cheese or Chocolate)","text":"<p>Skill: Whipped egg white foam structure; baking to serve immediately Read first: Savory Cheese Souffl\u00e9</p> <p>What you're learning: Souffl\u00e9s are not as hard as their reputation. What fails them is undermixed whites, overfolding, or an underprepared dish (unbuttered, no sugar/Parmesan coating). Make a cheese souffl\u00e9 tonight: it's impressive and straightforward with proper preparation.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Cheese souffl\u00e9 (Gruy\u00e8re + Parmesan) as main - Simple green salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Fast Cheese Souffl\u00e9 (Jacques P\u00e9pin) \u2014 His efficiency is the point: he makes this look like a weeknight dish. Understand which steps he collapses vs. which ones he refuses to rush.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#session-9-french-bistro-dinner","title":"Session 9 \u2014 French Bistro Dinner","text":"<p>Skill: Multi-component French bistro execution; proper service timing Goal: Cook a complete three-course French bistro meal:</p> <ol> <li>Starter: Salad Lyonnaise (fris\u00e9e, lardons, poached egg, Dijon vinaigrette)</li> <li>Main: Pan-seared duck breast with cherry or red wine reduction</li> <li>Dessert: Chocolate mousse (made ahead \u2014 Chocolate Mousse)</li> </ol> <p>Full Meal: - Salad Lyonnaise \u2192 Duck Breast \u2192 Chocolate Mousse - French baguette throughout</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Jacques P\u00e9pin Makes His Famous Cr\u00eapes \u2014 Add cr\u00eapes Suzette or plain cr\u00eapes as an alternative dessert; watch the wrist movement and how little batter goes in the pan \u2014 bistro cooking done with zero fuss.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#session-10-project-le-grand-aioli-provence-style","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Le Grand Aioli (Provence-Style)","text":"<p>Skill: Making aioli from scratch (emulsified garlic mayo); Proven\u00e7al composed platter Goal: Grand aioli is one of Provence's great communal dishes: a massive creamy garlic sauce served alongside a platter of vegetables (blanched and raw), salt cod, and hard-boiled eggs. Everything on the table, aioli in the center.</p> <p>Reference: Aioli technique = mayonnaise technique (from Weeks 9\u201310) with garlic and olive oil. The principle you already know \u2014 the application is new.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Le Grand Aioli: scratch-made garlic aioli + blanched vegetables + hard-boiled eggs + bread + whatever protein you choose - White wine from Provence if possible</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Old-Fashioned Handmade Aioli is Perfect for Spring Asparagus \u2014 Watch the mortar and pestle technique and compare it to your blender version \u2014 the texture and flavor absorption are genuinely different.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#classical-french-sauce-logic","title":"Classical French Sauce Logic","text":"<p>French cuisine is a system. Understanding where hollandaise sits in the sauce family \u2014 warm emulsion, egg-yolk-stabilized, related to b\u00e9arnaise by a flavor swap \u2014 shows how the system works.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Foolproof 2-Minute Hollandaise \u2014 The technique breakdown from SE, explaining why the blender method is actually more stable than the double-boiler version.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Guide to Cooking With Wine \u2014 Reduction sauces are at the heart of French bistro cooking. This is the wine guide that covers the how and why.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#aioli-and-emulsion-science","title":"Aioli and Emulsion Science","text":"<p>Aioli made with patience and good olive oil is nothing like the commercial version. It's also a direct relative of hollandaise \u2014 same emulsion principle, different fat.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Two-Minute Aioli \u2014 Kenji's immersion blender method makes the emulsification nearly foolproof. Understanding why it works \u2014 and what causes it to break \u2014 is the more important lesson than the recipe itself.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Cassoulet technique \u2014 The build order of cassoulet \u2014 confit, sausage, beans, breadcrumb crust \u2014 is visual. Look before you cook.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Jacques P\u00e9pin: New Complete Techniques \u2014 The definitive classical French kitchen reference. Every sauce, every cut, every technique. If you're going deep into French cooking, this is the shelf book.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 29\u201330: Charcuterie &amp; Curing | Block 33\u201334: Italian \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Block 29\u201330: French Classics","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/quick-ref.html#block-27-sauces-braises","title":"Block 27 \u2014 Sauces &amp; Braises","text":"Session Dish Technique Key Point Session 1 French Onion Soup Low-slow caramelized onions 45\u201360 mins for real caramelization Session 2 Eggs Benedict + Hollandaise Blender emulsified egg-yolk sauce 160\u00b0F danger zone \u2014 keep warm, not hot Session 3 B\u00e9arnaise + Steak Tarragon reduction + egg yolk emulsion Make reduction cold, whisk in butter warm Session 4 Steak Frites Parallel timing: steak rest + fries Twice-fry for crispy frites Session 5 \u23f0 PROJECT: Cassoulet Multi-component bean braise, 4\u20136 hrs Break crust and push down 3\u20134 times"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/quick-ref.html#block-28-duck-butter-sauces-composed-plates","title":"Block 28 \u2014 Duck, Butter Sauces &amp; Composed Plates","text":"Session Dish Technique Key Point Session 6 Beurre Blanc + Seared Fish Cold-butter emulsion into acid reduction Don't boil the beurre blanc \u2014 it will break Session 7 Duck \u00e0 l'Orange Gastrique + roasted duck Render fat slowly; sauce balance: not too sweet Session 8 Cheese Souffl\u00e9 B\u00e9chamel base + folded egg whites Stiff peaks; fold gently; serve immediately Session 9 French Bistro Dinner (3 courses) Multi-course timing + composition Do mousse ahead; mise en place everything Session 10 PROJECT: Le Grand Aioli Scratch aioli + composed vegetable platter Use room-temp eggs; add oil drop by drop first"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/quick-ref.html#key-french-sauce-reference","title":"Key French Sauce Reference","text":"Sauce Base Emulsifier Served With Hollandaise Clarified butter Egg yolks + lemon Eggs, asparagus, fish B\u00e9arnaise Clarified butter Egg yolks + tarragon reduction Steak, lamb Beurre Blanc Whole butter Shallot + white wine reduction Fish, scallops, vegetables Aioli Olive oil Egg yolk + garlic Vegetables, fish, bread Gastrique Sugar + acid n/a \u2014 syrup, not emulsion Duck, game, rich meats"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/quick-ref.html#cassoulet-component-timing-project-session","title":"Cassoulet Component Timing (project session)","text":"Component Cook Time Notes Soak white beans Overnight or quick-soak Cannellini or Great Northern Duck confit If not already made: 2 hrs Can use store-bought duck confit Toulouse sausage or garlic sausage 20 min Prick first Salt pork or pork belly 1 hr simmer Blanch first to remove excess salt Full cassoulet assembly 3\u20134 hrs oven Break crust 3\u20134\u00d7 during cooking"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 29\u201330: French Classics","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Plan ahead: Cassoulet (Saturday Week 27) requires dried whites beans soaked overnight. Duck confit (Tue Week 28) is better if started a day ahead. Plan accordingly.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Large Dutch oven / cocotte \u2014 essential for cassoulet</li> <li>[ ] Blender \u2014 for foolproof hollandaise (Tue Week 27)</li> <li>[ ] Souffl\u00e9 dish (6-cup) \u2014 for cheese souffl\u00e9 (Wed Week 28)</li> <li>[ ] Fine-mesh strainer \u2014 for sauces</li> <li>[ ] Heat-proof bowl \u2014 beurre blanc and b\u00e9arnaise work</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-27","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 27","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Duck confit \u2014 store-bought legs \u00d7 4 (Sat cassoulet; or make your own from Week 14 technique)</li> <li>[ ] Toulouse sausage or garlic sausage \u2014 1 lb (Sat cassoulet)</li> <li>[ ] Salt pork or pork belly \u2014 8 oz (Sat cassoulet)</li> <li>[ ] Steak \u2014 strip or sirloin \u00d7 2 (Wed b\u00e9arnaise + Fri frites)</li> <li>[ ] Canadian bacon \u2014 4 slices (Tue eggs benedict)</li> <li>[ ] Bacon lardons \u2014 4 oz (Fri bistro salad Week 28)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-28","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 28","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Halibut or salmon \u2014 2 fillets (Mon beurre blanc)</li> <li>[ ] Whole duck, 4\u20135 lb OR 2 duck breasts (Tue \u00e0 l'orange)</li> <li>[ ] Salt cod, if available \u2014 8 oz for grand aioli (Sat Week 28; optional \u2014 other protein works)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 2 dozen (hollandaise, poached eggs, souffl\u00e9, aioli, salad Lyonnaise)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/shopping-list.html#produce-week-27","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 27","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Russet or Yukon gold potatoes \u2014 2 lbs (Fri steak frites \u2014 separate from aioli platter potatoes)</li> <li>[ ] Onions \u2014 5 lbs (Mon French onion soup \u2014 ~3 lbs per pot)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 3 heads</li> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Fresh thyme \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Bay leaves</li> <li>[ ] Gruy\u00e8re cheese \u2014 6 oz (Mon gratin\u00e9e + Wed souffl\u00e9)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Dried cannellini or Great Northern beans \u2014 1 lb (Sat cassoulet \u2014 soak Fri night)</li> <li>[ ] Canned tomatoes \u2014 1 can (cassoulet)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/shopping-list.html#produce-week-28","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 28","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Oranges \u2014 4 (Tue duck \u00e0 l'orange: juice + zest)</li> <li>[ ] Asparagus \u2014 1 bunch (Mon beurre blanc)</li> <li>[ ] Fris\u00e9e lettuce \u2014 2 heads (Fri salad Lyonnaise)</li> <li>[ ] Assorted vegetables for grand aioli (Sat): carrots, green beans, radishes, cauliflower, beets, potatoes</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 1 additional head (aioli)</li> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 1 pint (Sat aioli platter)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh tarragon \u2014 1 bunch (b\u00e9arnaise + various)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/31-32-french/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Beef or chicken stock \u2014 2 quarts (onion soup)</li> <li>[ ] Cognac or brandy \u2014 small bottle (cassoulet + various)</li> <li>[ ] Dry white wine \u2014 2 bottles (beurre blanc, mussels, souffl\u00e9)</li> <li>[ ] Dry red wine \u2014 1 bottle (cassoulet)</li> <li>[ ] White wine vinegar (b\u00e9arnaise reduction)</li> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard \u2014 large jar (vinaigrettes + various)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 2 lbs (beurre blanc eats butter; hollandaise, souffl\u00e9)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 pint (souffl\u00e9 b\u00e9chamel + various)</li> <li>[ ] Parmesan \u2014 4 oz (souffl\u00e9)</li> <li>[ ] Baguette \u2014 multiple (souffl\u00e9 croutons, onion soup croutons, aioli platter)</li> <li>[ ] English muffins \u2014 1 pack (Tue Week 27 eggs benedict)</li> <li>[ ] Dark chocolate (70%+) \u2014 4 oz (chocolate mousse \u2014 classic French bistro dessert)</li> <li>[ ] Olive oil \u2014 extra-virgin (aioli + dressings)</li> <li>[ ] Duck fat \u2014 small jar if making duck confit vs. buying</li> <li>[ ] Orange marmalade \u2014 small jar (\u00e0 l'orange backup if juice not enough) | Whole black peppercorns \u2014 for gastrique</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html","title":"\ud83c\uddee\ud83c\uddf9 Block 33\u201334: Italian","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 31\u201332: French Classics | Block 35\u201336: Japanese \u2192</p> <p>\"Italian cooking is the most forgiving cuisine that still demands respect. No one cares if your risotto isn't perfect \u2014 but they care deeply if you added cream. Italian cooking's rules are not about technique. They're about ingredients. Get the right ones, and the technique almost takes care of itself.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#block-33-risotto-osso-buco-and-the-art-of-italian-patience","title":"Block 33 \u2014 Risotto, Osso Buco, and the Art of Italian Patience","text":"<p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 3 (Osso Buco): braise takes 2\u20133 hrs; start by early afternoon</li> <li>Session 10 (PROJECT: Italian Sunday Dinner): multi-component; allow 3\u20134 hrs for the full session</li> </ul> <p>Italian classics this week: risotto (patience + stirring + understanding when it's done), osso buco (braised veal shanks that take the afternoon and reward you royally), and a proper cold-weather ribollita. These are not quick Italian dishes. These are the ones that define why Italian cuisine is foundational.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#session-1-mushroom-risotto","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Mushroom Risotto","text":"<p>Skill: Ladle-by-ladle stock addition; risotto consistency (mantecatura); choosing the right rice Read first: Pressure Cooker Mushroom Risotto</p> <p>What you're learning: The SE version uses a pressure cooker for efficiency, but the lesson is the same: risotto requires Arborio or Carnaroli rice (short-grain, high starch), warm stock added in stages, and the final \"mantecatura\" \u2014 stirring in cold butter off heat until silky and slightly loose. Serve immediately; risotto kills itself waiting.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Mushroom Risotto (porcini + cremini, ideally) - Simple arugula salad with lemon and Parmesan</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Risotto \u2014 Two Chefs One Recipe (Italia Squisita) \u2014 Watch how two different chefs make the same dish diverge in texture and philosophy. The starch discussion alone changes how you hold your spoon at the mantecatura step.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#session-2-minestrone-the-full-version","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Minestrone (The Full Version)","text":"<p>Skill: Building vegetable-forward Italian broth; proper pasta-in-soup timing Read first: The Best Minestrone Soup</p> <p>What you're learning: Minestrone is not a simple ingredient dump \u2014 the vegetables go in stages based on cook time. Parmesan rind in the pot adds depth. The pasta/beans/bread component depends on region. This version respects the soup's architecture.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Minestrone with Parmesan rind broth - Crusty bread, additional Parmesan on top</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Minestrone Soup \u2014 Watch how he stages the vegetables by cook time \u2014 the architecture of the soup is the lesson, not the ingredient list.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#session-3-osso-buco-alla-milanese","title":"\u23f0 Session 3 \u2014 Osso Buco alla Milanese","text":"<p>Skill: Cross-cut veal shank braising; gremolata (the raw herb-lemon finish) Read first: Osso Buco \u2014 Italian Braised Veal Shanks</p> <p>What you're learning: Osso buco = \"bone with a hole.\" The marrow inside is the reward for patience. Brown the shanks aggressively (all sides), braise 2\u20133 hours until the bone loosens, finish with gremolata (parsley + lemon zest + garlic) added right before serving. The raw freshness of gremolata against the deep braise is the whole point.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Osso Buco alla Milanese - Saffron risotto alla Milanese (a simpler weeknight risotto)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Ossobuco alla Milanese (Italia Squisita) \u2014 The gremolata moment at the end is what separates this from any other braise \u2014 watch when exactly he adds it and why freshness on top of richness is the whole idea.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#session-4-ribollita-tuscan-bean-bread-soup","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Ribollita (Tuscan Bean Bread Soup)","text":"<p>Skill: Tuscan \"re-boiled\" soup; building body with day-old bread Read first: Pressure Cooker Ribollita</p> <p>What you're learning: Ribollita (\"re-boiled\") is meant to be made, cooled, then reheated (the name is the instruction). Thick with cavolo nero, cannellini beans, and day-old bread that dissolves into the soup. If it isn't thick enough to hold a spoon upright, it needs more bread or more time.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Ribollita, ideally made a day ahead and reheated with good olive oil poured on top at the table - Nothing else needed</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#session-5-project-pan-roasted-whole-branzino-tiramisu","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Pan-Roasted Whole Branzino + Tiramisu","text":"<p>Skill: Herbed whole fish for the table; tiramisu assembly and setting time Read first: Pan-Roasted Whole Branzino | Best Tiramisu</p> <p>Make the tiramisu in the morning \u2014 it needs at least 4 hours refrigeration before serving.</p> <p>What you're learning: Branzino is a mild Mediterranean sea bass ideal for the pan-roast technique (high heat, fat side/skin side down, briefly into oven). The tiramisu lesson is about layering, coffee saturation of ladyfingers (brief dip, not soak), and allowing the mascarpone cream to set \u2014 no gelatin, just structure from time and egg.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pan-Roasted Whole Branzino with herbs and lemon - Simple Italian green salad - Tiramisu for dessert</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#block-34-gnocchi-bistecca-and-the-italian-feast","title":"Block 34 \u2014 Gnocchi, Bistecca, and the Italian Feast","text":""},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#session-6-gnocchi-from-scratch","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Gnocchi from Scratch","text":"<p>Skill: Potato gnocchi dough; reading texture by feel; avoiding gummy results Read first: Light and Tender Potato Gnocchi</p> <p>What you're learning: Great gnocchi are light (barely there) because they contain barely enough flour to hold together. Too much flour \u2192 rubbery. The test: drop one in boiling water; if it rises and floats within 30 seconds and tastes right, roll the rest.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Gnocchi with brown butter and sage (simplest and best) - Roasted cherry tomatoes on the side</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Gnocchi di Patate: Veloce vs. Gourmet (Italia Squisita) \u2014 A quick weeknight version and a chef's version side by side \u2014 find where your dough lands on that spectrum and which version you'd choose again.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#session-7-pasta-fresca-fresh-egg-pasta","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Pasta Fresca (Fresh Egg Pasta)","text":"<p>Skill: Making egg pasta dough by hand; rolling and cutting; various shapes Read first: Reference pasta-making from Weeks 13\u201314 (pasta fresca was introduced there) \u2014 this session goes deeper into filled pasta</p> <p>What you're learning: Now that you know the dough, try a filled shape: either tortelloni (large), ravioli, or a simple pappardelle if fresh dough's not been practiced recently. The filling: ricotta + spinach + Parmesan + nutmeg.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Fresh ricotta and spinach ravioli with brown butter or sage cream sauce - Parmesan, black pepper</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Fresh Pasta from Scratch with a New York Chef (Italia Squisita) \u2014 Watch how he reads the dough by touch and feel, not by timing \u2014 the pasta you're making is the same recipe at the source.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#session-8-spaghetti-alle-vongole-revisited-from-italian-perspective","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Spaghetti alle Vongole (Revisited from Italian Perspective)","text":"<p>Skill: Building a white brothy sauce; pasta finishing technique; the two vongole versions (in bianco vs. in rosso) Read first: Spaghetti alle Vongole (used in Week 23 for shellfish technique \u2014 now revisit as Italian pasta lesson)</p> <p>What you're learning: The same dish from week 23, but now you're thinking about it differently: pasta al dente, reserved pasta water as sauce thickener, the ratio of clam liquor to olive oil. Make the white version (in bianco) if you made red baked mussels before; make red if not.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Spaghetti alle Vongole (the other version from Week 23) - Crusty bread</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#session-9-saltimbocca-alla-romana","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Saltimbocca alla Romana","text":"<p>Skill: Pan-searing thin veal or chicken cutlets; prosciutto application; sage crisp Read first: Veal Saltimbocca \u2014 or Chicken Saltimbocca if substituting</p> <p>What you're learning: Saltimbocca = \"jump in the mouth.\" Thin protein + salty prosciutto + sage + butter + white wine reduction. It's a 15-minute dish that requires absolute timing: in the pan, prosciutto-side down briefly, then flip, deglaze, done.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Saltimbocca alla Romana - Saut\u00e9ed spinach with garlic - Simple roasted potatoes</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#session-10-project-italian-sunday-dinner","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Italian Sunday Dinner","text":"<p>Skill: Multi-course Italian meal; timing, preparation, and service Goal: Build a complete Italian Sunday dinner for 4 or more:</p> <ol> <li>Antipasto: Cured meats, olives, fresh mozzarella, bruschetta</li> <li>Primo: Risotto or fresh pasta</li> <li>Secondo: Bistecca alla Fiorentina (thick T-bone, wood-fire or cast iron) \u2014 or osso buco if not done on Wed Week 29</li> <li>Contorni: Roasted vegetables or simple salad</li> <li>Dolce: Tiramisu or panna cotta (make ahead)</li> </ol> <p>Full Meal: - Complete 4-course Italian Sunday dinner - Italian wine appropriate to each course</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#the-italian-pantry","title":"The Italian Pantry","text":"<p>Italian cooking is defined by its pantry as much as its technique. Knowing what makes a San Marzano tomato different, why the olive oil matters for finishing, and what \"00\" flour does changes how you shop.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Best Slow-Cooked Tomato Sauce \u2014 The canonical red sauce breakdown, with the reasoning behind each ingredient choice.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#braising-italian-style","title":"Braising Italian-Style","text":"<p>Osso buco is a braise but it's also a study in gremolata \u2014 the lemon zest, garlic, and parsley condiment added at the end that lifts the entire dish. Italian braising is different from French braising in that finishing acid and fresh herbs are always part of the architecture.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Osso Buco (Italian Braised Veal Shanks) \u2014 The full technique for the dish: the sear, the soffritto, the wine reduction, the stock, and \u2014 critically \u2014 when to add the gremolata at the end. The structure is the template for every Italian braise.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Pasta Grannies \u2014 The most authentic window into Italian regional home cooking available on the internet.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Essentials of Classic Italian Cooking by Marcella Hazan \u2014 The foundational Italian cookbook in English. Everything you cooked this week, at greater depth, in one volume.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 31\u201332: French Classics | Block 35\u201336: Japanese \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Block 31\u201332: Italian","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/quick-ref.html#block-29-italian-patience-dishes","title":"Block 29 \u2014 Italian Patience Dishes","text":"Session Dish Technique Key Point Session 1 Mushroom Risotto Ladle-by-ladle stock; mantecatura Serve immediately; never cream Session 2 Minestrone Stage-order veg, Parmesan rind broth Pasta/beans go in last 15 min Session 3 \u23f0 Osso Buco + Saffron Risotto Brown all sides; 2\u20133 hr braise Gremolata added raw at serving Session 4 Ribollita Day-old bread in soup; reheat Better day 2; olive oil on top Session 5 \u23f0 PROJECT: Whole Branzino + Tiramisu Pan-roast fish; tiramisu sets 4+ hrs Make tiramisu in the morning"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/quick-ref.html#block-30-fresh-pasta-bistecca-and-the-the-day-before-feast","title":"Block 30 \u2014 Fresh Pasta, Bistecca, and the the day before Feast","text":"Session Dish Technique Key Point Session 6 Gnocchi Baked potato + minimal flour Test one before rolling all Session 7 Fresh Ricotta Ravioli Egg pasta dough + filled shape Don't over-flour the filling Session 8 Spaghetti alle Vongole White or red brothy pasta Reserve pasta water; finish in pan Session 9 Saltimbocca alla Romana Fast saut\u00e9; prosciutto-down first 15-minute dish; prep everything first Session 10 \u23f0 PROJECT: Italian Sunday Dinner 4-course meal; parallel timing Antipasto \u2192 Primo \u2192 Secondo \u2192 Dolce"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/quick-ref.html#risotto-troubleshooting","title":"Risotto Troubleshooting","text":"Problem Cause Fix Gluey, sticky Overcooked; too high heat Cook on medium; don't rush Soupy, watery Undercooked or too much stock More time; stop adding stock earlier Dry, clumpy Undercooked; mantecatura skipped Add splash of warm stock; stir in cold butter off heat No creaminess Wrong rice or no mantecatura Use Arborio/Carnaroli; cold butter off heat is mandatory"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/quick-ref.html#gnocchi-troubleshooting","title":"Gnocchi Troubleshooting","text":"Problem Cause Fix Dense / gummy Too much flour; boiled potatoes Bake potatoes; add flour gradually Falls apart Not enough flour Add 1 tbsp at a time; test one Chewy Overworked dough Mix just until cohesive"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 31\u201332: Italian","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Make-ahead note: Tiramisu (Saturday Week 29) needs 4+ hours to set \u2014 make it in the morning. Ribollita (Friday Week 29) is best made the day before and reheated. Plan accordingly.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dutch oven \u2014 for osso buco and ribollita</li> <li>[ ] Pressure cooker or Instant Pot \u2014 optional but SE's risotto and ribollita are tested with one</li> <li>[ ] Pasta machine or rolling pin \u2014 for Tuesday Week 30 fresh pasta</li> <li>[ ] Large heavy pot \u2014 for blanching gnocchi</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-29","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 29","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Veal shanks \u2014 2\u20134 cross-cut osso buco pieces, 1\u20131.5\" thick (Wed)</li> <li>[ ] Whole branzino or snapper \u2014 1\u20132, 500g\u20131kg each (Sat)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-30","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 30","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Veal scaloppine or chicken breast \u2014 4 thin pieces for saltimbocca (Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Prosciutto di Parma \u2014 4 thin slices (Fri saltimbocca)</li> <li>[ ] Bistecca protein \u2014 T-bone or Porterhouse, 1.5\u20132\" thick (Sat Sunday dinner)</li> <li>[ ] Cured meats for antipasto \u2014 prosciutto, salami, sopressata assortment (Sat)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/shopping-list.html#produce-week-29","title":"\ud83c\udf44 Produce \u2014 Week 29","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Porcini mushrooms \u2014 1 oz dried (Mon risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Cremini or button mushrooms \u2014 8 oz (Mon risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Arborio or Carnaroli rice \u2014 1\u00bd cups (Mon risotto + Wed osso buco risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Saffron \u2014 small pinch (Wed Milanese risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Cavolo nero (Lacinato kale) \u2014 1 bunch (Fri ribollita)</li> <li>[ ] Canned cannellini beans \u2014 2 \u00d7 15-oz cans (Fri ribollita)</li> <li>[ ] Day-old Tuscan bread or ciabatta \u2014 4\u20136 slices torn (Fri ribollita)</li> <li>[ ] Zucchini, carrots, celery, onion \u2014 (Tue minestrone + Fri ribollita)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Fresh sage \u2014 1 bunch (gnocchi Mon Week 30 + saltimbocca Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 6 (gremolata + various)</li> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 1 pint (Week 30 sides)</li> <li>[ ] Russet potatoes \u2014 2 lbs (Mon Week 30 gnocchi \u2014 large russets; must be floury, not waxy)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh spinach \u2014 5 oz bag (Tue Week 30 ravioli filling \u2014 wilt, squeeze dry, chop)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh basil \u2014 2 bunches (pasta, antipasto board, garnish throughout)</li> <li>[ ] Mixed olives \u2014 1 cup (Week 30 antipasto board)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/shopping-list.html#dairy-eggs","title":"\ud83e\udd5b Dairy &amp; Eggs","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Parmesan Reggiano \u2014 8 oz block (risotto, ribollita, minestrone, pasta)</li> <li>[ ] Parmesan rind \u2014 save from block (minestrone stock)</li> <li>[ ] Mascarpone \u2014 8 oz (Sat Week 29 tiramisu)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh ricotta \u2014 1 lb (Tue Week 30 ravioli filling)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh mozzarella \u2014 1 ball (Week 30 antipasto)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 \u00bd pint</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (gnocchi, pasta dough, tiramisu)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/33-34-italian/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Beef or veal stock \u2014 2 quarts (osso buco + Milanese risotto)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken or vegetable stock \u2014 2 quarts (risotto, minestrone, ribollita)</li> <li>[ ] Dry white wine \u2014 1 bottle (osso buco, saltimbocca, various)</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole San Marzano tomatoes \u2014 2 cans (minestrone + vongole rosso option)</li> <li>[ ] Dry pasta \u2014 spaghetti 1 lb + pappardelle or tagliatelle 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] All-purpose flour (pasta dough + gnocchi)</li> <li>[ ] Semolina flour \u2014 optional (pasta dusting)</li> <li>[ ] Espresso or strong brewed coffee \u2014 for tiramisu (Sat Week 29)</li> <li>[ ] Kahl\u00faa or rum \u2014 small amount (tiramisu)</li> <li>[ ] Ladyfinger biscuits (savoiardi) \u2014 1 pack (tiramisu)</li> <li>[ ] Unsweetened cocoa powder \u2014 (tiramisu topping)</li> <li>[ ] Manila clams \u2014 2 lbs (Wed Week 30 vongole \u2014 buy day of)</li> <li>[ ] Olive oil \u2014 extra-virgin, good quality</li> <li>[ ] Dried oregano, red pepper flakes, bay leaves</li> <li>[ ] Nutmeg \u2014 whole (ravioli filling)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html","title":"Full Guide","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 33\u201334: Italian</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#block-3536-japanese-cuisine","title":"\ud83c\uddef\ud83c\uddf5 Block 35\u201336: Japanese Cuisine","text":"<p>\"Japanese cooking is built on restraint. The ingredient is respected. The presentation says only what is needed. The broth is made from two things and contains multitudes. If French cuisine is the grammar of Western cooking, Japanese cuisine is its Eastern counterpart \u2014 a complete, internally consistent system with its own logic, its own philosophy, and its own taste.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#the-challenge-of-this-block","title":"The Challenge of This Block","text":"<p>Japanese cuisine is one of the most technically precise culinary traditions in the world \u2014 which means it is also one of the most legible once you understand the underlying logic. The flavor foundation is umami: the savory depth that comes from dashi (a 10-minute broth of kombu and bonito), miso, soy sauce, mirin, and sake. The cooking methods are precise. The textures are intentional. Nothing is accidental.</p> <p>Over two weeks, you will learn the dashi-based foundation; explore ramen, rice, and noodle cookery; master tempura batter and frying technique; understand sushi rice and simple maki construction; and execute a multi-course Japanese dinner as your project.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#block-35-the-japanese-flavor-foundation","title":"Block 35 \u2014 The Japanese Flavor Foundation","text":"<p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 1 (Dashi): Make a large batch \u2014 you'll use it throughout the block</li> <li>Session 5 (PROJECT): Plan your menu by Session 3; source ingredients by Session 4</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#session-1-dashi-the-umami-foundation","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Dashi: The Umami Foundation","text":"<p>Skill: Making kombu dashi and awase dashi; understanding umami at its source</p> <p>Read first: - How to Make Dashi \u2014 the foundational technique - What Is Umami? \u2014 understanding why dashi tastes the way it does</p> <p>What you're learning: Dashi is the foundation of most Japanese cooking \u2014 the broth that gives miso soup, ramen, nimono, and countless other dishes their characteristic depth. Kombu (dried kelp) contributes glutamates; katsuobushi (dried bonito flakes) contributes inosinates. Together, these two umami compounds multiply each other's effect \u2014 a phenomenon called synergistic umami enhancement. The result is a broth of extraordinary savoriness made from just two ingredients in 20 minutes.</p> <p>Exercise: 1. Kombu dashi: Soak 1 piece kombu (10g) in 1 liter cold water 30 min; heat to 140\u2013160\u00b0F and hold 10 min; remove kombu before boiling 2. Awase dashi: Bring kombu dashi to a simmer; add a handful of katsuobushi; remove from heat; steep 5 min; strain through fine cloth 3. Taste each at each stage: cold soak water, kombu dashi, finished awase dashi. Note the progression of umami. 4. Season a small cup of awase dashi with miso \u2014 make your first miso soup from scratch</p> <p>Reserve: Make 2 liters. You'll use it all week.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#session-2-miso-soy-the-japanese-pantry","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Miso, Soy &amp; the Japanese Pantry","text":"<p>Skill: Understanding the Japanese pantry; applications of miso, soy, sake, mirin, and rice vinegar</p> <p>Read first: - Japanese Pantry Essentials \u2014 the core ingredients and why each matters</p> <p>What you're learning: Japanese flavor comes from five foundational condiments: soy sauce (umami and salt), mirin (sweetness and gloss), sake (cooking alcohol evaporated for depth), rice vinegar (brightness and acidity), and miso (fermented umami). Understanding how these work in combination \u2014 the tare, the agedashi sauce, the teriyaki glaze \u2014 gives you access to the entire flavor system.</p> <p>Exercise: - Make teriyaki sauce from scratch: 2 tbsp soy sauce, 2 tbsp mirin, 1 tbsp sake, 1/2 tsp sugar \u2014 simmer to gloss - Apply it: brush onto chicken thighs in a cast iron pan, cook and glaze repeatedly until lacquered - Make miso butter: combine white (shiro) miso with softened butter 1:2 ratio; finish your next vegetable dish or steak with a small knob - Taste miso varietal differences: shiro (white, mild) vs. aka (red, intense, fermented longer)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#session-3-ramen-broth-tare-components","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Ramen: Broth, Tare &amp; Components","text":"<p>Skill: Building a ramen bowl from components; understanding the tare system; noodle selection</p> <p>Read first: - The Food Lab's Guide to Tonkotsu Ramen \u2014 the deepest dive into ramen science - The Components of Ramen Explained \u2014 the anatomy of a bowl</p> <p>What you're learning: A ramen bowl has three separate components that combine at serving: the broth (base flavor and body), the tare (concentrated seasoning sauce added to each bowl individually), and the toppings. This modular system is what allows one pot of broth to become shoyu ramen, shio ramen, or miso ramen by changing only the tare. Understanding this lets you build ramen at home without a 12-hour pork bone boil.</p> <p>Exercise \u2014 Weeknight Ramen from Dashi: - Use your Block 35 awase dashi as the broth base; enrich it with a small amount of chicken stock - Make a shoyu tare: soy sauce, mirin, sake, touch of sesame oil \u2014 simmer 5 min - Season broth with tare to taste - Toppings (make at least 3):   - Soft-boiled egg (marinated in soy/mirin mixture 4\u20136 hours)   - Chashu pork belly (braise thin-sliced pork in soy/mirin/sake/sugar, roll and tie, slice thin)   - Bamboo shoots, bean sprouts, nori, green onion - Cook and serve ramen noodles; combine at the last moment in a heated bowl</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#session-4-nimono-japanese-braising-simmered-dishes","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Nimono &amp; Japanese Braising (Simmered Dishes)","text":"<p>Skill: Japanese simmering technique; dashi-based braising; working with tofu and root vegetables</p> <p>Read first: - How to Make Nikujaga \u2014 the classic simmered dish</p> <p>What you're learning: Nimono are simmered dishes \u2014 vegetables and proteins cooked slowly in seasoned dashi until they absorb its flavor. The technique is gentle: a bare simmer, not a boil, covered with a drop lid (otoshibuta) or parchment to keep everything submerged. The result is radically different from Western braising \u2014 clean, dashi-forward, precise rather than rich and heavy.</p> <p>Exercise \u2014 Nikujaga (Japanese Beef and Potato Stew): - Thinly sliced beef (shabu-shabu cut) or ground beef, potato, onion, carrot, snap peas - Dashi base; seasoned with soy sauce, mirin, and a touch of sugar - Simmer gently until potatoes are just tender (don't overcook) - This is Japanese home cooking at its most fundamental \u2014 comfort food, not fancy</p> <p>Variation: Agedashi tofu \u2014 dust silken tofu with potato starch; fry until crisp; serve in warm dashi seasoned with soy and mirin; top with grated daikon and ginger.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#session-5-project-japanese-dinner-for-two","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Japanese Dinner for Two","text":"<p>Goal: A composed Japanese meal of 3\u20134 courses using techniques from Sessions 1\u20134</p> <p>Suggested structure: 1. Miso soup (from your dashi, with tofu and wakame seaweed) 2. Something fried: Agedashi tofu or tempura (see Session 6 for tempura technique \u2014 cook this block in any order) 3. Main: Teriyaki chicken or salmon; or a nimono dish; or ramen as a centerpiece course 4. Rice: Properly cooked Japanese short-grain rice (see Session 6 note); served with pickled vegetables (tsukemono) \u2014 even quick-pickled cucumber in rice vinegar works</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#block-36-tempura-sushi-rice-japanese-technique","title":"Block 36 \u2014 Tempura, Sushi Rice &amp; Japanese Technique","text":""},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#session-6-perfect-japanese-rice-ochazuke","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Perfect Japanese Rice &amp; Ochazuke","text":"<p>Skill: Washing and cooking Japanese short-grain rice; understanding the rice-to-water ratio; ochazuke (tea-on-rice)</p> <p>Read first: - How to Cook Japanese Rice Without a Rice Cooker \u2014 stove-top method - Ochazuke: Japanese Tea on Rice \u2014 the simplest Japanese meal</p> <p>What you're learning: Japanese short-grain rice is cooked differently from long-grain or basmati. It is washed until the water runs clear (washing removes excess starch). The absorption method is precise: fixed ratio, high heat to start, then low simmer, then rest with no peeking. The result is sticky, cohesive grains \u2014 not fluffy. This stickiness is a feature, not a bug; it is what makes rice the platform for Japanese food.</p> <p>Exercise: - Wash 2 cups Japanese rice until water runs clear (6\u20138 washes) - Cook using absorption method: 1:1.2 ratio (rice:water); lid on; never lift - Rest 10 minutes off heat before opening - Make ochazuke: pour hot green tea or dashi over leftover rice; top with salmon flakes, nori, pickled plum (umeboshi), or sesame seeds \u2014 this is what Japanese home cooks eat for breakfast with last night's rice</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#session-7-tempura-batter-oil-timing","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Tempura: Batter, Oil &amp; Timing","text":"<p>Skill: Tempura batter technique; deep-frying at correct temperature; draining and serving immediately</p> <p>Read first: - The Secret to Perfect Tempura Batter \u2014 why cold water and clumpy batter actually work</p> <p>What you're learning: Tempura batter seems counterintuitive \u2014 it should be lumpy, ice-cold, and thin. The lumps are undissolved flour pockets that create irregular, shatteringly crisp texture. The cold temperature keeps gluten from forming (gluten = tough, not crisp). The thinness means the batter drapes rather than coats. Fry at 340\u2013360\u00b0F in neutral oil; serve within 2 minutes or the crust loses its crunch.</p> <p>Exercise \u2014 Tempura Set: - Batter: Ice water, egg yolk, cake flour or a mix of all-purpose and potato starch; mix minimally with chopsticks; keep bowl over ice - Vegetables: Sweet potato (thin slices), shishito peppers, mushrooms, broccoli florets, asparagus - Protein option: Large shrimp (deveined, tail on; score belly to prevent curling) - Fry in batches at 350\u00b0F; drain on a wire rack; never paper towels (traps steam) - Tentsuyu dipping sauce: Dashi + soy sauce + mirin (2:1:1) simmered 2 min; serve with grated daikon and fresh ginger on the side</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#session-8-sushi-rice-simple-maki","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Sushi Rice &amp; Simple Maki","text":"<p>Skill: Making sushi rice (seasoned with vinegar, sugar, salt); rolling maki</p> <p>Read first: - How to Make Sushi Rice at Home \u2014 the technique for correctly seasoned, properly textured sushi rice</p> <p>What you're learning: Sushi does not require raw fish to learn. The skill is the rice. Sushi rice is cooled and seasoned immediately after cooking with a vinegar mixture (sushi-zu: rice vinegar, sugar, salt). It must be folded \u2014 not stirred \u2014 to preserve the rice structure while evenly distributing the seasoning. Maki (rolled sushi) is the most approachable format for home cooks; it requires nori, rice, and a filling.</p> <p>Exercise: - Make sushi rice: cook as per Session 6; season with sushi-zu immediately; fold with a rice paddle while fanning - Roll simple maki: nori sheet on bamboo mat; rice spread thinly (leave 1-inch gap at far edge); filling in center (cucumber, avocado, cooked shrimp, or canned tuna with mayo \u2014 all acceptable for learning) - Roll using mat; firm pressure; slice with a wet knife in single forward strokes - Serve with soy sauce, wasabi (real wasabi or prepared paste), pickled ginger</p> <p>Optional advancement: Temaki (hand rolls) \u2014 cone-shaped, no mat required; more casual but excellent for groups.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#session-9-gyoza-dumplings-and-crispy-bottom-pan-fry","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Gyoza: Dumplings and Crispy-Bottom Pan-Fry","text":"<p>Skill: Making gyoza dough or using wrappers; filling and pleating; the steam-fry technique</p> <p>Read first: - The Best Gyoza (Japanese Pork and Cabbage Dumplings) \u2014 complete technique</p> <p>What you're learning: Gyoza cooking is a two-step technique: steam to cook the filling, fry to crisp the bottom. The trademark crispy bottom-soft top texture comes from adding water to a hot oiled pan (creating steam) and covering immediately. When the water evaporates, the steam phase is complete; removing the lid and continuing to fry crisps the base.</p> <p>Exercise \u2014 Gyoza: - Filling: Ground pork, finely shredded and salted cabbage (squeeze dry), garlic, ginger, sesame oil, soy sauce, green onion - Use store-bought gyoza wrappers for first attempt; making wrappers from scratch is an optional advancement - Pleat and fold: fold wrapper in half over filling; crimp one side in small folds while pressing against the flat other side - Cook: neutral oil; lay flat-side down in single layer; add 1/4 cup water carefully; cover immediately; steam 5 min; uncover; fry until crispy base (2\u20133 more min) - Dipping sauce: Soy sauce + rice vinegar + sesame oil; chili oil optional</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#session-10-project-the-japanese-dinner-party","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: The Japanese Dinner Party","text":"<p>Goal: A complete Japanese dinner for 4\u20136 guests demonstrating techniques from across the block</p> <p>Suggested menu:</p> <p>Course 1 \u2014 Soup: Miso soup with dashi, tofu, and wakame; served in lacquer bowls if available</p> <p>Course 2 \u2014 Small Bites: One or two of: - Gyoza (crispy-bottom, pan-fried) - Agedashi tofu - Edamame with sea salt</p> <p>Course 3 \u2014 Main Selection (choose one or two): - Tempura set (vegetable + shrimp) with tentsuyu dipping sauce - Teriyaki salmon or chicken with steamed rice - Ramen course (unexpected as a dinner party dish; dramatic when served properly in heated bowls)</p> <p>Course 4 \u2014 Rice Course (if main was not rice-forward): - Steamed Japanese rice with pickled vegetables and a side of miso-marinated something</p> <p>Course 5 \u2014 Dessert (optional): - Mochi ice cream (purchased) - Matcha panna cotta (made in advance) - Fresh fruit sliced precisely \u2014 this is a legitimate Japanese dessert approach</p> <p>Logistics note: Much of this meal can be prepped in advance. The tempura must be fried \u00e0 la minute. Plan: everything else ready before guests arrive; fry tempura during a short kitchen break after the soup course.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#the-philosophy-behind-the-technique","title":"The Philosophy Behind the Technique","text":"<p>Japanese cooking has codified its principles into aesthetics \u2014 wabi (understated, imperfect beauty), kaiseki (the multi-course formal meal as an art form), and shun (cooking with seasonal ingredients at their peak). These are not decoration. They are why Japanese food looks and tastes the way it does.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Science of Japanese Fermentation \u2014 miso, soy sauce, and sake as fermented products; understanding how fermentation builds flavor over time</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 A Complete Guide to Japanese Noodles \u2014 soba, udon, somen, ramen: each has its own dough, texture, and ideal context</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/index.html#books-worth-having","title":"Books Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Japanese Soul Cooking by Tadashi Ono &amp; Harris Salat \u2014 ramen, tonkatsu, yakitori, gyoza, tempura: the full spectrum of Japanese food that people actually eat, day-to-day. Essential.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcda Japan: The Cookbook by Nancy Singleton Hachisu \u2014 400 recipes covering the full breadth of Japanese regional cooking. More ambitious; deeply rewarding.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 33\u201334: Italian | Block 37\u201338: Korean Cuisine \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/quick-ref.html","title":"Block 35\u201336: Japanese Cuisine \u2014 Quick Reference","text":""},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/quick-ref.html#block-overview","title":"Block Overview","text":"Weeks 35\u201336 Flavor Foundation Dashi (kombu + katsuobushi), soy, mirin, sake, miso, rice vinegar Project Sessions Session 5: Japanese Dinner for Two \u00b7 Session 10: Japanese Dinner Party Key Equipment Fine-mesh strainer (+ cheesecloth ideally), Dutch oven, wok or heavy pot for tempura frying, instant-read thermometer, bamboo sushi mat"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/quick-ref.html#the-japanese-flavor-system","title":"The Japanese Flavor System","text":"Ingredient Function Usage Kombu Umami base (glutamates) Dashi; never boil it Katsuobushi Umami boost (inosinates) Dashi; steep then strain Soy sauce (shoyu) Salt + umami + color All-purpose seasoning Mirin Sweetness + gloss Glazes, tare, sauces Sake Depth, aroma (alcohol cooks off) Marinades, braises, tare Rice vinegar Brightness and acidity Sushi rice, pickles, dressings White miso (shiro) Mild, sweet fermented umami Soup, butter, dressings Red miso (aka) Intense, salty fermented umami Heavier applications Sesame oil Aroma finish Never cook with it; add at end"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/quick-ref.html#dashi-the-two-versions","title":"Dashi \u2014 The Two Versions","text":""},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/quick-ref.html#kombu-dashi-vegan","title":"Kombu Dashi (vegan)","text":"<ol> <li>Soak 10g kombu in 1L cold water for 30 min</li> <li>Heat slowly to 140\u2013160\u00b0F; hold 10 min</li> <li>Remove kombu before water boils (boiling = bitter)</li> <li>Flavor: clean, vegetal umami</li> </ol>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/quick-ref.html#awase-dashi-standard","title":"Awase Dashi (standard)","text":"<ol> <li>Bring kombu dashi to a simmer</li> <li>Add a large handful of katsuobushi; remove from heat</li> <li>Steep 5 minutes; strain through fine cloth</li> <li>Flavor: rich, savory, deeply umami</li> </ol> <p>Uses: Base for miso soup, ramen broth, nimono braising liquid, tempura dipping sauce (tentsuyu), agedashi sauce, and countless other applications.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/quick-ref.html#master-ratios","title":"Master Ratios","text":"Application Ratio Miso soup 1 L dashi + 3\u20134 tbsp miso Tentsuyu (dipping sauce) 2 parts dashi : 1 part soy : 1 part mirin Teriyaki glaze 2 tbsp soy + 2 tbsp mirin + 1 tbsp sake + 1/2 tsp sugar Shoyu tare (ramen) Soy, mirin, sake, dash of sesame oil \u2014 simmer 5 min Sushi-zu (rice seasoning) 3 tbsp rice vinegar + 1.5 tbsp sugar + 1 tsp salt per 2 cups dry rice Gyoza dipping sauce 2 parts soy + 1 part rice vinegar + sesame oil + optional chili oil"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/quick-ref.html#tempura-critical-points","title":"Tempura \u2014 Critical Points","text":"Step Detail Batter temperature Ice cold \u2014 bowl over ice throughout Mixing Minimal \u2014 lumpy is correct; gluten = tough Batter texture Thin; should drape, not coat thickly Oil temperature 340\u2013360\u00b0F; use thermometer Frying Small batches; don't crowd; oil temp drops with each batch Drain Wire rack only; paper towels trap steam and destroy crispness Serve Within 2 minutes of frying <p>Batter ingredients: Egg yolk + ice water + cake flour (or 50:50 all-purpose + potato starch) \u2014 mix with chopsticks, 10\u201315 strokes maximum.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/quick-ref.html#sushi-rice-the-process","title":"Sushi Rice \u2014 The Process","text":"<ol> <li>Wash 2 cups Japanese short-grain rice until water runs clear (6\u20138 washes)</li> <li>Cook 1:1.2 rice-to-water; high heat \u2192 simmer \u2192 rest 10 min undisturbed</li> <li>Mix sushi-zu; fold (don't stir) into warm rice with rice paddle; fan while folding</li> <li>Cover with damp towel; use within 2 hours</li> </ol> <p>Do not refrigerate sushi rice \u2014 it hardens and becomes unusable.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/quick-ref.html#gyoza-the-steam-fry-method","title":"Gyoza \u2014 The Steam-Fry Method","text":"<ol> <li>Oil in pan over medium-high; lay gyoza flat-side down</li> <li>Add 1/4 cup water; stand back; cover immediately</li> <li>Steam 5\u20136 minutes until water evaporates</li> <li>Remove lid; fry 2\u20133 more minutes until base is golden and crisp</li> <li>Serve immediately; crispy bottom softens quickly</li> </ol> <p>Do not flip gyoza \u2014 one side should be crisp, the other soft. That's the design.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/quick-ref.html#ramen-component-map","title":"Ramen \u2014 Component Map","text":"Component What It Does Can Be Made Ahead Broth Body and base flavor Yes \u2014 days ahead; freeze Tare Seasoning concentrate Yes \u2014 weeks ahead Noodles Texture and chew Day of only Chashu Protein; richness Yes \u2014 3 days ahead Marinated egg Richness; visual 1\u20132 days ahead Toppings Freshness contrast Day of <p>Assembly: Heat bowl with hot water; discard; add tare first; pour hot broth; add noodles; top in arranged fashion. Serve immediately.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/quick-ref.html#session-targets","title":"Session Targets","text":"Session What You're Cooking Key Technique 1 Kombu dashi + awase dashi + miso soup Dashi making, umami understanding 2 Teriyaki chicken + miso butter Japanese pantry applications 3 Weeknight ramen bowl with toppings Tare, broth, component cooking 4 Nikujaga (simmered stew) or agedashi tofu Nimono technique 5 (PROJECT) 3\u20134 course Japanese dinner Complete service 6 Japanese rice + ochazuke Rice washing, absorption, repurposing 7 Tempura set with tentsuyu sauce Batter technique, deep frying 8 Sushi rice + simple maki rolls Seasoned rice, rolling 9 Gyoza (pan-fried dumplings) Steam-fry technique, pleating 10 (PROJECT) Japanese dinner party for 4\u20136 Full multi-course service"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/shopping-list.html","title":"Block 35\u201336: Japanese Cuisine \u2014 Shopping List","text":"<p>This list covers all 10 sessions. The Japanese pantry has a higher upfront investment; most items will last months and apply across all future cooking.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/shopping-list.html#japanese-pantry-one-time-purchases","title":"Japanese Pantry \u2014 One-Time Purchases","text":"<p>These are shelf-stable and will outlast this block by months or years.</p> Item Where to Find Notes Kombu (dried kelp) Japanese grocer, Asian market, Amazon 1 package (50\u2013100g) Katsuobushi (dried bonito flakes) Same as above 1 bag (40\u201350g) Soy sauce (Japanese-style, e.g., Kikkoman or Yamasa) Most grocery stores Standard shoyu Mirin Asian market or Amazon Look for \"hon mirin\" (real mirin vs. \"mirin-style seasoning\") Sake (cooking or drinking) Asian market, liquor store Cooking sake is fine; drinking sake is better Rice vinegar Most grocery stores Unseasoned White miso (shiro miso) Refrigerated section, Asian market Start with white; it's mildest Red miso (aka miso) Same \u2014 optional for contrast tasting Sesame oil (toasted) Most grocery stores Small bottle; finisher only Potato starch or katakuriko Asian market Tempura, agedashi coating Dashi powder Asian market Backup option if making dashi not possible"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/shopping-list.html#session-1-dashi-miso-soup","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Dashi &amp; Miso Soup","text":"Item Qty Kombu 20\u201330g Katsuobushi 20\u201330g Silken tofu 1 block Wakame (dried seaweed) Small package White miso 1 container"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/shopping-list.html#session-2-teriyaki-miso-applications","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Teriyaki &amp; Miso Applications","text":"Item Qty Chicken thighs (bone-in or boneless) 4 pieces Unsalted butter For miso butter Vegetables to glaze (broccolini, green beans, or similar) 1 lb"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/shopping-list.html#session-3-weeknight-ramen","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Weeknight Ramen","text":"Item Qty Notes Ramen noodles (fresh or dried) 2\u20134 portions Asian market; or Sun Noodle brand Pork belly (chashu) 1 lb Or substitute: chicken thighs Eggs 4 For marinated soft-boiled eggs Bamboo shoots (canned) 1 can Bean sprouts 1 bag Green onions 1 bunch Nori sheets 1 package Chicken stock 1 qt To supplement dashi broth"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/shopping-list.html#session-4-nikujaga-agedashi-tofu","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Nikujaga / Agedashi Tofu","text":"Item Qty Thinly sliced beef (shabu-shabu cut) or ground beef 1/2 lb Potatoes (Yukon Gold) 3\u20134 medium Carrots 2 Yellow onion 1 Snap peas or snow peas 1/2 lb Silken tofu 1\u20132 blocks (if making agedashi) Potato starch For agedashi coating Daikon (grated) Small piece Fresh ginger Small piece"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/shopping-list.html#session-6-japanese-rice-ochazuke","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Japanese Rice &amp; Ochazuke","text":"Item Qty Short-grain Japanese rice (e.g., Koshihikari) 2 lb bag Green tea (loose leaf or bags) 1 package Salmon flakes or canned salmon Small amount Umeboshi (pickled plum) Small jar Nori, sesame seeds Small amounts"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/shopping-list.html#session-7-tempura","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Tempura","text":"Item Qty Cake flour (or all-purpose + potato starch) 1 cup Eggs 2 Neutral oil for frying (avocado, vegetable, or peanut) 1\u20132 liters Sweet potato 1 medium Shishito peppers 1 small bag Shiitake or cremini mushrooms 8 oz Asparagus 1 bunch Large shrimp (deveined, tail-on) 1/2 lb Daikon for grating Small piece Fresh ginger Small piece"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/shopping-list.html#session-8-sushi-rice-maki","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Sushi Rice &amp; Maki","text":"Item Qty Short-grain Japanese rice (use from Session 6 purchase) Rice vinegar (use from pantry purchase) Nori sheets 1 package (10 sheets) Sushi fillings (choose 2\u20133): \u2192 Cucumber 1 \u2192 Avocado 2 \u2192 Cooked shrimp 1/2 lb \u2192 Canned tuna 1 can Soy sauce, wasabi paste, pickled ginger Standard sushi condiments Bamboo rolling mat (makisu) 1"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/shopping-list.html#session-9-gyoza","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Gyoza","text":"Item Qty Notes Ground pork 1/2 lb Or chicken; pork is traditional Napa cabbage 1/4 head Finely shredded + salted Garlic 4 cloves Fresh ginger 1-inch piece Green onions 1 bunch Gyoza wrappers 1 package (30\u201340 ct) Refrigerated at Asian market Neutral oil For frying"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/shopping-list.html#session-5-10-project-dinners-plan-based-on-your-menu","title":"SESSION 5 &amp; 10 \u2014 PROJECT DINNERS (Plan based on your menu)","text":"<p>Session 5: Japanese Dinner for Two - Source ingredients based on your chosen menu from Sessions 1\u20134 - Minimum: dashi, miso, rice, one protein, one vegetable application</p> <p>Session 10: Japanese Dinner Party for 4\u20136 - Recommended: Miso soup (always, serves a crowd easily) + gyoza or agedashi tofu starter + tempura or teriyaki main + rice + purchased mochi ice cream for dessert - Plan at least 2 days ahead; tempura is \u00e0 la minute but everything else can be prepped in advance</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/35-36-japanese/shopping-list.html#equipment-note","title":"Equipment Note","text":"Item Notes Bamboo rolling mat (makisu) Required for maki; ~$3\u20135 at Asian markets Drop lid (otoshibuta) or parchment circle Used in nimono; substitute: circle of foil or parchment Fine mesh strainer + cheesecloth For clear dashi; cheesecloth optional but produces cleaner broth Deep thermometer or candy thermometer Required for tempura oil temperature Wok or high-sided pot Tempura frying; the high sides manage splatter"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html","title":"\ud83c\uddf0\ud83c\uddf7 Block 37\u201338: Korean Cuisine","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 35\u201336: Japanese Cuisine | Block 39\u201340: Chinese \u2192</p> <p>\"Korean cooking is a cuisine of fermentation, fire, and contrast. The same meal might include mild steamed rice, fiercely spiced kimchi, umami-rich doenjang, and the charred sweetness of gochujang-lacquered short ribs. Heat and cooling. Sour and sweet. Pungent and subtle. Korea's table doesn't resolve these tensions \u2014 it holds them in deliberate, delicious balance.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#before-you-start-block-33","title":"Before You Start Block 33","text":"<p>Read these first:</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 Everything You Need to Know About Korean Ingredients \u2014 gochujang, doenjang, ganjang (soy), gochugaru, toasted sesame oil, perilla \u2014 the pantry that makes Korean food Korean</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Maangchi \u2014 About Korean Cooking \u2014 Maangchi is the most trusted Korean cooking resource in English. You'll use her recipes throughout this block.</li> </ul> <p>Stock your pantry before starting this block:</p> Ingredient Notes Gochujang (fermented chili paste) The backbone of Korean red sauce cooking Doenjang (fermented soybean paste) Korean miso \u2014 funkier, more complex Gochugaru (Korean chili flakes) Coarse red flakes \u2014 essential for kimchi and most banchan Sesame oil (toasted) Finishing oil, not cooking oil Soy sauce (Korean style or Japanese dark) Ganjang, or Korean soy sauce Rice vinegar Mild acid for dressings and pickles Fish sauce Background depth in many dishes Short grain white rice The foundation of every meal"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#block-37-foundations-fermentation-and-fire","title":"Block 37 \u2014 Foundations: Fermentation and Fire","text":"<p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 1 (Kimchi): kimchi needs 24\u201348 hrs fermentation before it's really ready; make it immediately and taste it each day</li> <li>Session 5 (PROJECT: Korean Barbecue Night): marinate galbi 24 hrs ahead; marinate bulgogi at least 4 hrs ahead</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#session-1-kimchi-the-soul-of-the-korean-kitchen","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Kimchi: The Soul of the Korean Kitchen","text":"<p>Skill: Kimchi is not just a condiment \u2014 it's a fermentation technique, a flavor system, and the defining element of Korean cuisine. Tonight you'll make a basic napa cabbage kimchi from scratch. The process takes about 2 hours of total hands-on time, and the kimchi will be ready to eat after 24\u201348 hours at room temperature.</p> <ul> <li>Read first: Maangchi \u2014 How to Make Kimchi \u2014 follow this recipe exactly your first time</li> <li>Also useful: BBC Good Food \u2014 Kimchi for a second perspective on timing and ratios</li> <li>Technique key: The cabbage must be properly salted and rinsed before the paste goes on. Under-salted cabbage will be mushy. Over-rinsed paste will be bland. The goal: leaves that are limp but still have some backbone, and a paste that coats evenly.</li> <li>The fermentation: Pack the kimchi tightly into a jar, leaving 2 inches of headspace (it will expand). Leave at room temperature for 24\u201348 hours; taste after 24 and refrigerate when it has a pleasantly sour, tangy quality.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Tonight is a light kimchi-making session \u2014 pair with store-bought japchae or bibimbap, or simple rice and whatever you have. The kimchi is the project, not the meal.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to make kimchi \u2014 Maangchi \u2014 Maangchi's video is simply the best tutorial available in English. Watch it in full before starting.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#session-2-japchae-glass-noodles-vegetables-and-technique","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Japchae: Glass Noodles, Vegetables, and Technique","text":"<p>Skill: Japchae is a celebratory Korean noodle dish \u2014 stir-fried dangmyeon (sweet potato glass noodles) with vegetables, beef, and sesame. The technique is component cooking: each element is cooked separately to its ideal texture, then combined at the end. This is mise en place as architecture, not just organization.</p> <ul> <li>Read first: Serious Eats \u2014 Japchae \u2014 the SE version is excellent and follows the correct technique</li> <li>Also see: Maangchi \u2014 Japchae for the more traditional approach</li> <li>Technique key: The noodles must be tossed in sesame oil immediately after cooking to prevent sticking. The vegetables must each be cooked separately (spinach takes 30 seconds; mushrooms Take 3 minutes; beef takes 4 minutes) and then assembled. Combining them prematurely ruins every component.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Japchae as the main dish + short grain rice + your fresh kimchi from Session 1 (taste it \u2014 see what 24 hours has done)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Maangchi \u2014 Japchae \u2014 Watch how she manages the heat for each component separately and assemble only at the very end. Component cooking is the lesson.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#session-3-doenjang-jjigae-the-everyday-soup","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Doenjang Jjigae: The Everyday Soup","text":"<p>Skill: Doenjang jjigae (fermented soybean paste soup) is to Korea what miso soup is to Japan \u2014 but deeper, more pungent, more complex. It's an everyday soup that uses doenjang as the primary seasoning, with vegetables, tofu, and sometimes meat or seafood. The key technique: the paste goes in early (not last) so it can bloom in fat and stock.</p> <ul> <li>Read first: Maangchi \u2014 Doenjang Jjigae \u2014 this is the definitive home version</li> <li>Technique key: Saut\u00e9 the doenjang briefly in a tiny bit of oil before adding the anchovy stock. This blooms the fermented paste, softening its raw funkiness. The tofu goes in last \u2014 it only needs 5 minutes. Over-cooking tofu in soups makes it rubbery.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Doenjang jjigae + steamed short grain rice + any remaining kimchi + banchan (any small vegetable side \u2014 spinach blanched with sesame oil and garlic, or cucumber in gochugaru)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Doenjang Jjigae \u2014 Korean Fermented Soybean Paste Stew \u2014 Watch when the paste goes in and how the stock is built from anchovies and kombu. The base stock technique is foundational Korean cooking.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#session-4-tteokbokki-spicy-rice-cakes","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Tteokbokki: Spicy Rice Cakes","text":"<p>Skill: Tteokbokki (spicy stir-fried rice cakes) is one of the most popular Korean street foods \u2014 soft, chewy tteok (rice cakes) cooked in a sweet-spicy gochujang sauce. The technique is straightforward but the sauce balance is the skill: gochujang, sugar, soy and anchovy stock must be in perfect proportion. Too sweet and it's candy; too spicy and you can't taste the rice cakes.</p> <ul> <li>Read first: Maangchi \u2014 Tteokbokki \u2014 follow the sauce ratios exactly your first time</li> <li>Ingredient note: Frozen or refrigerated tteok (cylindrical rice cakes) can be found at any Korean grocery. If you can't find them, substitute any thick, chewy Asian rice cake.</li> <li>Technique key: Start with cold tteok in cold sauce and bring everything up together. If you add them to hot sauce they'll seize on the outside and stay hard inside.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Tteokbokki + steamed eggs (gyeran-jjim, silky steamed egg custard in a stone pot) + rice + kimchi</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Tteokbokki \u2014 Maangchi \u2014 Watch the sauce progression as it reduces and thickens. The gochujang deepens in color as it cooks \u2014 that's what you're aiming for.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#session-5-project-korean-barbecue-night","title":"\u23f0 Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Korean Barbecue Night","text":"<p>The challenge: A full Korean barbecue table at home. Marinate everything the night before. Cook tableside (grill pan or tabletop grill) or sear in a cast iron skillet with very high heat.</p> <p>The spread:</p> Dish Recipe Notes Bulgogi (marinated beef) Maangchi \u2014 Bulgogi Marinate 4+ hrs; cook in thin slices, very hot pan Galbi (short ribs) Maangchi \u2014 Galbi Marinate 24 hrs; flanken-cut short ribs Kimchi Your kimchi from Session 1 Taste it \u2014 4 days of fermentation is significant Steamed rice Short grain, done properly The anchor of the table Ssam board Lettuce leaves, garlic, gochujang, perilla For wrapping meat Congee/porridge (optional) Simple anchovy broth rice Light closer if people want it <p>Skill targets: Both proteins marinated at least 4 hours (24 for galbi). Grill pan screaming hot before any meat goes on. All banchan ready before cooking the proteins.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#block-38-depth-fried-simmered-and-composed","title":"Block 38 \u2014 Depth: Fried, Simmered, and Composed","text":""},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#session-6-bibimbap-the-composed-bowl","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Bibimbap: The Composed Bowl","text":"<p>Skill: Bibimbap (mixed rice and vegetable bowl) is one of Korea's most famous dishes \u2014 a composed bowl of steamed rice, seasoned vegetables (namul), a fried egg, and gochujang, mixed together at the table. The skill is in the namul: each vegetable is prepared separately, each with its own seasoning, then arranged artfully on the rice before serving. Variety, technique, and visual presentation all matter.</p> <ul> <li>Read first: Maangchi \u2014 Bibimbap \u2014 detailed namul preparation for each vegetable</li> <li>Also see: BBC Good Food \u2014 Bibimbap for a simpler version if you're short on time</li> <li>Technique key: Each namul is different: blanched spinach gets sesame oil and garlic; bean sprouts get the same; saut\u00e9ed zucchini gets gochugaru; mushrooms get soy and sesame. The variety of seasoning within a simple framework is what makes bibimbap special.</li> <li>The egg: Fried, runny yolk. The yolk is the sauce. It's not negotiable.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Bibimbap is the complete meal \u2014 rice, vegetables, protein (if adding beef or tofu), egg, and gochujang at the table to mix with.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Bibimbap \u2014 Maangchi \u2014 Watch her namul preparation sequence. The order of vegetables and the specific seasoning for each one is the lesson.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#session-7-korean-fried-chicken-the-science-of-the-crisp","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Korean Fried Chicken: The Science of the Crisp","text":"<p>Skill: Korean fried chicken is distinguished from American fried chicken by three things: a double-fry technique (first fry at lower temp to cook through; second fry at high temp to super-crisp the skin), thinner batter (potato starch + a small amount of flour, no thick breading), and the lacquered sauce applied after the second fry. The result is extraordinarily crispy.</p> <ul> <li>Read first: Serious Eats \u2014 Korean Fried Chicken \u2014 the double-fry method explained</li> <li>Also see: Maangchi \u2014 Dakgangjeong (Crispy Korean Fried Chicken) \u2014 a soy-garlic style with sticky glaze</li> <li>Technique key: The first fry (325\u00b0F for 12\u201315 minutes) cooks the chicken through. The second fry (375\u00b0F for 3\u20135 minutes) drives off remaining moisture in the skin and creates the characteristic shatter. Skipping the second fry makes fine fried chicken \u2014 it just isn't Korean fried chicken.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Korean fried chicken (half plain, half glazed with yangnyeom sauce) + pickled daikon + steamed rice</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Korean Fried Chicken \u2014 Maangchi \u2014 Watch the double-fry temperatures and timing. The first and second fry serve completely different purposes \u2014 make sure you understand both before your first attempt.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#session-8-pajeon-korean-savory-pancakes","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Pajeon: Korean Savory Pancakes","text":"<p>Skill: Pajeon (scallion pancakes) exemplify the Korean approach to quick, satisfying everyday cooking. The batter is simple \u2014 flour, water, egg, and salt \u2014 but the technique matters enormously. The pan must be well-oiled and hot so the outside crisps immediately. And the toppings (scallions, seafood, kimchi) must be folded in gently, not mixed to death, so they hold their texture.</p> <ul> <li>Read first: Maangchi \u2014 Pajeon \u2014 haemul pajeon (seafood style) or basic scallion</li> <li>Technique key: All in one pan, medium-high heat, enough oil to shallow-fry the edges. Press the pancake flat with a spatula after pouring. Flip only once. The bottom should be deeply golden and crispy \u2014 pale pajeon isn't right.</li> <li>Dipping sauce: soy sauce + rice vinegar + sesame oil + gochugaru + scallion. Equal parts soy and vinegar, everything else to taste.</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Pajeon + dipping sauce + doenjang jjigae (quick version \u2014 20-minute soup) + rice</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Pajeon \u2014 Korean Scallion Pancake \u2014 Watch the oil quantity and the pan temperature. Korean pancakes need more oil than you'd expect \u2014 they're closer to a shallow-fry than a dry saut\u00e9.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#session-9-galbi-jjim-braised-short-ribs","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Galbi-Jjim: Braised Short Ribs","text":"<p>Skill: Galbi-jjim is the Korean-style braised short rib \u2014 the same cut as your galbi from Session 5, but thoroughly braised rather than quickly grilled. The sauce is soy-based rather than gochujang-based, with Asian pear or apple for tenderizing enzymes and deep sweetness. The results are glossy, deeply flavored, and profoundly satisfying.</p> <ul> <li>Technique: Blanch the ribs briefly in boiling water first (this removes blood and impurities and produces a cleaner, clearer braising liquid). Then braise in the soy-based sauce with garlic, ginger, Asian pear, and vegetables for 1.5\u20132 hours. The sauce should reduce to a thick, glossy coating in the last 20 minutes (uncover and increase heat).</li> <li>Reference: Maangchi \u2014 Galbi-Jjim \u2014 Korean braised short ribs</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: Galbi-jjim + steamed short grain rice + saut\u00e9ed spinach banchan (blanched, seasoned with sesame oil and garlic) + kimchi</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Korean Braised Short Ribs (Galbi-Jjim) \u2014 The pre-blanching step distinguishes Korean braising from French braising \u2014 it's not about fond development, it's about clarity.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#session-10-project-a-korean-dinner-party","title":"\u23f0 Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: A Korean Dinner Party","text":"<p>The challenge: Cook a full Korean dinner for guests. Every dish must be planned, prepped, and timed. The goal is a table where everything arrives together \u2014 not a procession of dishes with 10-minute gaps.</p> <p>The menu:</p> Course Dish Link Timing Welcome Makgeolli (Korean rice wine) or cold beer \u2014 Have it waiting Banchan Kimchi (yours), cucumber kimchi, spinach namul Various Make in advance Soup Doenjang jjigae Maangchi Make 30 mins before Main 1 Galbi-jjim (braised short ribs) Maangchi Start 3 hrs before service Main 2 Pajeon (seafood pancakes) Maangchi Cook to order, right before serving Rice Short grain, perfectly cooked \u2014 Time to finish with the mains Dessert Bingsu (Korean shaved ice) Maangchi \u2014 Patbingsu Assemble at the table <p>Skill targets: Banchan ready before guests arrive. Both mains plated at the same time. Doenjang jjigae served hot. Bingsu assembled at the table \u2014 it's theatrical and delicious.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#the-korean-pantry-fermentation-as-foundation","title":"The Korean Pantry: Fermentation as Foundation","text":"<p>Korean cooking's depth comes from fermented ingredients. Gochujang, doenjang, and kimchi aren't just condiments \u2014 they're the flavor infrastructure.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 Gochujang, Explained \u2014 what it is, how it's different from other chili pastes, and how to use it beyond the obvious</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 What is Doenjang? \u2014 the sister fermented paste to gochujang, and why it's more versatile than it looks</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#korean-barbecue-beyond-the-restaurant","title":"Korean Barbecue: Beyond the Restaurant","text":"<p>The Korean BBQ table at home is one of the most social, interactive meals you can cook.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Maangchi \u2014 Bulgogi \u2014 the canonical marinade explained in full, with the specific pear or kiwi enzyme tenderizing step that makes a difference</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 BBC Good Food \u2014 Bulgogi \u2014 a slightly simplified version for weeknight cooking</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Maangchi's YouTube Channel \u2014 Maangchi is the most trusted Korean cooking teacher on the internet. Her channel has every dish from this block; watch any video before you cook the dish.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Korean Home Cooking by Sohui Kim \u2014 The most comprehensive Korean cooking book for the home cook. Goes deep on banchan, fermentation, and the logic of the Korean table.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcda Koreatown by Deuki Hong &amp; Matt Rodbard \u2014 Korean-American cooking, with equal depth on technique and culture. The restaurant profiles add useful context.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 35\u201336: Japanese Cuisine | Block 39\u201340: Chinese \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/quick-ref.html","title":"\u26a1 Block 33\u201334 Quick Reference \u2014 Korean Cuisine","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/quick-ref.html#block-33-recipes-foundations-fermentation-and-fire","title":"Block 33 Recipes \u2014 Foundations: Fermentation and Fire","text":"Session Dish Skill Links Session 1 \u23f0 Kimchi (Baechu-Kimchi) Salting; gochugaru paste; fermentation 24\u201348 hrs before eating Kimchi \u2014 Maangchi Session 2 Japchae (Glass Noodle Stir-Fry) Component cooking; each veg separately; sesame oil finishing Japchae \u2014 Maangchi \u00b7 SE Session 3 Doenjang Jjigae (Fermented Soybean Paste Soup) Bloom paste in oil first; anchovy stock base; tofu timing Doenjang Jjigae \u2014 Maangchi Session 4 Tteokbokki (Spicy Rice Cakes) Cold tteok into cold sauce; gochujang-sugar-soy balance Tteokbokki \u2014 Maangchi Session 5 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Korean Barbecue Night Marinate ahead; screaming-hot grill; ssam board assembly Bulgogi \u00b7 Galbi"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/quick-ref.html#block-34-recipes-fried-simmered-composed","title":"Block 34 Recipes \u2014 Fried, Simmered &amp; Composed","text":"Session Dish Skill Links Session 6 Bibimbap (Mixed Rice Bowl) Namul preparation; different seasoning per veg; runny-yolk egg Bibimbap \u2014 Maangchi Session 7 Korean Fried Chicken (Dakgangjeong) Double-fry 325\u00b0F then 375\u00b0F; thin potato-starch batter; lacquer sauce KFC \u2014 SE \u00b7 Maangchi Session 8 Pajeon (Savory Pancakes) Plenty of oil; medium-high heat; press flat; flip once Pajeon \u2014 Maangchi Session 9 \u23f0 Galbi-Jjim (Braised Short Ribs) Pre-blanch ribs for clarity; soy-based braise; reduce to glossy Galbi-Jjim \u2014 Maangchi Session 10 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Korean Dinner Party Full table; banchan ready before guests; all dishes timed Patbingsu \u2014 Maangchi"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/quick-ref.html#the-korean-pantry-at-a-glance","title":"The Korean Pantry \u2014 At a Glance","text":"Ingredient Use Note Gochujang Tteokbokki, yangnyeom sauce, marinades Fermented chili paste; spicy + sweet + umami Doenjang Jjigae; finishing soups Stronger and funkier than Japanese miso Gochugaru Kimchi, banchan, dipping sauces Coarse red flakes; different from cayenne Sesame oil (toasted) Finishing oil on almost every dish Never cook with it; add at the end Fish sauce Kimchi, soups Background depth; add sparingly Soy sauce (ganjang) Marinades, braises, dipping sauces Korean soy is slightly lighter than Japanese Rice vinegar Dipping sauces, quick pickles Mild acid Asian pear or kiwi Bulgogi / galbi marinades Enzyme tenderiser; grate into marinade"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/quick-ref.html#fermentation-timing-reference","title":"Fermentation Timing Reference","text":"Product Time Signal Kimchi (room temp) 1\u20132 days Pleasantly sour, fizzy, tangy \u2014 then refrigerate Kimchi (fridge) Weeks\u2013months Gets more complex; use differently at each stage"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/quick-ref.html#kfc-double-fry-reference","title":"KFC Double-Fry Reference","text":"Fry Temp Time Purpose First fry 325\u00b0F 12\u201315 min Cook through; set the batter Rest Room temp 5 min Steam escapes; batter firms Second fry 375\u00b0F 3\u20135 min Drive off moisture; create shatter <p>Navigation: \u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 33\u201334: Korean Cuisine","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Where to shop: Most Korean pantry staples require a Korean or Asian grocery store (H Mart is ideal). Gochujang, doenjang, gochugaru, dangmyeon (glass noodles), tteok (rice cakes), and sesame oil in the quantities you need are rarely available at standard supermarkets. Shop the pantry section first, before you buy proteins.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Wok or large stainless skillet \u2014 japchae, tteokbokki, stir-fried banchan</li> <li>[ ] Stone pot (dolsot) \u2014 ideal for bibimbap; a heavy skillet works as substitute</li> <li>[ ] Large Dutch oven or heavy pot \u2014 galbi-jjim (braised short ribs)</li> <li>[ ] Grill pan or cast iron \u2014 Korean BBQ session; tabletop grill is optional</li> <li>[ ] Candy/frying thermometer \u2014 Korean fried chicken (must hit 325\u00b0F then 375\u00b0F)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/shopping-list.html#proteins-block-33","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Block 33","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Thin-sliced beef rib eye or sirloin \u2014 \u00bd lb (Session 2 japchae). Ask the Asian grocery to slice thin, or freeze briefly and slice yourself.</li> <li>[ ] Flanken-cut short ribs \u2014 2 lbs (Session 5 PROJECT galbi). Flanken = cut across the bones showing 3 bones per slice. Order from butcher if your market doesn't stock flanken.</li> <li>[ ] Beef sirloin or rib eye (whole) \u2014 1 lb (Session 5 PROJECT bulgogi). Slice very thin yourself from partially frozen meat.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/shopping-list.html#proteins-block-34","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Block 34","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Chicken thighs and drumsticks \u2014 3 lbs (Session 7 Korean fried chicken)</li> <li>[ ] Scallions \u2014 3 large bunches (Session 8 pajeon; also banchan)</li> <li>[ ] Flanken or bone-in short ribs \u2014 3\u20134 lbs (Session 9 galbi-jjim braised short ribs)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/shopping-list.html#vegetables-produce","title":"\ud83e\udd6c Vegetables &amp; Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Napa cabbage \u2014 1 large head (Session 1 kimchi)</li> <li>[ ] Daikon radish \u2014 1 medium (kimchi and pickled daikon banchan)</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 2\u20133 (kimchi and banchan)</li> <li>[ ] Spinach \u2014 2 bags (blanched spinach banchan, multiple sessions)</li> <li>[ ] Bean sprouts \u2014 1 bag (bibimbap namul, Session 6)</li> <li>[ ] Zucchini \u2014 2 (bibimbap namul)</li> <li>[ ] Shiitake mushrooms \u2014 8 oz dried or fresh (japchae, bibimbap)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 large heads</li> <li>[ ] Ginger \u2014 small knob</li> <li>[ ] Scallions / green onions \u2014 3 bunches (throughout)</li> <li>[ ] Asian pear or kiwi \u2014 1 (enzyme tenderiser for galbi and bulgogi marinades)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumber \u2014 1\u20132 (banchan, pickled side)</li> <li>[ ] Lettuce leaves \u2014 ssam (wrapping leaves for BBQ session)</li> <li>[ ] Perilla / shiso leaves \u2014 ssam board (optional but authentic)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/shopping-list.html#pantry-korean-staples-buy-all-before-starting","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry (Korean Staples \u2014 Buy All Before Starting)","text":"<p>Most of these keep for months or years. This is a one-time investment that covers many blocks.</p> Item Needed for Notes Gochujang (large tub) Tteokbokki, BBQ, fried chicken sauce Store in fridge after opening Doenjang (tub) Session 3 jjigae Not the same as Japanese miso \u2014 don't substitute Gochugaru (bag) Kimchi, banchan, dipping sauces Coarse flakes; medium heat Sesame oil (toasted) Every dish Finishing oil only; don't heat Soy sauce Marinades, jjigae Korean ganjang or Japanese dark Fish sauce Kimchi, jjigae Thai or Vietnamese fish sauce works Rice vinegar Dipping sauces, pickles Mirin Marinades Dangmyeon (sweet potato glass noodles) Session 2 japchae Soak before cooking Cylindrical tteok (rice cakes) Session 4 tteokbokki Frozen or refrigerated; Korean grocery Firm tofu Session 3 jjigae Press and cube Dried anchovies (myeolchi) Anchovy stock for jjigae Small silver ones Kombu Anchovy stock Dashi kombu works Short-grain white rice Every session Korean or Japanese variety Potato starch Session 7 KFC batter Shatteringly crispy coating Sesame seeds Garnish throughout Keep sealed; go rancid quickly once open"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/37-38-korean/shopping-list.html#drinks-dessert-optional","title":"\ud83c\udf77 Drinks &amp; Dessert (Optional)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Makgeolli (Korean rice wine) \u2014 welcome drink for BBQ session (Korean grocery)</li> <li>[ ] Soju \u2014 optional BBQ pairing</li> <li>[ ] Patbingsu supplies for Session 10 dessert: sweet red bean paste (tinned), condensed milk, fresh fruit</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html","title":"\ud83e\udd62 Block 39\u201340: Chinese Cuisine","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 37\u201338: Korean Cuisine | Block 41\u201342: Mexican Cuisine \u2192</p> <p>\"Chinese cooking is a philosophy of heat and time \u2014 of wok hei, the 'breath of the wok,' and of the patience to braise until the fat has melted into something transformed. Getting either right requires understanding the logic, not just following steps.\"</p> <p>Quick Reference: \u2192 Week 35\u201336 Recipe Quick Ref</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#before-you-start-block-39","title":"Before You Start Block 39","text":"<p>Chinese cuisine is the most codified and internally diverse cooking tradition in the world. The CIA teaches it because it contains techniques that have no Western analogue \u2014 wok hei (breath of the wok, achieved through intensely high heat), red-braising (hong shao rou, using soy and sugar to create a lacquer-like glaze), and the specific knife and cutting logic that underlies stir-fry.</p> <p>Two weeks is a narrow aperture. The goal is not representativeness \u2014 it is fluency in the techniques that are transferable to everything else you cook.</p> <p>What you're learning: - Wok technique and wok hei \u2014 what it is, why it requires a specific kind of heat, and how to approximate it at home - Chinese aromatic base \u2014 the \"flavor trinity\" of ginger, garlic, and scallion and how it differs from the French mirepoix or Italian soffritto - Red-braising (hong shao) \u2014 soy, sugar, Shaoxing wine, and time creating one of the world's great braised-meat techniques - Steaming as primary technique \u2014 the Cantonese philosophy of subtlety and freshness - Sichuan spice logic \u2014 m\u00e1l\u00e0 (numbing heat), the combination of Sichuan peppercorns and dried chilli, and why it works</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read first: Serious Eats \u2014 How to Build a Chinese Pantry \u2014 the pantry items in Chinese cooking are unlike a Western pantry. Stock these two weeks ahead of time.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#session-0-dan-dan-noodles-optional","title":"Session 0 \u2014 Dan Dan Noodles (optional)","text":"<p>Skill: Dan dan noodles are a Sichuan street food that demonstrates the entire Sichuan flavor vocabulary in one bowl: m\u00e1l\u00e0 (numbing + heat from Sichuan peppercorn + chilli), sour (black vinegar), sweet, rich (sesame paste), savory (soy), and the crunchy textural contrast of ya cai (preserved mustard greens).</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Dan Dan Noodles</p> <p>The sauce components \u2014 build this understanding:</p> Component Flavor role Sesame paste (or tahini) Richness, body, nutty depth Light soy sauce Salt, savory baseline Black vinegar (Chinkiang) Sourness, slight smoke Chilli oil Primary heat + red color Ground Sichuan peppercorns M\u00e1l\u00e0 numbing sensation Sugar Balance against the acid and heat Chicken stock or hot water Texture, loosens the sauce <p>This sauce formula \u2014 sesame + soy + vinegar + chilli + Sichuan pepper \u2014 is the Sichuan noodle sauce template. Understanding it unlocks a dozen dishes.</p> <p>Full Meal: Dan dan noodles (a full portion, made as a dinner for yourself or two people) \u2014 nothing else needed, they're substantial</p> Component Recipe Noodles Fresh wheat noodles or dried thin lo mein; al dente Topping Spiced pork mince with ya cai (preserved mustard greens) Sauce Full Sichuan dan dan sauce (above components) Garnish Chopped roasted peanuts, scallion greens, chilli oil drizzle"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#compare-notes-making-authentic-dan-dan-noodles-at-home-chinese-cooking-demystified-covers-the-sichuan-peppercorn-toasting-and-grinding-process-which-makes-a-meaningful-difference","title":"&gt; \ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Making Authentic Dan Dan Noodles at Home (Chinese Cooking Demystified) \u2014 covers the Sichuan peppercorn toasting and grinding process, which makes a meaningful difference.","text":""},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#the-chinese-pantry","title":"The Chinese Pantry","text":"<p>Before Week 35 begins, verify you have:</p> Item What it does Soy sauce (light/regular + dark) Light for seasoning; dark for color and body Shaoxing rice wine The workhorse alcohol in Chinese cooking; not the same as sake or mirin Sesame oil (toasted) Finishing oil \u2014 not for cooking high heat Doubanjiang (Pixian brand if possible) Fermented chilli-bean paste; the base of many Sichuan dishes Oyster sauce Adds rounded savory depth to stir-fries and braises Black rice vinegar (Chinkiang/Zhenjiang) Sharp, slightly smoky fermented vinegar Sichuan peppercorns Numbing (not burning) heat; floral and citrusy Dried red chilli (tianjin or facing heaven) Heat + smokiness in Sichuan cooking Five-spice powder Star anise-led spice blend; a little goes a long way Fermented black beans Funky, salty, savory; central to Cantonese cooking Corn or potato starch Thickens sauces and velvetizes proteins"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#block-39-core-chinese-techniques","title":"Block 39 \u2014 Core Chinese Techniques","text":"<p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 2 (Hong Shao Rou): plan for a 2\u20133 hr low braise; make it early in the day or the session before \u2014 it reheats beautifully</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#session-1-the-wok-heat-motion-and-wok-hei","title":"Session 1 \u2014 The Wok: Heat, Motion, and Wok Hei","text":"<p>Skill: Wok cooking at home is a compromise because home stovetops produce roughly 7,000\u201315,000 BTUs, while restaurant wok ranges produce 150,000+ BTUs. Understanding this limits your expectations and teaches you to optimize within the constraint.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 The Wok vs. Skillet Debate (and How to Cook Properly on a Home Range)</p> <p>Seasoning your wok (if new): 1. Scrub all factory oil/coating off with steel wool under hot water 2. Heat wok over high flame until it smokes 3. Rub a thin layer of neutral oil all over interior with paper towel using tongs 4. Let cool; repeat 3\u20134 times</p> <p>The wok should be dark and slightly shiny after seasoning. After this, never wash with soap \u2014 rinse with hot water and dry on the stove over heat.</p> <p>Wok hei at home: - Heat the wok until it's smoking before adding oil - Cook in very small batches (1 portion at a time \u2014 proteins will steam if crowded) - Keep everything moving with a wok spatula (chan) - If you have a gas stove, allow some of the stir-fry flame to lick up the sides of the wok \u2014 this is the controlled wok \"toss\"</p> <p>The stir-fry formula: 1. Velvetize protein (see below) 2. Heat wok until smoking; add oil; let it shimmer 3. Add aromatics (ginger + garlic + scallion whites) for 15\u201330 seconds 4. Add protein; spread and sear; don't stir for 30 seconds 5. Add vegetables; toss 6. Add sauce; toss 30\u201360 seconds; remove from heat 7. Sesame oil + scallion greens off heat</p> <p>Velveting:</p> <p>Velveting is the technique that makes restaurant Chinese chicken silky instead of rubbery. Mix protein with egg white + cornstarch + Shaoxing wine; marinate 15 minutes. The coating creates a protective barrier during the high-heat cook.</p> <p>Full Meal: Chicken and Broccoli Stir-Fry (substitute chicken) with velveted chicken and hand-cut florets, served on white rice</p> Component Recipe Protein Chicken breast, sliced thin against grain, velveted Sauce Oyster sauce + light soy + Shaoxing wine + cornstarch slurry Aromatics Ginger + garlic + scallion Vegetable Broccoli florets, blanched 1 minute first <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: The Secrets of Wok Hei (Chinese Cooking Demystified) \u2014 The most honest YouTube breakdown of what wok hei actually is and what's achievable at home.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#session-2-red-braised-pork-belly-hong-shao-rou","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Red-Braised Pork Belly (Hong Shao Rou)","text":"<p>Skill: Red-braising (hong shao) is one of China's great braising traditions and one of the most beautiful things that happens to pork. The combination of soy sauce, Shaoxing wine, aromatics, and rock sugar creates a lacquer-dark, glossy sauce and transforms pork belly into something that nearly dissolves on the tongue. This is Chairman Mao's favorite dish. It is not subtle.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Hong Shao Rou (Red-Braised Pork Belly)</p> <p>The technique: 1. Blanch pork belly to remove blood and impurities \u2014 cold water to start, bring to boil, discard water 2. In a clean pot: caramelize rock sugar in a small amount of oil until amber 3. Add pork belly; coat in the caramelized sugar 4. Add Shaoxing wine + soy sauce (light and dark) + aromatics (ginger, scallion, star anise, cinnamon stick, dried chili) 5. Add water just to cover; bring to boil; reduce to very low simmer 6. Braise partially covered 60\u201390 minutes until a chopstick slides through the fat cap with no resistance 7. Remove pork; reduce braising liquid over high heat until thick and glossy 8. Return pork; coat in glaze</p> <p>Full Meal: Hong shao rou over steamed white rice + blanched baby bok choy with garlic</p> Component Recipe Pork 1.5 lbs skin-on pork belly, cut into 1.5-inch squares Rice Plain jasmine rice cooked in a rice cooker or pot Vegetable Baby bok choy, halved, wok-saut\u00e9ed with garlic and a splash of oyster sauce <p>The patience principle: You cannot rush hong shao rou. A properly braised piece of pork belly trembles when you move the plate. The collagen has fully converted to gelatin and the fat has rendered into the sauce. Any shortcut produces chewy, fatty pork instead of the silk it should be.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#session-3-cantonese-steamed-fish","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Cantonese Steamed Fish","text":"<p>Skill: Steaming is the central Cantonese technique and the philosophy behind it is opposite to everything in French haute cuisine. Cantonese cooking prizes freshness and the natural flavor of the ingredient above all else. A Cantonese cook would look at a French braise and say it hides the ingredient. A steamed fish shows you everything \u2014 if the fish isn't fresh, you can't hide it.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Cantonese Steamed Fish</p> <p>The technique: 1. Select the freshest whole fish possible (sea bass, branzino, or tilapia); score diagonally on both sides 2. Season the inside cavity with ginger slices and scallion 3. Set fish on a plate or rack over boiling water; cover with a tight lid 4. Steam 8\u201312 minutes depending on size \u2014 the fish is done when a chopstick inserted at the thickest point meets no resistance 5. Drain accumulated liquid from the plate 6. Pour over: julienned ginger + scallion + soy + a pinch of sugar 7. Heat oil in a small pan until smoking; immediately pour over the garnish \u2014 the sizzle finishes the scallion and ginger</p> <p>Full Meal: Steamed whole fish + steamed rice + saut\u00e9ed morning glory or Chinese broccoli (gai lan) with oyster sauce</p> Component Recipe Fish Whole branzino or sea bass (1\u20131.5 lbs); or 2 large fillets Sauce Light soy + Shaoxing wine + sesame oil + pinch of sugar Garnish Julienned ginger, scallion chiffonade, hot oil flash <p>Why it matters: Steaming a whole fish correctly is a high-stakes test of precision \u2014 timing is unforgiving. Overcooked by 2 minutes it's dry; at the right moment it's silky and self-basting. This is exactly the kind of technique that separates experienced cooks from inexperienced ones.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#session-4-mapo-tofu","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Mapo Tofu (\u9ebb\u5a46\u8c46\u8150)","text":"<p>Skill: Mapo tofu is one of the most technically interesting dishes in all of Chinese cooking. It requires managing: braising the tofu gently so it holds shape while absorbing flavors, building a complex base from doubanjiang + black bean + aromatics, achieving the proper \"flower\" texture of soft tofu, and finishing with Sichuan peppercorn oil and the \"pushing\" motion (tu\u012b d\u00f2ufu) that moves the tofu without breaking it.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 The Real Mapo Tofu</p> <p>The technique notes: - Use silken or soft tofu (not medium-firm or firm) \u2014 if it breaks a little, that's fine - Blanch tofu cubes in salted water before adding to the wok \u2014 this firms the surface slightly and seasons the interior - The doubanjiang brands matter: Pixian-style is aged and deeply savory; regular brands are brighter and saltier - The finishing step \u2014 Sichuan peppercorn oil poured over, then the tofu pushed with a circular spatula motion \u2014 is what gives the dish its characteristic wobble and distribution of heat</p> <p>Full Meal: Mapo tofu over steamed rice + simple soy-dressed cucumber salad (smashed cucumbers with black vinegar + garlic + sesame oil + chilli flake)</p> Component Recipe Tofu Soft or silken tofu, cubed, blanched Base Doubanjiang + fermented black beans + ground pork + aromatics Sauce Stock + soy + rice wine; thickened with cornstarch slurry Finish Sichuan peppercorn oil + scallion greens"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#session-5-project-sichuan-dinner","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Sichuan Dinner","text":"<p>Cook a complete Sichuan-focused dinner for two to four people. The goal is to compose a meal where the different heat/numbing levels of the dishes balance each other \u2014 Chinese meals are designed this way.</p> Dish Heat level Role on table Smashed cucumber salad Low (just chilli flake) Refreshing, palate-clearing starter Mapo tofu High m\u00e1l\u00e0 Center of the table Stir-fried green beans with garlic None Cooling, textural contrast Steamed white rice None Base and palate reset Dan dan noodles (half portion, dressed lighter) Medium A second carbohydrate"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#before-you-start-block-40","title":"Before You Start Block 40","text":""},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#session-0-kung-pao-chicken-optional","title":"Session 0 \u2014 Kung Pao Chicken (optional)","text":"<p>Skill: Kung pao chicken is one of the most technically balanced dishes in Chinese cooking. It requires: velveted chicken, a fried-peanut garnish, the dual texture of the dried chillies (the shells add smokiness, the seeds add heat), and a sauce that is simultaneously sour, sweet, salty, and a little numbing.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Kung Pao Chicken</p> <p>The sauce formula:</p> Ingredient Amount Role Black vinegar 2 tsp Sour Soy sauce 2 tbsp Salt, savory Sugar 1 tsp Sweet Sichuan peppercorn oil 1 tsp Numbing Chilli oil 1 tsp Heat Cornstarch 1 tsp Thickener Chicken stock 3 tbsp Body <p>Full Meal: Kung pao chicken over steamed rice + sliced cucumber dressed with sesame oil and white vinegar</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#block-40-northern-cantonese-and-home-cooking","title":"Block 40 \u2014 Northern, Cantonese, and Home Cooking","text":""},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#session-6-congee-rice-porridge","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Congee (Rice Porridge)","text":"<p>Skill: Congee is cooked rice broken down in a large quantity of water or stock until it becomes a thick, creamy porridge. The skill is in the ratio (1:10 or more) and the time (45 minutes minimum). It is the ultimate test of whether you can make something completely humble taste extraordinary \u2014 through good stock, proper consistency, and thoughtful toppings.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Congee (Chinese Rice Porridge)</p> <p>Full Meal: A congee bar \u2014 make a large pot of plain rice congee, and provide:</p> Topping How to prepare Century egg Nicked and sliced (an acquired taste; try it) Poached or sous vide chicken Shredded; seasoned with soy + sesame Crispy shallots Thin-sliced, fried until deep gold Pickled ginger Pre-made or store-bought White pepper Freshly ground; essential Sesame oil A few drops to finish Sliced scallions Raw, added at the last moment Fried dough (youtiao) Buy from an Asian bakery or skip"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#session-7-dim-sum-at-home-har-gow-shrimp-dumplings","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Dim Sum at Home: Har Gow (Shrimp Dumplings)","text":"<p>Skill: Dim sum at home is ambitious and humbling. Har gow \u2014 translucent steamed shrimp dumplings \u2014 have a specific wheat starch wrapper that is unlike any pasta or dumpling wrapper in Western cooking. The folding technique is its own sub-skill that takes numerous attempts.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Har Gow (Cantonese Shrimp Dumplings)</p> <p>What the dough teaches: The har gow wrapper is made from wheat starch (not all-purpose flour) + cornstarch + boiling water. The hot water gelatinizes the starches, producing the translucent, slightly chewy wrapper characteristic of this dumpling. No other dough behaves this way.</p> <p>Full Meal: Har gow (make at least 16 \u2014 the first 4 will be ugly) + char siu bao (steamed BBQ pork buns) from store-bought char siu pork or pork belly</p> <p>Honesty note: This will take 2\u20133 hours and some of the dumplings will fall apart. That is exactly the right experience. Dim sum chefs spend months learning one fold. Your goal tonight is to understand the dough behavior and make a few that work.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#session-8-chinese-egg-fried-rice","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Chinese Egg Fried Rice","text":"<p>Skill: Egg fried rice is the Chinese test of wok technique \u2014 the dish that tells you exactly where your heat management is. The keys are: cold day-old rice (never fresh; it's too wet), eggs added early so they set in the hot rice rather than scramble separately, and restraint with soy sauce (the dish should taste of rice and egg, not soy).</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 The Best Fried Rice</p> <p>Full Meal: Egg fried rice (a proper full-dinner portion) + Chinese cucumber salad + any leftover hong shao rou from earlier in the week if you made it ahead</p> <p>The egg fried rice method: 1. Wok, maximum heat, smoking before any oil 2. Oil; add cold cooked rice; stir-fry until individual grains separate and sizzle 3. Push rice to the sides; crack eggs into the center of the wok; scramble briefly 4. Incorporate rice into eggs before the eggs fully set \u2014 the rice finishes the eggs 5. Season with light soy sauce + white pepper; toss 30 seconds 6. Off heat: sesame oil + scallion greens</p> <p>Cold rice is non-negotiable. Fresh cooked rice has too much moisture and steams in the wok, producing gluey clumps. Cook rice the day before, spread on a tray to dry, and refrigerate uncovered overnight.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#session-9-hot-and-sour-soup","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Hot and Sour Soup (\u9178\u8fa3\u6c64)","text":"<p>Skill: Hot and sour soup is the Chinese umami bomb \u2014 built on a well-made pork stock (or chicken stock), with the interplay of acid (black vinegar), heat (white pepper + chilli), and texture (wood ear mushrooms, silken tofu, egg ribbons). The egg ribbon technique \u2014 pouring beaten egg in a thin stream into simmering soup while stirring \u2014 produces the characteristic feathery strands.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Serious Eats \u2014 Hot and Sour Soup</p> <p>The thickening and egg ribbon technique: 1. Cornstarch slurry added to simmering stock thickens to a loose, viscous consistency 2. Egg: beat until uniform; hold over the pot; pour in a thin stream while stirring the soup in a circular motion with the other hand 3. The motion creates ribbons rather than clumps \u2014 the circular current spreads the egg before it sets</p> <p>Full Meal: Hot and sour soup as a complete dinner (it's substantial) + steamed white rice if needed + scallion pancakes (store-bought or make your own)</p> Component Recipe Stock Pork or chicken stock \u2014 good homemade makes this sing Mushrooms Reconstituted dried wood ear + shiitake Proteins Silken tofu cubes + thin pork strips Thickener Cornstarch slurry \u2014 add gradually until soup coats a spoon Acid + heat Black vinegar + white pepper \u2014 both added OFF heat to preserve sharpness"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#session-10-project-full-chinese-banquet-for-46","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Full Chinese Banquet (for 4\u20136)","text":"<p>The traditional Chinese dinner table presents everything at once \u2014 multiple dishes, a soup, rice. The guest serves themselves from shared platters. Cook a full banquet-style dinner:</p> Dish Why it's on the menu Celery root and cucumber appetizer Light opener; no cooking Hot and sour soup Starter; the egg ribbon technique on display Steamed whole fish Cantonese technique; freshness as the statement Hong shao rou Red-braised pork; make it early in the block, reheat and it's even better Stir-fried bok choy with garlic Fast, green, balancing the rich dishes Steamed jasmine rice Cook double the amount <p>Total cook time if hong shao rou made ahead: approximately 90 minutes active.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#checkpoint-what-you-can-now-do","title":"Checkpoint: What You Can Now Do","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Season and maintain a wok</li> <li>[ ] Velvetize protein for silky stir-fry</li> <li>[ ] Braise pork belly in the hong shao red-braise method</li> <li>[ ] Steam a whole fish to exactly done</li> <li>[ ] Build and taste-balance a Sichuan sauce (sesame + soy + vinegar + m\u00e1l\u00e0 spice)</li> <li>[ ] Make egg fried rice with proper wok technique</li> <li>[ ] Cook congee to the right consistency</li> <li>[ ] Make egg ribbons in hot and sour soup</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Serious Eats \u2014 The Chinese Cooking Primer \u2014 a comprehensive technique reference</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Sichuan Peppercorn Reference \u2014 the science of m\u00e1l\u00e0</li> <li>\ud83c\udfa5 Chinese Cooking Demystified (YouTube) \u2014 the best English-language YouTube channel for authentic Chinese technique, bar none</li> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Wok by J. Kenji L\u00f3pez-Alt \u2014 the definitive English-language treatment of wok cooking; reads like an engineering manual and a recipe book simultaneously</li> <li>\ud83d\udcda Land of Fish and Rice by Fuchsia Dunlop \u2014 Dunlop is the best Western writer on Chinese food; this volume covers Jiangnan (Shanghai region) cuisine with deep historical context</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/quick-ref.html","title":"Block 39\u201340 Quick Reference \u2014 Chinese Cuisine","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Block 35\u201336 Guide</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/quick-ref.html#core-techniques-at-a-glance","title":"Core Techniques at a Glance","text":"Technique What it produces Key rule Stir-fry (wok) Crisp-tender vegetables, silky protein Smoking hot wok; small batches; keep moving Velveting Silky, tender chicken or beef Egg white + cornstarch + Shaoxing wine; 15-min marinade Red-braising (hong shao) Dark, lacquered, meltingly tender pork Blanch first; caramelize sugar; low low heat; long time Cantonese steaming Delicate, fresh-flavored fish Tight lid; boiling water beneath; sizzling oil finish Egg fried rice Separated, slightly smoky grains Cold day-old rice only; eggs before they fully set Egg ribbons Feathery egg strands in soup Thin stream + circular stirring motion Cornstarch thickening Glossy, coating sauce Mix cold water 1:1 with starch; add to simmering liquid gradually Congee Silky, broken-down rice porridge 1 cup rice : 10\u201312 cups liquid; low simmer 45+ minutes"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/quick-ref.html#velveting-protocol","title":"Velveting Protocol","text":"<ol> <li>Slice protein thin, against the grain (chicken breast, beef, pork)</li> <li>Toss with: 1 egg white + 1 tbsp cornstarch + 1 tsp Shaoxing wine + pinch of salt</li> <li>Let sit 15\u201330 minutes at room temperature (or refrigerate up to 2 hours)</li> <li>Add to wok when the wok is properly hot \u2014 the coating protects the protein</li> </ol>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/quick-ref.html#hong-shao-rou-red-braise-process-summary","title":"Hong Shao Rou (Red Braise) \u2014 Process Summary","text":"Step Detail 1. Blanch Cold water \u2192 boil; discard water; rinse pork 2. Caramelize sugar Rock sugar in neutral oil over medium; swirl to amber 3. Coat pork Add pork; toss in caramel until coated 4. Add liquids Shaoxing wine + light soy + dark soy + aromatics + water to cover 5. Braise Simmer VERY low, partially covered, 60\u201390 min 6. Reduce Remove pork; boil liquid until thick and glossy 7. Return + coat Pork back in; toss to glaze"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/quick-ref.html#sichuan-flavor-components","title":"Sichuan Flavor Components","text":"Component Flavor role Can't substitute Doubanjiang Fermented chilli-bean heat, umami depth Use Pixian brand ideally Sichuan peppercorns Numbing (m\u00e1l\u00e0) sensation; floral, citrus No substitute Chinkiang black vinegar Sharp, smoky sourness Balsamic is NOT a substitute Chilli oil Heat + color + aroma Make or buy; not plain vegetable oil Ya cai Fermented mustard greens; crunch Tianjin preserved vegetable or skip"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/quick-ref.html#the-stir-fry-order-of-operations","title":"The Stir-Fry Order of Operations","text":"<ol> <li>Mise en place first \u2014 stir-fry happens in 4\u20136 minutes; prep everything before the wok heats</li> <li>Heat wok until smoking</li> <li>Add oil; swirl to coat</li> <li>Aromatics (ginger + garlic + scallion whites) \u2014 15\u201330 sec</li> <li>Protein \u2014 spread; sear 30 sec; toss; cook until just done; remove</li> <li>Vegetables \u2014 highest volume first; toss 1\u20132 min</li> <li>Sauce \u2014 pour in around the edges; let it sizzle; toss to coat</li> <li>Return protein</li> <li>Off heat: sesame oil + scallion greens</li> </ol>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/quick-ref.html#congee-ratios","title":"Congee Ratios","text":"Rice Liquid Time Result 1 cup 10 cups 45 min Thick, creamy 1 cup 12 cups 60 min Very silky/thin <ul> <li>Use day-before rice or raw rice (raw = creamier; cook raw from the start)</li> <li>For depth: use chicken or pork stock instead of plain water</li> <li>Stir occasionally to prevent sticking; low simmer throughout</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/quick-ref.html#the-dan-dan-sauce-formula","title":"The Dan Dan Sauce Formula","text":"Ingredient Amount (for 2 servings) Sesame paste or tahini 3 tbsp Light soy sauce 2 tbsp Chinkiang black vinegar 1 tbsp Chilli oil 1\u20132 tbsp (to taste) Ground Sichuan peppercorns \u00bd tsp Sugar 1 tsp Toasted sesame oil 1 tsp Hot stock or water 4\u20136 tbsp (adjust to texture) <p>Mix thoroughly; taste; adjust heat/sour/sweet. Spoon over noodles.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/quick-ref.html#steamed-fish-timing-guide","title":"Steamed Fish \u2014 Timing Guide","text":"Fish Weight Steam time Whole branzino 1 lb 8\u20139 min Whole sea bass 1.5 lb 11\u201313 min Sea bass fillets (thick) 6 oz 6\u20137 min Whole red snapper 2 lb 14\u201316 min <p>Done when: Chopstick slides through thickest part with zero resistance. Eyes should be opaque and protruding.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/quick-ref.html#block-3536-session-summary","title":"Block 35\u201336 Session Summary","text":"Session Dish Technique Session 1 Chicken and broccoli stir-fry Wok + velveting Session 2 \u23f0 Hong shao rou (red-braised pork belly) Red braise Session 3 Cantonese steamed whole fish Steaming Session 4 Mapo tofu Doubanjiang base + soft tofu Session 5 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Sichuan dinner party Multi-technique Session 6 Congee (rice porridge) Long simmer Session 7 Har gow + char siu bao Dim sum dough + steaming Session 8 Egg fried rice Wok + egg integration Session 9 Hot and sour soup Egg ribbon + thickening Session 10 \ud83d\udd28 PROJECT: Full Chinese banquet Multi-dish timing"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/shopping-list.html","title":"Block 39\u201340 Shopping List \u2014 Chinese Cuisine","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Block 35\u201336 Guide</p> <p>Specialty shopping note: Chinese pantry staples (doubanjiang, Shaoxing wine, Chinkiang vinegar, wheat starch, ya cai, etc.) will not be found at a mainstream grocery store. Shop at your nearest Asian supermarket (99 Ranch, H Mart, Mitsuwa, or any Chinese/Pan-Asian grocery) at least one week ahead. Once purchased, most of these items last months.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/shopping-list.html#pantry-staples-to-stock-ahead","title":"\ud83e\uded9 Pantry Staples to Stock Ahead","text":"<p>These are permanent pantry additions \u2014 not single-use items. Buy once, use throughout the remaining weeks.</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Light soy sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Pearl River Bridge or Lee Kum Kee recommended)</li> <li>[ ] Dark soy sauce \u2014 1 bottle (smaller; used in small amounts for color)</li> <li>[ ] Shaoxing rice wine \u2014 1 bottle (not \"cooking wine\" with salt added; find the real thing)</li> <li>[ ] Chinkiang black vinegar (\u9547\u6c5f\u9999\u918b) \u2014 1 bottle</li> <li>[ ] Doubanjiang \u2014 1 jar (Pixian brand if possible; found in Asian grocery stores)</li> <li>[ ] Oyster sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Lee Kum Kee panda label or similar)</li> <li>[ ] Toasted sesame oil \u2014 1 small bottle (finishing only; not cooking)</li> <li>[ ] Fermented black beans (douchi) \u2014 1 small bag or jar</li> <li>[ ] Sichuan peppercorns \u2014 1 small bag (buy fresh; they lose numbness over time)</li> <li>[ ] Chinese sesame paste (\u82b9\u9ebb\u9171) \u2014 1 small jar (dan dan noodles; not the same as tahini but tahini works as a substitute)</li> <li>[ ] Dried tianjin chillies or facing heaven chillies \u2014 1 bag</li> <li>[ ] Five-spice powder \u2014 1 small jar</li> <li>[ ] Rock sugar (\u51b0\u7cd6) \u2014 1 small package (for hong shao rou \u2014 can sub with brown sugar if needed)</li> <li>[ ] Star anise \u2014 6 whole pods (hong shao rou braising \u2014 whole pods required; five-spice is not a substitute)</li> <li>[ ] Cinnamon sticks \u2014 2 sticks (hong shao rou braising)</li> <li>[ ] Cornstarch \u2014 1 box (if you don't have it already)</li> <li>[ ] Chilli oil \u2014 1 jar (Lao Gan Ma or your homemade from Block 1\u20132 chilli oil)</li> <li>[ ] Ya cai (Yibin preserved vegetables) \u2014 1 small packet (for dan dan; optional but authentic)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/shopping-list.html#proteins","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Skin-on pork belly \u2014 2 lbs (hong shao rou, Block 35; buy extra \u2014 it's better the next day)</li> <li>[ ] Ground pork \u2014 1 lb (dan dan noodles + mapo tofu + hot and sour soup)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken breast or thigh \u2014 2 lbs (stir-fry + kung pao; thigh preferred for flavor)</li> <li>[ ] Whole branzino or sea bass \u2014 1 fish, 1\u20131.5 lbs (steamed fish, Block 35; pick the freshest one)</li> <li>[ ] Shrimp \u2014 1 lb, peeled and deveined (har gow, Block 36)</li> <li>[ ] Pork loin, thin-sliced \u2014 \u00bd lb (hot and sour soup strips)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd6c Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Broccoli \u2014 1 large head (stir-fry Block 35)</li> <li>[ ] Baby bok choy \u2014 2 bunches (steamed fish side + banquet satay)</li> <li>[ ] Soft or silken tofu \u2014 2 packages (mapo tofu + hot and sour soup)</li> <li>[ ] Ginger \u2014 1 large hand (used in everything; buy more than you think)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 2 heads</li> <li>[ ] Scallions \u2014 3 bunches (used daily)</li> <li>[ ] Chinese broccoli (gai lan) \u2014 1 bunch (Block 35 side or banquet)</li> <li>[ ] Celery \u2014 2 stalks (hot and sour soup)</li> <li>[ ] Long hot green peppers or Anaheim peppers \u2014 4 (kung pao)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumbers \u2014 3 (smashed cucumber salad; side dishes)</li> <li>[ ] Morning glory or Chinese water spinach \u2014 1 bunch (if available; use regular spinach if not)</li> <li>[ ] Green beans \u2014 1 lb (Sichuan dry-fried green beans; a classic of the Sichuan dinner night)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/shopping-list.html#dried-goods-mushrooms","title":"\ud83c\udf44 Dried Goods / Mushrooms","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dried wood ear mushrooms \u2014 1 small bag (hot and sour soup)</li> <li>[ ] Dried shiitake mushrooms \u2014 1 bag (hot and sour soup + congee toppings)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh oyster or king oyster mushrooms \u2014 \u00bd lb (banquet side optional)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/shopping-list.html#noodles-rice","title":"\ud83c\udf5c Noodles &amp; Rice","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Jasmine rice \u2014 5 lbs (used every day; cook extra night before for fried rice)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh wheat noodles or lo mein \u2014 1 lb (dan dan noodles; dried thin noodles work too)</li> <li>[ ] Wheat starch (\u6f84\u7c89, NOT wheat flour) \u2014 200g (har gow wrappers; found at Asian grocery only)</li> <li>[ ] Scallion pancakes \u2014 1 package frozen (if making them from scratch, flour + water + scallions)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/shopping-list.html#dairy-eggs","title":"\ud83e\udd5a Dairy &amp; Eggs","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (egg fried rice + har gow + hot and sour soup egg ribbons; velveting)</li> <li>[ ] Note: no dairy in this block besides eggs</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/shopping-list.html#for-char-siu-bbq-pork-for-bao","title":"\ud83c\udf56 For Char Siu (BBQ Pork for Bao)","text":"<p>Two options: 1. Buy char siu ready-made from a Chinese BBQ shop (the simplest and most authentic option) 2. Make your own: Pork shoulder or pork butt (1 lb) + hoisin + soy + honey + five-spice \u2192 recipe on index.md</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Pre-made char siu OR 1 lb pork shoulder + hoisin + honey (store-bought bao shells are also acceptable)</li> <li>[ ] Bamboo steamer \u2014 essential for dim sum and Cantonese steaming</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/shopping-list.html#congee-toppings-block-36","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Congee Toppings (Block 36)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Century eggs (\u76ae\u86cb) \u2014 2 (from Asian grocery; look for the dark preserved eggs; an experience)</li> <li>[ ] Shallots \u2014 3\u20134 (for crispy shallots)</li> <li>[ ] Pickled ginger \u2014 1 small jar (store-bought)</li> <li>[ ] White pepper (ground) \u2014 1 jar (essential for congee and hot and sour soup; different from black pepper)</li> <li>[ ] Peanuts (roasted, unsalted) \u2014 \u00bd cup (dan dan noodle garnish + kung pao)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/39-40-chinese/shopping-list.html#equipment-notes-for-this-block","title":"\ud83e\uddca Equipment Notes for This Block","text":"<ul> <li>Wok \u2014 carbon steel, 14-inch, flat-bottomed for home ranges (not round-bottomed without a wok ring)</li> <li>Wok spatula (chan) \u2014 the flat-edged wok ladle; essential for proper stir-fry motion</li> <li>Bamboo steamer \u2014 1 or 2 tiers; fits over a wok with boiling water below</li> <li>Rice cooker \u2014 strongly recommended; frees up attention for wok work</li> <li>Spider strainer or slotted spoon \u2014 for blanching and straining</li> <li>Heavy cleaver (optional) \u2014 for breaking down pork belly; a chef's knife works too</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html","title":"\ud83c\uddf2\ud83c\uddfd Block 41\u201342: Mexican","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 39\u201340: Chinese | Block 43\u201344: Indian \u2192</p> <p>\"Mexican cooking is not what you find at most restaurants north of the border. It's a cuisine of extraordinary depth \u2014 complex moles that take two days, fresh salsas that cook in ten minutes, braises that turn into sandwiches, soups that become street food. Understanding it properly changes how you think about heat, acid, and corn.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#block-41-pozole-tacos-al-pastor-and-carne-asada","title":"Block 41 \u2014 Pozole, Tacos al Pastor, and Carne Asada","text":"<p>Mexican cuisine covers centuries of indigenous technique layered with colonial influence and regional variation. This week focuses on the key dry-heat and braising techniques from Mexico's northern and central traditions. You've already done carnitas (Week 20) and al pastor-adjacent work \u2014 this week goes deeper.</p> <p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 6 (Birria de Res): marinade and braise: plan 3\u20134 hrs; best if marinated overnight</li> <li>Session 7 (Mole Negro): simplified mole still takes 2\u20133 hrs; start early in the session</li> <li>Session 8 (Tamales): soak corn husks 2 hrs ahead; have filling and chile sauce fully prepped before spreading masa</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#session-1-carne-asada","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Carne Asada","text":"<p>Skill: Marinating thin beef for grill; char without overcooking; proper resting Read first: Carne Asada</p> <p>What you're learning: Carne asada is grilled marinated beef, usually flank or skirt steak, cut thin after resting and used in tacos. The marinade is citrus-heavy \u2014 lime + orange + garlic + cumin + chili \u2014 and the char is non-negotiable. Kenji's approach talks through why you want extreme heat and a thin piece of meat rather than a thick steak treated like carne.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Carne Asada tacos on warm corn tortillas - Pico de gallo, guacamole (prevent browning with the right technique), sliced radish, fresh lime</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#session-2-pozole-rojo","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Pozole Rojo","text":"<p>Skill: Dried chile rehydration and integration; hominy preparation; pozole's garnish architecture Read first: Pozole \u2014 Mexican Red Chile Pork Soup</p> <p>What you're learning: Pozole is a pre-Columbian Mesoamerican soup built around hominy (nixtamalized corn) and slow-braised pork in a red chile broth. The dried chiles (guajillo, ancho, mulato) are toasted, rehydrated, and blended \u2014 this is the fundamental Mexican chile sauce technique you'll use throughout this block and beyond.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pozole Rojo with whatever garnishes you have: shredded cabbage, sliced radish, dried oregano, lime juice, tostadas</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Pozole Verde de Pollo \u2014 He makes the verde version; compare the green vs. red chile logic and notice how the hominy transforms the texture of the broth.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#session-3-guacamole-salsa-verde-the-fundamentals","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Guacamole + Salsa Verde (The Fundamentals)","text":"<p>Skill: Avocado selection and browning prevention; charring tomatillos; raw vs. cooked salsa Read first: How to Prevent Guacamole from Browning</p> <p>What you're learning: Guacamole is technique (not just mashing avocados). Acid + salt applied at the right moment prevent browning. The onion is rinsed to remove harsh sulfur compounds before adding. This session: make a perfect guacamole AND a charred salsa verde (the tomatillo charring technique was covered in Week 20 \u2014 revisit and refine it).</p> <p>Full Meal: - Guacamole + charred salsa verde served as dinner accompaniments - Pair with braised pinto beans (from scratch or canned), warm tortillas, queso fresco</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Great Guacamole \u2014 Watch specifically how he handles the acid and salt timing \u2014 it's the thing most people get backwards.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#session-4-tacos-al-pastor","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Tacos al Pastor","text":"<p>Skill: Al pastor marinade (achiote paste base); achiote spice profile; stovetop vs. grill comal technique Read first: Tacos al Pastor</p> <p>What you're learning: Al pastor derives from Lebanese shawarma brought to Mexico in the 19th century and transformed with achiote paste, pineapple, and dried chiles. The SE version makes it achievable at home without a vertical spit. The pineapple chunk broiled at the end (or grilled separately) is mandatory.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Tacos al Pastor: pork, pineapple, white onion, cilantro, lime, corn tortillas - Refried beans alongside</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#session-5-project-enchiladas-red-chile-sauce-from-scratch","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Enchiladas + Red Chile Sauce from Scratch","text":"<p>Skill: Making a proper red chile sauce (not store-bought); enchilada rolling and baking What you're learning: Real enchiladas are dipped in a chile sauce, not smothered in sauce after. The corn tortilla is briefly fried or softened in the sauce itself, then rolled around the filling, laid in a pan, and baked until the sauce caramelizes. The sauce is the skill \u2014 make it from at least two dried chile varieties.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Enchiladas Rojas (beef or cheese and onion) - Mexican rice, refried beans or black beans - Crema, white onion, fresh cilantro, queso fresco</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Crispy-Edged Enchiladas \u2014 Notice the dipping-not-smothering technique; that's the structural difference between real enchiladas and the casserole version most people make.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#block-42-deeper-mexico-birria-mole-and-tamales","title":"Block 42 \u2014 Deeper Mexico: Birria, Mole, and Tamales","text":""},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#session-6-birria-de-res-beef-birria","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Birria de Res (Beef Birria)","text":"<p>Skill: Long beef braise in a complex chile marinade; consomm\u00e9 for dipping Read first: Birria de Res (Beef Birria)</p> <p>What you're learning: Birria is Jalisco's slow-braised chile-rubbed beef (or goat in the original version). The braising liquid becomes the consomm\u00e9 \u2014 the broth in which you dip your quesabirria taco before eating it. This is a project session cook that ended up on Session 1 because of its recent popularity; know the real version.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Birria tacos / quesabirria with consomm\u00e9 for dipping - Pickled onions, lime, cilantro, salsa</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Tacos de Birria \u2014 Watch how he builds the consomm\u00e9 and the importance of the chile marinade penetrating the meat before braising.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#session-7-mole-negro-simplified-introduction","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Mole Negro (Simplified Introduction)","text":"<p>Skill: Multi-chile mole building; chocolate integration in savory sauce; depth layering Read first: Mole Negro (Oaxacan Black Mole Sauce)</p> <p>What you're learning: True mole negro is a week-long project. Today's simplified version should still require 2\u20133 hours and include: at minimum 3 dried chiles (toasted + rehydrated), tomatoes, tomatillos, dark chocolate, sesame, raisins, plantain, and spices. The result should be complex, savory, faintly bitter. Serve with chicken.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Simplified Mole Negro with chicken thighs - White rice and warm tortillas</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#session-8-tamales-team-project","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Tamales (Team Project)","text":"<p>Skill: Masa dough preparation (masa harina + lard or fat); spreading on husks; steaming Read first: How to Make Tamales \u2014 Comprehensive Guide</p> <p>What you're learning: Tamales are one of the most community-oriented foods in Mexican culture \u2014 typically made in large quantities at family gatherings (\"tamaladas\"). Make a batch with a simple filling (braised pork in red chile, or cheese and rajas). The key skill is spreading the masa thinly and evenly enough that the husk folds without tearing.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Tamales (makes 12\u201316) \u2014 eat some tonight; freeze the rest - Black beans, salsa, crema</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#session-9-chiles-rellenos","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Chiles Rellenos","text":"<p>Skill: Roasting and peeling poblano peppers; battered egg-white fry technique Read first: Chiles Rellenos (Mexican-Style Cheese-Stuffed Chiles)</p> <p>What you're learning: Chiles rellenos are another study in egg-white batter frying (similar to tempura structurally \u2014 the white is beaten stiff, yolks folded in). The poblanos are charred under a broiler, steamed in a bag, peeled \u2014 this is the standard technique for all roasted peppers that applies across cuisines.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Chiles Rellenos (cheese or picadillo filled) - Tomato salsa, rice, beans</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Chiles Rellenos \u2014 Pay attention to his egg-white batter technique and what \"stiff peaks\" actually does for the fry structure.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#session-10-project-full-mexican-celebration-dinner","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Full Mexican Celebration Dinner","text":"<p>Skill: Multi-dish coordination; table presentation of Mexican feast Goal: Choose 4\u20135 dishes from the two weeks and serve them restaurant-style:</p> <ol> <li>Botanas: Guacamole, salsa verde, tortilla chips</li> <li>Sopa: Remainder of pozole (reheat) or a fresh black bean soup</li> <li>Main I: Whatever birria or enchiladas remain</li> <li>Main II: Carne asada or al pastor freshly prepared</li> <li>Dessert: Churros with chocolate sauce, or tres leches cake (store-bought acceptable tonight)</li> </ol> <p>Full Meal: - Multi-dish Mexican celebration spread - Margaritas or agua fresca as appropriate</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#the-chile-framework","title":"The Chile Framework","text":"<p>Mexican cooking is a chile curriculum. Guajillo, ancho, pasilla, chipotle \u2014 each dried chile has a distinct flavor profile, heat level, and application. Learning to distinguish them by taste is the single biggest skill jump in Mexican cooking.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Carne Asada: The Food Lab Recipe \u2014 The science behind the marinade and the high-heat grill approach, explained in detail.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Pozole Rojo \u2014 The full technique for the multi-chile broth. Understanding how the dried chiles are toasted, soaked, and blended is the core skill of Mexican sauce-making.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#mole-one-of-the-most-complex-sauces-in-the-world","title":"Mole: One of the Most Complex Sauces in the World","text":"<p>Mole negro is typically a multi-day project in its native context. Understanding why each ingredient \u2014 chocolate, dried chiles, charred onion, toasted sesame, plantain \u2014 is there turns an intimidating recipe into a logical sequence.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 A Comprehensive Guide to Mexican Chiles \u2014 The full vocabulary of dried chiles used in mole: ancho, mulato, pasilla, chipotle, guajillo, and more. Knowing the flavor profile of each one before you cook is how mole stops being frightening and starts being navigable.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Bayless on mole \u2014 The foremost authority on Mexican cuisine in the American culinary world. His mole breakdowns are the clearest explanations available in English.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Mexico: The Cookbook by Margarita Carrillo Bosco \u2014 The Phaidon comprehensive reference on Mexican regional cooking. If you want to understand the full diversity of what you started this week, this is the book.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 39\u201340: Chinese | Block 43\u201344: Indian \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Block 37\u201338: Mexican","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/quick-ref.html#block-33-techniques-of-central-and-northern-mexico","title":"Block 33 \u2014 Techniques of Central and Northern Mexico","text":"Session Dish Technique Key Point Session 1 Carne Asada Tacos Citrus marinade; extreme-heat grill or cast iron Thin cut; rest; slice against grain Session 2 Pozole Rojo Dried chile rehydration + blend; hominy braise Toast chiles; don't burn Session 3 Guacamole + Salsa Verde Acid + salt timing; charred tomatillos Rinse onion before adding to guac Session 4 Tacos al Pastor Achiote marinade; comal/broiler finish Pineapple chunk is not optional Session 5 PROJECT: Enchiladas Rojas Dip tortilla in sauce; roll; bake Sauce first, not smothered after"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/quick-ref.html#block-34-deeper-mexico-birria-mole-tamales","title":"Block 34 \u2014 Deeper Mexico: Birria, Mole, Tamales","text":"Session Dish Technique Key Point Session 6 \u23f0 Birria de Res All-day braise in chile marinade; consomm\u00e9 Save broth for dipping Session 7 \u23f0 Simplified Mole Negro Multi-chile; chocolate; long simmer Balance bitter (chile) + sweet (chocolate, raisins) Session 8 \u23f0 Tamales Masa dough; corn husks; steam 1.5 hrs Spread masa thin; test one float test Session 9 Chiles Rellenos Broil + peel; egg-white batter fry Beat whites stiff; stuff cold Session 10 PROJECT: Full Mexican Celebration Multi-dish service from both weeks Prep botanas first; keep mains warm"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/quick-ref.html#key-dried-chile-reference","title":"Key Dried Chile Reference","text":"Chile Heat Flavor Common Use Ancho Mild Chocolate, berry, prune Mole, enchilada sauce, pozole Guajillo Mild-medium Fruity, bright Pozole, birria marinade Mulato Mild Chocolate, smoky Mole negro Pasilla Mild-medium Earthy, raisin-like Mole, salsas Chipotle (dried) Hot Smoky Adobo, salsas; also available canned \u00c1rbol Hot Bright, clean heat Salsas, birria"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/quick-ref.html#tortilla-basics","title":"Tortilla Basics","text":"<ul> <li>Corn tortillas \u2014 masa harina + water; press with tortilla press; cook 60\u201390 sec/side on hot comal</li> <li>Flour tortillas \u2014 wheat flour + fat + water; softer; roll thin; cook 30\u201345 sec/side</li> <li>Warm for service: Wrap in damp paper towel and microwave, or keep in foil in 200\u00b0F oven</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 37\u201338: Mexican","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Where to shop: A Mexican grocery or Latin market is the right place for dried chiles, hominy, masa harina, fresh tortillas, tomatillos, Mexican oregano, achiote paste, and queso fresco. These are not optional upgrades \u2014 they're the correct ingredients.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Tortilla press \u2014 for making corn tortillas from scratch ($15\u201320, worth it)</li> <li>[ ] Comal or flat cast iron griddle \u2014 for tortillas and carne asada</li> <li>[ ] Blender \u2014 for chile sauces; must be high-powered to blend rehydrated chiles</li> <li>[ ] Steamer / tamale pot \u2014 for tamales (large pot with rack works)</li> <li>[ ] Dutch oven \u2014 pozole, birria, enchilada braise</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-33","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 33","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Flank or skirt steak \u2014 1.5 lbs (Mon carne asada)</li> <li>[ ] Pork shoulder \u2014 2 lbs (Tue pozole + Fri al pastor)</li> <li>[ ] Bone-in chicken thighs \u2014 4 (Sat enchiladas, or ground beef for picadillo filling)</li> <li>[ ] Ground beef or pork \u2014 1 lb (Sat enchilada filling \u2014 or use leftover braised pork)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-34","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 34","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Beef chuck \u2014 3 lbs (Mon birria)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken thighs \u2014 4\u20136 (Tue mole)</li> <li>[ ] Pork shoulder \u2014 1 lb if making pork tamale filling (Wed; or use birria leftovers)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (Fri chiles rellenos batter)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/shopping-list.html#dried-chiles-buy-at-mexican-market","title":"\ud83c\udf36\ufe0f Dried Chiles (buy at Mexican market)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Guajillo \u2014 6 pods</li> <li>[ ] Ancho \u2014 4 pods</li> <li>[ ] Mulato \u2014 3 pods (mole)</li> <li>[ ] Pasilla \u2014 2 pods (mole)</li> <li>[ ] \u00c1rbol \u2014 4 dry pods (birria + salsas)</li> <li>[ ] Chipotle in adobo \u2014 1 small can (al pastor marinade + backup)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Tomatillos \u2014 1 lb (Wed salsa verde + Fri chiles rellenos salsa)</li> <li>[ ] Poblano peppers \u2014 10 (Fri chiles rellenos \u00d7 4\u20136; spare for enchiladas)</li> <li>[ ] Avocados \u2014 6 (Wed guacamole + tacos throughout)</li> <li>[ ] Jalape\u00f1os \u2014 4 (various)</li> <li>[ ] Serrano chiles \u2014 2 (guac heat)</li> <li>[ ] Cilantro \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] White onion \u2014 3 (various; always rinsed before adding raw)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 3 heads</li> <li>[ ] Limes \u2014 8</li> <li>[ ] Oranges \u2014 3 (carne asada marinade + al pastor)</li> <li>[ ] Tomatoes \u2014 6 (pico de gallo, enchilada sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Radishes \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Pineapple \u2014 1 (al pastor Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Mexican dried oregano (different from Italian)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/shopping-list.html#masa-and-corn","title":"\ud83c\udf3d Masa and Corn","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Masa harina (Maseca) \u2014 2-lb bag (tamales + corn tortillas)</li> <li>[ ] Canned hominy \u2014 2 \u00d7 29-oz cans (Tue pozole, or cook dried hominy from scratch)</li> <li>[ ] Corn husks \u2014 1 bag (Wed tamales)</li> <li>[ ] Corn tortillas \u2014 2 packs (various tacos; good to have even if you make some)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/41-42-mexican/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Achiote paste \u2014 1 small block or tablespoon (al pastor marinade Fri)</li> <li>[ ] Cumin \u2014 ground, large jar</li> <li>[ ] Mexican cinnamon (Ceylon) \u2014 1 stick</li> <li>[ ] Dark chocolate (70%+) \u2014 2 oz (mole)</li> <li>[ ] Raisins \u2014 small bag (mole)</li> <li>[ ] Sesame seeds \u2014 (mole)</li> <li>[ ] Pumpkin seeds (pepitas) \u2014 (mole + garnish)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken or beef stock \u2014 2 quarts</li> <li>[ ] Lard or shortening \u2014 for tamale masa fat (lard is traditional; makes it better)</li> <li>[ ] Refried beans \u2014 canned as backup; or make from scratch with pinto beans</li> <li>[ ] Black beans \u2014 2 \u00d7 15-oz cans or 1 lb dried</li> <li>[ ] Long-grain white rice \u2014 2 lbs (arroz rojo; rice sides appear multiple nights \u2014 completely the expected starch for this block)</li> </ul> <p>Fresh cheeses (buy at Mexican market): - [ ] Queso fresco \u2014 8 oz - [ ] Oaxacan cheese (quesillo) \u2014 4 oz (chiles rellenos or quesabirria) - [ ] Crema Mexicana \u2014 1 cup (not the same as sour cream; thinner and tangy)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html","title":"\ud83c\uddee\ud83c\uddf3 Block 43\u201344: Indian","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 41\u201342: Mexican | Block 45\u201346: Middle Eastern \u2192</p> <p>\"Indian cooking is chemistry in practice \u2014 the Maillard reaction in a tarka, the emulsion of yogurt in a marinade, the solubility of fat-soluble spice compounds in hot ghee. Learning to cook Indian food teaches you the molecular logic underneath every other cuisine, disguised as flavor.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#before-you-start-block-43","title":"Before You Start Block 43","text":""},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#session-0-garlic-naan-optional","title":"Session 0 \u2014 Garlic Naan (optional)","text":"<p>Skill: Leavened flatbread technique; cast-iron skillet substitute for tandoor; garlic + butter finish Read first: Garlic Naan</p> <p>What you're learning: Naan requires yeast or baking powder, yogurt (for color and tang), and extremely high heat. A fully preheated cast iron skillet at maximum heat is the home substitute for a 900\u00b0F tandoor. The result should have char spots, a slight chew, and elastic pull. Once you can make fresh naan, takeout naan will feel like a step backward.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Garlic Naan \u00d7 8\u201310 (it's flatbread night \u2014 pair with leftover dal from earlier in the block or butter chicken)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Naan in a Pizza Oven \u2014 Watch how he manages extreme heat and why the char spots are a feature, not a mistake.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#block-43-spice-mastery-butter-chicken-dal-and-naan","title":"Block 43 \u2014 Spice Mastery: Butter Chicken, Dal, and Naan","text":"<p>The first Indian week focuses on three foundational preparations: a tomato-cream curry (butter chicken), a lentil dish that teaches spice bloom and dal texture (moong dal), and flatbread from scratch (naan). Together they cover the core skills of Indian stovetop cooking.</p> <p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 4 (Dal Makhani): traditional version takes 4+ hrs low cook; pressure cooker = 40 min</li> <li>Session 10 (PROJECT: South Indian Thali + Dosa): ferment dosa batter 24\u201348 hrs ahead \u2014 start two days before</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#session-1-butter-chicken-murgh-makhani","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Butter Chicken (Murgh Makhani)","text":"<p>Skill: Tandoor-style marination; tomato cream sauce construction; achieving the balance no restaurant can get wrong Read first: Stovetop Butter Chicken</p> <p>What you're learning: Butter chicken (murgh makhani) is North Indian restaurant cooking at a global scale \u2014 marinated chicken (yogurt + spices + char under a broiler), then simmered in a buttery tomato cream sauce. The SE version happens entirely on the stovetop. The lesson: blooming whole spices in butter or ghee before adding aromatics and sauce unlocks fat-soluble flavor compounds.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Butter Chicken - Basmati rice - Store-bought naan (garlic naan is fine; you'll make fresh ahead of Session 4)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Lower-Calorie Butter Chicken (Ethan Chlebowski) \u2014 He approaches the same dish analytically \u2014 compare his sauce construction and fat tradeoffs to the SE version you made.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#session-2-moong-dal-yellow-split-lentils","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Moong Dal (Yellow Split Lentils)","text":"<p>Skill: Tarka (spice bloomed in fat); dal texture from liquid ratio; tempering as finishing technique Read first: Moong Dal</p> <p>What you're learning: A tarka is hot ghee or oil with spices (cumin seed, mustard seed, dry chiles, asafoetida) fried until they pop and bloom, then poured over the finished dal. The sizzle and fragrance is the signal \u2014 overcooked tarka becomes bitter, undercooked misses the bloom entirely. This is one of the most-used techniques in Indian cooking.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Moong Dal with tarka finish - Rice + papad (store-bought poppadom) - Mango pickle on the side</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#session-3-chicken-tikka-masala-grilled-version","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Chicken Tikka Masala (Grilled Version)","text":"<p>Skill: Tikka marinade; charring on high heat; integrating char flavor into sauce Read first: Chicken Tikka Masala for the Grill</p> <p>What you're learning: Tikka masala is arguably the most popular Indian-origin dish in the English-speaking world. The SE grill version gives the chicken the char you otherwise get from a tandoor. The masala sauce (tomato, cream, ginger, garam masala) is richer and more accessible than butter chicken's sauce but built the same way.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Chicken Tikka Masala (grilled tikka + masala sauce) - Basmati rice - Cucumber raita (yogurt + cucumber + cumin + salt) \u2014 cooling contrast, always needed</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#session-4-dal-makhani-all-day-slow-dal","title":"\u23f0 Session 4 \u2014 Dal Makhani (All-Day Slow Dal)","text":"<p>Skill: Long-cook black lentil + kidney bean dal; cream integration; patience Read first: Dal Makhani</p> <p>What you're learning: Dal makhani is the richest, most complex dal in the Punjabi repertoire \u2014 black urad lentils and kidney beans cooked for hours until they become creamy and almost stew-like, finished with cream and butter. The SE version adapts this to a pressure cooker for efficiency. The traditional version simmers overnight on a dying fire; the slow cooker is a valid home interpretation.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Dal Makhani - Basmati rice + naan (from Session 4's batch if any remain) - Chopped tomato, onion, cucumber salad alongside</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Dal Makhani (Ranveer Brar) \u2014 Restaurant-trained perspective on the long cook; pay attention to his point about why time \u2014 not more cream \u2014 is what makes dal makhani creamy.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#session-5-project-north-indian-feast","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: North Indian Feast","text":"<p>Skill: Coordinating multiple Indian dishes for simultaneous service Goal: Recreate a North Indian restaurant spread at home:</p> <ol> <li>Starters: Samosas (store-bought is fine, focus on chutney \u2014 make a tamarind chutney and mint chutney)</li> <li>Main dal: Dal makhani or moong dal</li> <li>Main curry: Butter chicken or tikka masala (from batch earlier in week)</li> <li>Bread: Fresh naan from Session 4</li> <li>Sides: Raita, papad, mango pickle</li> </ol> <p>Full Meal: - Full Indian banquet spread - Chai (Indian milk tea \u2014 steep strong black tea with ginger, cardamom, cinnamon, milk, sugar)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#block-44-south-india-vegetarian-mastery","title":"Block 44 \u2014 South India + Vegetarian Mastery","text":"<p>South Indian cooking is different from North Indian in almost every way: less cream, more coconut, more lentils, more rice, and hotter. Idli, dosa, sambar, rasam \u2014 a different grammar entirely.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#session-6-chana-masala-chickpea-curry","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Chana Masala (Chickpea Curry)","text":"<p>Skill: Dried chickpea preparation; tomato + onion + spice masala from scratch; amchur (dry mango powder) as souring agent Read first: Chana Masala</p> <p>What you're learning: Chana masala is one of the great vegetarian dishes in the world. The chickpeas absorb spices during cooking and take on the sauce's character. Amchur (dried unripe mango powder) plus fresh lemon is what makes chana taste like chana rather than generic chickpea stew \u2014 it's the acidic finish that completes it.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Chana Masala - Puri (fried hollow puffy bread \u2014 or plain roti, or naan) - Sliced raw onion and lemon</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Quick Chole Masala (Ranveer Brar) \u2014 Watch his masala-building sequence and how long he cooks the tomato down; the amchur addition near the end is the technique note to compare against your version.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#session-7-aloo-gobi-potato-and-cauliflower","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Aloo Gobi (Potato and Cauliflower)","text":"<p>Skill: Dry vegetable curry (no sauce); blooming spices in oil before vegetables; understanding dry vs. wet curry Read first: Aloo Gobi</p> <p>What you're learning: Aloo gobi is a dry curry \u2014 no sauce, no cream, just spiced vegetables cooked until tender and slightly crispy at the edges. The spice bloom is everything. The technique of cooking out raw spice smell in oil (bhunao) before adding vegetables is the central skill.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Aloo Gobi - Roti or naan - Toor dal alongside (quick version \u2014 see Session 4 Week 35 moong dal approach, applied to toor)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#session-8-lamb-biryani","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Lamb Biryani","text":"<p>Skill: Dum cooking (sealed pot, rice and meat layers); spiced rice; marinated lamb Read first: Lamb Biryani</p> <p>What you're learning: Biryani is one of the most complex Indian preparations \u2014 marinated meat, par-cooked rice, saffron milk, fried onions, and aromatics layered and then sealed (\"dum\") and steamed together for the final cook. The seal preserves steam, which finishes the rice and meat simultaneously. The result: each grain of rice is separate, fragrant, and distinct.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Lamb Biryani - Plain yogurt (raita) to cool against the spice - Simple green salad</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Chicken Dum Biryani (Ranveer Brar) \u2014 He uses chicken; you used lamb. Watch the dum sealing technique and par-cook timing \u2014 those are what transfer directly regardless of protein.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#session-9-garam-masala-from-scratch-spice-inventory","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Garam Masala from Scratch + Spice Inventory","text":"<p>Skill: Dry-toasting and grinding whole spices; building a custom blend; understanding garam masala's role Read first: Garam Masala</p> <p>What you're learning: Garam masala is not curry powder and not a substitute for it. It's a warm spice blend (cardamom, cinnamon, cloves, black pepper, cumin, coriander) used at the end of cooking to reinforce aroma, not during early stages. Make a small batch from whole toasted spices. Taste it against store-bought \u2014 the difference is remarkable.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Make garam masala as the session - Cook a simple tarka dal using your fresh blend vs. one portion with store-bought - Taste compare + serve both as dinner with rice</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#session-10-project-south-indian-weekend","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: South Indian Weekend","text":"<p>Skill: Dosai batter fermentation; sambar construction; full South Indian thali Goal: Try a South Indian preparation:</p> <ul> <li>Masala dosa: fermented lentil and rice batter crepe filled with spiced potato (requires batter made Session 4 or the evening before the project session in advance \u2014 or use fast-sour version)</li> <li>Sambar: Toor dal-based vegetable soup / curry (tamarind-based, South Indian)</li> <li>Coconut chutney: Fresh coconut + green chiles + curry leaves</li> </ul> <p>Full Meal: - Masala Dosa + Sambar + Coconut Chutney (South Indian thali) - Filter coffee if possible (South Indian coffee \u2192 chicory blend brewed through a metal filter)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#spice-blooming-why-the-order-matters","title":"Spice Blooming: Why the Order Matters","text":"<p>Indian cooking is largely about controlling heat's interaction with spice. Whole spices into hot oil before anything else \u2014 tempering \u2014 unlocks volatile flavor compounds that grinding and adding late cannot reproduce.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Stovetop Butter Chicken \u2014 The full technique for the dish you cooked, with the science behind the spice sequencing.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Moong Dal \u2014 Dal is the most honest expression of Indian pantry cooking. This recipe shows exactly how the tarka (tempered spice) finishes the dish.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#the-indian-pantry","title":"The Indian Pantry","text":"<p>Indian cooking draws on a pantry of 20\u201330 spices, but most dishes use the same core six: cumin, coriander, turmeric, chili, garam masala, and black mustard seed. Stocking these seven items puts 80% of the recipes within reach.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How Ghee Makes Everything Taste Better \u2014 Ghee is clarified butter with the milk solids removed \u2014 giving it a higher smoke point and a richer, nuttier flavor than butter. This explainer covers what it is, how to make it, and why Indian cooking depends on it.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Madhur Jaffrey's Indian Cooking \u2014 The woman who taught a generation of Western cooks to make Indian food at home. Every episode is a lesson in spice management.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda An Invitation to Indian Cooking by Madhur Jaffrey \u2014 The book that introduced Indian home cooking to the English-speaking world. Still the best starting point for building a usable Indian cooking repertoire.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 41\u201342: Mexican | Block 45\u201346: Middle Eastern \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Block 39\u201340: Indian","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/quick-ref.html#block-35-north-indian-fundamentals","title":"Block 35 \u2014 North Indian Fundamentals","text":"Session Dish Technique Key Point Session 0 \u23f0 Garlic Naan (optional BYS) Yeast flatbread on screaming-hot cast iron Optional; great as a standalone cook before the block Session 1 Butter Chicken Spice bloom in ghee; tomato cream sauce Broil chicken first for char Session 2 Moong Dal + Tarka Tarka = spices bloomed in hot fat poured over Cumin seed should sizzle immediately Session 3 Chicken Tikka Masala Grill char on tikka; masala sauce Yogurt marinade minimum 2 hrs Session 4 \u23f0 Dal Makhani Long-cook black lentils; cream + butter finish Pressure cooker shortcut: 40 min Session 5 PROJECT: North Indian Feast Multi-dish banquet coordination Reheat curries; fresh naan last"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/quick-ref.html#block-36-south-india-vegetarian-mastery","title":"Block 36 \u2014 South India + Vegetarian Mastery","text":"Session Dish Technique Key Point Session 6 Chana Masala Dried chickpea soak + tomato masala Amchur or lemon at finish Session 7 Aloo Gobi Dry curry; bhunao spice technique No sauce \u2014 crispy edges matter Session 8 Lamb Biryani Dum (sealed steam cook); layered rice Par-cook rice before layering Session 9 Garam Masala from Scratch Toast whole spices; grind fresh Use at end of cooking, not beginning Session 10 \u23f0 PROJECT: South Indian Thali Dosa + sambar + coconut chutney Ferment batter Thu/Fri night"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/quick-ref.html#key-indian-spice-reference","title":"Key Indian Spice Reference","text":"Spice Technique When to Add Example Use Cumin seeds Toast whole in fat Beginning (tarka) Dal, rice Mustard seeds Sizzle in fat until popping Beginning (tarka) South Indian, dal Turmeric Add to onion; cook out raw flavor Early All curries Garam masala Ground blend At end / finish Butter chicken, tikka Amchur (dry mango powder) Add near end Finish Chana masala Asafoetida (hing) Tiny pinch, never cook too long With tarka Dal (digestive role)"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/quick-ref.html#dal-water-to-lentil-ratios","title":"Dal Water-to-Lentil Ratios","text":"Lentil Cup Ratio (lentils:water) Cook Time Moong dal (split yellow) 1:3 20\u201325 min stovetop Toor dal (pigeon peas) 1:3 25\u201330 min stovetop Masoor dal (red lentils) 1:2.5 15\u201320 min stovetop Urad dal (black, whole) 1:4 45 min\u20131 hr (or pressure cooker) Chana dal (chickpea split) 1:3 30\u201340 min stovetop"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 39\u201340: Indian","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Where to shop: An Indian grocery store is mandatory for this block. You need fresh curry leaves, mustard seeds, asafoetida (hing), whole spices, moong dal, urad dal, idli/dosa rice, mango pickle, and ghee at proper prices and quality.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Heavy cast iron skillet \u2014 for naan and dosa</li> <li>[ ] Spice grinder or coffee grinder \u2014 for garam masala and fresh spice grinding</li> <li>[ ] Pressure cooker or Instant Pot \u2014 for dal makhani and biryani (quicker versions)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-35","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 35","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Chicken thighs, boneless \u2014 3 lbs (Mon butter chicken + Wed tikka masala)</li> <li>[ ] Lamb shoulder or cubes \u2014 1.5 lbs (Wed biryani Week 36; buy early)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-36","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 36","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (various; dosa batter)</li> <li>[ ] (Weeks 36 is largely vegetarian \u2014 no additional meat purchase required)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/shopping-list.html#lentils-and-beans","title":"\ud83e\uded8 Lentils and Beans","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Moong dal (yellow split mung) \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Whole urad dal (black lentils) \u2014 1 lb (dal makhani Fri Week 35)</li> <li>[ ] Toor dal (pigeon peas) \u2014 1 lb (sambar Week 36 Sat + weekday dal)</li> <li>[ ] Dried chickpeas \u2014 1 lb (Mon Week 36 chana masala; or 2 \u00d7 15-oz cans)</li> <li>[ ] Rajma (kidney beans) \u2014 \u00bd lb (dal makhani)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/shopping-list.html#produce","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 4 heads</li> <li>[ ] Ginger \u2014 1 large piece (use throughout)</li> <li>[ ] White onions \u2014 4 large</li> <li>[ ] Tomatoes \u2014 10 (pureed for sauces + fresh sides)</li> <li>[ ] Cauliflower \u2014 1 head (Tue Week 36 aloo gobi)</li> <li>[ ] Yukon gold potatoes \u2014 2 lbs (Tue + biryani + various)</li> <li>[ ] Lemon \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Serrano or green chiles \u2014 10 (used daily in small amounts)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh cilantro \u2014 3 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Cucumber \u2014 4 (raita)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh curry leaves \u2014 1 sprig (Indian grocery; South Indian tarka)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/shopping-list.html#dairy","title":"\ud83e\udd5b Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Full-fat yogurt \u2014 2 lbs (marinade + raita + naan dough)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream or double cream \u2014 1 pint (butter chicken, dal makhani)</li> <li>[ ] Ghee \u2014 8 oz jar (use throughout; superior to butter for Indian cooking)</li> <li>[ ] Whole milk \u2014 1 quart (chai + various)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/shopping-list.html#whole-spices-buy-at-indian-market","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Whole Spices (buy at Indian market)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Cumin seeds \u2014 large bag</li> <li>[ ] Coriander seeds \u2014 large bag</li> <li>[ ] Mustard seeds (black/brown) \u2014 1 bag</li> <li>[ ] Cardamom pods (green) \u2014 1 small bag</li> <li>[ ] Black cardamom pods \u2014 4\u20135 (biryani)</li> <li>[ ] Cinnamon sticks \u2014 4</li> <li>[ ] Whole cloves \u2014 1 small bag</li> <li>[ ] Black peppercorns \u2014 1 bag</li> <li>[ ] Dried red chiles \u2014 1 bag</li> <li>[ ] Bay leaves \u2014 Indian variety (tegpatta)</li> <li>[ ] Mace \u2014 1 small bag (biryani)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/shopping-list.html#ground-spices-condiments","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Ground Spices + Condiments","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Turmeric \u2014 large jar</li> <li>[ ] Cumin (ground) \u2014 large jar</li> <li>[ ] Coriander (ground) \u2014 large jar</li> <li>[ ] Kashmiri red chili powder \u2014 1 jar (mild heat + color)</li> <li>[ ] Regular red chili powder or cayenne \u2014 1 jar (heat)</li> <li>[ ] Garam masala \u2014 store-bought (for comparison; also make fresh Fri Week 36)</li> <li>[ ] Amchur (dry mango powder) \u2014 1 bag (chana masala)</li> <li>[ ] Asafoetida (hing) \u2014 small jar (dal tarka; tiny amount goes very far)</li> <li>[ ] Coconut milk \u2014 2 cans (South Indian thali + sambar)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh coconut \u2014 \u00bd coconut or 1 cup desiccated (coconut chutney for dosa/idli service; fresh is best, desiccated works)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/43-44-indian/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83c\udf5a Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Basmati rice \u2014 5-lb bag</li> <li>[ ] Parboiled rice (idli/dosa rice) \u2014 2 lbs (idli and dosa batter requires this \u2014 basmati will not work; find it at Indian grocery)</li> <li>[ ] All-purpose flour + bread flour (naan dough)</li> <li>[ ] Instant yeast \u2014 1 packet (naan)</li> <li>[ ] Saffron \u2014 small pinch (biryani)</li> <li>[ ] Tamarind paste \u2014 1 jar (sambar Week 36 Sat)</li> <li>[ ] Mango pickle (achar) \u2014 1 jar</li> <li>[ ] Papad (poppadum) \u2014 1 pack</li> <li>[ ] Samosas \u2014 store-bought fine for Saturday feast accompaniment</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html","title":"Block 41\u201342: Middle Eastern","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 39\u201340: Indian | Block 43\u201344: Southeast Asian \u2192</p> <p>\"Middle Eastern cooking is not a single cuisine \u2014 it's a family of cuisines spanning Persian, Lebanese, Israeli, Syrian, Turkish, Yemeni, Egyptian, and North African traditions, each distinct, many overlapping. What they share: olive oil, citrus, aromatics, legumes, and fire applied with extraordinary restraint. Start with hummus. Build from there.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#block-45-hummus-shakshuka-shawarma-and-the-mezze-framework","title":"Block 45 \u2014 Hummus, Shakshuka, Shawarma, and the Mezze Framework","text":"<p>The first week focuses on building the foundational components of a Middle Eastern meal: the mezze (small plates), the key dips, and one main protein (shawarma). By week's end you'll have the components for a complete mezze spread.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#session-1-hummus-btahini-from-scratch","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Hummus b'Tahini (From Scratch)","text":"<p>Skill: Dried chickpea cooking to the right texture; tahini ratio; blending technique for silky result Read first: Hummus b'Tahini</p> <p>What you're learning: Hummus from canned chickpeas is acceptable. Hummus from dried chickpeas cooked with baking soda until almost crumbling, then blended warm into tahini \u2014 is a revelation. The warm chickpeas blend more efficiently. The baking soda softens the skins, which can be rubbed off for ultra-smooth result. This is the technique.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Hummus b'Tahini with olive oil, cumin, paprika, and warm pita - Sliced cucumbers and tomatoes alongside</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to LEVEL UP Hummus (Middle Eats) \u2014 He focuses on the specific tricks that separate home hummus from restaurant hummus; compare his chickpea cooking approach and blending technique to yours.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#session-2-shakshuka","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Shakshuka","text":"<p>Skill: Tomato and pepper sauce construction; poaching eggs in sauce Read first: Shakshuka \u2014 North African Shirred Eggs</p> <p>What you're learning: Shakshuka is eggs poached in a spiced tomato and pepper sauce \u2014 one of the great one-pan meals of global cooking. The sauce (onion, peppers, tomato, cumin, paprika, often harissa) is made first, then wells are made in the sauce, eggs cracked in, and everything covered until the whites are set but the yolks still run. Timing is the only hard part.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Shakshuka with crusty bread or pita for scooping - Labneh (strained yogurt; buy or make) on the side</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#session-3-baba-ganoush-muhammara","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Baba Ganoush + Muhammara","text":"<p>Skill: Char-roasting eggplant for smoky flavor; red pepper walnut dip technique Read first: The Best Baba Ganoush | Muhammara</p> <p>What you're learning: Baba ganoush requires eggplant charred directly over a gas flame or under a broiler until the skin is entirely black and the interior is soft. This char creates the smoke flavor that makes baba ganoush what it is \u2014 without it, it's just mashed eggplant. Muhammara (Syrian roasted red pepper and walnut dip) is the day's second preparation \u2014 make both and compare how they complement versus compete on a mezze board.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Mezze board: baba ganoush + muhammara + hummus (from Session 1) + pita - Falafel from the freezer or store (you'll make fresh on Session 4)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Creamiest Baba Ghanoush (Middle Eats) \u2014 Watch how long he lets the eggplant char; most home cooks stop too early and miss the smoke flavor that makes the dish what it is.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#session-4-falafel","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Falafel","text":"<p>Skill: Dried chickpea-based falafel; herb incorporation; frying temperature management Read first: The Best Homemade Falafel</p> <p>What you're learning: Falafel uses dried (never canned) chickpeas soaked but not cooked \u2014 they're ground raw with herbs and spices and fried. Canned chickpeas produce wet, dense, falling-apart falafel. The raw soak approach gives the right texture: crispy outside, bright green inside. Fry at 350\u00b0F, 3 minutes.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Falafel in warm pita with tahini sauce, tomato, cucumber, pickled onions - Fattoush salad alongside (Fattoush) \u2014 fried pita + fresh vegetables + sumac dressing</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Falafel \u2014 He's emphatic about dried vs. canned chickpeas; watch the texture difference he describes and why canned ones fail.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#session-5-project-beef-shawarma","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Beef Shawarma","text":"<p>Skill: Thin beef marinade and cooking stack concept; shawarma wrap assembly Read first: Beef Shawarma</p> <p>What you're learning: Shawarma is a vertical rotisserie street food adapted at home as thin-sliced marinated beef (or chicken) cooked in a very hot pan or under a broiler to get the char-and-rendered-fat effect of a spit. The spice profile (cumin, coriander, cinnamon, cardamom, turmeric, garlic) is distinct from Indian spicing despite appearing similar. The wrap (pita + chicken or beef + pickled vegetables + tahini) is the delivery vehicle.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Beef Shawarma wraps with garlic sauce (toum) \u2014 mashed garlic + lemon + oil emulsion - Tabbouleh (Tabbouleh Salad) as a side \u2014 mostly fresh parsley, not mostly bulgur</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Legit Chicken Shawarma at Home (Middle Eats) \u2014 He uses chicken; you used beef \u2014 the marinade spice logic is the same. Compare his thin-sear technique and how both versions replicate the spit char at home.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#block-46-kebabs-adana-and-the-aromatic-rice-traditions","title":"Block 46 \u2014 Kebabs, Adana, and the Aromatic Rice Traditions","text":""},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#session-6-adana-kebab-turkish-ground-lamb-skewer","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Adana Kebab (Turkish Ground Lamb Skewer)","text":"<p>Skill: Hand-mixing ground lamb fat; skewer technique; flat metal skewer cooking Read first: Adana Kebab \u2014 Turkish Ground Lamb</p> <p>What you're learning: Adana kebab is ground lamb mixed with tail fat (or cold fatty lamb shoulder, ground finely) and red chile \u2014 shaped onto wide flat metal skewers and grilled directly over fire. The binding technique relies on kneading the mixture until it becomes sticky; this is what holds the lamb to the skewer without falling off.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Adana Kebab with warm flatbread, grilled tomatoes and peppers - Yogurt and sumac, sliced raw onion with sumac</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#session-7-fattoush-tabbouleh-deep-dive","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Fattoush + Tabbouleh Deep Dive","text":"<p>Skill: Fried pita crisp; sumac dressing; understanding bulgur vs. couscous vs. freekeh Read first: Fattoush | Tabbouleh</p> <p>What you're learning: Both are Lebanese-origin salads, both involve fresh herbs, both use an acid-forward dressing. The difference: fattoush uses fried pita + pomegranate molasses + sumac; tabbouleh is mostly fresh parsley (minimal bulgur, widely misunderstood in the West). Cook both today and taste them back-to-back.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Fattoush + Tabbouleh (a vegetarian evening) - Hummus, pita, labneh to round it out</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Fattoush Lebanese Chopped Salad \u2014 Notice how the fried pita and sumac define the dish; compare his ratios to tabbouleh's herb-forward logic and see how different they actually are.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#session-8-persian-style-herb-frittata-kuku-sabzi-or-rice-chelow","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Persian-Style Herb Frittata (Kuku Sabzi) or Rice (Chelow)","text":"<p>Skill: Herb-heavy egg bake; or Persian steamed rice with tahdig crust Read first: For kuku sabzi \u2014 use a handful each of fresh dill, parsley, cilantro, and fenugreek leaves (dried works), with eggs, turmeric, and barberries; baked or pan-cooked. For chelow with tahdig: Chelow (Persian Steamed White Rice) | Tahdig (Persian Crunchy Rice)</p> <p>What you're learning: Either preparation represents a distinct Persian approach absent from the rest of the Middle Eastern block. Chelow with tahdig (the crispy bottom) is a study in rice control: high starch rice, soaked, parboiled, then steamed with a lid lined with a towel that absorbs steam. The bottom goldifies into a crust that is split among the table.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Kuku Sabzi with yogurt and bread, OR Chelow with tahdig as a side to grilled lamb - Simple cucumber and tomato salad</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#session-9-kabsa-saudi-spiced-chicken-and-rice","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Kabsa (Saudi Spiced Chicken and Rice)","text":"<p>Skill: One-pot rice and chicken; aromatic spiced stock; kabsa spice profile Read first: Kabsa \u2014 Spiced Chicken and Rice</p> <p>What you're learning: Kabsa is the national dish of Saudi Arabia \u2014 a one-pot preparation where chicken is braised in a spiced tomato broth, then rice is cooked in that same broth, absorbing all the flavor. The spice profile (cardamom, cloves, cinnamon, black lime, rosewater) is distinct from any other \"spiced rice and meat\" dish you've made.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Kabsa with charred tomato salsa (dakka) on the side - Yogurt, flatbread</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#session-10-project-full-mezze-table","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Full Mezze Table","text":"<p>Skill: Coordinating, plating, and timing a traditional mezze spread Goal: Assemble the most complete mezze table you can from the two weeks of Middle Eastern cooking:</p> <p>Cold mezze: Hummus, baba ganoush, muhammara, tabbouleh, fattoush, labneh, olives, pita Hot mezze / mains: Falafel (fried fresh), adana kebab skewers, shawarma meat (reserved or freshly made) Sauces: Tahini, toum (garlic sauce), harissa Bread: Warm pita throughout</p> <p>Full Meal: - Complete Middle Eastern mezze table - Arak, mint tea, or lemon juice to drink</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#the-mezze-philosophy","title":"The Mezze Philosophy","text":"<p>Middle Eastern cooking is organized around the table, not the plate. Mezze \u2014 the spread of small dishes \u2014 is an eating philosophy as much as a cooking style. Hummus, baba ganoush, and tabbouleh are designed to be eaten together with bread, not sequentially.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 The Best Baba Ganoush \u2014 The technique that separates good baba ganoush (charred, smoky eggplant) from bad (oven-roasted, bland eggplant).</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Hummus with Tahini \u2014 The recipe, plus the technique notes that explain why restaurant hummus is always smoother than yours (until now).</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#tahini-and-olive-oil","title":"Tahini and Olive Oil","text":"<p>Two pantry ingredients define the flavors of this week's food. The quality of your tahini and olive oil shows up directly in everything you made.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Tahini Sauce With Garlic and Lemon \u2014 Kenji's guide to tahini sauce covers the ratio, the thin-down technique with cold water, and why the sauce tightens before it loosens. All of this connects directly to your hummus and everything else you drizzled this week.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Jerusalem by Yotam Ottolenghi &amp; Sami Tamimi \u2014 The most influential Middle Eastern cookbook of the past two decades, blending Israeli and Palestinian food traditions. Every dish you cooked this week has a deeper version here.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 43\u201344: Indian | Block 47\u201348: Southeast Asian Review \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Block 41\u201342: Middle Eastern","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/quick-ref.html#block-37-hummus-shakshuka-shawarma","title":"Block 37 \u2014 Hummus, Shakshuka, Shawarma","text":"Session Dish Technique Key Point Session 1 Hummus b'Tahini Dried chickpeas + baking soda; blend warm Warm chickpeas \u2192 silkier blend Session 2 Shakshuka Tomato-pepper sauce; eggs poached in it Don't over-set the yolks Session 3 Baba Ganoush + Muhammara Direct flame char; roasted pepper walnut blend Black eggplant skin = the smoke flavor Session 4 Falafel + Fattoush Raw soaked chickpeas (never canned); 350\u00b0F fry Must use dried chickpeas Session 5 PROJECT: Beef Shawarma + Tabbouleh Thin-cut marinated beef; broil or sear hot Tabbouleh = mostly parsley"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/quick-ref.html#block-38-kebabs-grains-aromatic-rice","title":"Block 38 \u2014 Kebabs, Grains, Aromatic Rice","text":"Session Dish Technique Key Point Session 6 Adana Kebab Kneaded ground lamb on flat skewers Knead until sticky; no egg needed Session 7 Fattoush + Tabbouleh deep dive Fried pita; sumac; herb-heavy Both are acid-forward; compare them Session 8 Kuku Sabzi or Chelow with Tahdig Herb frittata or Persian steamed rice Tahdig: crust forms at bottom; requires confidence Session 9 Kabsa One-pot rice + spiced chicken stock Black lime is essential Session 10 PROJECT: Full Mezze Table Multi-component spread from both weeks Cold mezze first; hot served last"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/quick-ref.html#middle-eastern-pantry-essentials","title":"Middle Eastern Pantry Essentials","text":"Ingredient Role Source Tahini Sesame paste; base for hummus, sauces Soom or Seed + Mill brand Sumac Tart red spice; dressings, kebab finish Middle Eastern market Za'atar Thyme-based herb blend; used on bread and labneh Middle Eastern market Pomegranate molasses Tart-sweet syrup; fattoush + glazes Middle Eastern market Dried black lime (loomi) Intensely citrusy; used whole in stews Middle Eastern market Rose water Floral; desserts + kabsa Middle Eastern market Harissa North African chile paste Available widely Labneh Strained yogurt; smooth, tart Make by straining Greek yogurt overnight"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/quick-ref.html#key-ratios","title":"Key Ratios","text":"Preparation Ratio Hummus tahini 1 cup cooked chickpeas : \u00bc cup tahini : 2 tbsp lemon : 1 garlic clove Tabbouleh By volume: \u00be parsley : \u00bc everything else (not the reverse) Tahini sauce 1 part tahini : 1 part lemon juice : garlic + water to thin Falafel Soak dried chickpeas 12\u201324 hrs; do not cook; grind raw"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 41\u201342: Middle Eastern","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Where to shop: A Middle Eastern market (Lebanese, Persian, Turkish, or Arab grocery) is strongly recommended. You need: dried chickpeas, quality tahini, sumac, pomegranate molasses, dried black lime, za'atar, labneh, and pita from a bakery if possible.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Food processor \u2014 for hummus, baba ganoush, muhammara, falafel grinding</li> <li>[ ] Flat metal skewers \u2014 for adana kebab (at least 4\u20136)</li> <li>[ ] Fine-mesh strainer \u2014 for labneh straining (cheesecloth works)</li> <li>[ ] Blender \u2014 blender gives silkier hummus than food processor</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-37","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 37","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Beef \u2014 flank, skirt, or sirloin, 2 lbs (Sat shawarma \u2014 marinate Fri night)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (Tue shakshuka + Wed frittata Week 38)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-38","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 38","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Ground lamb \u2014 1.5 lbs (Mon adana kebab)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken thighs, bone-in \u2014 4 (Fri kabsa)</li> <li>[ ] Optional additional protein \u2014 chicken thighs or lamb for Sat mezze table</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#legumes","title":"\ud83e\uded8 Legumes","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dried chickpeas \u2014 2 lbs (hummus Mon + falafel Fri \u2014 must be dried, not canned)</li> <li>[ ] Canned chickpeas \u2014 1 can (backup for quick applications mid-week)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#produce-week-37","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 37","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Eggplant \u2014 3 medium (Wed baba ganoush; char all 3)</li> <li>[ ] Red bell peppers \u2014 4 (Wed muhammara; roast and peel)</li> <li>[ ] Walnuts \u2014 1 cup (Wed muhammara)</li> <li>[ ] Tomatoes \u2014 8 (Tue shakshuka + tabbouleh Sat + various)</li> <li>[ ] Red bell pepper \u2014 3 more (Tue shakshuka sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Italian frying peppers or cubanelle \u2014 4 (Tue shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Jalape\u00f1os \u2014 2 (shakshuka heat)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh parsley \u2014 4 bunches (tabbouleh is mostly parsley; use throughout)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh mint \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Green onions \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Cucumber \u2014 6 (mezze side, fattoush, tabbouleh)</li> <li>[ ] Romaine or Little Gem lettuce \u2014 1 head (fattoush base)</li> <li>[ ] Radishes \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 10 (used every day)</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 4 heads</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#produce-week-38","title":"\ud83e\udd66 Produce \u2014 Week 38","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Pita bread \u2014 2 packs fresh (or buy from Middle Eastern bakery)</li> <li>[ ] Persian cucumbers \u2014 6</li> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 2 pints</li> <li>[ ] Pomegranate \u2014 1 (seeds for garnish Sat)</li> <li>[ ] Onion \u2014 4 medium (kabsa + various)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh herbs: parsley, mint, dill \u2014 additional bunches</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#pantry-middle-eastern-market","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry (Middle Eastern Market)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Tahini \u2014 1 large jar (Soom, Al Kanater, or Ziyad brand preferred)</li> <li>[ ] Sumac \u2014 1 small jar</li> <li>[ ] Za'atar \u2014 1 small jar</li> <li>[ ] Pomegranate molasses \u2014 1 bottle</li> <li>[ ] Dried black lime (loomi) \u2014 4\u20135 (kabsa Fri Week 38)</li> <li>[ ] Rose water \u2014 small bottle (kabsa)</li> <li>[ ] Harissa \u2014 1 jar or tube (shakshuka optional heat + mezze board)</li> <li>[ ] Labneh \u2014 1 tub (or make by straining Greek yogurt in cheesecloth overnight)</li> <li>[ ] Bulgur wheat \u2014 1 cup (tabbouleh \u2014 a tiny amount)</li> <li>[ ] Arak or pastis \u2014 optional for mezze drinks</li> <li>[ ] Pita chips \u2014 for mezze board (or fry stale pita for fattoush crisps)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#spices","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Spices","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Cumin \u2014 ground</li> <li>[ ] Coriander \u2014 ground</li> <li>[ ] Allspice \u2014 ground (shawarma)</li> <li>[ ] Cinnamon \u2014 ground</li> <li>[ ] Cardamom \u2014 ground (kabsa)</li> <li>[ ] Cloves \u2014 ground (kabsa)</li> <li>[ ] Turmeric \u2014 ground</li> <li>[ ] Smoked paprika</li> <li>[ ] Red pepper flakes + cayenne</li> <li>[ ] Black pepper</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/45-46-middle-eastern/shopping-list.html#pantry-staples","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry Staples","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Olive oil \u2014 1 large bottle (extra-virgin; used for basically everything)</li> <li>[ ] Neutral oil (grapeseed, sunflower, or vegetable) \u2014 1 small bottle (toum requires neutral oil; olive oil makes it bitter and broken)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken stock \u2014 2 quarts (kabsa + shakshuka)</li> <li>[ ] Canned San Marzano tomatoes \u2014 2 cans (shakshuka + kabsa)</li> <li>[ ] Basmati rice \u2014 5 lbs (kabsa + multiple meals)</li> <li>[ ] Greek yogurt \u2014 32 oz (raita, labneh, shakshuka side)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html","title":"\ud83c\udf3f Block 47\u201348: Module 4 Capstone \u2014 Southeast Asian Cuisines","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 45\u201346: Middle Eastern | Block 53\u201354: Bread \u2192</p> <p>\u2697\ufe0f Experimental \u2014 This block has not yet been cooked through by the author. Content is draft; recipes and timing are untested.</p> <p>\"Southeast Asian cooking is the most flavor-dense cooking on earth per ingredient \u2014 the balance between salt (fish sauce), sour (lime), sweet (palm sugar), and heat (chili) is the entire lesson. Get that balance right in a pad Thai or a bowl of pho, and you understand the grammar of the whole region.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#block-47-the-big-four-thailand-vietnam-indonesia-malaysia","title":"Block 47 \u2014 The Big Four: Thailand, Vietnam, Indonesia, Malaysia","text":"<p>Southeast Asia is not one cuisine but a family of distinct traditions connected by rice, fish sauce, lemongrass, galangal, and the philosophy that every dish should balance all five flavors simultaneously. This week covers the central dishes of each major tradition.</p> <p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 4 (Beef Rendang): 3\u20134 hr low simmer; builds better flavor if made the day before</li> <li>Session 5 (Project: SE Asian Feast): Rendang is best made Session 4 and reheated \u2014 plan accordingly</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#session-1-pad-thai","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Pad Thai","text":"<p>Skill: Wok technique for noodles; tamarind-palm sugar sauce balance; egg incorporation  Read first: Pad Thai</p> <p>What you're learning: Pad Thai isn't a dump-everything noodle \u2014 it's a study in wok heat management, timing, and the push-pull of the five flavors. The sauce (tamarind + fish sauce + palm sugar) must be pre-mixed and tasted before the noodles ever hit the pan. If the sauce is right, the dish is 80% there.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pad Thai with shrimp (or tofu) - Bean sprouts, peanuts, lime, green onion served at the table for individual seasoning</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: My BEST Authentic Pad Thai Recipe (Pailin's Kitchen) \u2014 Watch her handling of the noodle-to-heat ratio and the tamarind sourcing decision. Her explanation of what \"authentic\" actually means in a Thai context is worth the full video.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#session-2-traditional-beef-pho","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Traditional Beef Pho","text":"<p>Skill: Long bone broth (or pressure cooker shortcut); pho spice toasting; assembly  Read first: Traditional Beef Pho</p> <p>What you're learning: Pho broth is charred ginger and onion + toasted cinnamon, star anise, cloves, and cardamom simmered with marrow bones for hours. The SE traditional version requires time (start morning). The finished broth should be clear, deeply fragrant, and lightly beefy. Everything goes in the bowl at service \u2014 herbs, sprouts, sliced raw beef (cooked by broth), lime on the side.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Traditional Beef Pho with full herb plate: Thai basil, cilantro, bean sprouts, lime, jalape\u00f1o, hoisin, sriracha</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Southern-Style Vietnamese Chicken Pho \u2014 He makes the chicken version; compare the broth-building logic and see how the aromatic charring technique carries across both.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#session-3-nasi-goreng-indonesian-fried-rice","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Nasi Goreng (Indonesian Fried Rice)","text":"<p>Skill: Day-old rice technique; shrimp paste (terasi) handling; kecap manis application  Read first: Nasi Goreng</p> <p>What you're learning: Nasi goreng is Indonesia's national fried rice \u2014 darker, more caramelized, and more complex than Chinese fried rice. The key ingredients: kecap manis (sweet soy sauce) and terasi (shrimp paste, which must be toasted in the pan). Make the day before's leftover rice the base.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Nasi Goreng topped with a fried egg (mandatory) and prawn crackers (krupuk) - Pickled cucumber + sliced tomato on the side</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Egg Fried Rice Three Ways \u2014 He shows the same day-old rice technique across three styles; notice what changes and what the wok heat is really doing in each version.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#session-4-curry-laksa-malaysian","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Curry Laksa (Malaysian)","text":"<p>Skill: Coconut curry broth; building the spice paste (rempah) from scratch; laksa garnish assembly  Read first: Curry Laksa</p> <p>What you're learning: Laksa is a rich coconut curry noodle soup from Malaysia and Singapore with a spice paste base that includes lemongrass, galangal, dried shrimp, and shallots \u2014 blended and fried until fragrant. The broth is finished with coconut milk. The result is silky, spiced, and uniquely complex. It's one of the great noodle soups of the world.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Curry Laksa with tofu puffs, shrimp, bean sprouts, hard-boiled egg, laksa leaf - Sambal on the side</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Thai Green Curry Recipe \u2014 The Right Way (Pailin's Kitchen) \u2014 Coconut-based Southeast Asian curry vs. the laksa you just made: same base logic, different spice architecture. Watch how she blooms the paste before the coconut milk.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#session-5-project-thai-chicken-satay-som-tam","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Thai Chicken Satay + Som Tam","text":"<p>Skill: Satay marinade (turmeric, lemongrass, coconut milk); peanut sauce from scratch; green papaya prep  Read first: Thai Chicken Satay | Som Tam \u2014 Green Papaya Salad</p> <p>What you're learning: Satay is Southeast Asian street food at its most elegant: thin strips of marinated chicken threaded on bamboo skewers, grilled over direct fire, served with peanut sauce and fresh cucumber. Som tam is the great Thai salad made of shredded unripe green papaya, fish sauce, lime, palm sugar, chiles, and peanuts \u2014 pounded in a mortar, not dressed like a Western salad.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Thai Chicken Satay with peanut sauce - Som Tam (green papaya salad) - Sticky rice if available</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Thai Pork Satay &amp; Peanut Sauce (Pailin's Kitchen) \u2014 Pork vs. chicken, same skewer. Her peanut sauce proportions are worth writing down \u2014 compare them directly to what you made.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#block-48-pad-see-ew-pho-ga-rendang-banh-mi-and-the-third-quarter-review","title":"Block 48 \u2014 Pad See Ew, Pho G\u00e0, Rendang, Banh Mi, and the Third Quarter Review","text":""},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#session-6-pad-see-ew","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Pad See Ew","text":"<p>Skill: Wide rice noodle technique; high-wok-heat char (\"wok hei\"); soy-based noodle sauce  Read first: Pad See Ew</p> <p>What you're learning: Pad See Ew uses wide rice noodles (sen yai) that require different handling than the thin noodles in pad Thai \u2014 they tear easily, must be very fresh, and need the highest possible heat to develop the char edges that make the dish. This is a wok heat exercise. Use the hottest burner you have.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pad See Ew with beef or chicken - Simple cucumber salad with rice vinegar</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#session-7-chicken-pho-pho-ga-30-minute-pressure-cooker","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Chicken Pho (Pho G\u00e0 \u2014 30-Minute Pressure Cooker)","text":"<p>Skill: Pressure cooker pho technique; understanding pho g\u00e0 vs. pho b\u00f2; quick broth extraction  Read first: 30-Minute Pressure Cooker Pho G\u00e0</p> <p>What you're learning: Pho g\u00e0 is lighter and faster than beef pho. The pressure cooker approach extracts enough flavor in 20\u201325 minutes from a whole chicken broken down with aromatics. Compare it to the beef pho from Session 1 Block 39 \u2014 how does the lighter chicken broth change the eating experience?</p> <p>Full Meal: - Pho G\u00e0 with the same herb plate: basil, lime, bean sprouts, chili</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#session-8-banh-mi","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Banh Mi","text":"<p>Skill: Picking/curing the daikon and carrot; Vietnamese p\u00e2t\u00e9 or headcheese; bread selection  Read first: Breakfast Banh Mi</p> <p>What you're learning: Banh mi is the culinary child of French colonialism \u2014 a baguette (French bread) filled with Vietnamese proteins and condiments. The DO-AHEAD element: the pickled daikon and carrot must be made at minimum 1 hour ahead (overnight is better). The bread must be light and crackly \u2014 a French roll, specifically.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Banh Mi sandwiches (one of: pork belly, grilled pork, chicken liver p\u00e2t\u00e9 + fried egg, or breakfast style) - Fresh jalape\u00f1o slices, cucumber spears, extra cilantro</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#session-9-beef-rendang-malaysianindonesian","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Beef Rendang (Malaysian/Indonesian)","text":"<p>Skill: Dry coconut braising technique; toasting desiccated coconut; rendang spice paste  Read first: Beef Rendang</p> <p>What you're learning: Rendang is one of the few dishes that is wet (a braise) when it starts and completely dry when it's done \u2014 the coconut milk reduces entirely, and the beef almost fries in its own coconut fat at the end. This creates an intensely caramelized, complex exterior that stores for a week at room temperature. A technical masterpiece.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Beef Rendang - Steamed jasmine rice and coconut rice (variation) - Cucumber and tomato kachumber</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#session-10-project-southeast-asian-dinner-party-selection","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Southeast Asian Dinner Party (Selection)","text":"<p>Skill: Multi-nationality Southeast Asian menu; timing a large spread  Goal: Build a Southeast Asian dinner from dishes spanning the block:</p> <p>Choose 3\u20134: - Som Tam (can make ahead or make fresh) - Satay skewers (make fresh on the grill) - Curry Laksa (make broth ahead; assemble to order) - Nasi Goreng (best made on the spot at high heat) - Beef Rendang (reheat from Session 4 beautifully) - Pho G\u00e0 broth from Session 2 as an opening \"tea\"</p> <p>Full Meal: - Southeast Asian Dinner Party - Tropical fruit for dessert: mango, pineapple, papaya - Thai iced tea or fresh coconut water</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#fish-sauce-and-fermented-flavors","title":"Fish Sauce and Fermented Flavors","text":"<p>Fish sauce is the backbone flavor of Thai, Vietnamese, and Indonesian cooking the way soy sauce is for Japanese and Chinese. Understanding how to use it \u2014 early for depth, late for brightness \u2014 is the central skill of SE Asian cooking.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Pad Thai \u2014 The full recipe and technique breakdown, including the proper sequence for tamarind, fish sauce, and sugar.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Pad Kee Mao (Drunken Noodles) \u2014 Another noodle dish from the Thai canon, using similar technique with different aromatics.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Pad See Ew \u2014 The third of the major Thai noodle preparations. These three together cover the core wok-noodle technique at different heat levels.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#wok-hei-the-impossible-home-kitchen-goal","title":"Wok Hei: The Impossible Home Kitchen Goal","text":"<p>Wok hei \u2014 the breath of the wok \u2014 is the smoky, slightly charred flavor you taste at Thai and Chinese restaurants. It's produced by extremely high heat (above what most home burners can generate) and professional woks. You probably can't fully replicate it at home, but you can get closer.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Traditional Beef Pho \u2014 The 8-hour stock approach, the spice-toasting technique, and the charred ginger and onion that give pho its signature depth.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Hot, Sour, Salty, Sweet by Jeffrey Alford &amp; Naomi Duguid \u2014 A sprawling, beautiful book on SE Asian cooking organized by the flavors of the region rather than by country. Essential reading if this week sparked serious interest.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#module-4-checkpoint","title":"Module 4 Checkpoint","text":"<p>Before you move on to Module 5 (Mastery &amp; Pastry), take stock of where you are. Module 5 assumes you can execute a full dinner under pressure. The world cuisine work you've done gave you eight new flavor grammars. The question is whether they've landed.</p> <p>This is not graded. It is honest.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#cuisine-fluency-benchmark","title":"Cuisine Fluency Benchmark","text":"<p>Pick any cuisine from Module 4 \u2014 one you want to cook again. Write its pantry logic from memory:</p> <ul> <li>What fat does it use?</li> <li>What acid does it use?</li> <li>What are its three foundational aromatics?</li> <li>What cooks the aromatics in \u2014 dry pan, oil bloom, or wet paste?</li> </ul> <p>You shouldn't need notes. If you do for more than two cuisines, those are the ones to revisit before Block 45.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#cook-from-memory-test","title":"Cook-From-Memory Test","text":"<p>Without opening any recipe, cook one of the following from scratch:</p> <ul> <li>A complete Japanese meal: rice, dashi-based soup, one protein, one pickled or dressed vegetable</li> <li>A French bistro plate: protein with a pan sauce using fond + wine + butter, one classic vegetable preparation</li> <li>A SE Asian bowl: the correct balance of fish sauce, lime, sugar, and heat \u2014 served over rice or noodles</li> </ul> <p>The only rule: once anything goes on heat, no tabs open.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/index.html#skills-checklist","title":"Skills Checklist","text":"<p>Before Module 5, you should be able to answer yes to all of these:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] I can identify the pantry logic (fat, acid, aromatics, heat profile) of at least five of the eight cuisines from this module</li> <li>[ ] I know what \"wok hei\" is and have produced it at least once (or understand why my setup limits it)</li> <li>[ ] I can make a French pan sauce from fond \u2014 deglazing with wine, reducing, mounting with butter</li> <li>[ ] I can cook a complete Indian dish from scratch: whole-spice bloom, paste, protein or vegetable, final seasoning</li> <li>[ ] I understand how Mexican chili-based sauces (mole, enchilada, adobo) are built \u2014 and have made at least one</li> <li>[ ] I can plate three components of a meal so they finish together</li> </ul> <p>If you're checking all of these: you're ready for Module 5.</p> <p>If you have two or more unchecked: you don't need to go back and redo every block. But identify the specific gap and cook one dish from that cuisine before Block 47. Muscle memory is the goal.</p> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 45\u201346: Middle Eastern | Block 53\u201354: Bread \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Block 43\u201344: Module 4 Capstone: Southeast Asian Cuisines","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/quick-ref.html#block-39-thailand-vietnam-indonesia-malaysia","title":"Block 39 \u2014 Thailand, Vietnam, Indonesia, Malaysia","text":"Session Dish Technique Key Point Session 1 Pad Thai Wok; tamarind-palm sugar sauce Pre-mix sauce and taste before cooking Session 2 Traditional Beef Pho Charred aromatics; long bone broth Start morning; clear broth required Session 3 Nasi Goreng Shrimp paste toast; kecap manis; day-old rice Terasi must be cooked in the pan Session 4 \u23f0 Curry Laksa Rempah (spice paste) fried in oil; coconut broth Fry paste until oil separates (dry look) Session 5 \u23f0 PROJECT: Satay + Som Tam Grilled skewers; mortar-pounded papaya salad Pound, don't toss the som tam"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/quick-ref.html#block-40-pad-see-ew-pho-ga-banh-mi-rendang","title":"Block 40 \u2014 Pad See Ew, Pho G\u00e0, Banh Mi, Rendang","text":"Session Dish Technique Key Point Session 6 Pad See Ew Wide noodle wok; maximum heat for char Fresh wide noodles only Session 7 Pho G\u00e0 (Pressure Cooker) Quick broth extraction Compare to beef pho; lighter character Session 8 Banh Mi Pickled daikon + carrot; Vietnamese protein in French bread Pickle night before Session 9 Rest + Review Third-Quarter Journal 9 months in \u2014 write your review Session 10 Beef Rendang Wet \u2192 dry braise; all coconut milk evaporates Takes 3\u20134 hrs; don't rush dry Session 11 PROJECT: SE Asian Dinner Party Multi-dish selection; timing across cuisines Start broth before guests arrive"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/quick-ref.html#flavor-balance-reference-southeast-asian-five-element-seasoning","title":"Flavor Balance Reference \u2014 Southeast Asian Five-Element Seasoning","text":"Element Thai Vietnamese Indonesian Malaysian Salty Fish sauce (nam pla) Fish sauce (n\u01b0\u1edbc m\u1eafm) Kecap asin / fish sauce Fish sauce / soy Sour Lime juice Lime juice Tamarind Tamarind / lime Sweet Palm sugar Palm sugar Kecap manis Palm sugar Heat Bird's eye chili Fresh chili Sambal Sambal / bird's eye Umami Shrimp paste (kapi) Dried shrimp Terasi (shrimp paste) Shrimp paste"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/quick-ref.html#key-ingredient-notes","title":"Key Ingredient Notes","text":"<ul> <li>Day-old rice \u2014 mandatory for fried rice (Nasi Goreng); fresh rice is too wet</li> <li>Shrimp paste (terasi/kapi) \u2014 smells intense raw; frying or toasting transforms it</li> <li>Palm sugar \u2014 mellower than white sugar; substitute light brown sugar if unavailable</li> <li>Wide rice noodles (sen yai) \u2014 must be fresh or soaked just before cooking; never boil before stir-frying</li> <li>Green papaya \u2014 buy unripe, rock-hard; shred with mandoline or grater</li> <li>Fish sauce brands \u2014 Tiparos, Megachef, or Red Boat (higher quality); taste varies significantly</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 43\u201344: Southeast Asian","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Where to shop: A Southeast Asian grocery (or combined Asian supermarket) is ideal. You need: fresh wide rice noodles, lemongrass, galangal, kaffir lime leaves, dried shrimp, shrimp paste (terasi), kecap manis, palm sugar, fish sauce, tamarind paste, unripe green papaya, laksa paste or spice ingredients, and fresh herbs (Thai basil, Vietnamese mint, laksa leaf).</p>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Wok \u2014 essential for nasi goreng and pad see ew; cast iron acceptable but wok preferred</li> <li>[ ] Mortar and pestle \u2014 for som tam (clay mortar preferred for Thai salads)</li> <li>[ ] Pressure cooker or Instant Pot \u2014 for pho g\u00e0 (Tue Week 40) and pho b\u00f2 (Tue Week 39)</li> <li>[ ] Bamboo skewers \u2014 soaked 30 min before grilling (satay Sat Week 39)</li> <li>[ ] Fine-mesh strainer \u2014 for pho broth</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-39","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 39","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Shrimp \u2014 1 lb, peeled (Mon Pad Thai)</li> <li>[ ] Beef bones with marrow \u2014 2\u20133 lbs (Tue pho broth)</li> <li>[ ] Beef brisket or eye round \u2014 1 lb (Tue pho \u2014 cooked brisket slice + raw thin-sliced for bowl)</li> <li>[ ] Chicken thighs \u2014 1 lb (Sat satay)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#proteins-week-40","title":"\ud83e\udd69 Proteins \u2014 Week 40","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Beef or chicken \u2014 1 lb, thinly sliced (Mon Pad See Ew)</li> <li>[ ] Whole chicken \u2014 3.5\u20134 lbs (Tue Pho G\u00e0 \u2014 break it down yourself)</li> <li>[ ] Pork belly \u2014 1 lb (Wed Banh Mi \u2014 marinate + roast or braise)</li> <li>[ ] Beef chuck \u2014 2 lbs (Fri Rendang \u2014 cut into 3-inch chunks)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (nasi goreng, banh mi egg, various)</li> <li>[ ] Extra firm tofu \u2014 1 block (laksa Fri Week 39; optional pad Thai Mon Week 39)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#fresh-southeast-asian-aromatics-asian-market","title":"\ud83c\udf3f Fresh Southeast Asian Aromatics (Asian Market)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Lemongrass \u2014 4 stalks</li> <li>[ ] Galangal \u2014 1 small piece (or substitute ginger; not the same)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh ginger \u2014 1 large piece</li> <li>[ ] Kaffir lime leaves \u2014 1 pack (fresh or frozen)</li> <li>[ ] Thai bird's eye chiles \u2014 1 small bag (very hot; use with care)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh turmeric \u2014 1 small piece (or use 1 tsp ground)</li> <li>[ ] Lime \u2014 12 (used every day)</li> <li>[ ] Thai basil \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Vietnamese mint / perilla \u2014 1 bunch (pho + banh mi)</li> <li>[ ] Cilantro \u2014 3 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Green onions \u2014 2 bunches</li> <li>[ ] Unripe green papaya \u2014 1 (Sat Week 39 som tam; must be rock hard)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumber \u2014 6 (sides + banh mi + various)</li> <li>[ ] Bean sprouts \u2014 2 bags</li> <li>[ ] White onion + red onion \u2014 4 each</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#southeast-asian-pantry-asian-market","title":"\ud83e\udd6b Southeast Asian Pantry (Asian Market)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Fish sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Tiparos, Red Boat, or Megachef)</li> <li>[ ] Kecap manis (sweet soy sauce) \u2014 1 bottle (nasi goreng Wed Week 39)</li> <li>[ ] Fermented shrimp paste / terasi \u2014 1 small block (nasi goreng; laksa rempah)</li> <li>[ ] Coconut milk \u2014 4 cans (satay marinade, laksa, rendang)</li> <li>[ ] Desiccated coconut \u2014 1 cup (rendang kerisik \u2014 toast until dark golden and grind to paste; this is what makes rendang rendang)</li> <li>[ ] Tamarind paste (or block) \u2014 1 jar/block</li> <li>[ ] Palm sugar \u2014 1 block (or substitute light brown sugar)</li> <li>[ ] Oyster sauce \u2014 1 bottle (Pad See Ew Mon Week 40)</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce (light) \u2014 1 bottle</li> <li>[ ] Hoisin sauce \u2014 small jar (pho tableside)</li> <li>[ ] Sriracha \u2014 1 bottle</li> <li>[ ] Sambal oelek \u2014 1 jar</li> <li>[ ] Dried shrimp \u2014 1 small bag (som tam, rempah)</li> <li>[ ] Peanuts \u2014 roasted, unsalted \u2014 2 cups (pad Thai + satay sauce)</li> <li>[ ] Sesame oil \u2014 toasted</li> <li>[ ] Prawn crackers (krupuk) \u2014 1 bag (nasi goreng garnish)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#noodles-and-rice","title":"\ud83c\udf5d Noodles and Rice","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Flat rice noodles, thin (sen lek) \u2014 1 lb (Pad Thai Mon Week 39)</li> <li>[ ] Wide rice noodles, fresh (sen yai) \u2014 1 lb (Pad See Ew Mon Week 40) \u2014 buy day of if possible</li> <li>[ ] Pho rice noodles (medium width) \u2014 1 pack (pho Tue both weeks)</li> <li>[ ] Jasmine rice \u2014 5-lb bag</li> <li>[ ] Glutinous rice (sticky rice) \u2014 2 lbs (Sat Week 39 som tam always comes with sticky rice \u2014 eat it with your hands; also served with satay)</li> <li>[ ] Rice already cooked and cooled for nasi goreng \u2014 cook night before</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#banh-mi-components-wed-week-40","title":"\ud83c\udf3f Banh Mi Components (Wed Week 40)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Daikon radish \u2014 1 small (pickle)</li> <li>[ ] Carrots \u2014 4 (pickle)</li> <li>[ ] White vinegar \u2014 for pickle</li> <li>[ ] French baguettes or hoagie rolls \u2014 light, crackly crust mandatory</li> <li>[ ] Pork liver p\u00e2t\u00e9 or store-bought liverwurst \u2014 for classic banh mi</li> <li>[ ] Vietnamese chili garlic sauce (Huy Fong) \u2014 for banh mi</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/04-worlds-kitchens/47-48-southeast-asian-review/shopping-list.html#pho-aromatics","title":"\ud83c\udf39 Pho Aromatics","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Onion \u2014 2 (charred for pho)</li> <li>[ ] Ginger \u2014 charred for pho</li> <li>[ ] Star anise \u2014 4 pods</li> <li>[ ] Cinnamon stick \u2014 2</li> <li>[ ] Whole cloves \u2014 4</li> <li>[ ] Cardamom pods \u2014 2</li> <li>[ ] Rock sugar or regular sugar \u2014 small amount (pho broth finish)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/index.html","title":"Module 5: Mastery &amp; Pastry (Blocks 53\u201362)","text":"<p>The goal of this module: Finish strong. Bread and pastry demand precision that sharpens every other skill you've built. Then design your own signature dishes, learn to orchestrate a full dinner party, and cap the year with a self-administered final exam that proves \u2014 to yourself \u2014 that you can cook.</p> <p>By the end of Week 62, you will have completed a full professional-level culinary curriculum, delivered at home, over one year.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/index.html#weeks-in-this-module","title":"Weeks in This Module","text":"Weeks Topic Full Guide Quick Ref Shopping List 53\u201354 Bread \u2014 Fundamentals \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 55\u201356 Pastry \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 57\u201358 Your Signature Dishes \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 59\u201360 Menus, Timing &amp; Dinner Party Execution \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping 61\u201362 Module 5 Capstone: The Final Exam \u2192 Guide \u2192 Quick Ref \u2192 Shopping"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/index.html#core-skills-covered","title":"Core Skills Covered","text":"<ul> <li>Bread \u2014 levain maintenance; autolyse, bulk ferment, shaping, scoring; Pullman loaf for beginners; baking in Dutch oven</li> <li>Pastry \u2014 p\u00e2te bris\u00e9e, p\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e, rough puff; lamination logic; blind-baking; tart construction; choux</li> <li>Desserts \u2014 cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e; layer cake; Swiss and Italian meringue; ganache; bain-marie technique; tempering chocolate</li> <li>Signature dishes \u2014 developing, documenting, and refining 3 original dishes that reflect your palate and history</li> <li>Menus &amp; timing \u2014 backwards-planning a dinner party; mise en place at scale; timing charts; expediting</li> <li>Final exam \u2014 multi-course meal planned, shopped, and executed solo; written reflection on the year</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/index.html#equipment-youll-need","title":"Equipment You'll Need","text":"<p>See the Kitchen Equipment Guide. New items introduced in this module:</p> Item Introduced Kitchen scale (digital, 0.1g resolution) Week 45 Bench scraper Week 45 Banneton (proofing basket) Week 45 Pullman loaf pan with lid Week 45 Bread lame (scoring blade) Week 45 Stand mixer with dough hook Week 45 9-inch tart pan with removable bottom Week 47 9-inch pie dish Week 47 Pie weights (or dried beans) Week 47 Pastry bag + tips Week 47 Madeleine pan (optional) Week 47 Kitchen torch Week 49 Ramekins, 4\u20136 oz (set of 6) Week 49 9-inch round cake pans (\u00d73) Week 49 Pastry brush Week 49 Candy thermometer Week 49 Large roasting pan (for bain-marie) Week 49 Springform pan (optional) Week 49 Whetstone Week 57 Multiple-channel timer Week 59 <p>Previous module: Module 4 \u2014 The World's Kitchens (Weeks 31\u201348)</p> <p>Congratulations on completing the 62-Week Culinary Project. You cooked.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html","title":"\ud83c\udf5e Block 53\u201354: Bread","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 47\u201348: Southeast Asian | Block 55\u201356: Pastry \u2192</p> <p>\u2697\ufe0f Experimental \u2014 This block has not yet been cooked through by the author. Content is draft; recipes and timing are untested.</p> <p>\"Bread is the thing that most home cooks believe is beyond them and is not. It requires no special equipment, no professional skill, and no exotic ingredients. It requires: flour, water, salt, and time. The baker's greatest tool is patience, followed by touch. The recipe is the least important part.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#block-53-no-knead-focaccia-and-the-logic-of-bread","title":"Block 53 \u2014 No-Knead, Focaccia, and the Logic of Bread","text":"<p>This week establishes the principles of bread-making through the two most forgiving and impressive loaves a home baker can produce: no-knead bread (develops gluten passively through time) and focaccia (high-hydration dough with a generous olive oil soak). Both will reset your confidence about baking.</p> <p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 1 (Better No-Knead Bread): mix dough the night before the block starts (12\u201318 hr rise)</li> <li>Session 5 (PROJECT: Sourdough Starter + First Loaf): starter must be active; feed it the day before this session</li> <li>Session 6 (Sourdough: First Real Loaf): bulk ferment 4\u20135 hrs + overnight cold proof</li> <li>Session 8 (Brioche): dough needs overnight cold retard after initial mix</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#session-1-better-no-knead-bread","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Better No-Knead Bread","text":"<p>Skill: Autolyse; long cold fermentation; Dutch oven steam baking  Read first: Better No-Knead Bread</p> <p>What you're learning: No-knead bread works because a long rest (12\u201318 hours) allows gluten strands to organize themselves without the mechanical action of kneading. The Dutch oven creates the steam that a commercial deck oven provides \u2014 essential for the brittle, shiny crust. Dough should be shaggy and wet; this is correct.</p> <p>Note: Mix the dough the night before the block starts for Session 1 baking.</p> <p>Full Meal: - No-Knead Bread, first loaf - Tear and eat warm with cultured butter and good olive oil. That's the meal.</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: No-Knead Bread, Revisited \u2014 He updates the original technique with a few small tweaks; compare his rationale for the changes to what you experience with your own first loaf.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#session-2-no-knead-bread-variation-folding-technique-upgrade","title":"Session 2 \u2014 No-Knead Bread Variation (Folding Technique Upgrade)","text":"<p>Skill: Stretch-and-fold technique during bulk fermentation; shaping surface tension  Read first: Reference the better no-knead technique; try incorporating 3\u20134 rounds of stretch-and-fold during the first 2 hours</p> <p>What you're learning: The \"better\" part of Better No-Knead Bread is using the stretch-and-fold technique instead of just leaving the dough alone. This builds more structure and improves the crumb. Compare your Session 2 loaf to earlier in the block's \u2014 the crumb should be more open and even.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Bread loaf #2 with different toppings or served alongside a simple soup</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#session-3-no-knead-focaccia","title":"Session 3 \u2014 No-Knead Focaccia","text":"<p>Skill: High-hydration bread; olive oil bath; dimpling and topping technique  Read first: Easy No-Knead Focaccia</p> <p>What you're learning: Focaccia is essentially no-knead bread taken through a different shaping process (poured into an oil-slicked pan, dimpled enthusiastically, topped generously). The high olive oil content creates a crispy-bottom, fluffy-interior bread. Toppings: fleur de sel, fresh rosemary mandatory; add olives, cherry tomatoes, or caramelized onions as taste dictates.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Focaccia with simple accompaniments - Serve with whatever soup or leftover protein you have \u2014 it elevates everything</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Extra-Flavorful Focaccia (Adam Ragusea) \u2014 Watch his oil quantity and the dimpling logic \u2014 he explains why the fat pools create the crust they do. Compare to your bake: where did the oil go, and how did the surface behave?</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#session-4-pullman-loaf-sandwich-bread","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Pullman Loaf (Sandwich Bread)","text":"<p>Skill: Enriched bread dough technique; Pullman pan use; proper slice structure  Read first: Pullman Loaf \u2014 Sandwich Bread</p> <p>What you're learning: Pullman bread is the American sandwich loaf at its best \u2014 tight, even crumb, soft crust, slightly enriched (some butter and milk) so it toasts beautifully. A Pullman pan (with a sliding lid) creates the rectangular profile. This is a different bread philosophy from artisan loaves \u2014 engineered for utility as well as flavor.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Sliced Pullman bread, the ideal vehicle for anything - Make sandwiches from the week's proteins/leftovers \u2014 use your best bread for your best filling</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: A Beginner's Guide to Making the Best Sandwich Bread (Ethan Chlebowski) \u2014 He documents the texture difference between enriched loaves at different hydrations. Slice yours next to a store loaf and notice what \"structure\" actually means.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#session-5-project-sourdough-starter-first-sourdough","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Sourdough Starter + First Sourdough","text":"<p>Skill: Starting a natural yeast culture; understanding sourdough fermentation timeline  Read first: Sourdough Starter</p> <p>Note: You won't eat this bread today. Establishing a sourdough starter takes 5\u20137 days. Start it today; it will be ready for your first actual sourdough loaf in Block 42.</p> <p>What you're learning: Sourdough starter is a live culture of wild yeast and bacteria captured from the flour and air. It ferments flour as food. Feeding it (discarding and adding fresh flour + water on schedule) keeps the culture healthy. Consistency of temperature and timing is the key.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Focaccia (make a second batch if desired \u2014 your no-knead skill is solid by now) - the project dinner designed around the focaccia</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: A Non-Baker's Guide to Making Sourdough Bread (Alex French Guy Cooking) \u2014 His beginner lens matches yours right now. Watch when he knows the fermentation is right and how he reads the dough before shaping \u2014 that instinct is what you're building today.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#block-54-sourdough-croissants-and-brioche","title":"Block 54 \u2014 Sourdough, Croissants, and Brioche","text":""},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#session-6-sourdough-first-real-loaf","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Sourdough: First Real Loaf","text":"<p>Skill: Levain build; bulk fermentation judgment; shaping; cold retard  Read first: Reference the sourdough starter from Block 41; consult your flour brand's recommended ratios</p> <p>What you're learning: Your starter (if started the project session Block 41) should now be active and bubbly. Build a levain (a measured feeding of your starter used as the leavener), mix into a dough, bulk ferment 4\u20136 hours with stretch-and-folds, shape, refrigerate overnight. Bake in a Dutch oven Session 2 morning.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Continue building the starter (no bread from this session yet) - Make dinner from something non-bread related tonight</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#session-7-sourdough-bake-day","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Sourdough: Bake Day","text":"<p>Skill: Cold-retarded sourdough baking; scoring technique; reading the oven spring  Read first: Continue sourdough journey \u2014 score with a lame or sharp razor; bake covered 20 min, uncovered 20\u201325 min</p> <p>What you're learning: The most important bake of the whole bread week. Oven spring (the final rise in a hot oven), scoring (the line you cut before baking that guides the bloom), and the crumb reveal after cooling (don't cut hot \u2014 wait 1 hour minimum) are all key moments.</p> <p>Full Meal: - First real sourdough loaf - Tear open warm with butter. You earned this.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#session-8-brioche","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Brioche","text":"<p>Skill: Enriched dough with high butter content; emulsifying butter into dough; long cold overnight rest  Read first: Brioche Loaf</p> <p>What you're learning: Brioche is bread enriched with so much butter (up to 50\u201360% of flour weight) and eggs that it blurs the line between bread and cake. The butter must be at room temperature and added gradually while the dough is already developed. If you add cold butter, the gluten breaks \u2014 the emulsification is fragile and temperature-sensitive.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Brioche loaf with jam and cultured butter - Use the remaining slices for French toast the next morning</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#session-9-croissants","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Croissants","text":"<p>Skill: Laminated dough technique (d\u00e9trempe + beurrage); layering (tourage); the fold method  Read first: Croissants</p> <p>What you're learning: Croissants are laminated \u2014 thin sheets of butter layered into a dough through a series of folds, creating hundreds of distinct layers that steam and puff in the oven. This requires cold butter (firm), cold dough, and patience between rest periods. Block out the full day. The result: the most honest test of your patience and precision so far.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Croissants (plain, butter, and chocolate-stuffed if you have pastry chocolate) - This is also dinner tonight</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How to Make Amazing French Baguettes at Home (Alex French Guy Cooking) \u2014 The lamination logic in croissants and the crust logic in baguettes come from the same place \u2014 steam and structure. Watch his scoring and look for the same \"ear\" on your croissants.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#session-10-project-bread-tasting-and-final-bake","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Bread Tasting and Final Bake","text":"<p>Skill: Assessing all your bakes; understanding the baker's vocabulary for evaluating bread  Goal: Slice and taste all breads you baked this week alongside the best bread you can buy locally. Evaluate: crust texture, crumb structure, flavor complexity, fermentation character.</p> <p>Then: make one more loaf of whatever bread felt most satisfying. Practice it again while everything is fresh.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Bread tasting board with cultured butter, olive oil, jams - Build a cheese and charcuterie spread using breads as the carrier</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#gluten-the-thing-youre-actually-working-with","title":"Gluten: The Thing You're Actually Working With","text":"<p>Bread baking is flour + water + time. But the mechanism is gluten development \u2014 the protein network that traps CO\u2082 from yeast and gives bread its structure. Understanding what gluten is and how kneading, hydration, and fermentation affect it changes how you approach every recipe.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Better No-Knead Bread \u2014 The technique and the science, side by side. Why the long, cold ferment produces more complex flavor than a fast room-temperature rise.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Easy No-Knead Focaccia \u2014 High hydration, olive oil, and air holes explained. This is also the template for every Roman-style pan bread.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#sourdough-the-next-frontier","title":"Sourdough: The Next Frontier","text":"<p>No-knead and focaccia are gateway loaves. If you finished this week intrigued rather than intimidated, sourdough is the natural next project \u2014 wild yeast, longer fermentation, more complex crust.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Sourdough Starter \u2014 The complete guide to building a culture from scratch: hydration, feeding schedules, flour types, and how to know when your starter is actually ready to bake with. Don't attempt your first sourdough before reading this.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Chad Robertson shapes a loaf \u2014 The hand technique for shaping sourdough loaves is completely visual. Watch the pre-shape and the final shape before you attempt them.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Bread Science by Emily Buehler \u2014 The scientific explanation of everything that happens when you make bread \u2014 yeast activity, gluten networks, crust formation \u2014 written for home bakers who want to understand, not just follow instructions.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 47\u201348: Southeast Asian | Block 55\u201356: Pastry \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Block 45\u201346: Bread","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/quick-ref.html#block-41-the-forgiving-loaves","title":"Block 41 \u2014 The Forgiving Loaves","text":"Session Bread Hydration Method Timing Session 1 \u23f0 No-Knead Boule ~80% Mix Sun night; bake Mon 12\u201318 hr ferment + 45 min bake Session 2 No-Knead (stretch-and-fold upgrade) ~80% 3\u20134 folds in first 2 hrs Compare crumb to Session 1's Session 3 No-Knead Focaccia ~80\u201385% Pan bake; oil-slicked Mix morning; dimple + bake same day Session 4 Pullman Sandwich Loaf ~65% Enriched; Pullman pan Standard 2-hour proof Session 5 \u23f0 Sourdough Starter (start) n/a Mix flour + water; 5\u20137 day culture Won't use until Week 42"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/quick-ref.html#block-42-sourdough-brioche-croissants","title":"Block 42 \u2014 Sourdough, Brioche, Croissants","text":"Session Bread Method Key Milestone Session 6 \u23f0 Sourdough \u2014 levain build + mix Levain 4\u20136 hrs; bulk ferment; refrigerate overnight Check starter is bubbly before mixing Session 7 Sourdough \u2014 Bake Dutch oven; 250\u00b0C; covered then uncovered Score before loading; wait 1 hr to cut Session 8 \u23f0 Brioche Enriched; butter added gradually; refrigerate overnight Butter must be room temp Session 9 Croissants Laminated; 3+ book folds; refrigerate between Keep everything cold; block out full day Session 10 PROJECT: Bread Board + Rebake Taste + evaluate; rebake best loaf Compare all five breads side by side"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/quick-ref.html#bread-hydration-scale","title":"Bread Hydration Scale","text":"Bread Hydration Texture Shape Pullman / sandwich 60\u201365% Soft, tight crumb Loaf pan No-knead boule 75\u201380% Open, irregular crumb Free-form or Dutch oven Focaccia 80\u201385% Soft, airy, oily Sheet pan Sourdough 70\u201380% Open crumb, chewy Banneton \u2192 Dutch oven Brioche 65\u201370% (enriched) Tender, rich Loaf tin Croissant dough 55\u201360% Layered, laminated Rolled + shaped"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/quick-ref.html#bakers-troubleshooting","title":"Baker's Troubleshooting","text":"Problem Likely Cause Fix Dense, gummy crumb Underbaked; too much water Bake longer; check internal temp (210\u00b0F) No oven spring Weak yeast; didn't proof enough Use active starter/yeast; proper proof time Thick crust, no crunch Insufficient steam Use Dutch oven or steam pan Flat croissants Butter melted into dough during folds Keep dough cold; rest between folds Sourdough not rising Inactive starter Feed starter 2\u00d7 daily until bubbly before using"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 45\u201346: Bread","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Bread shopping is mostly flour. Get good flour \u2014 it matters here more than anywhere else in this program. King Arthur Bread Flour is reliable and widely available. For sourdough and higher-hydration loaves, bread flour (higher protein) performs better than all-purpose.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Dutch oven \u2014 essential for no-knead and sourdough; 5\u20137 quart, cast iron</li> <li>[ ] Pullman pan with lid \u2014 for sandwich bread (Block 41); ~$25\u201335</li> <li>[ ] Banneton (proofing basket) \u2014 for sourdough shaping (Block 42); optional but helpful</li> <li>[ ] Bench scraper \u2014 for dough handling</li> <li>[ ] Kitchen scale \u2014 bread is by grams, not cups; this is mandatory here</li> <li>[ ] Lame \u2014 a specialized razor blade for scoring sourdough; a very sharp knife works</li> <li>[ ] Stand mixer with dough hook \u2014 for brioche (the butter incorporation is nearly impossible by hand)</li> <li>[ ] Instant-read thermometer \u2014 internal bread temp: 200\u2013210\u00b0F when fully baked</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/shopping-list.html#flour-buy-more-than-you-think-you-need","title":"\ud83c\udf3e Flour (buy more than you think you need)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Bread flour \u2014 10 lbs (no-knead, pullman, sourdough, croissants)</li> <li>[ ] All-purpose flour \u2014 2 lbs (starter feeding, some focaccia applications)</li> <li>[ ] Whole wheat flour \u2014 1 lb (starter feeding; some add to sourdough for flavor)</li> <li>[ ] Rye flour \u2014 small bag (sourdough starter boost; optional)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Kosher salt \u2014 Diamond Crystal; other salts change hydration ratios</li> <li>[ ] Active dry yeast or instant yeast \u2014 1\u20132 packets (no-knead, pullman, brioche, croissants; sourdough uses starter)</li> <li>[ ] Olive oil \u2014 1 large bottle (focaccia uses a substantial quantity)</li> <li>[ ] Butter, European-style \u2014 2 lbs (brioche and croissants are butter-hungry; European-style has less water)</li> <li>[ ] Whole milk \u2014 1 quart (pullman enrichment, brioche)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 \u00bd pint (enriched doughs + egg wash for croissants)</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 1 dozen (brioche dough + egg washes)</li> <li>[ ] Sugar / honey \u2014 small amounts (enriched doughs)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/shopping-list.html#toppings-and-finishing","title":"\ud83c\udf5e Toppings and Finishing","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Fleur de sel or Maldon \u2014 for focaccia topping</li> <li>[ ] Fresh rosemary \u2014 2 sprigs (focaccia)</li> <li>[ ] Cherry tomatoes \u2014 for focaccia topping (Block 41)</li> <li>[ ] Olives \u2014 1 small jar (focaccia option)</li> <li>[ ] Cultured butter \u2014 Kerrygold or similar (for the bread tastings \u2014 this is the fun part)</li> <li>[ ] Good olive oil \u2014 for dipping alongside fresh bread</li> <li>[ ] Jam \u2014 2 varieties (for brioche)</li> <li>[ ] Pain au chocolat chocolate sticks or bittersweet chocolate \u2014 for chocolate croissants (Block 42)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/53-54-bread/shopping-list.html#for-cheese-and-charcuterie-board-block-42","title":"For Cheese and Charcuterie Board (Block 42)","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] 2\u20133 cheeses (firm and soft)</li> <li>[ ] Prosciutto or salami</li> <li>[ ] Cornichons, honey, whole-grain mustard</li> <li>[ ] Grapes or dried fruit</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html","title":"\ud83c\udf70 Block 55\u201356: Pastry &amp; Desserts","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 53\u201354: Bread | Block 57\u201358: Signature Dishes \u2192</p> <p>\u2697\ufe0f Experimental \u2014 This block has not yet been cooked through by the author. Content is draft; recipes and timing are untested.</p> <p>\"Pastry is baking with stakes. A bread that's slightly underbaked can go back in the oven. A puff pastry that's overworked, or a tart shell that absorbed too much liquid \u2014 those failures are harder to fix. Pastry rewards obsessive mise en place, cold everything, and the willingness to start over when something goes wrong.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#block-55-the-pastry-doughs","title":"Block 55 \u2014 The Pastry Doughs","text":"<p>French pastry week is the most technically demanding section of this program. The payoff is proportional to the investment. These are skills that make you the person in any dinner party circle who brings something people still talk about months later.</p> <p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 1 (P\u00e2te Sucr\u00e9e): tart dough needs 30+ min cold rest before rolling; make ahead</li> <li>Session 2 (Pastry Cream): make a day ahead and refrigerate \u2014 it only improves overnight</li> <li>Session 5 (Mille-Feuille PROJECT): rough puff needs cold rest between folds; start the day before</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#session-1-pate-sucree-sweet-tart-dough","title":"Session 1 \u2014 P\u00e2te Sucr\u00e9e (Sweet Tart Dough)","text":"<p>Skill: Creaming method for tart dough; blind baking; preventing shrinkage  Read first: P\u00e2te Sucr\u00e9e \u2014 Sweet Tart Shell</p> <p>What you're learning: P\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e (sweet paste) is the French shortcrust tart dough \u2014 butter creamed with sugar, then flour added just until combined, then rested cold, then pressed or rolled into a tart ring and blind-baked. The creaming method (unlike rubbing cold butter into flour for pie crust) gives it a more cookie-like texture. No water \u2014 no gluten development.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Fill the baked tart shell with pastry cream and fresh fruit (strawberry, raspberry, kiwi) - Apricot glaze finish (brush with warm apricot jam)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#session-2-pastry-cream-creme-patissiere","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Pastry Cream (Cr\u00e8me P\u00e2tissi\u00e8re)","text":"<p>Skill: Egg yolk + starch custard; tempering; the nappe; cooling without skin  Read first: Vanilla Pastry Cream</p> <p>What you're learning: Pastry cream is the filling for every French pastry: eclairs, mille-feuille, fruit tarts, cream puffs. It's thickened with cornstarch and egg yolks. The key skills: tempering (pouring hot milk slowly into yolks to prevent scrambling), cooking while whisking constantly until it thickens (it will lump if you stop), and pressing plastic wrap directly on the surface to prevent a skin.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Eclairs or cream puffs using pastry cream (choux pastry \u2014 see for the full technique, or make a basic choux: butter + water + flour + eggs piped and baked at 400\u00b0F) - Chocolate glaze dipped</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: How To Make A Fruit Tart (Claire Saffitz) \u2014 Pastry cream is the central skill in this video; watch her tempering step and the moment she declares it done \u2014 that's the texture you're aiming for.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#session-3-tarte-tatin","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Tarte Tatin","text":"<p>Skill: Dry-heat caramelization in a pan; fruit arrangement; inverted bake  Read first: Tarte Tatin</p> <p>What you're learning: Tarte Tatin is an upside-down apple tart \u2014 apples cooked in caramelized butter and sugar in a cast iron skillet, then tart dough pressed over the top and baked, then flipped. The caramel soaks into the apples and glazes the finished tart on top. Timing the inversion is the scary part \u2014 too soon and it's liquid chaos; too late and the caramel hardens.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Tarte Tatin with cr\u00e8me fra\u00eeche or vanilla ice cream - No other accompaniment needed \u2014 it's sufficient on its own</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Foolproof Tarte Tatin &amp; Rough Puff Pastry (Claire Saffitz) \u2014 Note how far she lets the caramel darken before adding the apples, and her confidence at the inversion step \u2014 that's the point most people flinch.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#session-4-choux-pastry-eclairs-or-profiteroles","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Choux Pastry (\u00c9clairs or Profiteroles)","text":"<p>Skill: Choux dough technique (p\u00e2te \u00e0 choux); piping consistent shapes; filling and glazing  Read first: Choux au Craquelin (for plain \u00e9clairs or profiteroles, skip the craquelin sugar disc \u2014 the choux base technique is identical)</p> <p>What you're learning: Choux is a cooked starch paste \u2014 one of the four French grande p\u00e2tes. The eggs are beaten in gradually; correct dough consistency is \u201cribbon-y\u201d when dropped from a spoon (falls in a thick, slow V). Underbaked choux will collapse. Properly baked choux has a hollow interior ready for filling. This technique underlies \u00e9clairs, profiteroles, goug\u00e8res, Paris-Brest, and churros.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Chocolate-glazed \u00e9clairs with pastry cream filling (pastry cream from Session 2) - Or profiteroles with vanilla ice cream + chocolate sauce</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Chocolate \u00c9clairs / P\u00e2te \u00e0 Choux (Claire Saffitz) \u2014 Watch her dough consistency test \u2014 the ribbon drop off the spoon \u2014 that's the single diagnostic that tells you whether the choux will rise properly or collapse.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#session-5-project-mille-feuille-napoleon","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: Mille-Feuille (Napoleon)","text":"<p>Skill: Rough puff pastry; baked puff sheets; layering and assembly; icing finish Read first: Mille-Feuille for the layer principle. For rough puff: grate frozen butter into flour, barely combine with ice water, fold 4x with 20-minute rests between. Store-bought all-butter puff pastry is a perfectly acceptable substitute \u2014 the assembly and pastry cream execution are the point.</p> <p>What you're learning: Rough puff achieves 70\u201380% of classic feuilletage in a fraction of the time. The mille-feuille puts everything from this block together: pastry cream from Session 2 as the filling, puff pastry sheets baked flat and weighted, icing or powdered sugar finish.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Mille-Feuille: pastry cream + puff pastry - Espresso to accompany</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#block-56-dessert-techniques","title":"Block 56 \u2014 Dessert Techniques","text":"<p>This block covers five core dessert structures \u2014 each uses a different mechanism to achieve texture and stability. These are dinner-party desserts that can be made completely ahead while guests are arriving.</p> <p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 6 (Caramel): caramel sauce keeps refrigerated for 2 weeks \u2014 make it whenever and use later</li> <li>Session 7 (Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e): custard must set 2+ hrs (or overnight) before torching</li> <li>Session 8 (Panna Cotta): needs 4+ hrs to set; ideal make-ahead</li> <li>Session 10 (Layer Cake PROJECT): bake layers a day ahead; frost the morning of service</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#session-6-dessert-sauces-caramel-creme-anglaise-and-coulis","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Dessert Sauces: Caramel, Cr\u00e8me Anglaise, and Coulis","text":"<p>Skill: The three foundational pourable dessert sauces \u2014 each using a different mechanism. Making all three in one session teaches you how fat-based, egg-based, and fruit-based sauces differ.</p> <p>Skill: Dry vs. wet caramel; egg custard thickening; fruit coulis reduction Read first: Caramel vs. Butterscotch vs. Toffee</p> <p>Caramel sauce: Sugar has distinct flavor stages as it heats. Dry caramel (no water) is faster and more consistent but harder to control. Wet caramel (water added first) is more forgiving. The difference between caramel, butterscotch, and toffee is entirely about when and how butter enters. Make a caramel sauce from scratch today.</p> <p>Cr\u00e8me anglaise \u2014 pourable egg custard: egg yolks + sugar + hot milk or cream, cooked gently to 170\u00b0F until it coats a spoon (the nappe). This is the sauce that turns a simple dessert into a restaurant plate \u2014 pool it beneath a tarte tatin, flood it around a warm chocolate brownie, or spoon it over fresh fruit.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Read: Simply Recipes \u2014 Cr\u00e8me Anglaise</p> <p>Raspberry coulis \u2014 blended and strained fresh or frozen berries with a little sugar and lemon juice. Simple, fast, bright. Used throughout the block as a foil to rich cream desserts.</p> <p>\ud83d\udcd6 Reference: BBC Good Food \u2014 Raspberry Coulis (also used in Session 8 panna cotta)</p> <p>Full Meal: - Taste all three sauces with vanilla ice cream \u2014 the comparison is the lesson - Butterscotch variation for further comparison (add butter at the start of caramel instead of the end)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Perfect Stovetop Chocolate Caramels (Claire Saffitz) \u2014 She's working at hard-crack stage rather than sauce stage; watch how she reads colour as the primary signal and treats the thermometer as secondary.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#session-7-creme-brulee","title":"Session 7 \u2014 Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e","text":"<p>Skill: Baked custard; water bath technique; caramelizing the sugar crust Read first: Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e</p> <p>What you're learning: Cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e is a baked cream custard set with egg yolks only \u2014 no whites, no starch \u2014 relying entirely on egg protein coagulation, the same mechanism as the quiche in Block 8. Here the ratio is richer (heavy cream, more yolks) and the water bath (bain-marie) provides gentle, even heat. Internal temperature: 160\u2013165\u00b0F. The sugar crust is caramelized with a kitchen torch immediately before serving.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e \u00d7 4 (make ahead; refrigerate; br\u00fbl\u00e9e right before serving)</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e &amp; Cr\u00e8me Caramel (Claire Saffitz) \u2014 She makes both in one session; the cr\u00e8me caramel comparison shows how the same custard base behaves completely differently without the br\u00fbl\u00e9e crust.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#session-8-panna-cotta","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Panna Cotta","text":"<p>Skill: Gelatin quantity and bloom; cream-to-milk ratio; demoulding Read first: Classic Panna Cotta</p> <p>What you're learning: Panna cotta is gelatin-set, not egg-set \u2014 a completely different mechanism from Sessions 7 and 9. The gelatin amount must be precise: too much and it bounces; too little and it collapses when unmolded. The right amount barely holds its shape and quivers when touched. This precision with gelatin transfers directly to bavarois, mousses, and any set cream preparation.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Panna cotta with raspberry coulis or simply excellent olive oil and sea salt (the Sicilian approach)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#session-9-chocolate-mousse","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Chocolate Mousse","text":"<p>Skill: Egg white foam; chocolate ganache base; folding without deflating Read first: Chocolate Mousse</p> <p>What you're learning: Classic French chocolate mousse is chocolate + butter, then beaten egg whites folded in. The chocolate must be cooled before the eggs go in \u2014 hot chocolate kills the foam instantly. The folding technique \u2014 large, enveloping strokes that preserve the air \u2014 is the same foundational movement used in souffl\u00e9s and g\u00e9noise cake. This is the session that teaches you how air becomes structure.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Chocolate mousse, chilled 2 hours minimum - Whipped cream + bitter chocolate shavings</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#session-10-project-layer-cake","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Layer Cake","text":"<p>Skill: G\u00e9noise or butter cake layers; simple syrup moistening; crumb coat; final frosting Read first: G\u00e9noise Sponge for the cake layers</p> <p>What you're learning: A well-executed layer cake requires: even layers (weigh the batter into the pans), flat tops (trim the dome or use baking strips), full cooling before frosting (warm cake melts buttercream), a thin crumb coat refrigerated before the final layer, and patience. Buttercream is a fat emulsion \u2014 its temperature sensitivity ties back to Block 6. Make a 3-layer cake: vanilla, chocolate ganache between layers, Swiss meringue or American buttercream outside.</p> <p>Full Meal: - Layer cake \u2014 serve to anyone available; this is a milestone bake - Champagne or sparkling water</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#pate-sucree-the-mother-of-tart-doughs","title":"P\u00e2te Sucr\u00e9e: The Mother of Tart Doughs","text":"<p>Sweet tart dough is the pastry equivalent of a mother sauce \u2014 once you can make it from memory, dozens of recipes open up. The gluten control (minimal mixing) and the fat distribution (workable but not warm) are the whole technique.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 P\u00e2te Sucr\u00e9e: Sweet Tart Shell \u2014 The full recipe with the technique notes that explain what blind baking is actually doing.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Vanilla Pastry Cream (Cr\u00e8me P\u00e2tissi\u00e8re) \u2014 Pastry cream is thickened with egg yolks and starch. Understanding the ratio between those two thickeners explains how you can adjust the texture.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#custard-science","title":"Custard Science","text":"<p>Cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e and panna cotta are both custards in the common sense, but they're set by different mechanisms: egg proteins vs. gelatin. Understanding the difference explains every texture variation in the custard family.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Classic Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e \u2014 The ratio, the water bath technique, and the blowtorch logistics all in one place.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Classic Panna Cotta \u2014 Gelatin sets at a specific concentration. This recipe explains how to dial the bloom and amount to land the texture you want.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#sticky-toffee-pudding-when-you-want-something-deeply-comforting","title":"Sticky Toffee Pudding (When You Want Something Deeply Comforting)","text":"<p>Sticky toffee pudding is a date-rich British cake soaked in toffee sauce \u2014 not a high-technique preparation, but one of the most genuinely satisfying things you can bake for people you like. It made an earlier draft of this block and was cut to keep the curriculum focused on classical technique. It earns its place on a winter table.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Sticky Toffee Pudding \u2014 The dates pur\u00e9e into the batter and disappear; the warm toffee sauce poured immediately after baking is what makes it a \"pudding.\" Serve warm with vanilla ice cream or clotted cream.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#chocolate-a-module-of-its-own","title":"Chocolate: A Module of Its Own","text":"<p>Chocolate mousse is your introduction to working with chocolate structurally. The deeper rabbit hole \u2014 tempering, ganache ratios, bonbons, bark \u2014 is long and genuinely satisfying.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Chocolate Mousse \u2014 The full recipe and technique, including the egg white folding method that creates the airy texture.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda BraveTart by Stella Parks \u2014 The most scientifically rigorous American baking book ever written. Parks applies Food Lab-style testing to pastry. If you want to understand why your tart shell shrinks (and how to stop it), start here.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 53\u201354: Bread | Block 57\u201358: Signature Dishes \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/quick-ref.html","title":"Quick Reference \u2014 Block 47\u201348: Pastry","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Shopping List</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/quick-ref.html#block-43-french-pastry-foundations","title":"Block 43 \u2014 French Pastry Foundations","text":"Session Preparation Key Technique Critical Point Session 1 P\u00e2te Sucr\u00e9e + Fruit Tart Creaming method; blind bake No water; press wrap to cool Session 2 Pastry Cream (Cr\u00e8me P\u00e2tissi\u00e8re) Temper eggs; constant whisking Plastic wrap directly on surface to prevent skin Session 3 \u23f0 Tarte Tatin Dry caramel in cast iron; inversion Time inversion: golden, not liquid, not rock-hard Session 4 Rough Puff Pastry Grated frozen butter; fold 3\u20134\u00d7 Keep cold; rest between folds Session 5 PROJECT: Mille-Feuille Baked puff sheets + pastry cream layers Level the pastry sheets; press layers gently"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/quick-ref.html#block-44-applied-pastry-quiche-pie-lemon-tart-choux","title":"Block 44 \u2014 Applied Pastry: Quiche, Pie, Lemon Tart, Choux","text":"Session Preparation Key Technique Critical Point Session 6 \u23f0 Quiche Lorraine Savory custard in tart shell Pull at 160\u00b0F; jiggly center is correct Session 7 Apple Pie (double crust) Flaky pie crust; butter-lard blend Ice cold fat; add water 1 tbsp at a time Session 8 Lemon Tart Lemon curd to 170\u00b0F; pour warm into shell Balance acid-sweet; should taste clearly sour Session 9 \u23f0 Choux Pastry / \u00c9clairs Cooked paste; eggs added one at a time Ribbon test; fully bake (25\u201330 min) Session 10 PROJECT: Afternoon Tea Multi-pastry spread; composed service Most items make-ahead; assemble 1 hr before"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/quick-ref.html#pastry-fat-reference","title":"Pastry Fat Reference","text":"Dough Fat Amount (vs. flour) Result P\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e Unsalted butter ~50\u201360% Crisp, cookie-like, not flaky P\u00e2te bris\u00e9e Unsalted butter ~40% Flaky-tender American pie crust Butter + lard ~60% combined Flaky, rich Rough puff European butter ~75% Flaky, layered Brioche Unsalted butter 50\u201360% Rich, tender, not pastry-crisp Choux Unsalted butter 40% of water weight Hollow, crisped shell"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/quick-ref.html#custard-ratio-reference","title":"Custard Ratio Reference","text":"Preparation Eggs Liquid Temp Pastry cream 4 yolks per 500ml milk Milk + cornstarch Cook to 200\u00b0F (thick and glossy) Quiche custard 1 egg per \u00bc cup cream Heavy cream Pull at 160\u00b0F Lemon curd 4 yolks + 2 whole Lemon juice + butter Cook to 170\u00b0F Cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e 5\u20136 yolks per 500ml Heavy cream + vanilla Bake to 160\u00b0F"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/shopping-list.html","title":"\ud83d\uded2 Shopping List \u2014 Block 47\u201348: Pastry","text":"<p>\u2190 Back to Full Guide | Back to Quick Ref</p> <p>Cold butter is the recurring hero of this entire block. European-style butter (84%+ butterfat, lower water) is worth the premium here \u2014 Plugr\u00e0, Kerrygold, Isigny Sainte-M\u00e8re, or similar. Everything else builds on that.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"\u26a0\ufe0f Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] 9-inch tart pan with removable bottom \u2014 for p\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e and lemon tart</li> <li>[ ] 9-inch cast iron skillet \u2014 for tarte tatin</li> <li>[ ] Pie dish \u2014 for apple pie (9 inch)</li> <li>[ ] Pie weights or dried beans \u2014 for blind baking tart shells</li> <li>[ ] Stand mixer \u2014 for choux and pastry cream whisking</li> <li>[ ] Pastry bag + tips \u2014 for eclairs; a zip-top bag with corner cut works fine</li> <li>[ ] Madeleine pan \u2014 optional (Saturday's afternoon tea)</li> <li>[ ] Box grater \u2014 for grating frozen butter into rough puff dough</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/shopping-list.html#eggs-and-dairy","title":"\ud83e\udd5a Eggs and Dairy","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 2 dozen (pastry cream, quiche, tarte tatin caramel, choux, lemon curd, cake)</li> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter, European-style \u2014 3 lbs (used every day this week; buy in bulk)</li> <li>[ ] Heavy cream \u2014 1 quart (pastry cream, quiche, chantilly, \u00e9clairs)</li> <li>[ ] Whole milk \u2014 1 quart (pastry cream)</li> <li>[ ] Cr\u00e8me fra\u00eeche \u2014 1 cup (tarte tatin serving + quiche variation)</li> <li>[ ] Gruy\u00e8re \u2014 6 oz (quiche Mon Week 44)</li> <li>[ ] Bacon lardons \u2014 4 oz (quiche lorraine Mon Week 44)</li> <li>[ ] Mascarpone or cream cheese \u2014 optional (filling variations)</li> <li>[ ] Clotted cream \u2014 1 jar (scones service Sat Week 44 afternoon tea; Devon clotted cream at specialty grocers or Whole Foods)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/shopping-list.html#produce-fruit-and-savory-fillings","title":"\ud83c\udf4e Produce \u2014 Fruit and Savory Fillings","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Apples \u2014 6 Granny Smith or Golden Delicious (tarte tatin Wed + pie Tue Week 44)</li> <li>[ ] Lemons \u2014 10 (lemon curd Wed Week 44; various)</li> <li>[ ] Fresh berries \u2014 2 cups assorted (p\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e fruit tart Mon)</li> <li>[ ] Strawberries \u2014 1 pint (tart topping)</li> <li>[ ] Kiwi \u2014 3 (tart decoration)</li> <li>[ ] Cucumber \u2014 4 (finger sandwiches Sat Week 44)</li> <li>[ ] Smoked salmon \u2014 4 oz (finger sandwiches Sat Week 44 afternoon tea; smoked salmon + cream cheese is a classic)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/55-56-pastry/shopping-list.html#pantry","title":"\ud83e\uddc2 Pantry","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] All-purpose flour \u2014 5 lbs (all doughs)</li> <li>[ ] Cake flour \u2014 1 lb (optional; lighter p\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e)</li> <li>[ ] Powdered sugar (confectioner's) \u2014 1 lb (p\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e, icing, d\u00e9cor)</li> <li>[ ] Granulated sugar \u2014 2 lbs (caramel, custard, pastry cream, pie)</li> <li>[ ] Cornstarch \u2014 1 box (pastry cream thickener)</li> <li>[ ] Kosher salt \u2014 Diamond Crystal</li> <li>[ ] Vanilla extract or vanilla bean paste \u2014 2 oz (pastry cream + various)</li> <li>[ ] Pure vanilla beans \u2014 2\u20133 (pastry cream; worth it)</li> <li>[ ] Almond extract \u2014 small bottle (optional tart variations)</li> <li>[ ] Apricot jam / preserves \u2014 1 jar (glaze for fruit tart + tarte tatin)</li> <li>[ ] Bittersweet chocolate (65\u201370%) \u2014 8 oz (\u00e9clair glaze + mille-feuille d\u00e9cor)</li> <li>[ ] Dark couverture chocolate (60\u201372%, high cocoa butter) \u2014 1 lb for Session 0 tempering; look for Valrhona, Callebaut, or Guittard; must be couverture-grade (not chips)</li> <li>[ ] Cocoa powder \u2014 (chocolate variations)</li> <li>[ ] Lard \u2014 4 oz (Tuesday Week 44 pie crust; optional but dramatically better)</li> <li>[ ] Puff pastry, store-bought \u2014 1\u20132 sheets as backup for mille-feuille (Sat Week 43)</li> <li>[ ] Ladyfingers \u2014 1 pack (optional; afternoon tea additions)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html","title":"\u2b50 Block 57\u201358: Signature Dishes","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 55\u201356: Pastry &amp; Desserts | Block 59\u201360: Menus &amp; Timing \u2192</p> <p>\"A signature dish is not the hardest dish you can make. It is the dish that is most you \u2014 the dish you make better than anyone else makes it, better every time, effortlessly, and that people ask for again and again. Signature dishes are earned through repetition, not invention.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#the-concept","title":"The Concept","text":"<p>By now you have cooked approximately 200 dishes across 46 weeks. You have made braises and stocks, fried and grilled, cured and fermented, made bread and croissants and mole. The question of this two-week block is not \"what can I make?\" but \"what do I make that is mine?\"</p> <p>A signature dish satisfies several criteria:</p> <ol> <li>Repeatability \u2014 you have made it enough times that you don't use a recipe</li> <li>Personal identity \u2014 it reflects your taste, your background, or a perfect moment</li> <li>Consistent improvement \u2014 each iteration is measurably better than the last</li> <li>Versatility \u2014 it can go on a weeknight dinner table or a dinner party table</li> </ol> <p>This block is structured differently. The first week is technical catch-up and deep refinement. The second week is your own creative project.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#before-you-start-block-57","title":"Before You Start Block 57","text":""},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#session-0-mise-en-place-at-scale-optional","title":"Session 0 \u2014 Mise en Place at Scale (optional)","text":"<p>Skill: Station organization; timing a multi-dish dinner from scratch; cook-to-plate flow Read first: Mise en Place</p> <p>What you're learning: Professional kitchens work because everything is prepped before service begins. Your mise en place practice has evolved through the year \u2014 tonight, apply it formally to a 3-course dinner. Write out every prep step before you start cooking. Time the sequence. Identify what can be done ahead vs. what is last-minute. This is the cognitive skill that separates capable home cooks from experienced ones.</p> <p>Session: - Plan a 3-course dinner entirely from your existing repertoire - Write full mise en place list before cooking - Execute using proper station workflow - Debrief: what was left undone? What hit the table late?</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#block-57-mastery-sessions-wok-knife-chocolate-mise-en-place","title":"Block 57 \u2014 Mastery Sessions: Wok, Knife, Chocolate, Mise en Place","text":"<p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 1 (Signature #1 + 2 Design): commit to both dishes now \u2014 let the ideas rest before Session 3</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#session-1-advanced-wok-technique","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Advanced Wok Technique","text":"<p>Skill: High-heat wok work; \"wok hei\" production; toss technique; seasoning a wok Read first: How to Buy, Season, and Care for a Wok</p> <p>What you're learning: Wok hei (literally \"breath of the wok\") is the smoky, slightly charred, Maillard-browned quality you get only from extremely high heat applied briefly. It requires a seasoned wok, maximum burner heat, dry ingredients, and decisive action. Today: season your wok if you haven't; cook a simple stir-fry at maximum heat and study what happens. No recipe \u2014 technique only.</p> <p>Session: - Wok seasoning (if not done): high heat + oil + paper towel \u00d7 3 - Stir-fry: aromatics, vegetables, protein, sauce \u2014 separately, in rapid sequence - Take notes: was there smoke? A char smell? What happened to the garlic?</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#session-2-knife-skills-where-are-you-now","title":"Session 2 \u2014 Knife Skills: Where Are You Now?","text":"<p>Skill: Speed and accuracy assessment; brunoise; chiffonade; the \"claw\" grip Read first: How to Chop an Onion, compare your Week 1 time</p> <p>What you're learning: Return to the first skill you practiced in Week 1. Dice an onion and track time and uniformity. Chiffonade a stack of basil leaves. Cut a carrot into fine brunoise (2mm cubes). Speed is less important than consistency \u2014 uniform cuts cook evenly; uneven cuts produce uneven results. You have cooked for 47 weeks. How much faster and cleaner is your knife technique?</p> <p>Session: - Timed onion dice (compare Week 1 estimate) - Carrot brunoise (tedious; requires patience and a sharp knife) - Basil chiffonade (sharp knife only \u2014 a dull knife bruises and blackens basil)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#session-3-the-best-chocolate-chip-cookie-refinement","title":"Session 3 \u2014 The Best Chocolate Chip Cookie (Refinement)","text":"<p>Skill: Cookie formula refinement; understanding your preferences; repeating with intention Read first: The Best Chocolate Chip Cookies</p> <p>What you're learning: The Serious Eats \"Food Lab\" chocolate chip cookie is a foundational study in technique: browned butter, bread flour, overnight rest, and the decision to use chips vs. chopped chocolate. After making them last week, today you make adjustments based on your notes. Do you want crunchier edges? More brown sugar. Chewier? More bread flour, less bake time. Crisper overall? Less brown sugar.</p> <p>Session: - Make cookie dough with intentional variation from last week - Document the variable changed and the result - Freeze half the dough as \"emergency cookies\" for future dinner parties</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Broiled Chocolate Chip Cookies (Adam Ragusea) \u2014 His technique is the opposite instinct from the Food Lab method \u2014 intense top heat vs. even oven heat. Watch how the variable changes the cookie structure and ask yourself which result you'd rather eat.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#session-4-the-caramel-sauce-perfection","title":"Session 4 \u2014 The Caramel Sauce (Perfection)","text":"<p>Skill: Repeating a technique until it is automated Focus: Caramel sauce from Week 46. Make it again. Faster and without hesitation.</p> <p>What you're learning: There is no new technique today. You are implementing the principle of \"repetition until the hands remember.\" The caramel sauce is chosen because sugar work is one of the skills that only becomes reliable through repetition. The first time you made it, you were watching the color carefully. Today you should begin to know by smell and sound.</p> <p>Session: - Caramel sauce (dry method \u2014 no water) - Butterscotch variation for comparison - Use over ice cream, cake, or sticky toffee pudding (if any remains)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#session-5-project-the-dish-you-havent-perfected-yet","title":"Session 5 \u2014 PROJECT: The Dish You Haven't Perfected Yet","text":"<p>Skill: Choosing and attacking a weak point in your cooking Goal: Make one dish from any previous unit that you felt was the weakest or least successful.</p> <p>Look back at your notes across 47 weeks. Which dish didn't go as planned? Which one did you never feel settled with? Identify it and execute it again, this time with full attention: a better understanding of the technique, a cleaner mise en place, and the experience of 47 weeks behind you.</p> <p>Session: - Choose one dish from any prior week - Research any remaining questions about it - Execute it cleanly and completely - Document: what's different, what's the same</p> <p>\ud83c\udfa5 Compare Notes: Three Salting Methods You Should Know (Samin Nosrat) \u2014 Whatever dish you chose, salt is in it. Watch her explain the \u201cwhen\u201d and \u201chow much\u201d across different protein and cooking contexts \u2014 then apply it consciously to what you're making today.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#block-58-building-your-signature","title":"Block 58 \u2014 Building Your Signature","text":""},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#session-6-define-it","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Define It","text":"<p>Exercise: Write three dishes you have made this year that you would feel confident serving to any person at any time. Not the most impressive \u2014 the most yours.</p> <p>There are no correct answers. These might be your braised short ribs, your pad thai, your sourdough, your tiramisu. They are yours because: - You made them multiple times - You know exactly where they might go wrong - You adjusted the recipe to your taste - You would make them without a recipe now</p> <p>Write these down. These are your current signatures.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#session-2-session-3-refine-signature-1-and-2","title":"Session 2, Session 3 \u2014 Refine Signature #1 and #2","text":"<p>Skill: Intentional, focused repetition Goal: Execute Signature dishes #1 and #2 from your list, back-to-back on consecutive evenings. Make notes:</p> <ul> <li>What is your personal variation from the original recipe?</li> <li>What would you serve alongside it?</li> <li>At what point in a dinner party would you serve it?</li> <li>What is the one thing that could still go wrong?</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#session-9-develop-a-new-recipe","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Develop a New Recipe","text":"<p>Skill: Synthesis \u2014 combining techniques across the 48 weeks into something original Challenge: Invent a dish or a meaningful variation on an existing dish. Use any technique from this year, applied to an ingredient or combination you have not cooked before.</p> <p>This is not a test. There is no grade. Failures here are valuable. The goal is to think like a cook \u2014 to ask \"what if\" and act.</p> <p>Session: - 30 minutes of planning (flavors, techniques, components) - Cook the experiment - Eat it, honestly assess it - Write one paragraph on what you would change next time</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#session-10-project-the-personal-tasting-menu","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: The Personal Tasting Menu","text":"<p>Goal: Cook and serve a 4-course meal entirely from your own repertoire, your own variations, for people who will give you honest feedback.</p> <p>Suggested structure: 1. Amuse-bouche: One bite \u2014 a compressed melon, a spoonful of something surprising, one perfect piece 2. Starter: A dish from your cured/vegetable/shellfish repertoire 3. Main: Your most comfortable, reliable, personal protein preparation 4. Dessert: The dessert you are most proud of from weeks 43\u201346</p> <p>House rules: - No recipe open during cooking - Music and candles acceptable - Write a menu card for the table (even if handwritten) - After dinner: ask each person for one honest criticism and one honest compliment</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#wok-mastery-building-the-foundation","title":"Wok Mastery: Building the Foundation","text":"<p>The wok is the most efficient cooking vessel ever designed. Seasoning it correctly, managing the heat zones, and developing the muscle memory for constant motion are the three skills required.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Buy, Season, and Care for a Wok \u2014 The complete guide to buying, seasoning, and maintaining a wok \u2014 from initial cure to ongoing care.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Butter-Baste Steaks, Chops, and Fish \u2014 Wok cooking and butter basting share the same principle: constant, deliberate application of fat over heat to build a crust and baste simultaneously.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#developing-a-signature-dish","title":"Developing a Signature Dish","text":"<p>The jump from following a recipe to owning a dish happens through iteration: make it 3 times, tweak one thing each time, then make it from memory. The dishes that feel like yours come from this process.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Dry-Brining Is the Best Way to Brine Meat, Poultry, and More \u2014 One of the highest-leverage techniques to apply to your signature dish if it involves any protein \u2014 the results are dramatic enough to impress guests immediately.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Martin Yan's wok technique \u2014 The master of wok showmanship, but the technique underneath is real and careful. His one-handed chopping and wok tossing are aspirational benchmarks.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Wok: Recipes and Techniques by J. Kenji L\u00f3pez-Alt \u2014 The most thorough wok cookbook ever written in English. Every heat level, every protein, every regional application. The natural follow-on from your Week 47\u201348 work.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 55\u201356: Pastry &amp; Desserts | Block 59\u201360: Menus &amp; Timing \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html","title":"Block 49\u201350: Signature Dishes \u2014 Quick Reference","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 47\u201348: Pastry &amp; Desserts | Block 51\u201352: Final Exam \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#wok-hei-what-it-is-and-how-to-get-it","title":"Wok Hei: What It Is and How to Get It","text":"Factor Requirement Common Failure Heat Maximum burner output \u2014 gas preferred Electric/induction: insufficient BTU Pan Seasoned wok; screaming hot before oil Cold wok = steaming, not searing Ingredients Dry surface; small batches Wet veg/protein releases steam Motion Constant toss; 30\u201360 seconds max Over-stirring = temperature drop Oil High smoke-point (peanut, grapeseed) Olive oil \u2192 burns bitter Sequence Aromatics \u2192 protein \u2192 veg \u2192 sauce Wrong order = mushy or raw"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#wok-seasoning-method","title":"Wok Seasoning Method","text":"<ol> <li>Heat wok over high flame until water droplets vanish instantly</li> <li>Add 1 tbsp high-smoke-point oil; swirl to coat</li> <li>Rub with folded paper towel (tongs \u2014 do NOT burn yourself)</li> <li>Repeat 3\u00d7 until surface is uniformly darkened</li> <li>Store dry; never soap-scrub; re-season if rust appears</li> </ol>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#knife-skill-self-assessment","title":"Knife Skill Self-Assessment","text":"Skill Block 1 Target Block 49 Target Benchmark Onion dice (medium) 3\u20134 minutes Under 90 seconds 1 min = professional Carrot brunoise (2mm) Rough approximation Uniform cubes Zero guesswork on size Basil chiffonade Bruised or thick Clean, thin, no black Sharp knife only Garlic minced Chunky Near-paste Flat-side press + rock Julienne carrot Skipped Consistent 2mm strips Patience + sharp blade"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#mise-en-place-workflow","title":"Mise en Place Workflow","text":"<p>Before you cook: 1. Read the full recipe twice 2. Write a mise en place list (every ingredient prepped to what state) 3. Group by timing: what cooks longest goes first 4. Set up stations: cutting board, stove, plating area</p> <p>While cooking: - Keep mise en place bowls/plates in use order left to right - Clean as you go \u2014 wipe board between tasks - Taste as you build \u2014 every layer, not just the end</p> <p>For a 3-course dinner (timing template): | Stage | Window | Tasks | |---|---|---| | T-2 hours | Active prep | Stock, braises, doughs, marinades, dessert | | T-1 hour | Component prep | All veg cut, proteins seasoned, sauces made | | T-30 min | Final staging | Plates warmed, sauces reheated, garnish ready | | T-0 | Service | Cook-to-order only; assemble components |</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#chocolate-chip-cookie-variables-decision-chart","title":"Chocolate Chip Cookie Variables (Decision Chart)","text":"Preference Adjustment Crispier edge More white sugar; higher temp (375\u00b0F); thinner dough ball Chewier center More brown sugar; bread flour; underbake slightly More complex flavor Brown butter; overnight rest (minimum); flaky salt on top Crunchy throughout Lower temp (325\u00b0F); longer bake; fully cool before eating Deeper chocolate Chopped dark chocolate instead of chips; chips melt different Bigger pools of chocolate Chopped wafers; reserve chunks for pressing on top before baking"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#caramel-trouble-guide","title":"Caramel Trouble Guide","text":"Problem Cause Fix Crystallized / grainy Sugar crystals on pan sides got in Wet brush pan sides; start over Didn't get dark enough Under-cooked; light amber isn't enough Go to deep amber (350\u00b0F+) Bitter / burnt Over-cooked past 370\u00b0F Start over Seized when cream added Cream too cold; rapid temp drop Warm cream slightly first Too thick when cool Too little cream Add more warm cream and stir"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#signature-dish-evaluation-criteria","title":"Signature Dish Evaluation Criteria","text":"<p>When deciding if a dish is \"yours,\" ask:</p> Question Yes / No Can I make this without a recipe? Have I made this 3+ times? Do I know what can go wrong and how to fix it? Have I adjusted it to my own taste? Would I serve this at a dinner party without anxiety? <p>3+ Yes answers: This is likely a signature dish for you.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/quick-ref.html#block-4950-sessions-at-a-glance","title":"Block 49\u201350 Sessions at a Glance","text":"Session Dish / Focus Key Skill Session 0 (optional) Mise en place \u2014 formal setup 3-course timing Session 1 Wok technique deep dive Wok hei, seasoning Session 2 Knife skills assessment Self-audit; brunoise Session 3 Chocolate chip cookies (refined) Variable adjustment Session 4 Caramel sauce (repeated) Automation via repetition \ud83d\udd28 Session 5 The difficult dish revisited Weak point attack Session 6 Define your signatures Reflection + writing Sessions 7\u20138 Refine signatures #1 and #2 Intentional repetition Session 9 Develop a new recipe Creative synthesis \ud83d\udd28 Session 10 Personal Tasting Menu (4 courses) Full dinner party"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html","title":"Block 49\u201350: Signature Dishes \u2014 Shopping List","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 47\u201350: Pastry &amp; Desserts | Block 51\u201352: Final Exam \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html#equipment-check","title":"Equipment Check","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] Wok (carbon steel; 14-inch recommended)</li> <li>[ ] Wok spatula (chan dao / wok shovel)</li> <li>[ ] Sharpened chef's knife (hone before Week 47 knives session)</li> <li>[ ] Whetstone or knife sharpening service if needed</li> <li>[ ] Stand mixer with whisk and paddle (cookies, buttercream)</li> <li>[ ] Digital scale (cookies)</li> <li>[ ] Kitchen timer (mise en place drills)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html#block-49-wok-session","title":"Block 49 \u2014 Wok Session","text":"<ul> <li>[ ] High smoke-point oil (peanut, grapeseed, or avocado) \u2014 16 oz</li> <li>[ ] Garlic \u2014 1 head</li> <li>[ ] Ginger \u2014 1 knob</li> <li>[ ] Scallions \u2014 1 bunch</li> <li>[ ] Protein of choice (chicken thigh, shrimp, or firm tofu) \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Mixed vegetables (bell pepper, broccoli, snap peas) \u2014 2\u20133 cups combined</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce, oyster sauce, sesame oil (use existing pantry stock)</li> <li>[ ] Cornstarch \u2014 (velveting protein if desired; existing stock)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html#block-49-cookie-session","title":"Block 49 \u2014 Cookie Session","text":"<p>Note: purchase based on your planned variation from Week 46 batch</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Unsalted butter \u2014 1 lb</li> <li>[ ] Bread flour \u2014 2 lbs</li> <li>[ ] Granulated sugar \u2014 2 cups</li> <li>[ ] Dark brown sugar \u2014 2 cups</li> <li>[ ] Eggs \u2014 6 (room temperature)</li> <li>[ ] Baking soda \u2014 (existing stock)</li> <li>[ ] Flaky sea salt (Maldon) \u2014 (existing stock)</li> <li>[ ] High-quality dark chocolate \u2014 12 oz, chopped (better than chips if trying variation)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html#block-49-mise-en-place-dinner-3-course","title":"Block 49 \u2014 Mise en Place Dinner (3-Course)","text":"<p>These items depend entirely on your menu choice; below is a suggested path:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Protein for main course (from your signature list)</li> <li>[ ] Vegetables for starter</li> <li>[ ] Dessert components (pull from existing Week 45-46 stock if any remains)</li> <li>[ ] Wine or beverage for dinner party simulation</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html#block-48-personal-tasting-menu","title":"Block 48 \u2014 Personal Tasting Menu","text":"<p>All 4 courses should be drawn from your existing repertoire. No new ingredients required that you don't already know.</p> <p>Suggested shopping by category: - [ ] Amuse-bouche protein or produce \u2014 1 small piece (enough for 1\u20132 bites per person) - [ ] Starter: pull from shellfish block (clams, mussels, oysters) or cured (gravlax, rillettes) - [ ] Main: your signature protein \u2014 buy the best quality version you can afford - [ ] Dessert: choose from Weeks 43\u201346 repertoire; buy any missing components</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html#pantry-replenishment-whole-project","title":"Pantry Replenishment (whole project)","text":"<p>Now that you are in the final weeks, check and replenish:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Extra virgin olive oil \u2014 fresh bottle</li> <li>[ ] Diamond Crystal kosher salt \u2014 full box</li> <li>[ ] Black peppercorns (whole) \u2014 grinder or mill refill</li> <li>[ ] Flaky sea salt (Maldon) \u2014 for finishing</li> <li>[ ] Vinegars \u2014 sherry, red wine, white wine (replace any empties)</li> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard \u2014 full jar</li> <li>[ ] Soy sauce \u2014 full bottle</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce \u2014 check level</li> <li>[ ] Tahini \u2014 check level (if using)</li> <li>[ ] Capers \u2014 check level</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/57-58-signature-dishes/shopping-list.html#planning-notes","title":"Planning Notes","text":"<p>Week 47 is a technical week \u2014 all sessions except Saturday are repeat/refine. Minimal shopping required beyond the cookie ingredients and the wok session.</p> <p>Week 48 is about you \u2014 the shopping list for Week 48 is entirely based on your personal signature dishes. Look at your Week 48 menu, write your own shopping list customized to those dishes, and buy the highest-quality ingredients you have all year.</p> <p>Freezer note: Cookie dough from Week 47 Wednesday should be portioned and frozen; tag with date and bake time. These are your emergency dinner party cookies for weeks 49\u201352.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html","title":"Full Guide","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 57\u201358: Signature Dishes</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#block-5960-menus-timing-dinner-party-execution","title":"\ud83c\udf7d\ufe0f Block 59\u201360: Menus, Timing &amp; Dinner Party Execution","text":"<p>\"The difference between a cook and a chef is service. A cook makes one plate. A chef makes six plates \u2014 the same plate, at the same time, every night. The home cook equivalent: hosting a dinner party where every dish hits the table at the right temperature, in the right sequence, having been made by one person.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#the-challenge-of-this-block","title":"The Challenge of This Block","text":"<p>You have now cooked approximately 230 dishes across this program. The remaining barrier between you and true fluency is not technique \u2014 it is logistics. Cooking for yourself, cooking for two, and cooking for six are three completely different skills. This block teaches the last one.</p> <p>Over two weeks, you will plan and execute three increasingly ambitious dinners, learning the structure of a tasting menu, the dynamics of cooking multiple dishes simultaneously, and the emotional control required when something goes wrong during service.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#block-59-the-architecture-of-a-dinner-party","title":"Block 59 \u2014 The Architecture of a Dinner Party","text":"<p>\u23f0 Planning Ahead</p> <ul> <li>Session 1 (Dinner Party Planning): plan your menu now \u2014 final dinner requires multi-day prep</li> <li>Session 5 (PROJECT: Final Dinner Party): write your mise en place timeline the night before</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#session-1-menu-design-theory","title":"Session 1 \u2014 Menu Design Theory","text":"<p>Skill: Menu composition; flavor arc; season-appropriate choices; dietary accommodation</p> <p>What you're learning: A menu is not a list of dishes \u2014 it is a narrative. It has a beginning (something light and inviting), a middle (the main event), and an end (resolution or surprise). Weight increases, then decreases. Flavors build and contrast. One rich dish does not follow another. One acid-forward dish cleans the palate between two heavy ones.</p> <p>Exercise: - Write three different 4-course menus using only dishes from this program - Identify the weight/flavor arc of each - Choose one to execute this Session 4</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#session-2-the-make-ahead-audit","title":"Session 2 \u2014 The Make-Ahead Audit","text":"<p>Skill: Identifying what in any menu can be prepared in advance vs. cooked \u00e0 la minute</p> <p>What you're learning: The professional kitchen trick for home cooks is the same as it is in restaurants: almost nothing at a dinner party should be cooked to order. The goal is to have 80% of the meal finished before guests arrive so you are present at the table, not absent in the kitchen. Today, take one of your three menus and do a component-by-component make-ahead audit.</p> <p>Exercise \u2014 Build a run-of-show for later in the block dinner:</p> Component How Far Ahead Notes Dessert Day before Tiramisu, panna cotta, mousse \u2014 all gel overnight Braise Day before Better the next day; reheat gently Bread Day before Slice just before service Starter Morning of Keep covered and refrigerated Sauce Hour before Hold warm in bain-marie Protein final cook 20\u201330 min before Only truly last-minute item Plating During service Pre-warm plates; garnish ready"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#session-3-timing-under-pressure","title":"Session 3 \u2014 Timing Under Pressure","text":"<p>Skill: Executing a complete 3-course meal exactly on schedule Read first: How to Set Up a Prep Station Like a Pro Cook \u2014 the professional setup framework applies directly to dinner party timing</p> <p>What you're learning: Time pressure reveals the gaps in your prep. Today, cook a full 3-course dinner with a fixed start time (say, 7:00 PM). Work backward from that time to build a prep schedule. Stick to it. If something runs late, triage: what can be held? What cannot wait? What is the fallback?</p> <p>Session: - 3-course dinner, timed to your fixed service time - Debrief in writing: what was late? What was perfect? What would you prep differently?</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#session-4-dinner-party-1-small-table","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Dinner Party #1: Small Table","text":"<p>Goal: Execute a 4-course dinner for 4\u20136 guests on schedule, without major stress</p> <p>Suggested menu structure (your choices): 1. Amuse / nibbles: Put these out as guests arrive \u2014 olives, charcuterie, something spreadable, bread 2. Starter: Cold or room-temperature (already plated before guests sit) 3. Main: Your most reliable protein preparation; components made-ahead; only final cooking during service 4. Dessert: Fully pre-made and refrigerated; plate during main course clearing</p> <p>Rules: - Kitchen timer on from the moment the first guest sits down - Estimate each course's timing and stick within 10 minutes - Clear one course completely before the next appears - Pour between courses; don't rush</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#session-5-post-dinner-debrief","title":"Session 5 \u2014 POST-DINNER DEBRIEF","text":"<p>No cooking today. Write or record:</p> <ol> <li>What went exactly as planned?</li> <li>What went wrong and how did you recover?</li> <li>Which dish got the best reaction?</li> <li>What would you change about the menu composition?</li> <li>At what point did you feel most and least in control?</li> </ol>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#block-60-advanced-service-larger-table-multi-course-timing","title":"Block 60 \u2014 Advanced Service: Larger Table, Multi-Course Timing","text":""},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#session-6-scaling-recipes","title":"Session 6 \u2014 Scaling Recipes","text":"<p>Skill: Scaling a recipe from 4 to 8 to 12 servings; understanding what doesn't scale linearly Read first: How to Scale a Recipe</p> <p>What you're learning: Most recipes scale linearly in ingredients \u2014 double the recipe, double the quantities. But timing does not scale linearly: a 2-inch-thick steak and a 4-pound roast don't take twice as long in proportion; they take 4\u00d7 longer. Braising liquid doesn't always need to double. Seasoning perception can shift when quantities are large. Baking, especially, does not always scale simply.</p> <p>Exercise: - Take your Session 4 dinner recipe and scale it from 4 to 8 servings - Identify every element that requires adjustment beyond simple multiplication - Practice scaling a sauce or braise quantity on your stovetop</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#session-7-the-art-of-mise-en-place-for-groups","title":"Session 7 \u2014 The Art of Mise en Place for Groups","text":"<p>Skill: Station organization with multiple active pots and pans; delegating one component to a helper Read first: How to Set Up a Prep Station Like a Pro Cook</p> <p>What you're learning: Cooking for 8\u201310 people requires either a helper or a radically different structure \u2014 most of the meal cannot be \u00e0 la minute. Today: plan a dinner party with one additional element from Week 59's dinner, scaled to 8 people, and map out how you would execute it if you had one helper vs. none.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#session-8-wine-and-beverage-pairing-basics","title":"Session 8 \u2014 Wine and Beverage Pairing Basics","text":"<p>Skill: Pairing beverages to a multi-course meal; non-alcoholic pairing options Read first: - The Basics of Pairing Drinks With Your Food - How to Organize Your Home Bar</p> <p>What you're learning: The classic rules of pairing (white with fish, red with meat) are guidelines, not laws. What matters more: weight of the dish matches weight of the wine; high-acid food pairs with high-acid wine; salt contracts tannin. A single well-chosen bottle per course is better than a confusing progression of many. For non-drinkers: shrubs, sparkling water with citrus, and soft herbal drinks should be prepared with the same care as wine.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#session-9-final-prep-day","title":"Session 9 \u2014 Final Prep Day","text":"<p>Full day of cooking in advance: - Morning: Start anything that requires 4+ hours (braise, stock, dessert, dough) - Afternoon: All vegetable prep; all sauces; all components plated/organized - Evening: Final walkthrough of your mise en place; set the table; rest</p> <p>Target: When guests arrive the project session, you have less than 30 minutes of cooking left.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#session-10-project-dinner-party-2-the-full-table","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Dinner Party #2 \u2014 The Full Table","text":"<p>Goal: A complete, multi-course dinner party for 6\u201310 guests executed with composure</p> <p>Five-course structure: 1. Canap\u00e9s / cocktail nibbles (served standing before sitting) 2. Cold starter (plated in advance) 3. Soup or palate cleanser (optional; ideal for refining timing) 4. Main course with sides (the centerpiece; 2+ components) 5. Dessert (pre-made; plated during main clearing)</p> <p>Metrics for success: - Every course served within 15 minutes of the target time - No course served cold that should be hot - You sat at the table for at least 60% of the meal - The dessert was placed without panic</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#menu-design-the-architecture-behind-the-meal","title":"Menu Design: The Architecture Behind the Meal","text":"<p>A great dinner party menu isn't a collection of dishes \u2014 it's a narrative. Something light and sharp at the start, something rich and satisfying in the middle, something refreshing or sweet at the end. Understanding the rhythm of courses means every meal you host has an internal logic, even if guests can't articulate it. Getting multiple dishes to the table simultaneously \u2014 all at the right temperature, nothing held too long \u2014 isn't talent. It's planning, a written timeline, and repetition.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 Guide to Cooking With Wine \u2014 If you're building a menu, you're building wine pairings. This is the reference that covers the logic of pairing by texture, weight, and acidity.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How to Set Up a Station Like a Pro \u2014 Mise en place from Week 1, revisited at the dinner party scale. The principle of prep-before-service is the same whether you're cooking for 2 or 8.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/index.html#a-book-worth-having","title":"A Book Worth Having","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda Setting the Table by Danny Meyer \u2014 Meyer built some of New York's most beloved restaurants. This book is about the art of hospitality \u2014 how the experience of a meal is constructed beyond what's on the plate. Essential reading if you want to understand what separates a good dinner party from one people talk about afterward.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 57\u201358: Signature Dishes | Block 61\u201362: Final Exam \u2192</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html","title":"Block 59\u201360: Menus, Timing &amp; Dinner Party Execution \u2014 Quick Reference","text":""},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html#block-overview","title":"Block Overview","text":"Weeks 59\u201360 Focus Menu design, timing, multi-course execution, hosting Project Sessions Session 5: POST-DINNER DEBRIEF \u00b7 Session 10: Full Dinner Party Key Equipment All the equipment you already own \u2014 this block is about organization, not new gear"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html#the-make-ahead-hierarchy","title":"The Make-Ahead Hierarchy","text":"Component When to Prep Strategy Dessert Day before Anything that needs to set or chill overnight Braise Day before (or 2 days before) Reheats better; sauce concentrates Stocks and sauces Day before Refrigerate; reheat gently before service Bread Day before Slice at service; wrap tightly Starter (cold) Morning of Plate before guests arrive Vegetables (prepped) Morning of or afternoon Covered in damp towel in refrigerator Protein (final cook) 20\u201330 min before service The only truly \u00e0 la minute element Plating During service Pre-warm plates; garnishes staged"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html#the-timeline-building-process","title":"The Timeline-Building Process","text":"<p>Start with your target service time (e.g., 7:00 PM) and work backward:</p> Time Before Service What You're Doing 3+ days before Menu finalized; shopping list written 2 days before Long braises, stocks, desserts made Day before Bread, additional make-ahead components Morning of Vegetable prep; sauce base; mise en place 2 hours before Final prep; stress test the timeline 1 hour before Protein ready to cook; plates warming; table set 30 min before Table set; yourself ready; low-stress mode Guests arrive Final thing still cooking: 1 item maximum"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html#flavor-arc-menu-composition-principles","title":"Flavor Arc \u2014 Menu Composition Principles","text":"Position Weight Flavor Direction Example Amuse / nibbles Very light Savory, snackable Olives, charcuterie, blini Cold starter Light Acid-forward, fresh Salad, crudo, ceviche Soup (optional) Medium Comfort, warmth Bisque, consomm\u00e9, velout\u00e9 Main Heavy Rich, satisfying Braise, roast, pasta centerpiece Cheese (optional) Medium-heavy Savory finish before sweet 2\u20133 cheeses with accompaniments Dessert Light-sweet Resolution, contrast Panna cotta, tart, sorbets <p>Rule: Never follow rich with rich. Every course should prep the palate for the next.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html#scaling-what-does-and-doesnt-scale-linearly","title":"Scaling \u2014 What Does and Doesn't Scale Linearly","text":"What Scales Linearly What Does NOT Scale Linearly Ingredient quantities Cooking time for thick proteins Basic ratios (1 tbsp per pound, etc.) Oven temperatures Seasoning by weight Baking (chemistry changes at scale) Braising liquid volume (roughly) Reduction times Sauce yields Delicate emulsions (may break) <p>General rule: Ingredients scale linearly. Time and heat do not.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html#wine-beverage-pairing-quick-reference","title":"Wine &amp; Beverage Pairing Quick Reference","text":"Dish Weight Pairing Direction Light (salads, seafood, delicate proteins) Light-bodied, high-acid wine or sparkling Rich (braises, cream sauces, roasts) Full-bodied red or white; lower acid Spicy Off-dry Riesling, sparkling; avoid high tannin (amplifies heat) Fatty/Rich (pork belly, duck, cheese) High-acid cuts through fat; Champagne is the cheat code Dessert Wine must be sweeter than the dish; otherwise the wine tastes flat <p>For non-drinkers: Treat shrubs (vinegar-fruit syrups), sparkling water with citrus, and herb-infused still water as seriously as wine pairings.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/quick-ref.html#service-checklist","title":"Service Checklist","text":"<p>Night before: - [ ] All make-ahead cooking done - [ ] Mise en place list written for cooking day - [ ] Table setting plan confirmed</p> <p>Day of: - [ ] Vegetable prep completed - [ ] Starters plated and refrigerated - [ ] Sauces made and warmed - [ ] Plates warming in low oven or dishwasher safe warming setting - [ ] Dessert ready or in refrigerator</p> <p>During service: - [ ] First course goes out before you sit down (or as guests sit) - [ ] Clear each course completely before next appears - [ ] Pour between courses; use the transition - [ ] Last course cleared \u2192 dessert \u2192 coffee or tea \u2192 relax</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html","title":"Block 59\u201360: Menus, Timing &amp; Dinner Party Execution \u2014 Shopping List","text":"<p>This block has no fixed recipes \u2014 you will be executing dinners from your own menu choices. The list below covers what you are likely to need for a dinner party of 4\u20136 and the planning materials.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#this-block-is-different","title":"This Block Is Different","text":"<p>Unlike every other block, Block 59\u201360 doesn't prescribe what you cook. You choose the menu from dishes you've learned throughout the program. The shopping list below is a template and checklist, not a fixed list.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#planning-materials","title":"Planning Materials","text":"Item Purpose Notebook or printed planning sheet Writing timeline, run-of-show, and mise en place lists Timer or phone with multiple alarms Tracking course pacing during service Sticky notes or whiteboard Staging notes during day-of prep"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#session-3-3-course-timed-dinner-solo-practice","title":"Session 3 \u2014 3-Course Timed Dinner (Solo Practice)","text":"<p>Choose your own menu from the program. General categories likely to appear:</p> Category Likely Items Protein 1 piece per person of your chosen cut Starch Pasta, rice, potatoes, polenta, or bread Vegetable 1\u20132 vegetable preparations Sauce or condiment Pan sauce, vinaigrette, or compound butter Dessert Something fully make-ahead (fruit tart, panna cotta, ice cream)"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#session-4-dinner-party-1-small-table-46-guests","title":"Session 4 \u2014 Dinner Party #1: Small Table (4\u20136 Guests)","text":"<p>Template \u2014 adjust quantities to your menu and guest count:</p> Course Ingredients Notes Nibbles / amuse Charcuterie, cheese, olives, bread, crackers Put out immediately as guests arrive Starter Cold preparation of your choice Already plated before guests sit Main protein 6 oz per person minimum (more for generous cuts) Plan 10\u201320% extra Main starch 3\u20134 oz dry pasta or 6 oz potatoes per person Main vegetable 4\u20136 oz per person Sauce Enough to coat all plates (2\u20133 tbsp per person) Make extra Dessert Fully pre-made Account for dietary restrictions Wine or beverage 1 bottle per 2 guests minimum for a dinner party Pair to menu <p>Pantry to have stocked: - [ ] Kosher salt, black pepper - [ ] Olive oil and neutral oil - [ ] Unsalted butter - [ ] Stock (beef, chicken, or vegetable) at least 1 qt - [ ] Dijon mustard - [ ] Capers, anchovies, or other flavor boosters - [ ] Bread and good butter (always, always)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#session-10-project-full-dinner-party-610-guests","title":"Session 10 \u2014 PROJECT: Full Dinner Party (6\u201310 Guests)","text":"<p>Template \u2014 5-course dinner:</p> Course Category Make-Ahead Status 1. Canap\u00e9s / nibbles Purchased or simple from scratch Same day or day before 2. Cold starter Salad, crudo, terrine, charcuterie Morning of 3. Optional soup or palate cleanser Simple, elegant Day before; reheat gently 4. Main course + sides Your centerpiece dish Protein: day-of; sides: day before 5. Dessert Pre-made, unmolded at service Day before <p>Quantities for 8 people (adjust):</p> Item Quantity Main protein 6\u20138 oz per person = 3.5\u20134 lb total (bone-in adds weight) Starter salad greens 2 oz per person = 1 lb Starch (dry pasta) 3 oz per person = 1.5 lb dry Two vegetable sides 4 oz per person each = 2 lb each Sauce Double what you think you need Wine 1 bottle per 2\u20133 guests + 1 bottle reserve Bread 2 loaves for 8 Butter 1\u20132 sticks for the table"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#things-to-have-ready-in-your-kitchen","title":"Things to Have Ready in Your Kitchen","text":"<p>Before Session 4 begins: - [ ] All make-ahead components refrigerated or finished - [ ] Plates warming or stack ready - [ ] Serving vessels chosen - [ ] Timer set for each course gap (aim for 15\u201320 minutes between courses) - [ ] Water glasses and wine glasses on table - [ ] Garbage space cleared in kitchen - [ ] Only 1 component still requiring active cooking at service</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/59-60-menus-and-timing/shopping-list.html#notes-for-planning","title":"Notes for Planning","text":"<p>Protein math: - 6 oz raw per person for a boneless centerpiece protein - 8\u201310 oz raw per person for bone-in (bone adds weight; guests eat less net) - Braises typically lose 25\u201330% weight during cooking \u2014 buy more than it seems you need</p> <p>Alcohol-free dinner party pairings to source: - Sparkling water (multiple bottles \u2014 this runs out) - Citrus \u2014 lemon, lime for sparkling water or shrub drinks - Shrub or drinking vinegar: look at specialty food stores or make your own - Good-quality non-alcoholic sparkling wine if available</p> <p>For guests with dietary restrictions: - Ask at invitation time, not the day before - Plan one substitution path for each restriction rather than an entirely separate meal - Most vegetarian adaptations of your protein dish work well (roasted mushrooms, cauliflower steak, or a well-seasoned legume dish at the centerpiece)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html","title":"Full Guide","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 59\u201360: Menus, Timing &amp; Dinner Party Execution</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#block-6162-the-final-exam","title":"\ud83c\udf93 Block 61\u201362: The Final Exam","text":"<p>\"There is no final exam with a pass or fail. There is only the cook you have become, compared to the cook you were. The real exam was every Session 1 morning when you had to decide to keep going. You kept going.\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#the-year-in-review","title":"The Year in Review","text":"<p>Sixty weeks of cooking. Approximately 300 to 350 dishes executed. Knife skills you didn't have. Stocks you now make on weekends without being asked. Techniques stored in your hands that require no recipes to activate.</p> <p>The final two weeks of this program are structured as a culmination and a retrospective \u2014 not a performance or an audition, but a homecoming. You will cook three meals that mean something: the most ambitious dinner you have ever planned, a quiet version of the first meal you ever cooked, and a dinner that answers the question \"who are you as a cook?\"</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#block-61-the-self-assessment","title":"Block 61 \u2014 The Self-Assessment","text":""},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#session-11-skills-inventory","title":"Session 11 \u2014 Skills Inventory","text":"<p>Exercise: Pull out any notes, journals, or memories from Week 1. Answer the following questions honestly:</p> <ol> <li>What was the first dish you cooked in Week 1?</li> <li>Which week was the hardest? Why?</li> <li>What is a dish you thought you'd never make \u2014 and then made?</li> <li>What technique do you still find genuinely difficult?</li> <li>What do you now do without thinking that required real concentration in Week 1?</li> </ol> <p>Read first: The Serious Eats Knife Tutorial \u2014 your original knife skill reference. Time yourself on an onion dice. Compare.</p> <p>Session: Write at least one page (or record notes). This is the benchmark that gives meaning to everything else.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#session-12-the-forgotten-dish","title":"Session 12 \u2014 The Forgotten Dish","text":"<p>Exercise: Cook one dish from the first 10 weeks that you have not returned to since. Not because it was bad \u2014 because life moved on and you never circled back.</p> <p>Dig into weeks 1\u201310. Find the dish you meant to repeat but didn't. Cook it today with all subsequent knowledge applied.</p> <p>Session: - Choose and cook the dish - Note how differently you approach it now - Serve it simply; eat and think</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#session-13-cook-something-from-memory","title":"Session 13 \u2014 Cook Something From Memory","text":"<p>Skill: Executing a complete dish with no written recipe Challenge: Cook a complete 2-course meal entirely from memory. No recipe open. No quick checks. Only what your hands remember.</p> <p>This is the final practical test. It is not graded. But it reveals \u2014 more clearly than any other measure \u2014 what you have actually internalized vs. what you have only read.</p> <p>Debrief: Afterward, look up the recipe you cooked from memory. Where did you differ? Was your version better or worse? Why?</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#session-14-the-final-mise-en-place-drill","title":"Session 14 \u2014 The Final Mise en Place Drill","text":"<p>Skill: Professional prep at home speed Goal: Prep a full 4-course dinner in under 2 hours of active kitchen time, starting from whole uncut ingredients</p> <ul> <li>Protein seasoned and resting</li> <li>All vegetables cut, portioned, organized</li> <li>All sauces made or prepped</li> <li>Dessert in refrigerator</li> <li>Table set</li> <li>You showered and at ease by 6 PM</li> </ul> <p>Whether or not guests are invited, execute the prep as if they are.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#session-15-project-the-anniversary-dinner","title":"Session 15 \u2014 PROJECT: The Anniversary Dinner","text":"<p>Goal: Cook the dinner you would serve to mark the completion of this year</p> <p>Who do you invite? Your closest people. People who have eaten with you, who watched you improve, who benefited from your cooking experiments. A minimum of 4, a maximum of however many fit at your table.</p> <p>The menu: Let it be entirely yours. No prescribed structure. What do you want to cook? What represents the year? What represents you?</p> <p>Suggested constraints only: - At least 3 courses - At least one dish you learned in the first half of the year - At least one dish from the second half - One true new thing you've never served before</p> <p>Serve it. Sit at the table. Be present.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#block-62-the-final-exam","title":"Block 62 \u2014 The Final Exam","text":""},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#session-16-define-the-exam-for-yourself","title":"Session 16 \u2014 Define the Exam for Yourself","text":"<p>Exercise: Write a brief personal culinary philosophy. 1\u20133 paragraphs. Answer these questions:</p> <ol> <li>What kind of cook do you want to be?</li> <li>What role does food play in your life now, compared to a year ago?</li> <li>What is your signature dish (from the Signature Dishes block)?</li> <li>What is the most valuable single thing you learned this year?</li> </ol> <p>There are no correct answers. There is only what is true for you.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#session-17-cook-the-final-exam-dish","title":"Session 17 \u2014 Cook the Final Exam Dish","text":"<p>The exam: Cook one dish that represents everything.</p> <p>No constraints on cuisine, technique, or difficulty. But it must: - Require real skill (not just effort) - Be completely executed without assistance or recipe - Be something you would be proud to serve to anyone - Taste exactly the way you want it to taste</p> <p>Photograph it. Eat it. Write two sentences about it.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#session-18-the-retrospective-meal","title":"Session 18 \u2014 The Retrospective Meal","text":"<p>Exercise: Cook a meal that traces the arc of the year:</p> <ul> <li>A bite or starter from weeks 1\u201310 (foundations)</li> <li>A smaller course from weeks 11\u201330 (proteins)</li> <li>A main from weeks 31\u201350 (global techniques)</li> <li>A dessert from weeks 51\u201362 (pastry, desserts, mastery)</li> </ul> <p>This is a one-person retrospective tasting \u2014 a private tasting menu of the year. Eat slowly. Think about each one.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#session-19-the-open-kitchen","title":"Session 19 \u2014 The Open Kitchen","text":"<p>Goal: Cook for people. Whatever they want.</p> <p>Open your kitchen to family, friends, or anyone who wants to taste what you can do. Let them request dishes. Let them watch you cook. Show them the techniques. Cook without a net.</p> <p>This is not a class \u2014 you are not teaching. You are sharing.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#session-20-week-62-the-final-dinner","title":"Session 20 \u2014 Week 62: The Final Dinner","text":"<p>No instructions. No structure. No format.</p> <p>You are a cook who has spent 62 weeks building this. Tonight, cook whatever you want, for whoever you love, in whatever way feels most like you.</p> <p>The year is complete.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#what-comes-next","title":"What Comes Next","text":"<p>The 62 weeks were a foundation \u2014 thorough, rigorous, intentional. But the cooking life doesn't end at week 62; it accelerates. Every additional meal is practice. Every new cuisine is a new unit. Every dish you repeat is a refinement.</p> <p>Resources to continue:</p> <ul> <li>Serious Eats \u2014 your primary source throughout; continue using it</li> <li>Kenji L\u00f3pez-Alt's work \u2014 the Food Lab framework; apply it to any new recipe you encounter</li> <li>The recipe you want to make next \u2014 start there</li> </ul> <p>The cook you are now:</p> Skill Week 1 Week 52 Sharp knife, proper grip Learning Automatic Stock from scraps Unknown Weekend habit Sauce from pan drippings Never Reflex Pasta from flour and eggs Unfamiliar Memory Sourdough from wild yeast Impossible-seeming Ongoing relationship A 3-course dinner for 8 Stressful Achievable Cook anything with what's available Unlikely The natural mode Dashi from two ingredients Unknown Instinctive Braise from scratch Intimidating Reliable A steak, cooked correctly Hit or miss Automatic <p>You are a cook. You were always going to be.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#optional-go-deeper","title":"Optional: Go Deeper","text":"<p>These aren't required reading \u2014 but if something from this block sparked a question, here's where to go.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#deepening-a-skill-you-already-have","title":"Deepening a Skill You Already Have","text":"<p>The best cooks pick one thing and develop mastery. Not breadth \u2014 depth. Pick the area that felt most alive during the year and go further.</p> <ul> <li>\ud83d\udcd6 How and When to Brine Vegetables \u2014 A small technique that applies to nearly every vegetable preparation. Classic \"go deeper\" territory.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#watching-a-pro-do-it","title":"Watching a Pro Do It","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcfa Chef's Table \u2014 Documentary portraits of the world's most interesting chefs. The best cooking education that isn't actually about cooking \u2014 it's about why a life in the kitchen matters.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/index.html#books-for-the-years-ahead","title":"Books for the Years Ahead","text":"<ul> <li>\ud83d\udcda The Food Lab by J. Kenji L\u00f3pez-Alt \u2014 If you haven't read it cover to cover yet, that's the next year of education right there.</li> <li>\ud83d\udcda On Food and Cooking by Harold McGee \u2014 The science behind everything you did this year. Read it once and you'll understand why at the level that makes you a better cook forever.</li> </ul> <p>Navigation: \u2190 Block 59\u201360: Menus, Timing &amp; Dinner Party Execution</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/quick-ref.html","title":"Block 51\u201352: Module 5 Capstone \u2014 The Final Exam: Quick Reference","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 49\u201350: Signature Dishes</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/quick-ref.html#year-end-skills-audit","title":"Year-End Skills Audit","text":"<p>Rate each skill honestly on a 1\u20135 scale: - 1 \u2014 Still can't do this reliably - 3 \u2014 Can do this correctly most of the time - 5 \u2014 Automatic; no recipe needed; would teach this</p> Skill Week 1 Rating Week 52 Rating Notes Knife skills \u2014 onion dice Sear protein without sticking Make stock from carcass/bones Pan sauce from drippings Season confidently without recipe Cook egg any style to order Emulsify a butter sauce Make fresh pasta by hand Grill protein to correct temp Braise a tough cut to tenderness Bake bread (any style) Make pastry dough (pie/tart) Make a gelatin-set dessert Cook 3-course dinner without stress Cook for 6+ people on schedule"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/quick-ref.html#52-week-cumulative-technique-reference","title":"52-Week Cumulative Technique Reference","text":"Technique Family Weeks Benchmark Dish Egg fundamentals 1\u20132 Perfect fried egg; French omelette Stocks and sauces 3\u20134 Brown chicken stock; pan sauce Knife and vegetable 5\u20136 Uniform brunoise; vegetable mise en place Braising and roasting 7\u20138 Braise to fork-tender; perfect roast Stewing and soups 9\u201310 Soup from stock; coq au vin variation Poultry all-in 11\u201312 Spatchcock roast; duck confit Beef fundamentals 13\u201316 Steak sear; short rib braise Beef advanced 17\u201318 Galbi; Bolognese from scratch Pork all cuts 19\u201320 Chashu; carnitas; porchetta Fish fundamentals 21\u201322 Crispy skin salmon; sole meuni\u00e8re Shellfish 23\u201324 Vongole; moules; lobster thermidor Curing and charcuterie 25\u201326 Gravlax; rillettes French cuisine 27\u201328 Cassoulet; b\u00e9arnaise; duck \u00e0 l'orange Italian cuisine 29\u201330 Osso buco; gnocchi; tiramisu Japanese cuisine 31\u201332 Dashi; tonkatsu; ramen tare Mexican cuisine 33\u201334 Pozole; mole; tamales Indian cuisine 35\u201336 Butter chicken; biryani; garam masala Middle Eastern 37\u201338 Hummus from dried; falafel; shawarma SE Asian 39\u201340 Pad thai; pho; rendang Bread 41\u201342 Sourdough loaf; croissants Pastry 43\u201344 P\u00e2te sucr\u00e9e; tarte tatin Desserts 45\u201346 Panna cotta; cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e; pavlova Signature / Mastery 47\u201348 Your defined dishes Menus / Timing 49\u201350 Dinner party for 8, on time"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/quick-ref.html#the-final-dish-self-assessment","title":"The Final Dish Self-Assessment","text":"<p>Answer before cooking your final exam dish:</p> Question Your Answer What dish have you chosen? Why this one? What technique does it require? Where could it go wrong? What is your contingency if it does? How will you know it's right?"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/quick-ref.html#recommended-ongoing-resources","title":"Recommended Ongoing Resources","text":"Resource What It's For Serious Eats Primary reference; continue using indefinitely The Food Lab articles (Kenji) Deep-dive technique science on any topic SE Recipe Index Find any specific dish SE Techniques Searchable by skill Local farmers market Seasonal ingredients teach more than recipes A notebook It always comes back to writing things down"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/quick-ref.html#what-you-have-made-52-week-summary","title":"What You Have Made (52-Week Summary)","text":"Category Approximate Dishes Egg and breakfast dishes 12+ Soups and stocks 20+ Vegetable preparations 40+ Fish and shellfish 30+ Poultry 20+ Beef 25+ Pork 15+ International complete meals 40+ Bread and pastry 20+ Desserts and custards 20+ Estimated total ~250\u2013280 dishes"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/quick-ref.html#week-5152-at-a-glance","title":"Week 51\u201352 at a Glance","text":"Session Activity W51 Mon Skills inventory + knife time trial W51 Tue Cook one dish from weeks 1\u201310 W51 Wed Cook complete 2-course meal from memory W51 Thu Rest W51 Fri Final mise en place drill W51 Sat Anniversary Dinner \u2014 your people, your menu W52 Mon Write culinary philosophy W52 Tue Final Exam Dish \u2014 no recipe W52 Wed Retrospective tasting menu (personal) W52 Thu Do not cook W52 Fri Open kitchen \u2014 cook for anyone W52 Sat The Final Dinner \u2014 no instructions"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/shopping-list.html","title":"Block 51\u201352: Module 5 Capstone \u2014 The Final Exam: Shopping List","text":"<p>\u2190 Block 49\u201350: Signature Dishes</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/shopping-list.html#equipment-check-full-year","title":"Equipment Check (Full Year)","text":"<p>This is a good moment to evaluate which equipment you've acquired over 52 weeks and what gaps remain.</p> <p>Essential \u2014 you should have these by now: - [ ] Chef's knife (8\u201310 inch), well-maintained and sharp - [ ] Carbon steel or cast iron skillet - [ ] Heavy-bottomed stainless saut\u00e9 pan - [ ] Dutch oven (5\u20137 qt) - [ ] Stock pot (8+ qt) - [ ] Instant-read thermometer - [ ] Digital scale - [ ] Mandoline (or very good knife skills) - [ ] Standing or hand mixer - [ ] Sheet pans \u00d7 2, with wire racks</p> <p>Nice to have if not yet acquired: - [ ] Wok (14-inch carbon steel) - [ ] Banneton and Dutch oven (sourdough) - [ ] Kitchen torch (cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e) - [ ] Spider strainer (frying) - [ ] Bench scraper (pastry + bread)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/shopping-list.html#week-51-shopping","title":"Week 51 Shopping","text":""},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/shopping-list.html#tuesday-the-forgotten-dish-from-weeks-110","title":"Tuesday \u2014 The Forgotten Dish (from weeks 1\u201310)","text":"<p>Items depend on which dish you choose. Common choices: - Coq au vin: whole chicken, mushrooms, pearl onions, lardons, wine - Roast chicken: whole bird, lemon, garlic, herbs, butter - Braised short ribs: bone-in short ribs, mirepoix vegetables, red wine - French omelette \u00d7 several: eggs, butter \u2014 no other ingredients needed</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/shopping-list.html#friday-final-mise-en-place-drill-4-course","title":"Friday \u2014 Final Mise en Place Drill (4-course)","text":"<p>Choose your menu; buy what that menu requires. Suggested: - Protein (your best cut): highest quality you can afford \u2014 this is the final practice - Vegetables \u00d7 3 types - Fresh herbs - Butter, cream, stock (from pantry or fresh) - Wine for braising or sauce</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/shopping-list.html#week-52-shopping","title":"Week 52 Shopping","text":""},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/shopping-list.html#tuesday-the-final-exam-dish","title":"Tuesday \u2014 The Final Exam Dish","text":"<p>This is your personal dish. Buy the ingredients for the dish you choose as your final exam.</p> Component Your Item Quantity <p>Recommendation: Buy the best version of every ingredient. This meal is worth it.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/shopping-list.html#wednesday-the-retrospective-tasting-menu","title":"Wednesday \u2014 The Retrospective Tasting Menu","text":"<p>This meal is built from previously mastered dishes. Pull from your freezer (stocks, braises, doughs) where possible. Buy only fresh components: - [ ] Fresh herbs for garnish - [ ] Fresh fish or shellfish if the retrospective includes one - [ ] Cream or mascarpone if needed for dessert layer - [ ] A small amount of good cheese (optional intermezzo)</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/shopping-list.html#friday-the-open-kitchen","title":"Friday \u2014 The Open Kitchen","text":"<p>Plan for however many people you expect; this is a free-form session. - [ ] Good bread \u00d7 2 loaves - [ ] Charcuterie and cheese board (always a backup) - [ ] Protein for on-request cooking (chicken thighs are forgiving; excellent pantry backup) - [ ] Eggs \u2014 2 dozen (the most versatile on-demand ingredient) - [ ] Pantry essentials fully restocked</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/shopping-list.html#saturday-the-final-dinner","title":"Saturday \u2014 The Final Dinner","text":"<p>No shopping list. You know what you're cooking. You know what you need.</p> <p>Buy the best you can find. Cook it the way you've learned. That's the whole thing.</p>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/shopping-list.html#pantry-final-inventory","title":"Pantry Final Inventory","text":"<p>Complete this before the final week, then replace anything low:</p> <ul> <li>[ ] Olive oil (replace with new bottle if more than 6 months old)</li> <li>[ ] Kosher salt (Diamond Crystal or Morton \u2014 check level)</li> <li>[ ] Maldon sea salt for finishing</li> <li>[ ] Whole peppercorns (grind fresh)</li> <li>[ ] Dried pasta \u00d7 4 shapes</li> <li>[ ] Canned whole tomatoes \u00d7 4 (San Marzano)</li> <li>[ ] Stock (homemade in freezer, or good quality purchased)</li> <li>[ ] Vinegars: sherry, red wine, white wine, champagne</li> <li>[ ] Fish sauce, soy sauce, oyster sauce, mirin (check levels)</li> <li>[ ] Dijon mustard, whole grain mustard</li> <li>[ ] Tahini (if using in your signature repertoire)</li> <li>[ ] Capers, anchovies (small-batch flavor bombs)</li> <li>[ ] Dried chiles \u00d7 assortment (guajillo, ancho, \u00e1rbol)</li> <li>[ ] Good canned tuna or sardines (emergency pantry dinner)</li> <li>[ ] Chocolate: bittersweet 70% \u00d7 1 bar</li> </ul>"},{"location":"blocks/05-mastery-and-pastry/61-62-final-exam/shopping-list.html#a-final-note","title":"A Final Note","text":"<p>After 52 weeks, you have a pantry that took a year to build. The stocks you're holding in the freezer, the dried chiles in the cabinet, the anchovy jar you learned to reach for \u2014 these are the materials of a cook's kitchen. </p> <p>The greatest investment of this year was not in equipment or ingredients. It was in the decision, repeated approximately 250 times, to cook rather than not cook.</p> <p>That practice is yours to keep.</p>"}]}